<head>
<title>Jan 96: Editorial</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>from the pages of January 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="jan96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h1 align=center>Editorial </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By Z Staff </strong></em></h2>
<p>To &#147;balance the budget&#148; faster is better, everyone says, but we shouldn't shoot ourselves in 
the foot trying to do more than we can afford. Does this make sense? </p>
<p>Z is planning this summer's Z Media Institute. To complete the project we have to over 
extend, and then pay off debts. Does that mean it is a bad idea? Everybody realizes that to 
answer you must consider what is the project worth? If the benefits exceed the cost, proceed. 
If not, desist. </p>
<p>Suppose you want to buy a house. It means incurring a debt that will last 30 years. Is this 
stupid? Not if you benefit sufficiently. </p>
<p>The logic is to spend more than you have makes sense if what you get for your borrowed 
money is worth the price you pay. And what makes something worthwhile? It needs to meet 
pressing needs or to prepare you to earn so much that even after the payments you wind up 
better off than if you hadn't made the purchase. One issue is meeting real needs to improve 
life; another issue is investing to generate more future earning power than the fees you pay. </p>
<p>Now what if you are a company? Will your investment increase productivity or lower costs 
sufficiently to more than meet the incurred expenses? Large companies often have huge debts, 
relatively larger per output than the Federal Government, and this is generally a good rather 
than bad sign for the company. </p>
<p>Suppose we look at the Federal Government. Again, it should spend on important needs or on 
what will produce more than it costs, and not on other stuff. </p>
<p>But aren't we sacrificing future generations to current desires? This is true if we borrow from 
some other country, so the payments of the next generations go outside. But if we borrow 
from our own country, when the next generation pays the bill, it goes to themselves. The real 
issue is which members of the future generation are paying (all tax payers) and which are 
getting paid (bond holders). So there can be a redistributive effect which can be a reason to 
curb borrowing, though not one often given nowadays. In any event, it is true that if we spend 
on giving some citizens now luxuries that afford great fulfillment but have no payoff in future 
productivity, future generations of taxpayers wind up paying for current pleasures. But if we 
meet basic needs now that should be universally met later, or if we make expenditures now 
that prevent larger expenditures later or that produce returns later that together sum to more 
than future generations must pay, then we are actually benefiting those future generations as 
well as ourselves, by borrowing now. </p>
<p>And what of the argument that by borrowing we are reducing the pool of resources available 
for investments? This has an element of truth. Any expenditure uses resources that might be 
put elsewhere. But in this case as in all others it means that we should spend on what we 
really need, or on what is a good investment, and not on frivolous or wasteful ends, or to 
benefit only a few. Anyone who says we ought to cut social programs on this ground and who 
doesn't say we ought to first slash the defense budget, is a hypocritical wager of class war for 
capital against labor. It is that simple. </p>
<p>And what about redistribution? Could spending impose fees on future generations of working 
and poor people to benefit rich people now? Sure. This is a real possibility and one that any 
humane person would oppose. But it means, again, that we have to look at each type of 
expenditure we propose so that we reject those that are inhumane in their distributive effects, 
making the rich richer and the poor poorer, but favor those that are egalitarian. </p>
<p>So if pundits and policy makers were really worried about wise investments, the next 
generation, or redistribution, there would be no generalized assault on spending. There 
would, instead, be a public discussion of which spending is valid, and which isn't, and of 
course we would have to ask -- according to whose interests? </p>
<p>Once we do this, however, all becomes clear. On the road to the balanced budget over the 
projected 7 years, corporate welfare -- that is, aid to dependent corporations and their 
owners -- is slated to decline by about 1 percent or $30 billion, with doubts about whether 
even that will occur. But social welfare programs will be cut an estimated 17 percent, or 
about $300 billion. </p>
<p>The great budget debate is a scam. The drive to balance the budget is class war, period. It is 
just a useful scare story to prepare people to justify cutting programs which increase the 
balance of power of poor and working people, while preserving programs that increase the 
power of the rich and corporate. The agenda is class war on the poor. The debate is about 
how viciously they wage it. &lt;W0S&gt; </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

