<head>
<title>Jan 96: Carter; Interview with Difranco</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>from the pages of January 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="jan96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>An Interview With Ani Difranco </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By Sandy Carter </strong></em></h2>
<p>i am not a pretty girl <br>
that is not what i do <br>
ain't no damsel in distress <br>
and i don't need to be rescued <br>
so put me down punk <br>
wouldn't you prefer a <br>
maiden fair <br>
isn't there a kitten <br>
stuck up a tree somewhere </p>
<h4 align=left>-- Ani Difranco </h4>
<p>Over the last ten years, through constant touring and seven self-produced albums on her own 
label, singer/songwriter Ani Difranco has built a steadily growing, incredibly devoted 
following. With an explosive vocal delivery, fiery percussive guitar work, and a batch of 
unflinchingly honest songs about a woman's struggle for identity and meaning, she has defined 
a dynamic and original sound. Balancing acoustic-based tunefulness with aggressive energy, 
hard-edged realism, and social idealism, Difranco is a modern day troubadour with roots 
running from Woody Guthrie and Joni Mitchell to the Clash and Rick James. </p>
<p>Her music, however, accounts for only part of her appeal. In a time where most of the 
&#147;alternative rock&#148; world made its peace with the corporate music industry, Difranco remains 
a steadfast critic of major label music making. </p>
<p>On her own since age 15 when she moved out of her mother's apartment in Buffalo, New 
York, Difranco forged her unique style playing in bars and coffeehouses under the guiding 
supervision of a 30-year-old &#147;degenerate folk singer&#148; named Mike. When she was 18, she 
moved to New York and after raiding her bank account and borrowing from friends, financed 
and produced her first album. Following a brief encounter with a small record company, 
Difranco decided to start her own label, Righteous Babe Records. To date, the company has 
sold over 200,000 CD's and tapes, while also providing Difranco the artistic freedom to 
publish, produce, and market her music as she sees fit. Now, at the age of 25, with her latest 
album, Not A Pretty Girl, gaining mainstream media attention and rave reviews, Difranco's 
audience is &#147;suddenly&#148; widening. </p>
<p>Labeled a punk folksinger by the pop media, Difranco writes and performs in a way that is 
accessible to young and old music listeners. Still, she is an artist who defies the comfort zone 
of conventional tastes. In &#147;Light Of A Kind&#148; from Not A Pretty Girl, she tells her boyfriend 
of an affair with a woman. Her poem &#147;TipToe&#148; recalls an abortion: </p>
<p>the skyline of jersey <br>
walking towards the water <br>
with a fetus holding court <br>
in my gut <br>
my body hijacked <br>
my tits swollen and sore </p>
<p>On &#147;Crime For Crime,&#148; she takes an unfashionable stand on the death penalty reminding us: </p>
<p>you might be the wrong color <br>
you might just be too poor <br>
justice isn't something <br>
just anyone can afford. </p>
<p>&#147;The Million You Never Made&#148; is a fierce declaration of independence denouncing the 
star-making machinery of the corporate music business. On &#147;Coming Up,&#148; she confronts &#147;our 
father who art in a penthouse&#148; with a warning that if things don't change &#147;we are coming up.&#148; </p>
<p>Then there's her concert performances. With a pierced nostril, dreadlocks, and double thick 
fashion nails secured with glue and electrical tape (so that she can freely assault her acoustic 
guitar), Difranco certainly doesn't look like any brand of folkie. When drummer Andy 
Stochansky, who also plays on her records, kicks in a bone-crunching back beat, she 
transcends all sonic preconceptions of folk or folk-rock. Yet if her look and energy seem to 
have more in common with punk than folk, Difranco's warm, outgoing stage manner contrasts 
sharply with the detached, tortured personas that dominate alternative rock. Her nervous 
laughter and self-deprecating humor is charming and utterly unhip. When she confesses her 
vulnerabilities in quiet, delicate love songs (aimed sometimes to men, sometimes to women), 
she reveals a full range of emotions. </p>
<p>In mid-November, just before a concert at UC Berkeley's 2,000 seat Zellerbach Hall, I talked 
with Difranco by phone about folk music, fame, and politics. </p>
<p>CARTER: <em>Let's begin by talking a little bit about folk music. I know you were doing cover 
versions of Beatles tunes at age nine. When did you first get turned on to folk music and 
what was the attraction</em>? </p>
<p>DIFRANCO: Well, I guess, almost from the beginning. I was kind of a precocious kid who 
would just be at the corner of the bar soaking it all in and I just fell in with this crowd. All 
my friends were in their 30s, and kind of alcoholic barfly songwriter people. So what they 
were doing became part of my vocabulary early on. </p>
<p>But my feelings about folk music have changed a lot over the years. I'm not so much a folk 
music fan anymore for the way that it sounds. I'm more interested in it now economically and 
politically speaking. People now often use the words &#147;folk&#148; and &#147;punk&#148; to describe what I 
do, and to me that's totally cool. I mean I can agree with it in that punk music and folk music 
are traditionally subcorporate kinds of music. They are of communities and not as 
commercialized as a lot of other kinds of music. </p>
<p><em>How much does your audience mix up the traditional urban folk crowd with the younger 
punk and alternative rock audience</em>? </p>
<p>Pretty much these days, it's just young folks. I mean it depends on where I'm playing. The last 
few nights, I've played these sleepy little towns and I got an older crowd. Especially last 
night where I was in this town of 1,200 people and it's just left over hippies and their kids. 
So the audience is either 45 or 12. Nobody was my age. But it was great, everybody was 
doing this kind of seaweed dance and having a good time. It was a benefit for people trying to 
save one of the last old growth redwood stands. </p>
<p><em>When you first started performing the early punk movement was emerging. Did you pick 
up on that at the time</em>? </p>
<p>No. I was so young, I mean single digits. The thing about me is, I never had a stereo growing 
up and was really pretty much unaware of recorded music, except for what I got from public 
spaces and radios. My experience with music, for the most part, was all first hand. There 
were real people sitting there in front of me playing. I never really knew any kind of music 
other than that. </p>
<p><em>Aside from the feminist/bisexual/gender themes that run through your work, there's also a 
very clear class conscious, anti-racist, anti-capitalist perspective. Did you grow up in a 
leftist oriented household or did these views come later</em>? </p>
<p>My parents were liberal people, in an old world sort of way. Not really political people, but 
very open-minded for their age. But I'd say I came into my politics in my late teens. I'd been 
on my own since the age of 15, emancipated, taking care of myself, and very much a part of 
the adult world. So a lot of my experiences, early on, tended to politicize. Out of that came 
the ideals that I carry today. </p>
<p><em>Those ideals have been put into practice with your Righteous Babe label. Why don't more 
artists do what you're doing instead of leaving the dirty work of business to others</em>? </p>
<p>I don't know. Possibly because it's a lot of work. You have to be willing to make personal 
sacrifices, as with any kind of political work. People tell me all the time, and truthfully so, 
you're holding your career back. Because starting your own record company is not the most 
glamorous or accelerated way to govern your career. </p>
<p>Also, I think things are ever changing and what I've done just hasn't been an option in the past. 
I mean Woody Guthrie would go and record for Columbia Records because he needed 
fucking work and they'd give him 25 bucks or whatever. I'm sure Woody didn't think, wow, if 
I could just start my own company and get my music right to the people. At the time there was 
just no such thing happening. But now, the technology is more and more accessible. The 
means of making art and distributing information, be it through movies, music, books, 
newspapers, magazines, is more at our disposal. And I would hope that more artists would 
become interested in keeping control, rather than giving up the production and distribution of 
their art to corporate interests. So I'm trying to offer a model, even though I'm kind of flying 
blind. </p>
<p><em>Your album Not A Pretty Girl has gained a lot of acclaim and some mainstream visibility. 
How are you holding up to all this new media attention and are the big labels still trying 
to court you</em>? </p>
<p>Yeah, the big labels call all the time. But it's been funny lately, because even though I've 
recently been in the mainstream industry news, Rolling Stone, Spin, MTV, this is what I've 
always done. People in that other world may think of me as this new face or an overnight 
success or something, but for me, it's been a long, slow organic growth. There's nothing 
happening now that's going to change or influence the way I live my life. </p>
<p><em>Because you're viewed as a strong, assertive, creative woman and you're up on a stage, 
some of your fans see you as a role model or a spokesperson. Does that kind of image 
make you feel uncomfortable</em>? </p>
<p>Well, its unfortunate in that people have a tendency to rely on other people to speak for them. 
So many of us are starving for affirmation of our existence and when we find somebody who 
says something that makes sense, we latch onto it. For me, this is disconcerting because if 
you've found me to speak for you, it means you're still not speaking for yourself. And that's 
the problem to begin with. </p>
<p>It's also really a drag when people dehumanize you. And fans sometimes do. I mean they hurt 
me. It's unfortunate to find yourself a symbol rather than a human being. But I try to look at 
that as an indication of how much people must need. </p>
<p><em>You seem to try very hard to keep things on a human scale</em>? </p>
<p>Yeah, I keep trying to undercut that whole rock star thing. I mean I get up on stage every night 
and I'm like, &#147;Well it's just me and I'm just like you, la de da.&#148; But it can get surreal 
nonetheless. </p>
<p><em>Your songs are very open-hearted, some have called them &#147;confessional,&#148; and yet 
simultaneously they draw in social and political issues of our time. Do your songs come to 
you that way, with the personal and political all mixed up</em>? </p>
<p>Well, I do look at the world through a political lens. The old adage the personal is political, 
holds very true for me. Politics is not just newspaper headlines and T-shirts, it's what we do 
all day long. It's what we eat, it's what we wear, how we talk, how we treat each other. My 
writing is informed by that sort of perspective. </p>
<p>But you know mainstream media people ask me all the time, &#147;So what issues do you like to 
write about?&#148; And I think, well, my life, that's kind of my issue. My experience on the planet. 
Really, all I intend to do in my songs is tell my story. I think it's important that we all do that 
for each other. Until you've made noise about your experience and what you know to be true, 
I don't think you can be taken into account. </p>
<p><em>In many ways these are pretty dark times we're living through, and a lot of rock music 
reflects that in its anger and gloom and doom. Your music challenges people to move in 
another direction</em>. </p>
<p>To me the whole &#147;alternative music&#148; thing now is kind of unfortunate. You know, all this 
angst-ridden, navel-contemplating, isolationist sort of vibe. I just can't stand it. Then here I 
am with, evil of all evils, an acoustic guitar. Even worse, I get up on stage and try to talk to 
people and make some connection, which is not in vogue these days. The fact that what I do 
is so uncool kind of pleases me. </p>
<p>There is anger in many of my songs. There are many things in the world to be angry about and 
if you're not angry, you're either unaware or numb. But I don't want to be stereotyped as just 
an &#147;angry young girl.&#148; I have a sense of humor and hope and ideals and all that's in my songs 
too. By telling my stories and being who I am I hope I can be some kind of inspiration. 
Because we'd all like to live in a better world. But it won't happen unless we make it happen. </p>
<p>As for my audience, I'm really lucky. The people who come to my shows actually enjoy being 
challenged to move in another direction and they're so much more respectful than so many 
audiences. I demand a lot of them. In one minute we're all moshing and screaming and in the 
next minute, I ask them to listen to something very quiet and go right there with me, and for 
the most part, they do. There's also a lot of exchanging of ideas and I try to get them to talk 
back to me. So given the nature of what I do, it weeds out any but the open-minded. I show up 
and it's throngs of queers and young feminists and sensitive boys. It's really wonderful. </p>
<p><em>Sandy Carter is a regular contributor to Z Magazine</em>.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

