<title>Feb 96: Cook; Brave New Working World</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>From the pages of February 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="feb96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>&#160;Congress Proposes<br>
Brazen New World for Workers </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By Christopher D. Cook </strong></em></h2>
<p>With congressional appropriations politicking cranked to the highest notch, the prevailing 
wisdom of pols and press alike is that the budget deficit, Medicare, and welfare are the 
make-or-break, election-year issues. While lawmakers alternately fawn over the middle 
class and demonize the underclass, however, big business and industry lobbies are quietly 
guiding Republicans down a deregulatory path with grave consequences for the nation's 
working class. </p>
<p>From repeals of prevailing wage laws to deep cuts in health and safety regulations and 
organizing rights, Congress is delivering a flurry of legislative punches which, if successful, 
could leave workers more vulnerable to hazards and exploitation than at any time since the 
1930s. </p>
<p>Proposals in the House Committee on Economic and Educational Opportunities include 
eliminating minimum wage and overtime laws, expanding employer-friendly loopholes in the 
National Labor Relations Act, creating a national right-to-work law, and effectively turning 
the Occupational Safety and Health Administration into a consulting service for business. </p>
<p>Whether these proposals become law in the coming months depends on a number of factors. 
The success of more popular measures, such as an OSHA rollback and prevailing wage 
repeal, may turn on behind-the-scenes vote trading and arm twisting. </p>
<p>But the wide-ranging labor rollback will also test the clout and priorities of new AFL-CIO 
President John Sweeney, and the frayed alliances between organized labor and the 
Democrats. </p>
<p>In a recent interview, Sweeney insisted the congressional assault will not go unopposed. &#147;I 
think workers across this country, both organized and unorganized, are getting the message 
loud and clear that the present leadership of the Congress wants to rip the guts out of 
programs that workers find necessary,&#148; he said, &#147;in order to give tax breaks to the wealthy 
and corporations.&#148; </p>
<p>He promised vigorous grassroots electoral campaigning in 1996 to &#147;send a message loud and 
clear that American workers and families are fed up with the attacks.&#148; Although Sweeney has 
already backed President Clinton for reelection, he added that &#147;all of those who are a part of 
significantly cutting these programs are not friends of workers, regardless of what party 
they're in.&#148; </p>
<p>The Republican prescription for budget-balancing and regulatory &#147;flexibilization&#148; is 
unprecedented cuts to federal labor budgets and a brazen new deregulated world for workers 
-- in which business draws the bottom line on workplace safety and labor organizing. </p>
<p>Among the proposals gliding through congressional appropriations, often cloaked in the 
benign guise of government streamlining and cost-cutting: </p>
<ul>
<li>@ZBULLET = Reducing the National Labor Relations Board budget by one-third, 
severely curtailing investigations of unlawful firing and harassment complaints, and 
delaying union election certifications. The NLRB would also be stripped of its authority 
to issue temporary injunctions in emergency situations. <br>
</li>
<li>Cutting 30 percent of the Occupational Safety and Health Administration budget and 
eliminating the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH), the 
research agency that identifies workplace hazards. The Mine Health and Safety 
Administration would also disappear, and mine safety inspections be drastically 
reduced. <br>
</li>
<li>The Job Training Partnership Act would get 40 percent less money, eliminating dozens 
of programs. Funds previously earmarked for homeless veteran assistance, refugee 
education assistance, Appalachian vocational training, and migrant farmworker higher 
education would be repealed, replaced by block grants to be spent at the whim of state 
governments. <br>
</li>
<li>The Department of Labor's Wage and Hour Division would be cut by 12 percent, 
meaning a massive scaling back of investigations into violations of minimum wage, 
overtime, child labor, and farmworker protection laws. With wage and hour 
enforcement staff already &#147;pruned down beyond the bone,&#148; said Department of Labor 
official Rick Sawyer, more employers &#147;will play the odds&#148; -- and get away with 
flagrant labor violations. <br>
</li>
<li>Department of Labor discretionary funds, which provide emergency relief to displaced 
and disadvantaged workers during massive plant layoffs, would be cut by a &#147;disastrous&#148; 
20 percent, according to Sawyer, Labor Secretary Reich's West Coast representative. </li>
</ul>
<p>The appropriations bill also contains several riders which could prove hazardous to 
workers. Ergonomic standards would go out the window, and OSHA would no longer 
research or regulate repetitive stress injuries, America's fastest-growing job hazard. Fall 
protection standards for construction workers would be seriously diminished, changing the 
height at which workers are covered by OSHA from 6 feet to 16. Minors working for 
cardboard baling companies would no longer be protected by federal weight-lift rules. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>A Smaller, Gentler OSHA </h3>
<p>Led by New Hampshire Senator Judd Gregg and North Carolina Rep. Cass Ballenger, 
Republican budget cuts and reforms amount to the biggest Occupational Safety and Health 
Administration (OSHA) rollback since its inception in 1970. And their plans to cut 30 
percent of OSHA's budget and eliminate NIOSH are only the beginning. </p>
<p>Conveniently paralleling the budget reductions, Republican OSHA reforms give employers 
broad new self-policing powers through &#147;peer review panels&#148; designed explicitly to 
pre-empt OSHA inspections. In lieu of OSHA's surprise investigatory visits, companies will 
be allowed -- in fact, encouraged -- to hire their own certified workplace safety inspectors. </p>
<p>Thanks to cost-benefit analysis and risk assessment, OSHA and company-hired inspectors 
will have far fewer hazards to look for. &#147;In determining the priority for establishing 
standards relating to toxic materials or harmful physical agents,&#148; says a bill sponsored by 
Senator Gregg, OSHA must &#147;consider the number of workers exposed to such materials or 
agents, the nature and severity of potential impairment, and the likelihood of such 
impairment.&#148; Protective standards must be shown to &#147;produce benefits to employee health 
and safety or the environment that will justify the cost to the Federal Government and the 
public.&#148; </p>
<p>Labor Secretary Reich staunchly opposes this change, calling it &#147;standards based on profits, 
not science.&#148; At a congressional hearing Reich testified that HR 1834, Ballenger's 
widely-supported OSHA reform bill, would &#147;allow parties with a direct financial interest to 
participate in `peer review' panels that would guide the development of new standards.&#148; The 
bill, Reich said, would institute &#147;a new regulatory petition process to allow perpetual 
challenge to OSHA's protective rules,&#148; and &#147;delay rules for months or years at the expense of 
workers safety and health.&#148; </p>
<p>Ballenger's measure chokes OSHA enforcement -- already hampered by downsizing which 
has left one OSHA inspector for every 6,000 businesses -- by eliminating violation fines 
used to increase industry's compliance. According to Reich, more than half of all American 
businesses would be exempt from OSHA's general inspection program, and the agency would 
be prevented from increasing penalties for willful or repeat violations. </p>
<p>Ballenger, who chairs the House Subcommittee on Workforce Protections, began laying 
groundwork for OSHA rollback in the first week of Republican majority control. His 
supporting cast includes the Heritage Foundation, the National Mining Association, and the 
National Stone Association. While proclaiming their dedication to worker safety, they 
proposed eliminating the Mine Safety and Health Administration, and reducing federal mine 
safety inspections to just one per year. </p>
<p>A Kentucky coal miner, presumably not invited by Ballenger, made another side clear to the 
committee. &#147;If your bill becomes law,&#148; he told Ballenger's panel, &#147;the small, non-union 
mines of eastern Kentucky will become death traps.&#148; </p>
<p>For union and non-union workers alike, the 30 percent cut to the National Labor Relations 
Board &#147;would really have a devastating impact,&#148; says Owen Marron, executive secretary of 
the central labor council for Alameda County, California, a group serving 68,000 workers in 
135 local unions. Employees who are unfairly fired, or harassed during organizing drives, 
would have little recourse. If the cuts go through, says one AFL-CIO member, &#147;nobody will 
get prosecuted for violating the National Labor Relations Act...If you can't investigate the 
allegations, how in the hell are you going to prosecute anybody?&#148; </p>
<p>And with unions on the decline, says Bill Sokol, a prominent West Coast labor attorney, &#147;the 
NLRB, from the point of view of working people is the only recourse they have when an 
employer fires them or screws around with them.&#148; At a time when a revitalized AFL-CIO 
plans major organizing campaigns, a disempowered NLRB would mean &#147;tremendous delays&#148; 
in union election certifications, Marron predicts. &#147;The NLRB's ability to meet the demand 
will be virtually impossible,&#148; Sawyer adds. Ironically, this could usher &#147;a return to the kind 
of 1930s industrial unrest which necessitated the birth of the NLRB in the first place.&#148; </p>
<p>The House also proposes eliminating the NLRB's temporary injunction authority, which is 
often used to bring severe violations, such as harassment and unlawful firing of workers 
during organizing drives, to a halt. &#147;When you combine that with the 30 percent cut in 
funding, it virtually means the NLRB ceases to exist,&#148; says Sawyer. </p>
<p>As with OSHA, the NLRB cuts are merely one part of a full-fledged rollback. The 
&#147;Teamwork for Employees and Management Act&#148; moving through both the House and Senate, 
many labor leaders fear would bring back the company union. The proposal has been in 
Congress for years, with no greater chance of passage than the present. </p>
<p>While promising to &#147;preserve existing protections against deceptive, coercive employer 
practices,&#148; the Teamwork bill enables employers to create committees that address &#147;matters 
of mutual interest,&#148; such as productivity and efficiency -- broad and loosely -- defined areas 
which could easily affect wages, pay rates, and working hours and conditions. There is no 
concrete guarantee to prevent employee involvement programs from being used as virtually 
powerless substitutes for unions. </p>
<p>In a &#147;cost-cutting&#148; move that many Democrats warn will hit workers and the economy hard, 
Republicans are attempting to repeal the Davis-Bacon and Service Contract Acts, which 
guarantee prevailing wage rates to federally contracted construction and service workers. 
Ballenger, sponsor of a Davis-Bacon repeal, claims &#147;taxpayers will be saved an estimated 
$3.1 billion in construction costs and bureaucratic overhead&#148; over five years. </p>
<p>Ballenger, whose repeal bill is mirrored by a Senate measure by supposedly &#147;moderate&#148; 
Labor Committee chair Nancy Kassebaum, offered particularly instructive reasoning for 
ending the prevailing wage law. The requirement is &#147;demonstrably unnecessary,&#148; he argued 
on the House floor, because minimum wage laws offer all the protection workers need. &#147;The 
Fair Labor Standards Act establishes a minimum wage and overtime rate,&#148; he said, providing 
all the wage guarantee workers need. </p>
<p>President Clinton has vowed to veto the Davis-Bacon repeal, and congressional Democrats 
like Connecticut Rep. Rosa DeLauro say it would drive down worker earnings and tax 
revenues by the billions. Prevailing wage repeal would also compound the effects of anemic 
OSHA enforcement, Democrats point out, since construction worker accident rates are 15 
percent higher in states that don't have their own Davis-Bacon law. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Reaping America Competitive </h3>
<p>One of the prime movers behind labor law rollback is the innocuous-sounding Employment 
Policy Foundation and its muscular lobbying arm, the Labor Policy Association. The group, 
which reportedly has the ready ear of Rep. Bill Goodling, chair of the House Committee on 
Economic and Educational Opportunities, last year published a policy lobbying book called 
Keeping America Competitive, which parallels the spirit and letter of congressional 
measures. </p>
<p>According to the Wall Street Journal, the book is widely viewed as &#147;the bible&#148; (i.e., 
legislative blueprint) by Goodling committee members and staffers. The Republican 
congressional majority, the Journal noted, &#147;has created the first opportunity in four decades 
for business groups to overturn portions of the nation's labor laws.&#148; </p>
<p>The Labor Policy Association (LPA) is a 220-member business lobby group representing 
major corporations such as Motorola, Texas Instruments, Honeywell, and Eastman Kodak, 
according to the Journal. Comparing the association's proposals to those in Goodling's 
committee, former LPA lobbying staffer Brad Cameron told the Journal, &#147;Sure, it's identical. 
But it isn't a conspiracy. It didn't happen overnight behind closed doors and in secret. This 
has been years in the making.&#148; </p>
<p>In Keeping America Competitive, The Employment Policy Foundation calls for a 
&#147;fundamental reassessment&#148; of U.S. labor law and employment policy, lamenting the impact 
of mandated benefits and expanded civil rights protections on competitiveness and 
productivity. Blaming worker protection and benefits laws for America's competitiveness 
crisis, the authors propose flexibility policies under which employees and managers would 
work as a team, unrestricted by &#147;rigid&#148; (read: legislated) wage and hour laws, collective 
bargaining rules, and OSHA regulations. </p>
<p>But while employer advocates and Republican lawmakers chip away at labor laws in the 
name of employee involvement, they have fiercely opposed any mandated worker 
participation in health and safety matters. Last year, for example, they defeated 
comprehensive OSHA reforms by Senator Edward Kennedy and Michigan Rep. William 
Ford which would have required joint worker-management safety committees. </p>
<p>The Employment Policy Foundation describes the 1990s as an era of bucolic labor relations. 
&#147;If an `us versus them' mentality plays any part in employee involvement cultures,&#148; the 
foundation writes, &#147;it is likely that the `us' refers to the company and the `them' refers to the 
company's competitors, domestic and/or foreign.&#148; In the new, egalitarian corporation -- built 
on the concept of permanent &#147;core&#148; staff and &#147;peripheral,&#148; or &#147;just-in-time&#148; temporary labor 
-- workers supposedly have little need for unions or, it seems, for labor rights. </p>
<p><em>Christoperh D. Cook is a freelance writer from San Francisco who has written for </em><em><strong>The 
Nation</strong></em><em>, I</em><em><strong>n These Times</strong></em><em> and </em><em><strong>The San Francisco Bay Guardian</strong></em>. </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

