<head>
<title>Feb 96: Emory &amp; Smith; Voice of the Peacock</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>From the pages of February 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="feb96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>Voice of the Peacock </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By Theo Emery &amp; Jeremy Smith </strong></em></h2>
<p>We are born from the sun, and the peacock is a symbol of the sun,&#148; says Moe Thee Zun, 
President of the All Burma Students' Democratic Front (ABSDF). In his fingers, he cradles a 
pin smelted from shell casings and molded into the shape of a bird. &#147;When a peacock fights, 
it fights to the death.&#148; </p>
<p>Moe Thee Zun's ABSDF has chosen an extravagant symbol for their organization, and like the 
bird that represents them, the group wears its plumage proudly. Dressed in army fatigues, 
Moe Thee Zun sits in a cramped apartment in Brookline, Massachusetts, speaking to a group 
of U.S. student activists. </p>
<p>&#147;We were able to organize the whole country to rise up against the military,&#148; Moe Thee Zun 
says of the Burmese student union, recalling the days before August 8, 1988, when the State 
Law and Order Restoration Council (SLORC) violently shattered the Burma's pro-democracy 
movement. &#147;Our demonstrations were the biggest in our history.&#148; </p>
<p>Touring the United States this fall, Moe Thee Zun is seeking what might seem to be unlikely 
solidarity with his American counterparts, given the sharply contrasting realities of the 
paramilitary Burmese and the comfortable Americans with whom they met. </p>
<p>&#147;We have a tradition of the students trying to get independence,&#148; according to Htun Aung 
Gyaw, the first chair of the ABSDF. &#147;Under the British in the 1920s, the students mobilized 
the people, and [again] in the 1940s ... The people believe the students.&#148; </p>
<p>Few words can describe what Burmese students have experienced. In 1962, the government 
dynamited the student union building at Rangoon University, killing 300 students inside. In 
1974, approximately 1,000 students were killed during anti-government demonstrations. One 
student leader was hanged, and Htun Aung Gyaw was sent to jail for life. </p>
<p>Granted amnesty in 1980, he is now a doctoral student at Cornell, and is still a member of the 
ABSDF. &#147;The SLORC doesn't want to negotiate with the students. If they negotiate with the 
students, it will be a big problem for them because the people totally support the students. 
They trust the students.&#148; </p>
<p>Clashes between students and the military remain fierce, violent, and often deadly. In 1988, 
as the government teetered after months of robust democratic action, students led the 
burgeoning democracy movement. &#147;We controlled everything,&#148; says Moe Thee Zun. &#147;We 
ruled the whole country. We were so busy we could not sleep.&#148; </p>
<p>On August 8, SLORC troops tore through demonstrations in Rangoon, firing on crowds from 
&#147;slaughter vans, shattering the movement and killing 2,000. Ten thousand students fled to 
camps along the Thai border, many within regions controlled by militant ethnic minorities 
such as the Karen and the Mon. In November of that year, a Congress of students assembled 
in a border camp to form the ABSDF. &#147;The military said before we left that we wouldn't 
last... seven days in the jungle,'' says Moe Thee Zun. &#147;We have been in the jungle for seven 
years.&#148; </p>
<p>It was &#147;very obvious from the beginning&#148; that the ABSDF would be a military outfit. 
&#147;Everyone was waiting for the student army,&#148; says Htun Aung Gyaw. &#147;The conditions were 
really good at the time.&#148; </p>
<p>Since 1988, the ABSDF has fought back from their jungle outposts sending communiques via 
their newspaper, Voice of the Peacock, and watching their once-mighty student movement 
fray into factionalism and infighting. The ABSDF has ruptured into two factions -- a minority 
faction which Moe Thee Zun represents, and a larger one headed by Dr. Naing Aung, a 
popular former vice-chair of the ABSDF. </p>
<p>Much of the factionalism has fiercely sectarian overtones, little of which reaches the 
generally non-ideological audience of the Burmese prodemocracy drama. Before the 1992 
split, ABSDF leaders secretly organized a left-wing organization, a Counter Revolutionary 
Council; created to move the ABSDF further toward the left. On becoming chair, Moe Thee 
Zun officially declared that the ABSDF was a military force pursuing armed revolution, 
which garnered a prompt international response and student flight to Dr. Naing Aung's camp. 
&#147;After that, the NGOs stopped supporting us,&#148; says Htun Aung Gyaw. </p>
<p>Of the 10,000 students who fled SLORC, there are now less than 1,500 students living on the 
border, most of them in Naing Aung's camp. Since January alone, over 300 students have left 
the camps to seek political asylum in third countries, or to live in Bangkok as day laborers, 
according to Zunetta Liddell of Human Rights Watch/Asia. Radio Myanmar, a SLORC 
mouthpiece, periodically sends out Orwellian broadcasts: &#147;(A)fter realizing the genuine 
goodwill and deeds of the government and rejecting the destructive policies of their 
organizations, fourteen insurgents...from the ABSDF surrendered on October 15. They were 
warmly welcomed by responsible personnel and local people and given necessary 
assistance.&#148; </p>
<p>The Burmese struggle has captured the imagination of people all over the world, particularly 
since Daw Aung San Suu Kwi won the Noble Prize for her pro-democracy efforts last year. 
While the political situation in Burma continues to worsen, as Human Rights Watch/ Asia 
reports, the country is gaining visibility in the U.S., particularly among students whose 
organizational issues and political ideals bridge the 10,000 miles between America and 
Southeast Asia. The broad array of issues in Burma -- including forced prostitution, political 
repression; environmental destruction, human rights, torture, slavery, and rapine corporate 
policies -- suggests all the elements for a powerful international solidarity. </p>
<p>The fruits of solidarity are evident: students throughout the U.S. are pressuring their schools 
and communities to create ``selective purchasing&#148; laws to limit the SLORC's corporate allies 
-- Pepsi, Unocal, and others -- from doing business in their communities. On October 27, 
students picketed the Burmese Embassy and Pepsi plants, held educational events, and 
negotiated to cancel alumni expeditions to Burma. Seventy-five colleges in over a dozen 
countries have formed a Burma response network, according to the Free Burma Coalition in 
Madison. </p>
<p>While the Burmese struggle has inspired U.S. students, the Americans have also provided 
inspiration for the Burmese activists. ABSDF Foreign Affairs Secretary Aung Naing Oo, who 
traveled with Moe Thee Zun, was stunned at the energy of a Burmese solidarity 
demonstration in Chapel Hill, NC. &#147;We were very surprised to see...young people coming 
together, and telling freely whatever they wanted to tell, singing songs,&#148; says the battle-worn 
Burmese student leader. &#147;It's something that we hope that we can do in Burma, standing up 
against injustice.&#148; </p>
<p>There is little doubt that the student split has damaged the ABSDF's credibility in Burma, and 
the students who once augured the downfall of their country's military government now 
realize the price of discord. &#147;I want to reunite these two groups to be one again. For me, it is 
a very shameful thing...that the ABSDF is split. Without unity, we can't improve,&#148; says Htun 
Aung Gyaw. </p>
<p>Zarni, a Burmese student who works with the Free Burma Coalition, believes that the 
students impact on the movement has ebbed. &#147;The ABSDF is the not the backbone of the 
movement internationally. Not to undermine the role that they have played, but the 
international solidarity movement does not depend on any single individual or 
organization...The two leaders are both good guys, and I don't see any reason why we should 
not work together.&#148; </p>
<p>The reality is that the cliches of communism are now as distant as the long-ago revolutions 
that bore them. For many students -- whether in the U.S. or in nations wracked by a colonial 
past -- the idealism of a struggle for democracy and human rights is more attractive than 
discordant battles over ideology. </p>
<p>This year, Moe Thee Zun's and Dr. Naing Aung's sections of the ABSDF begin a dialogue in 
the hopes of repairing the fissures which have split the student army, a necessary process if 
the Burmese students are to regain their credibility with pro-democracy supporters both 
abroad and at home. </p>
<p>&#147;If we believe in democracy, we have to follow the democratic tradition,&#148; says Htun Aung 
Gway. &#147;If we can't, we can't set up a democratic country. We will set up another 
dictatorship.&#148; </p>
<p><em>Jeremy Smith is with the University Conversion Project. Theo Emery is a freelance writer 
from Vermont. </em></p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

