<title>Feb 96: Gutman; Drug War II</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>From the pages of February 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="feb96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>The War No One Wants To Win, Part II </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By W. E. Gutman </strong></em></h2>
<p>In October 1994, Thomes Theiss is arrested in Germany as he attempts to smuggle in a large 
shipment of cocaine. His flight originates in Colombia -- with a stopover in Costa Rica. A 
month later, a German national, whose identity is being protected by Costa Rican police, is 
arrested at the Juan Santamaria Airport in San Jose for smuggling 17 kilos of top-grade 
cocaine concealed in a voltage regulator. Early in 1995, based on information provided by 
the as-yet unidentified suspect, an undercover operation leads to the arrest in Italy of Douglas 
Cruz, a key U.S. runner for a German narcotics ring working out of Colombia, Costa Rica, the 
U.S., and southern Europe. The sting also nets Cruz's Costa Rican contacts, Rosa Mery 
Condonero and Roxana Vindas. Vindas is arrested in Germany and flown back to Costa Rica. 
The women finger Volkert Ruhe, the ring leader. Ruhe is arrested in Panama and now awaits 
extradition to Germany. </p>
<p>Acting on a tip from U.S. DEA agents, Colombian police seize over two tons of cocaine in 
the engine compartment of a boat docked at the Caribbean port of Cartagena. Destined for 
Miami, the vessel had been grounded since December when police found 750 kilos of 
high-grade cocaine. According to police,who made no arrests, over five tons of cocaine was 
seized in Colombia since January. The DEA estimates that at least as much cocaine has since 
eluded interception and reached major U.S. cities. </p>
<p>In the West Indies, as tensions grow to undiplomatic proportions between the U.S. 
ambassador and the prime minister of St. Vincent and the Grenadines over allegations by the 
U.S. that the archipelago is up to its neck in drug running, three Vincentians attempt to import 
90 pounds of marijuana to New York via Barbados and are arrested. One of them, the 
relative of a high-ranking police official, had been convicted on drug trafficking charges in 
1992 and released on a &#147;technicality.&#148; </p>
<p>Also in Barbados, an Australian and a Briton are arrested for possession of a &#147;trafficable 
quantity&#148; of cocaine (3 kilograms) and charged with unlawful importation and intent to 
export. </p>
<p>A puddle-jump north, normally placid St. Lucia is abuzz with rumors that murky transactions 
(between the prime minister, the foreign minister, the United Nations, and New York's 
Chemical Bank) involving funds allocated to an ad-hoc organization called the Eastern 
Caribbean Research Center might allegedly conceal a larger but as yet unhatched 
drug-related scheme. The scandal is widening amid strident calls for Prime Minister John 
Compton's resignation. </p>
<p>Ivor Bird, general manager of the family-owned ZDK radio station, is seen collecting a 
suitcase containing 10 kilos of cocaine at Antigua's Vere Bird airport from an incoming 
Venezuelan visitor. Bird, the younger brother of Antigua Prime Minister Lester Bird, is 
released on $20,000 bail. If convicted, he faces a maximum five-year prison term. The 
visitor, Marcus Alberto Trottman, is being held without bail. </p>
<p>A Guyanese journalist traveling &#147;on assignment&#148; to the U.S. via Trinidad on behalf of a 
Guyanese state-owned media house is arrested at Georgetown's Timehri International 
Airport. One of her suitcases contains neatly stacked bricks of marijuana valued at over 
$60,000 on the U.S. wholesale market. </p>
<p>Nearly 20 percent of the heroin and virtually all of the cocaine and marijuana seized in the 
U.S. comes from Latin America and the West Indies. Dealers now undersell their Southeast 
Asian competitors by using existing networks and lower transportation costs, and by 
exploiting unscrupulous politicians and greedy military bigwigs. While Central America is a 
&#147;trans-shipment area&#148; for cocaine destined for North America, the Caribbean serves as a 
transit area for large quantities of U.S.- and Europe-bound cocaine and cannabis. According 
to Interpol, the Netherlands Antilles (Aruba, Bonaire, Curacao, and St. Martin) are also fast 
emerging as important transit points for cocaine arriving from Colombia, Suriname, and 
Venezuela. Jamaica has been singled out by the International Narcotics Control Board 
(INCB) as the &#147;premier supplier&#148; of cannabis to Canada, the U.S., and Great Britain. 
According to the INCB, 75 tons of cannabis were seized in Jamaica in 1993, compared with 
35 tons in 1992. Seizures of cannabis oil increased from 165 kilos to 235 kilos in that same 
period. </p>
<p>In a letter dated October 24, 1994 to U.S. Congressperson Lee Hamilton, the chair of the 
Foreign Affairs Committee, Colombia's President Ernesto Samper Pizano said that during his 
brief time in office police had seized seven tons of cocaine, compared with four tons for the 
first six months of 1994; raided 59 cocaine laboratories, and destroyed eight airstrips. 
Samper added that 1,300 hectares of coca plants had also been razed -- twice as much as in 
all of 1993. In a later statement to Time Magazine, Samper said that &#147;the dismantling of 
Colombia's cartels&#148; can only be achieved &#147;with an integral strategy supported by a 
commitment from the international community to attack money laundering, cocaine 
consumption and trafficking in precursor chemicals used in narcotics manufacture.&#148; A senior 
Colombian government official added that U.S. insistence on an uncompromising policy of 
suppression would &#147;get us into another war with the narcos and leave us holding the bag. The 
gringos only want to punish narco-trafficking, not eradicate it.&#148; </p>
<p>The Colombians insist they cannot fight an all-out war against the cartels, let alone win it. 
Defense Minister Fernando Botero Zea claims that the battle against cocaine is eating up 
$250 million of his $1.7 billion annual budget -- while the Cali cartel pulls in $700 million 
to $2 billion a year. &#147;The most amazing aspect of the cartel,&#148; he says, &#147;is its intelligence 
capability.&#148; Indeed, Colombian drug bosses have erected a sophisticated telecommunications 
system which allows them to tap into police operations. In Cali alone, they are said to be 
employing as informants 1,500 taxi drivers, 1,500 street vendors, and an equal number of 
private security guards. </p>
<p>The difficulties inherent in surveillance, and the traffickers' ability to intimidate or buy off 
prosecutors, judges, witnesses, and jurors makes effective prosecution and indictment of the 
cartel virtually impossible. Thus there is only one drug-trafficking charge outstanding against 
the world's leading cocaine traffickers, brothers Gilberto and Miguel Rodriguez Orejuela. 
Gilberto is charged with &#147;illegal enrichment&#148; and alleged assassination of Medellin drug 
czar, Pablo Escobar. Miguel is accused of running cocaine through Costa Rica. </p>
<p>The Rodriguezes, who are thought to be controlling 70 percent of the world's cocaine market, 
are also wanted in the U.S. There are at least five indictments against Gilberto -- two in 
Miami and one each in New York City, New Orleans, and Los Angeles -- and three 
indictments against Miguel. The pair is also charged with running a &#147;continuing criminal 
enterprise,&#148; a felony that carries a life sentence. None of these charges has resulted in 
prosecutions in Colombia. First, U.S. prosecutors do not trust the office of Colombia's 
Prosecutor-General; they have stopped sharing information with it. Second, rules of evidence 
in Colombian courts are more stringent than in the U.S., especially on conspiracy charges. 
Bogota's willingness to consider a widely publicized offer by the Rodriguez brothers to 
surrender in exchange for slap-on-the-wrist punishment is based on the assertion by a senior 
government official that Colombia no longer leads the world's cocaine trade but that Brazil, 
Costa Rica, Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico, and Venezuela are taking over more and more of 
the activity. This explanation is widely seen as an attempt to divert attention from the 
continuing influence Colombian drug bosses command in these countries. </p>
<p>What happened to a $200 million wholesale cocaine shipment on the morning of August 4 on 
an airstrip near the old mining town of Sombrete tells the story of the official corruption 
gripping Mexico, a country that has become the main conduit for U.S.-bound Colombian 
cocaine. According to confidential reports, Mexican federal police officers stole part of a 
10-ton cocaine shipment from a plane originating in Colombia, possibly with the assent or 
collusion of some highway patrols. Despite considerable evidence of wrongdoing, appeals 
for action from some Mexican officials and pressure from the U.S., a federal investigation 
turned up nothing, and the case was officially closed last month. </p>
<p>After six years under former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari in which heightened 
Mexican drug enforcement helped defuse worsening relations with the U.S., the issue has 
reemerged as one of the most contentious areas of relations between the two countries. U.S. 
officials now say that while the partnership between the two countries has grown closer 
under the NAFTA aegis, the traffickers' influence over Mexican law enforcement agencies 
has grown and the flow of cocaine through Mexico has steadily risen. Testifying in March 
before a U.S. congressional subcommittee, the senior State Department narcotics expert, 
Robert S. Gelbard said U.S officials &#147;had always been aware of the corruption of Mexican 
law enforcement agencies.&#148; </p>
<p>Emerging details in the Sombrete affair make Gelbard's assessment, direct and unambiguous 
as it is, something of an understatement. Most of the officials involved in the case either 
remain on the job or have been moved to more desirable posts. The two prominent 
exceptions are the man responsible for the initial investigation, Jorge Stergios, a former 
inspector general in the Attorney General's staff, and Mario Ruiz Massieu, the Deputy 
Attorney General who was his direct boss. Ruiz Massieu was recently charged with trying to 
cover up the role of Salinas's elder brother, Raul Salinas de Gortari, in the slaying of Ruiz 
Massieu's own elder brother, Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu. Raul Salinas was jailed in 
February 1995 on charges of ordering the assassination. </p>
<p>Investigators also reveal they are trying to determine the source of almost $10 million that 
Mario Ruiz Massieu deposited last year in bank accounts in Houston and Mexico City. 
Though many gaps in the Sombrete case still remain, evidence suggests that the partnership 
between traffickers and the police could not have existed without the knowledge and 
complicity of senior Mexican [government] officials. Blaming his country's ineffectual justice 
system on &#147;deep cultural and historical roots,&#148; and conceding the existence of a conspiracy 
between police and drug kingpins, Mexico's President Ernesto Zedillo, recently admitted 
being &#147;worried&#148; that government officials may also be involved. </p>
<p>If Colombia is the world's undisputed cocaine-producing champion, Guatemala is its 
top-ranking middleperson. According to the DEA and the U.S. State Department's 
International Narcotics Matters Bureau (INMB), Guatemala transships between 60-80 metric 
tons annually to the U.S. -- roughly two-thirds of all the cocaine entering the U.S. -- via 
Mexico. The DEA has also uncovered evidence of government corruption and scores of 
military officers have been implicated in audacious drug-smuggling operations. One of them, 
General Carlos Pozuelos Villavicencio, a former air force commander, used military aircraft 
to transport cocaine. Another is Army Lt. Colonel Carlos Ochoa Ruiz who, with the help of 
two captains, was caught on tape by DEA agents loading half a ton of cocaine worth $75 
million wholesale on board a private plane. The plane landed in Tampa, where Ochoa was 
indicted in absentia by a U.S. grand jury. Since 1990, Guatemala has systematically denied 
the State Deptartment's request for Ochoa's extradition on the grounds that it lacked evidence. 
One Guatemalan judge who took the evidence seriously, fought to reopen the case and 
lobbied for Ochoa's extradition -- Epaminondas Gonzalez Dubon, the Constitutional Court 
chief who declared then-president Jorge Serrano's &#147;self-coup&#148; unconstitutional -- was 
murdered last year in front of his wife and son. </p>
<p>In February, the Constitutional Court denied the extradition of another Guatemalan, 
multimillionaire businessperson Roberto Antonio Beltranena Bufalino -- Ochoa's 
co-defendant in the Tampa indictment. Also in February, long-simmering rumors gave way to 
direct accusations that Guatemalan Defense Ministry Chief of Staff, Col. Jose Fernandez 
Ligorra, and a number of other officers had engaged in drug trafficking, car theft and murder. 
Angrily calling the charges &#147;an attempt to blacken the military's reputation, Col. Fernandez 
threatened to sue and asked the U.S. Embassy to investigate. The Embassy politely declined 
the colonel's request. Other key figures implicated in the Fernandez case include Col. Otto 
Morn Carranza, in charge of airport security during the Cerezo regime -- fired but never 
prosecuted; Jose Domingo Enriquez, director general of Customs and brother of Defense 
Minister Enriquez; and Miguel Fernandez Ligorra, a police commissioner and brother of the 
accused chief of staff. </p>
<p>It is barely two years old, but the $10 million Grand Cayman radar station which tracks 
drug-carrying planes and ships in the Caribbean, and shares data with units surveilling 
Central America's Atlantic coastline will shut down on June 1. U.S. Air Force spokesperson 
Maj. David Thurston said the closure is due in part to &#147;budget cuts at the Pentagon and to a 
&#147;strategy reorganization&#148; of the Caribbean Basin Radar Network (CBRN). He added that five 
other stations would close by October 1, leaving 12 operational sites in the Caribbean. He 
declined to identify which countries would continue to operate CBRN facilities and which 
would close on grounds of &#147;official security.&#148; The network maintains stations in Jamaica, 
Honduras, Mexico, Panama, and the &#147;Western Caribbean.&#148; </p>
<p>With fresh evidence suggesting that Costa Rica continues to be used as a benevolent land 
bridge by none other than Miguel Angel Rodriguez Orejuela's local partners, abandonment of 
a state-of-the-art radar system donated to Costa Rica by the U.S. will further weaken what the 
DEA says is an already severe emasculation of its regional interdiction efforts. DEA agents 
and State Department specialists interviewed by this writer paint a bleak picture of Central 
America, a region described as &#147;awash in drugs and narco dollars willingly laundered by an 
ever-increasing number of banks.&#148; </p>
<p>Central America is a region rocked by political chaos, plagued by economic decay, and 
convulsed by violence. Military governments and puppet regimes continue to thwart efforts at 
democratization by intimidation. Gross inequalities in wealth and status (fewer than 10 
percent of the people own and control more than 90 percent of national resources), 
unfavorable currency exchange rates and mounting trade deficits have further weakened 
faltering economies by increasing unemployment, freezing wages and unleashing unforgiving 
rates of inflation. Under the circumstances, observers agree, chances of winning the war 
against a scourge from which elites continue to profit while corrupt judicial systems turn a 
blind eye, are nil. </p>
<p><em>A Connecticut-based journalist, W.E. Gutman is currently on assignment in Latin America. </em></p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

