<head>
<title>Feb 96: Lusane; Mobilized, Marching, and Mad</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>From the pages of February 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="feb96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>&#160;Mobilized, Marching, and Mad </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By Clarence Lusane </strong></em></h2>
<p>In 1995, the anti-black Republican Contract With America set the political context for fairly 
dramatic changes in black political activism. Interpreted by many as a sign of the failed 
politics of liberalism, black and white, black nationalist rhetoric and behavior grew 
substantially. Racial polarization, most egregiously displayed around the OJ verdict, moved 
even many pro-integrationist black leaders to give a nod to the impulse of black nationalism. 
While some black leaders played musical chairs, angry black men and women took to the 
streets, the floor of Congress, campuses, and their communities to declare opposition to the 
conservative and openly racist atmosphere. </p>
<p>Two unexpected developments dominated black politics last year: the highly successful 
October 16 Million Man March and the possible entry of retired General Colin Powell into 
the 1996 presidential race. Both of these occurrences indicate a strong rejection of black 
politics as usual. </p>
<p>Black nationalists, for the first time in a generation, were able to mobilize a significant sector 
of the black community around a number of issues, most notably the campaign to save 
journalist and activist Mumia Abu Jamal and the Million Man March (MMM). A global 
mobilization was galvanized in the case of Jamal and helped to highlight the continuing issue 
of police harassment and judicial racism. </p>
<p>About a million words have been written about the MMM. Politically, it signaled the surge of 
nationalist leadership and the mobilization capabilities of charismatic leaders such as the 
Nation of Islam's Louis Farrakhan. Whether this position is fleeting remains to be seen, but 
the event placed Farrakhan, Ben Chavis, and a number of other previously ostracized 
activists in a more central role in the debate over the direction and ideology of black politics. 
At this juncture, the MMM movement lacks strategic direction and the National African 
American Leadership Summit, under the controversial and increasing embattled leadership of 
Chavis, is desperately searching for its political footing. Reportedly, a number of local 
activists have used the MMM as a springboard for renewed community organizing. </p>
<p>The Powell for President effort provided a convenient alternative to the rhetoric fires of 
Farrakhan and Rev. Jesse Jackson. Powell teased the political establishment, the post-OJ 
media cartels, and some in the black community down to the last second before he declared 
that he was not a candidate (and that he was a Republican). His potential candidacy vastly 
overshadowed the anemic campaigns of two real declared black Republican presidential 
candidates: the perpetually running and unsuccessful Alan Keyes and former Nixon official 
Arthur Fletcher. </p>
<p>The past year was awash with retreats and setbacks for traditional black political leaders. 
The Congressional Black Caucus, after being blasted by the Newt-tron bomb, had a troubled 
year to say the least. </p>
<p>Although it was able to keep Clinton's feet to the fire around affirmative action, it was unable 
to save the nomination of Dr. HenryFoster for Surgeon General or halt the legislative 
blitzkrieg of the Republicans in Congress. The embarrassing resignations and convictions of 
Reps. Mel Reynolds (D-IL) and Walter Tucker (D-CA) on charges of child molestation and 
taking a bribe respectfully were low points for the CBC to be sure. Two black members ran 
for governor of Louisiana -- Reps. William Jefferson (D-LA) and Cleo Fields (D-LA) -- and 
both lost badly. </p>
<p>There were also defeats in the Supreme Court on several redistricting cases thus forcing 
Fields, Rep. Cynthia McKinney (D-GA), and other black Representatives to at least 
contemplate dusting off their resumes. The CBC is also losing a couple of veteran members. 
Rep. Cardiss Collins (D-IL), a House member for over two decades, has announced her 
retirement. In December, black political observers were shocked to hear Rep. Kweisi Mfume 
(D-MD) announce that he was leaving Congress in February to begin his job as the new 
President and CEO of the NAACP. </p>
<p>Questions have arisen of why Mfume would leave a rather comfortable position on Capitol 
Hill for the uncertain and difficult task he faces, along with Board Chair Myrlie 
Evers-Williams, in trying to remold the NAACP. He had received mainly cheers for his 
tenure as CBC chair during the 103rd Congress and many had hoped that he would break 
precedent and run for the office again. Many CBC members and others still look to Mfume 
for leadership before the current less charismatic chair Rep. Donald Payne (D-NJ). Prior to 
the Gingrich coup d'etat, Mfume even saw the possibility of becoming the first African 
American Speaker of the House. </p>
<p>Actually, it is not that hard to see why Mfume may no longer see Congress as the political 
arena of choice. Black Representatives are marginalized and Mfume, in particular, has to 
have felt a freefall of authority and influence from two years ago when he led the CBC. On 
the personal side, the position pays more than $200,000 and frees Mfume from the 
money-making restrictions that Congressmembers now face. It will also allow him to accept 
positions on corporate boards that he is currently prevented from doing. </p>
<p>It is also easy to see why the NAACP would select Mfume. The well-respected 
Congressperson brings stature, street smarts, and rich political experience to the job. He is 
only 47-years-old, which makes him relatively young by NAACP standards, and apparently 
still has the energy to wrestle with the work ahead that everyone acknowledges will be 
difficult. </p>
<p>Already Mfume has yielded a promise from Evers-Williams that an effort will be launched to 
restructure the board to make it smaller and more manageable. In addition, the title of the 
former executive director position has been changed to reflect the new duties and vision that 
Evers-Williams and others have for whoever will lead the NAACP into the next century. </p>
<p>The relationship of the NAACP to various black nationalist leaders, Louis Farrakhan to name 
the most obvious, may be tricky. Mfume got into hot water a couple of years ago with his 
CBC colleagues when, as chair of the CBC, he announced an &#147;understanding&#148; between the 
CBC and the Nation of Islam. Criticized by other black members, denounced by some Jewish 
leaders, and attacked in the press, Mfume moonwalked and created some space between 
himself and the Nation of Islam. </p>
<p>However, Mfume was perhaps the most visible black Congressmember involved with the 
NOI-initiated Million Man March. He spoke at the event and has committed himself to 
participating in post-Million Man March activities. While the NAACP did not endorse the 
MMM, many of its leaders and members enthusiastically participated. </p>
<p>To move the NAACP forward will take more than just the will and skills of Mfume. 
Restructuring of the National Board of Directors, getting the financial house in order, and 
developing a coherent and relevant political program must all be at the top of Mfume's 
agenda. The 1996 elections will be a barometer of the political strength and direction of the 
NAACP under Mfume. A resurgent NAACP could have significant impact on black 
registration and turnout. A resurgent NAACP could be instrumental in efforts to defeat Newt 
Gingrich (R-GA) or Sen. Jesse Helms (R-NC), two contestable races that are highly 
symbolic of the conservative racial mood. Finally, a resurgent NAACP could reshape black 
politics and give it a strategic direction that is sorely missing at the moment. </p>
<p>Then there is Jesse Jackson. In November, Jackson held a press conference and announced 
that he was heading back to Chicago to retake his former position as head of operation 
PUSH, the organization he abandoned to launch his National Rainbow Coalition (NRC). 
Although Jackson was elected &#147;Shadow&#148; Senator in Washington in 1990, the position carries 
no authority, is not funded, and remains an obscure political post to most people in DC. As 
the city went down the toilet under the iron rule of a congressionally-appointed financial 
control board and token leadership of D.C. Mayor Marion Barry, Jackson was harder to spot 
than Waldo. </p>
<p>On the other hand, the move to Chicago seems to be calculated along several lines. First, 
Jackson wants to capitalize on the political base that his son, Rep. Jesse Jackson, Jr. (D-IL), 
recently acquired when he won the congressional seat vacated by Reynolds. Second, the 
upcoming Democratic National Convention will be in Chicago and Jackson will be 
positioned to play a visible role. Third, it is also no accident that Chicago happens to be 
Farrakhan's homebase. Finally, the word is that Jackson is also interested in running for the 
Senate seat currently held by Sen. Carol Moseley Braun. Should she decide not to seek 
re-election or if her performance continues to be, shall we say, less than spectacular then a 
Jackson entry is not out of the question. </p>
<p>If liberalism has not completely died in the black community, it is certainly on its last leg. 
Into this vacuum will step a long line of would-be leaders. However, the emergence of a 
sustained movement will require more than long speeches and kente-draped stages. 
Mobilization, which is imperative, must be accompanied by an understanding and strategic 
approach that recognizes the post-Cold War, globalized economy that shapes the life of the 
nation including the black community. </p>
<p><em>Clarence Lusane teaches political science at Howard University</em>. </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

</html>
