<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>AFL-CIO Changes </h1>
<h2 align=center>By Laura McClure </h2>
<p>Labor leftists don't have Lane Kirkland to kick around anymore -- or his long-time sidekick 
Tom Donahue. These two people headed the nation's 13-million-member labor federation, 
the AFL-CIO, for 16 years. And what a gloomy 16 years it was, marked by a precipitous 
slide in unionization levels, workers' wages, and labor's political power. The duo was 
brought down by a faction of top union leaders who got tired of such low-watt leadership. 
The new AFL-CIO president, Service Employees International Union president John 
Sweeney, says he wants to revitalize the U.S. labor movement. His election does afford a 
glimmer of hope for the thousands of militants, dissidents, and nitty-gritty local organizers 
who have kept the labor movement on life support all these years. It's possible that the 
election of Sweeney and his slate will begin to bridge the huge chasm that has long separated 
these activists from top labor leaders. However, labor progressives, accustomed as they are 
to disappointment, aren't holding their breath. After all, Sweeney has been a compliant 
member of the AFL-CIO Executive Council for years, and he's no radical. He certainly 
wasn't progressives' first choice for president. Many would have preferred United Mine 
Workers president Richard Trumka for the job. Trumka, who ran on Sweeney's slate, has 
been elected instead to the number two slot in the AFL- CIO, secretary-treasurer. The third 
member of Sweeney's ticket, now AFL-CIO executive vice president Linda 
Chavez-Thompson, is not yet well known. </p>
<p>In the weeks since the AFL-CIO convention that elected Sweeney and company, the dust has 
yet to settle. Staffers at the AFL-CIO headquarters in Washington report that the transition has 
just begun. Meanwhile, the new leaders have been out and around. All three showed up for 
marches in Everett, Washington and Wichita, Kansas, on behalf of striking Boeing workers -- 
the kind of activism Lane Kirkland avoided. There was cause for both hope and cynicism at 
the AFL-CIO convention which took place at New York City's Sheraton Hotel October 
23-26. Refreshingly, there were no precedents, no protocols to follow, since it was the first 
ever contested election for AFL-CIO leadership. In the months leading up to the convention, 
both sides politicked heavily, debating and glad-handing in a way that was unheard of in the 
politburo-style elections of previous years. Sweeney's supporters, which included presidents 
of most of the federation's largest unions, were especially thorough. In particular, they 
lobbied the nation's neglected local labor bodies, the central labor councils and state 
federations, offering to help pay to get their delegates to New York. </p>
<p>Partly as a result, this convention included a rowdy crowd of 488 labor council delegates -- 
nearly three times the number that attended the last convention in 1993. Although their voting 
strength was small (union delegates vote the strength of their membership, while local labor 
bodies get only one vote apiece), they added to a sense that there were actually folks -- not 
just suits -- on the floor of the AFL-CIO convention. There was good-sounding rhetoric from 
both sides -- repeated pledges to put organizing at the center of labor's agenda and to actively 
promote leadership by women and people of color. Rank-and-file struggles, usually 
completely sidelined at AFL-CIO gatherings, got a bit of attention on the convention's final 
day, when workers from a number of labor struggles took the podium, and the new federation 
leaders marched downtown to a protest against sweatshops. </p>
<p>On the other hand, the AFL-CIO's stultifying internal culture was still in evidence. Too many 
white men in suits making too many sexist, off-color comments. At a pre-convention Sweeney 
bash, the spread of free food and alcohol was overwhelming. Unionists say that at previous 
AFL conventions, food and booze were usually a bigger draw than the proceedings. &#147;I don't 
know if the change will extend to that,&#148; concedes one federation staffer who supported 
Sweeney. &#147;I thought it might, but I sort of left that reception thinking -- so they're into that 
too.&#148; </p>
<p>The first weeks of Sweeney's tenure have produced no sweeping purges of federation staff, 
and only a handful of new appointments. More will probably come as Sweeney's transition 
committees emerge with plans to revamp the AFL-CIO's efforts at organizing, strategic 
campaigns, political strategy, education and training, and public affairs. If the new leaders 
are going to put the kind of resources they've promised into new organizing, cuts elsewhere 
are inevitable. &#147;There are a lot of departments at the AFL-CIO, and I'm really not sure what 
all of them do,&#148; confesses one union staffer. A federation staffer also hints that there's fat to 
be cut: &#147;There are a lot of anxieties and fears around here. Those who need to feel anxious 
and fearful know who they are. They ought to feel anxious and fearful.&#148; </p>
<p>During the campaign, Sweeney pledged to create a new organizing department and to 
quintuple funding for this work. Funding for the federation's Organizing Institute, which trains 
organizers and sends them out to unions around the country, will also increase dramatically. 
Sweeney says he plans to make next summer the &#147;organizing summer,&#148; recruiting 1,000 
college students to volunteer for a national organizing blitz. Most activists welcome the 
heightened commitment to organizing. &#147;I work as an organizer, so when people talk about 
more resources for organizing, I think, 'Oh, finally!'&#148; says Laura Gordon of the American 
Federation of State, County, and Municipal Employees Union in Asheville, NC. But Gordon, 
who attended the convention on behalf of her local central labor council, doesn't like the 
emphasis on getting college students and recent graduates to do the organizing. &#147;I don't blame 
the college students, they come in very idealistic, and their hearts are in the right place. But 
who's going to know how to organize better than someone who knows what it's like to punch 
a clock and to raise a family?&#148; She hopes the federation's new organizing efforts won't 
employ the kind of hit-and-run strategy of previous organizing blitzes. &#147;The South is sort of 
like one big small town,&#148; says Gordon. &#147;Stories travel and people have long memories. And 
there's been a whole history down here where people come in, they begin to realize how hard 
it is, they lose the union election, and then they leave, and the workers who supported the 
union are left holding the bag. And so unions have gotten a really bad name. They have to 
make a long-term commitment, they have to know it's not going to happen overnight, that 
they're going to lose elections. But they really have to plan on staying and backing up those 
people inside the plant who are really putting their jobs on the line to bring the union in. And 
they need to hire those people to do the organizing.&#148; Gordon also hopes the federation will 
do something to re-energize central labor councils like hers. &#147;Maybe there'll be some trickle 
down of resources. It's great to see that it's on the agenda.&#148; AFL-CIO executive vice 
president Linda Chavez-Thompson has been assigned to build stronger alliances between the 
local labor bodies and the federation, and to try to help local bodies become more effective 
in organizing and in political action. </p>
<p>For the most part, the AFL-CIO hasn't been very good at coming to the rescue of local 
unionists. It's an institution that has preferred instead to focus on closed-door lobbying on 
Capitol Hill and anti-Communist international politics. In fact, the AFL-CIO will never be 
workers' first line of defense: constituent unions and their affiliated locals have a more direct 
connection to workers. But sometimes, people need national, multi-union resources -- and 
when they do, the federation has generally let them down. </p>
<p>The need for such coordination and support is greater than ever. Labor's old ultimate tactic -- 
the strike -- is rarely ventured and rarely won these days. To win, or even to fight effectively, 
workers often have to come up with &#147;corporate campaigns&#148; or other strategic approaches, 
using publicity; direct action; links to the community, environmentalists and to workers 
nationally; or precisely executed in-plant tactics to force the employer's hand. The problem 
is, all these techniques require tremendous expertise and often multi-union strategizing. Only 
a handful of strategists in a few unions, and a couple of people in the AFL-CIO are prepared 
to conduct these kinds of campaigns. </p>
<p>Sweeney and friends have recognized this problem, and propose to create a &#147;Strategic Action 
Center&#148; inside the AFL-CIO to conduct special campaigns and train others to conduct them. 
All this may be too little too late for the people in Decatur, Illinois, where three nasty labor 
battles -- at Caterpillar, Staley Manufacturing, and Bridgestone-Firestone -- have been raging 
on and on. Workers in Decatur -- known as the &#147;war zone&#148; -- have been frustrated by the lack 
of support from the AFL-CIO. They've been dogging federation leaders for a year now, 
coming uninvited to closed gatherings of the federation's executive council in Florida. Dave 
Watts, president of the union local that represents workers at Staley, was part of a 
two-dozen-member delegation from Decatur that attended the AFL-CIO convention. Watts's 
members have been locked out for two years, and during this period he's had plenty of time to 
get angry about the state of the U.S. labor movement. &#147;Sweeney versus Donahue isn't the 
point for us,&#148; he says. &#147;I don't care who's at the helm as long as it's somebody who's a hell of 
a lot more progressive than who's been there the past 20 years. We cannot take another 
complacent decade and expect workers to have any confidence whatsoever in the labor 
movement. The workers out on the picket lines and at the burn barrels, they don't feel 
connected to the top of the house. If you pay dues for 25 years and then all of a sudden you've 
got a labor dispute that nobody can help you with, it makes you wonder.&#148; Watts has an axe to 
grind against union leaders who promote labor-management cooperation programs -- and 
almost all top union leaders do. For years, his members participated earnestly in partnership 
programs with Staley, only to be rewarded by a lockout. Donahue, under Lane Kirkland's 
administration, was labor's leading proponent of labor-management cooperation, even 
making it the centerpiece of his vision. Sweeney favors cooperative programs too, although 
he attaches more provisos about the need for a two-way relationship. </p>
<p>Watts is guarded about the new leadership: &#147;We've got no choice but to hope that they'll live 
up to some of the commitments they've made. But we're not going to idly sit by and let those 
commitments fade away.&#148; On November 4, Sweeney pledged to create a task force to 
coordinate the AFL's support for Staley workers and for strikers at the Detroit News and 
Free Press. But it took the near death of Staley hunger striker Dan Lane to exact that pledge. 
Baldemar Velasquez, president of the Ohio-based Farm Labor Organizing Committee, is also 
guarded about change at the top. &#147;We've been around for 28 years, and we've seen a lot of 
people come and go,&#148; he says. &#147;And the bottom line is, unless we have a campaign on our 
own that we're generating and that we're finding leadership for, nothing's going to happen -- 
no matter how progressive or liberal people at the top are.&#148; Velasquez is glad that Sweeney 
has been to United Farmworkers rallies in California, and that UFW president Arturo 
Rodriguez was elected to the new (and expanded) AFL-CIO leadership body, the executive 
council. &#147;As long as the issues of farmworkers are raised in the consciousness of the national 
labor leaders -- even if its just the UFW issues -- that's all right. So maybe when some noise 
is made somewhere else, they'll say -- `Oh. Farmworkers. We know what those are'.&#148; He 
adds: &#147;The more localized we are, the more chance we've got to put it to the test. Let's see 
how this translates at the bottom. Is this a trickle-down theory again that never gets to the 
bottom? Is this real or is this just a labor version of supply-side economics?&#148; Velasquez is 
irked by Sweeney's support for the Democratic Party and his lack of interest in the effort to 
build a U.S. labor party. For years, labor has offered unconditional support for the 
Democrats, and this is not likely to change under Sweeney. At the convention, Clinton's 
arrival was greeted with chants of &#147;Four more years!&#148; -- despite Clinton's many betrayals, 
beginning with his support of NAFTA. &#147;That's ominous,&#148; comments Velasquez. </p>
<p>Sweeney says he wants to be harder on Democrats who betray labor; in the past, unions 
haven't lived up to that threat. Sweeney's team plans to create a &#147;political training center&#148; to 
develop political campaign organizers and help affiliates lobby Democrats. They also want 
to establish a labor policy think tank inside the AFL-CIO. A former key supporter of Jobs 
with Justice, Steve Rosenthal, has been named as the federation's new political director. Jobs 
with Justice, a coalition of unions and community groups, has been on the activist edge of 
official labor politics for the past several years. As a staffer at the Communications Workers 
of America, Rosenthal supported JwJ's sit-ins and marches; he later became a deputy for 
Labor Secretary Robert Reich. </p>
<p>Velasquez argues that labor needs more leverage against the Democrats -- a labor party. &#147;The 
only thing they've got to trade off right now is at what level we are going to support the 
Democrats. And that's no bargaining position. Why should the Democrats care?&#148; Velasquez, 
who has worked hard to establish links with Mexican unions, is also passionate about the 
need to change the way U.S. labor relates to workers internationally. &#147;One thing Sweeney has 
to do if he's going to modernize the labor movement and get past the racism, the xenophobia, 
the provincialism of American labor -- he needs to make an all-out effort to really 
internationalize the labor movement. Instead of being spokespeople for the American foreign 
policy all over the world, promoting the cold war,&#148; Velasquez says, U.S. unions ought to 
begin to establish solid links with unions in Mexico to fight common employers. Sweeney has 
pledged to begin building stronger global links. </p>
<p>He plans to create a &#147;transnational corporate monitoring project&#148; as a source of information 
on global corporations. A Washington-based staffer of Sweeney's union, SEIU, says he 
believes Sweeney &#147;is looking at a post-Cold War labor solidarity approach.&#148; But Sweeney 
has been very noncommittal about the federation's Cold War apparatus, which still chugs 
away to this day. About $40 million in federal money is funneled each year to the AFL-CIO's 
quasi-independent institutes, like the infamous American Institute for Free Labor 
Development. These institutes have long helped support anti-Communist unions and political 
movements overseas. At the convention, Sweeney stated flatly that he had no intention of 
dismantling the institutes. A progressive federation staffer notes with concern that Sweeney 
has named no &#147;transition team&#148; to help recast the AFL's international affairs work. Perhaps, 
he conjectures, it's too much of a political hot potato. Progressive unionists -- cynics and 
optimists alike -- seem to have a common idea about how to proceed in this post-Kirkland 
AFL- CIO: Keep up the local organizing, and apply the pressure. </p>
<p>Bob Wages, president of the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers Union, was elected by 
convention delegates to the AFL-CIO's 51-member executive council. A leading proponent of 
Labor Party Advocates and an outspoken critic of AFL-CIO past practice, Wages is agnostic 
now. </p>
<p>&#147;I think the AFL-CIO can be a very powerful voice for working people,&#148; he says. &#147;I think the 
federation can be visionary, it can reshape itself, it can lead strategic initiatives against 
recalcitrant employers, against industry, against global capital...The question is, will it? I 
don't know.&#148; He adds: &#147;I hope my participation on the council will be meaningful -- I don't 
intend for it to be symbolic. I intend to keep doing what I'm doing and we'll see what 
happens.&#148; SEIU education director Bill Fletcher, a strong supporter of Sweeney, feels &#147;a 
great opening has been created.&#148; At a gathering of Black trade unionists in Milwaukee, he 
says, &#147;people wanted to know what kind of resources were going to go into different things. 
But people are very aware that it's going to be important -- as Sweeney himself said -- to 
keep the pressure on him. People should not sit back and say, `Okay, let's see what the AFL 
does.' Create your project, get the unions together, reach out to the community organizations, 
and then let's go to the AFL-CIO and say, okay, now we need some support for this. I think 
that would really make some difference.&#148; </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

</html>
