<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>from the pages of January 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="jan96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>&#160;Asset Forfeiture </h1>
<h2 align=center>By Susan Meeker-Lowry </h2>
<p>It's no secret that this country's declared war on drugs is one of the most corrupt, unjust, and 
racist travesties of our criminal &#147;justice&#148; system. The billions of dollars invested in this war 
have done little more than crowd the prisons. There are more drugs on the street than ever 
and the social and economic woes that lead to drug abuse are much worse. </p>
<p>Two of the most insidious aspects of the war on drugs (though by no means the only ones) are 
mandatory minimum sentences and the asset forfeiture of personal property (houses, cars, 
cash, businesses). Judges no longer have the ability to decide for themselves, based on the 
evidence and the unique aspects of each case, the amount of time a person will spend behind 
bars. Instead, x amount of drugs equals x number of years. There is some allowance for 
&#147;deviating&#148; from these &#147;sentencing guidelines&#148; but they are restrictive. The result is that 
murderers, rapists, and child abusers are often back on the street long before a first-time, 
non-violent drug offender. And drug offenders are not entitled to &#147;good time&#148; -- the time they 
get is the time they serve. To make matters worse, hearsay evidence is allowed. What this 
means is that if paid confidential informants say they saw a five pound bag of cocaine on the 
kitchen table, then that's the way it was. It doesn't matter whether there is substantiating 
evidence -- or even if there is evidence to the contrary. This is in sharp contrast to other 
crimes whose judgment requires conscientious attention to physical evidence and disallows 
hearsay &#147;evidence.&#148; </p>
<p>The fact is the majority of drug offenders in the prison system are basically small-time 
dealers. The big guys don't usually get caught and when they do, they are often able to get off. 
Sometimes they even end up on the Drug Enforcement Agency (DEA) or FBI payroll as 
highly paid informants. Ignored in the war on drugs is the reality that society (as well as the 
incarcerated non-violent drug offender) would most often be better served through treatment 
programs and job training combined with activism to change the social, political, and 
economic realities that lead people to turn to drugs in the first place. </p>
<p>Drug offenders in prison have very few sympathizers on the outside since the average person 
has generally bought into the government's scapegoating tactics. Rather than wondering 
whether justice is really served by all those years spent in prison, and the wasted lives they 
represent, people are apt to say, &#147;They knew what they were doing. They got what they 
deserve.&#148; The desire for retribution seems to overpower more appropriate responses such as 
compassion, understanding, and a desire for healing. </p>
<p>Further, as John Edgar Wideman stated in The Nation (&#147;Doing Time, Marking Race,&#148; 
10/30/95), &#147;In the guise of outrage at crime and criminals, hard-core racism (though it never 
left us) is making a strong, loud comeback. It's respectable to tar and feather criminals...It's 
not racist to be against crime, even though the archetypal criminal in the media and the public 
imagination almost always wears `Willie' Horton's face.... For many, the disproportionate 
number of blacks in prison is not a worrisome issue; the statistics simply fulfill racist 
prophecy and embody a rational solution to the problem of crime. Powerful evidence, 
however, suggests racism may condition and thereby determine where the war on drugs is 
waged most vigorously.&#148; Wideman then cites a recent study indicating that while 
African-Americans represent 13 percent of the population and 13 percent of those who are 
monthly drug users, they make up 35 percent of people arrested for possession, 55 percent of 
those convicted, and 74 percent of those who end up serving sentences for possession. </p>
<p>This is not to say many illegal drugs aren't dangerous. They are. It's important to remind 
ourselves that often the main difference between people in recovery and drug offenders in 
prison is luck -- or race or class. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>The Basics </h3>
<p>Forfeiture is the term referring to the government's seizing of property because of an alleged 
crime. There are two types of forfeiture procedures. Criminal forfeiture requires the 
defendant to be found guilty of the crime in criminal court before property can be seized. In 
these cases, legal representation is constitutionally guaranteed and the jury must find &#147;beyond 
a reasonable doubt&#148; that the property was integrally connected with the crime. Criminal 
forfeiture charges are brought at the same time as any other criminal charges, resulting in one 
case against the defendant. </p>
<p>Civil forfeiture, which is most commonly used these days, is an in rem (&#147;against the thing&#148;) 
procedure against &#147;guilty&#148; property rather than against the owner. As crazy as it seems, the 
property is arrested. Most of the protections afforded by the Constitution to individuals don't 
apply in civil forfeiture cases. When the government shows &#147;probable cause&#148; to initiate 
proceedings, &#147;innocent until proven guilty&#148; is reversed. David B. Smith, former Associate 
Director of the Department of Justice Asset Forfeiture Office concedes, &#147;the property owner 
generally has the burden of proof, the innocence of the owner is not a defense, rank hearsay is 
admissible.&#148; Since the forfeiture is a civil, not criminal proceeding the right to a jury trial is 
often denied plus defendants are not entitled to legal representation unless they can pay for it 
themselves (a difficult task since often the seized property is the defendant's only asset). 
Civil forfeiture cases are brought separately from any criminal charges, resulting in two 
cases against the defendant for the same offense. </p>
<p>Most people believe the official rhetoric -- that forfeiture is designed to confiscate the 
luxurious possessions of drug &#147;kingpins&#148; -- yachts, Cadillacs, planes, and second homes 
obtained through the proceeds of drug deals. It's hard to feel sympathy for major drug dealers, 
so forfeiture isn't given much thought. However, the public image has little to do with reality. 
According to the DEA's own database, 83 percent of the property seized from June 1989 to 
December 1990 was valued at less than $50,000 (usually much less). Moreover, the 
government needs very little evidence (some would say none) to justify confiscating 
property. The word of a paid informant, who may have personal reasons for wanting property 
seized (like being cut in on the take), is enough. In fact, there are numerous cases on the 
books where property was seized on suspicion of some kind of drug activity which was later 
proven to be false. Yet, the victims either had to fight in court to get their property back 
(which can take years), or worse, were unable to recover it at all despite their proven 
innocence. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>&#147;What a Long, Strange Trip It's Been&#148; </h3>
<p>The history of forfeiture dates back to the Anglo-Saxon period when it was the major means 
of tax enforcement; confiscating the estates of felons and traitors added substantially to the 
English Crown's coffers. </p>
<p>Modern forfeiture statutes are often traced to the mid-17th century English Navigation Acts 
which required most goods to be shipped in English vessels and considered the owner of a 
ship liable for the actions of the crew, regardless of whether he was aware of them or not. 
This law also invested objects (in this case, ships) with personal responsibility. Because the 
English Crown imposed forfeiture on American colonists through the colonies' vice 
Admiralty Courts, it was prohibited in the Constitution -- except for ships and cargo in 
violation of customs laws. </p>
<p>But after the outbreak of the Civil War, the Confiscation Act of July 17, 1862 was passed 
giving the government power to confiscate the property of Southern rebels and their 
sympathizers. Even though the Act was passed, it was considered controversial by some, one 
Senator predicting that it would bring about &#147;a total revolution in our criminal jurisprudence, 
and in spite of all the safeguards of the Constitution, proceedings in personam for the 
punishment of crime may be totally ignored, and punishment [will be] inflicted by proceeding 
against property alone.&#148; The State Supreme Court of Kentucky declared the Act 
unconstitutional stating, &#147;These proceedings may today be engines of punishment to the 
rebels, but, in the future, they may be the instruments of oppression, injustice, and tyranny...&#148; 
Despite the controversy, the Supreme Court (in three separate cases) determined the law 
constitutional and &#147;legitimate, unless applied to others than enemies.&#148; </p>
<p>Forfeiture law was expanded again during the Prohibition era when the Supreme Court 
decided property itself could be declared guilty and seized if it was used for the production 
or distribution of alcoholic beverages. </p>
<p>In the 1980s, civil asset forfeiture was fully embraced by Congress as a weapon in the war 
on drugs. The Comprehensive Crime Control Act of 1984 and the Drug Abuse Act of 1986 
effectively allow punishment to be inflicted with total disregard for Constitutional 
protections. Today there are over 100 different federal forfeiture statutes. Numerous federal 
agencies have statutory forfeiture authority, including the DEA, FBI, Coast Guard, Postal 
Service, Bureau of Land Management, Fish &amp; Wildlife, Securities &amp; Exchange Commission, 
Food &amp; Drug Administration, Immigrant Naturalization Service, Dept. of Housing and Urban 
Development, and the IRS. More than 3,000 state and local police departments exercise 
forfeiture powers. </p>
<p>So far the majority of civil forfeiture cases involve the alleged use or sale of drugs. 
However, forfeiture for other crimes is rapidly increasing. In California, being caught driving 
with a suspended license forfeits the car. In New Jersey, forfeiture can be triggered by any 
alleged crime, even shoplifting and minor theft. For example, Kathy Schrama was accused of 
stealing UPS packages worth about $500 from her neighbors' doorsteps. She pled guilty and 
paid a $5,000 fine. While most would consider this appropriate punishment, the local police 
also confiscated her home, two cars, furniture, even the Christmas presents she had bought 
for her son. (The property was eventually returned, but not without a struggle.) </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>The Abuse of Forfeiture </h3>
<p>Civil forfeiture is a fertile breeding ground for various and sundry abuses. Property is often 
seized before any charges are brought; even if no crime was actually committed the property 
is not automatically returned, instead the owner has to fight for it; since drug enforcement 
agencies and local police departments get to keep the lion's share of the proceeds from the 
sale of forfeited property, there is a strong incentive to take first, ask questions later; and 
finally informants receive a percentage of the take. </p>
<p>Before the Comprehensive Crime Control Act of 1984, money from federal civil forfeitures 
went into the general fund of the U.S. Treasury. Now it is deposited into the Justice 
Department's Asset Forfeiture Fund or the Treasury Department's Forfeiture Fund to be spent 
with little or no oversight by the same authorities who confiscated it. In 1985, one year after 
the Crime Control Act went into effect, $27 million was deposited in the Deptartment of 
Justice's Fund. Every year since 1989, deposits have exceeded $500 million (except for 
1990, which was slightly less). </p>
<p>While law enforcement officials make a big deal out of the occasional large drug bust, the 
majority are relatively small-time dealers or users who do not have lots of valuable personal 
property. This means that lots of property must be confiscated to add up to the big bucks 
involved. For example, in Michigan in 1992 civil asset forfeiture was used in 9,770 
instances netting, on average, only $1,434 in each case. Fifty-four private homes were taken 
with an average value of $15,881 and 807 cars worth $1,412 on average. No police 
department (out of 123 reporting) gave any evidence of convictions associated with the 
seizures. </p>
<p>Officers at the state and local level also get to keep much of the assets they seize which 
provides quite an incentive to &#147;structure arrests&#148; by setting up stings in valuable places rather 
than on a back road somewhere. (Although in practice homes, cars, etc. are seized even when 
drugs are not found in them -- all it takes is the statement of one informant to connect the 
property with drugs and it's gone.) </p>
<p>Brenda Grantland, a defense attorney specializing in forfeiture and President of FEAR 
(Forfeiture Endangers American Rights, a national organization committed to the reform of 
forfeiture laws and assisting in the defense of forfeiture's victims), states, &#147;[Allowing law 
enforcement officials to keep the proceeds of forfeiture] began the war on the private 
property of innocent Americans -- not just the &#147;proceeds of crime&#148; or the assets of convicted 
criminals. Armed with statutory authorization...and with no legislative oversight over how 
they spent it, the popularity of asset forfeiture immediately skyrocketed. This provision not 
only gave the police the power to terrorize innocent citizens -- it also allowed the police to 
finance their own new police state out of the property they seized.&#148; </p>
<p>Law enforcement agencies at all levels are addicted to the funds brought in by forfeiture to 
supplement their budgets. A July 1990 U.S. Department of Justice bulletin sent to all U.S. 
attorneys entreats them to &#147;significantly increase forfeiture production to reach our budget 
target. Failure to achieve the $470 million projection would expose the Department's 
forfeiture program to criticism and undermine confidence in our budget predictions. Every 
effort must be made to increase forfeiture income in the three remaining months of fiscal year 
1990.&#148; Further, Acting Assistant Attorney General Edward Dennis, Jr., advised all U.S. 
attorneys &#147;to divert personnel from other activities,&#148; including criminal cases, to prepare all 
forfeiture cases for judicial action. </p>
<p>In 1992, the Committee on Public Safety of the California State Assembly had this to say 
about forfeiture in that state, &#147;Asset forfeiture is a multi-million dollar source of revenue for 
law enforcement. Thus, there is an incentive to seize property as a revenue source.... 
[P]ersons suspected of participation in or having knowledge of drug crimes rarely will be 
given the benefit of the doubt by those who will gain financially by the seizure. This is 
viewed as a particular problem in times of tight budgets.&#148; </p>
<p>Since the 1980s, forfeiture has delivered billions of dollars worth of property to prosecutors 
and police. In 1990, 1992, and again in 1995, the General Accounting Office (GAO) 
identified asset forfeiture as among the top ten programs that run a high risk of waste, fraud, 
abuse, and mismanagement. An article in the National Review (2/20/95) notes nine studies 
by the GAO in ten years that &#147;have shown that forfeited property not used or sold by police is 
usually trashed or stolen -- often by the police. A former Los Angeles County deputy sheriff 
testified in 1993 that narcotics-squad officers stole $60 million in forfeited cash and property 
in 1988-89. In 1994 a special commission reported a similar pattern of activity by New York 
City police officers.&#148; </p>
<p>Still, the public remains generally unconcerned about forfeiture abuses. As a criminal 
defense lawyer from Somerset County New Jersey commented, &#147;If you are tainted with drug 
use, even the `weekend warrior' kind of recreational use, no one seems to get upset if 
[officials] grab your home and business and claim it's all tainted by drug money.&#148; </p>
<p>Not every victim is involved in drugs, or any other crime, as the murder of 61-year-old 
retired millionaire Donald Scott illustrates. In October 1992, he and his wife Frances were 
asleep in their home in the Santa Monica mountains when a 27-person police task force 
stormed through the front door of their house. Scott, hearing his wife crying, &#147;Don't shoot 
me!&#148; grabbed his gun and rushed to the top of the stairs. While lowering the gun after being 
ordered to do so, he was shot to death by Gary Spencer, the LA County deputy sheriff who 
led the raid. Spencer had received what turned out to be a false tip that the Scotts were 
growing marijuana on their ranch. The subsequent investigation revealed that the raid was, in 
part, an attempted land grab. The police hoped to sell the land to the National Park Service 
which had repeatedly tried to purchase the land to add to the Santa Monica Mountains 
National Recreation Area. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Informants are Everywhere </h3>
<p>In 1990, the Asset Forfeiture fund of the U.S. Justice Department paid $24 million to 
informants. If you travel by plane, train, or bus you have most likely run into an informant or 
two whether you knew it or not. A series of articles published in the Pittsburgh Press in 
August 1991 on asset forfeiture stated, &#147;At 16 major airports, drug agents, counter and 
baggage personnel, and management reveal an underground economy running off seizures and 
forfeitures. All but one of the airports' drug interdiction teams reward private employees who 
pass along reports about suspicious activity. Typically, they get about 10 percent of the value 
of whatever is found.&#148; Police and airport management say using airport personnel as 
informants provides a &#147;public service,&#148; but the lure of high paybacks is very attractive to 
someone working a low paying job. In general, informants can legally be paid up to 25 
percent of the proceeds (not to exceed $250,000 in each case) if their tips result in a 
forfeiture (not a conviction -- a forfeiture). </p>
<p>Yet it's not private citizen informants who receive the lion's share of kickbacks; it's the 
professional informant. The most highly paid are convicted drug dealers and self-confessed 
users. These people have made deals with law enforcement that keep them above prosecution 
and that pay handsomely. Their contacts and insider knowledge are invaluable to the DEA 
and FBI and their tactics involve setting people up in operations like reverse stings where 
agents pose as dealers. Cash is always involved in stings like this, and informants always get 
their share. What's more, the informant's identity is protected -- they don't even have to testify 
in court. </p>
<p>A 10-month Pittsburgh Press investigation of drug seizure and forfeiture included an 
examination of court records on 121 &#147;drug courier&#148; stops where money was seized but no 
drugs were found. Black, Latino, and Asian people accounted for 77 percent of the cases. 
The Pittsburgh Press also reported that in Memphis, Tennessee in 1989, drug officers 
testified that about 75 percent of the people they stopped in the airport were black, yet figures 
from the Air Transport Association show only 4 percent of the flying public that year was 
black. In Eagle County, Colorado a class-action suit charged that race was the main element 
of the profile used in drug stops on the 60 mile-long strip of Interstate 70 that winds its way 
past Vail and other ski areas. Five hundred people, primarily Latino and black motorists, 
were stopped and searched during 1989 and 1990. </p>
<p>Willie Jones, an African-American and owner of a landscaping service in Tennessee, paid 
cash for a round-trip plane ticket to Houston where he planned to purchase plants and 
shrubbery from growers there -- a trip he takes twice a year. The ticket agent decided paying 
cash for his ticket was &#147;suspicious behavior&#148; and alerted the Nashville police, who promptly 
searched Jones and his luggage. No drugs were found, however the money he planned to use 
to buy plants for his business ($9,600) was promptly seized because a drug-sniffing dog 
detected traces of drugs on the bills. Jones was not arrested, but it took him two years to get 
his money back by suing the DEA for discrimination based on race. </p>
<p>In Buffalo, New York, Juana Lopez, a dark-skinned Dominican was stopped and searched 
after getting off a bus from New York City. The DEA agent found $4,750 in cash, but no 
drugs. Even though Lopez had receipts showing the money was legally obtained, and could 
prove she was taking the money to be used to pay legal fees for her common-law husband, the 
money was seized because a drug dog reacted to it. </p>
<p>Former New York Giants center Kevin Belcher was stopped and searched after a security 
officer spotted &#147;a big, black man carrying a large amount of money in his jacket pocket.&#148; 
Belcher planned to purchase some classic old cars at an auction and had to pay for them in 
cash. Again, a drug dog reacted to the money, so it was seized. </p>
<p>But drug tainted money is the rule rather than the exception these days. Scientists at 
Toxicology Consultants in Miami tested currency over a seven-year period in numerous U.S. 
cities and London and found an average of 96 percent of U.S. currency tests positive for 
cocaine. Similarly, scientists at National Medical Services in Willow Grove, Pennsylvania 
tested money from banks and other legal sources and consistently found cocaine on 80 
percent of the bills. And marijuana's smell is so long-lasting dogs can detect it on clothing 
and in cars or containers months after it has been removed. Results of credible tests like 
these are making their way into the courts. In November 1994 the U.S. Court of Appeals for 
the Ninth Circuit, hearing a case involving $30,060 seized in Los Angeles, set a precedent by 
stating that &#147;the probative value of a positive dog alert in currency forfeiture cases...is 
significantly diminished and the continued reliance of courts and law enforcement officers on 
[such an alert] to separate legitimate currency from drug-connected currency is logically 
indefensible.&#148; </p>
<p>By far the most innocent victims of forfeiture are the children. Officials give little thought to 
the price children pay when adding up the profits of forfeiture. Roger Guevara, a 
spokesperson for the FDA, said it was not known how many children had been affected by 
forfeitures. It isn't part of the equation. Helen Toor, Head of Civil Division, U.S. Attorney's 
Office stated in a phone conversation in 1991 that children are not recognized by her office 
as having legal rights to the homes in which they live. The U.S. Attorney's Office &#147;looks at 
the children in the home&#148; but they don't have funds to do investigations on the effect of their 
decisions on children. In fact, a major difficulty in considering the damage to the children is 
they &#147;don't know how to value it&#148; when they have no &#147;guidance from the law.&#148; </p>
<p>When Scott and Patricia Manning were faced with both prison sentences and the loss of their 
Vermont home, some had very little sympathy for their efforts to keep their four children 
together in the only home they had ever known. Their response when asked, &#147;But what about 
the children?&#148; was &#147;Well, they should have thought about that before they got involved with 
drugs.&#148; </p>
<p>Fighting negative public opinion, the Mannings persisted in bringing their concerns to the 
press and their legislators. Their efforts were instrumental in raising awareness of the plight 
of child victims of forfeiture, and resulted in a debate on the rights of children in such cases, 
as well as front-page coverage in Vermont papers and on TV, and a piece in the New York 
Times law section, picture and all (&#147;When a Forfeiture Means Uprooting the Innocent,&#148; 
5/15/92). In this article, Jessica, the Manning's oldest child, then 15 said, &#147;I haven't done 
anything for the past two years. I can't go on vacation because I don't want to come back and 
find the house boarded up. My parents should serve time for what they did, but the 
government shouldn't take our house. I've lived here since I was three. It's punishing us kids a 
lot.&#148; (In this case, the Manning's two oldest children were actually part owners of their home 
under the terms of a divorce settlement between Patricia and their father -- a fact the 
government wished to ignore). </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Constitutional Violations </h3>
<p>Even though civil forfeiture would appear to violate the double jeopardy clause of the Fifth 
Amendment and would seem to constitute the &#147;excessive fines&#148; prohibited by the Eighth 
Amendment, it is only within the past year that courts have begun to recognize and uphold 
these basic constitutional rights. Despite years of fighting forfeiture cases on constitutional 
grounds, it wasn't until September 1994 that a court finally gave a defendant relief based on 
double jeopardy in a civil forfeiture case. </p>
<p>In this case, known as &#147;405K,&#148; the defendants were subjected to two simultaneous 
proceedings (which is how it goes) -- a civil forfeiture and a criminal prosecution. After 
conviction and sentencing, the government moved for summary judgment (a ruling in the 
government's favor without a trial) in the forfeiture case, which was granted. The defendants 
appealed -- and eventually prevailed -- arguing that since they were serving prison sentences 
they were already being punished for their crime. The court stated, &#147;The most basic element 
of the Double Jeopardy Clause is the protection it affords against successive prosecution -- 
that is, against efforts to impose punishment for the same offense in two or more separate 
proceedings...A decade ago, the law was clear that civil forfeitures did not constitute 
`punishment' for double jeopardy purposes...However, as sometimes happens, the Court 
changed its collective mind.&#148; </p>
<p>This landmark case opens the door for other forfeiture victims to either get back their 
property or get out of jail. The Ninth Circuit case was followed by a victory in the Sixth 
Circuit and a partial victory in the Third. Currently, all three of these cases are pending in the 
Supreme Court. Recently in Vermont, Judge Franklin Billings reversed his own decision 
made three years ago by ruling that since a drug offender had already lost his property, 
sending him to prison constitutes double jeopardy. </p>
<p>While some lament that drug offenders could go free on a &#147;silly technicality,&#148; as Brenda 
Grantland explains, &#147;prosecutors have a choice which lets them forfeit assets and criminally 
prosecute at the same time, in the same case -- criminal forfeiture.... But they preferred civil 
forfeiture procedures -- which gave them unbelievable advantages over criminal defendants. 
Now they're complaining because their shortcut to due process backfired.&#148; </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Strange Bedfellows? </h3>
<p>Forfeiture victims and their supporters have found a friend in U.S. Representative Henry 
Hyde (R-IL) who, in June 1995, introduced his Forfeiture Reform Bill (HR 1916). While 
FEAR states that it is &#147;not our ideal bill, it contains several of the reforms we advocate.&#148; For 
example, it puts the burden of proof on the government by &#147;clear and convincing evidence&#148; 
(not as good as &#147;beyond a reasonable doubt&#148; but better than the current &#147;probable cause&#148; 
standard), provides for counsel of &#147;indigent claimants&#148; (folks unable to afford counsel), and 
provides additional protection for people raising the innocent owner defense. </p>
<p>Hyde also wrote Forfeiting Our Property Rights (1995, Cato Institute) a concise, hard-hitting, 
and well-referenced book. In the introduction, Hyde writes, &#147;As much as any public official, 
I too want to rid our nation of the multifarious problems caused by drug abuse.... But in my 
view, a drug `war' has been perverted too often into a series of frontal attacks on basic 
American constitutional guarantees -- including due process, the presumption of innocence, 
and the right to own and enjoy private property. Foremost among the invasions we now 
witness are unrelenting government assaults on property rights, fueled by a dangerous and 
emotional vigilante mentality that sanctions shredding the U.S. Constitution into meaningless 
confetti.&#148; His major concerns include the &#147;trampling of civil rights&#148;; that billions of dollars 
are spent without controls; property is confiscated even if no crime was committed; &#147;a flimsy 
standard of proof&#148;; and &#147;questionable official conduct.&#148; </p>
<p>Given Hyde's belief in the sanctity of private property, it should come as no surprise that he 
strongly opposes civil asset forfeiture, especially in its current extreme form. Nor is it 
surprising that he should speak out as greedy officials increasingly target the wealthy and 
middle class. Meanwhile, environmentalists are constantly coming up against the right wing's 
rabid defense of private property (and profit, since money is property) as a &#147;God-given&#148; 
right that supersedes the protection of endangered species, ancient forests, dwindling 
wetlands, and clean air and water. Strange bedfellows? You bet! </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Conclusion </h3>
<p>Forfeiture and the criminal &#147;justice&#148; system in general became a personal issue for me in 
1990 when two of my closest friends were arrested. Since it was a first offense and the 
amount of drugs found in their car was what would be considered a &#147;personal use&#148; amount, I 
assumed things would somehow work out. Instead, my friends were set up by a confidential 
informant who led the Northern Drug Task Force to believe they were major dealers in 
Vermont. Even though only a small amount of drugs was actually seized (and no drugs or 
evidence of drugs were found in their home), the court took the word of their informant as 
fact. My friends, who were probably considered &#147;hippies&#148; by the authorities, received 
court-appointed lawyers. One was totally incompetent, the other extremely over-worked. 
They were both predisposed to believe the government's story. It was only towards the end of 
the ordeal, about two months before sentencing, that they finally came to see that my friends 
weren't the horrible &#147;pushers&#148; they were painted to be, and instead were unfortunate addicts 
caught in a web of abuse they had only begun to dig themselves out of before they were set 
up. </p>
<p>While they were fighting for their lives in the courts, my friends were also fighting for their 
home, which had been seized in a separate, civil action. Their struggle to save their home 
centered around their concern for the future of their four children. (This story is cited in the 
section on children.) With the help of a legal aid lawyer, it was decided to put the house and 
property into a trust for the children. This had never been done before in this kind of 
situation, and the feds said they would at least consider it. Today, five years later, the case 
remains unresolved and we are hoping the recent double jeopardy rulings will hold in their 
case as well. </p>
<p>FEAR, 20 Sunnyside, Ste. A-204, Mill Valley, CA 94941; (415) 388-8128. </p>
<p><em>Susan Meeker-Lowry is the author of </em><em><strong>Economics as if the Earth Really Mattered</strong></em><em> (1988) 
and </em><em><strong>Invested in the Common Good</strong></em><em> (1995), both New Society Publishers</em>. </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

