<title>Feb 96: Peterson; Militant Capitalism</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>From the pages of February 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="feb96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>Militant Capitalism </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By David Peterson </strong></em></h2>
<p>I want to examine the challenges the world faces, and discuss what I believe is necessary for 
the future,&#148; Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin told his audience at the Washington, DC-based 
Center for Strategic and International Studies in June 1995. In little more than a week, he'd be 
off to Halifax, Nova Scotia, the site of the 21st annual summit of the Group of Seven 
industrial nations. </p>
<p>Looming in the background to the G-7 Summit was the Mexican Meltdown, the seminal event 
in international finance this decade, bar none. The austerity measures that the U.S. 
government and the IMF forced on Mexicans in the aftermath of last winter's assault on the 
peso by short-sellers in the foreign exchange markets have been something to behold. Almost 
overnight, the Mexican people have had to endure dramatic cuts in government spending; a 
sharp hike in regressive sales taxes; at least one million layoffs (a conservative estimate); a 
spike in interest rates so pronounced as to render their debts unserviceable (hence El Barzon, 
a nation-wide movement of small debtors to resist property seizures and to seek a 
rescheduling of their debts); a collapse in consumer spending on the order of 25 percent by 
mid-year; and, in brief, a 10.5 percent contraction in overall economic activity during the 
second quarter, with more of the same sure to follow. </p>
<p>Central to Rubin's speech was the issue of global governance -- the &#147;potential for problems 
created by modern financial markets,&#148; as he put it, and the need to create institutions &#147;as 
modern as the marketplace&#148; to deal with them. He went on to make a number of 
recommendations, all of which would resurface in the final communique at the Halifax 
Summit. &#147;The major challenge confronting us is to manage this increased interdependence [of 
international trade and finance] while working with the grain of markets,&#148; the Halifax 
communique asserts. Working with the grain of the markets -- a telling phrase. </p>
<p>Shortly after the U.S.-IMF bailout of Mexico's creditors was unveiled last winter, IMF 
managing director Michel Camdessus let it slip that there were as many as ten countries 
besides Mexico where a Mexico-style financial meltdown was a decided possibility. Though 
he refused to name them, they are countries that combine high current account deficits with 
high levels of short-term borrowing, high ratios of debt to GDP, and low levels of hard 
currency reserves -- the mix of macroeconomic factors that foreign investors tend not to like, 
and savage every chance they get. In the hope of averting the next meltdown, the G-7 used the 
Halifax Summit to propose an &#147;early warning system&#148; as well as closer &#147;surveillance of 
national economic policies and financial market developments.&#148; </p>
<p>Judging the likelihood of another meltdown, sometime, somewhere, to be as good as gold, 
however, the G-7 also proposed the creation of an &#147;Emergency Financing Mechanism&#148; 
within the IMF &#147;which would provide faster access to [IMF] arrangements with strong 
conditionality and larger upfront disbursements in crisis situations&#148; -- precisely what was 
lacking when the Mexican Meltdown began, not that such a mechanism could have averted it. 
The G-7 also urged the adoption of &#147;safeguards, standards, transparency and systems 
necessary to monitor and contain risks&#148; of the type endemic to the world financial system. 
How the containment of risk jibes with the &#147;continued encouragement to countries to remove 
capital market restrictions,&#148; yet another of the G-7's recommendations, was left for the 
communique from next year's Summit in Lyon to explain. </p>
<p>&#147;[S]teps should be taken to deal with the issue of regulation with regard to financial markets 
and the risk of systemic crises arising, not from sovereign defaults but from the financial 
markets and their particular nature,&#148; Rubin had affirmed at the CSIS. &#147;We cannot eliminate 
this type of systemic risk,&#148; he admitted, &#147;but we can better monitor and limit it.&#148; </p>
<p>Interesting words. For in point of fact, what sunk the Mexican peso was never the threat of 
sovereign default. The face value of the Tesobonos that the government of President Carlos 
Salinas had turned to as a way of attracting short-term capital to finance the country's 
growing current account deficit leading up to the August 1994, national elections may indeed 
have been indexed to the dollar. But Tesobonos were repayable in pesos, not dollars. 
Crucially, there never was a threat that the Mexican government couldn't meet its Tesobonos 
obligations. </p>
<p>In the eyes of foreign investors, then, the immediate problem lay not in the fear of a Mexican 
default on sovereign debt, but in their fear that Mexico wouldn't have sufficient foreign 
reserves for them to exchange their pesos into the dollars and the other hard currencies they 
would need to repatriate their money. When the new government of President Ernesto Zedillo 
first took the decision to conserve its dwindling reserves of dollars in late December 1994, 
by raising the ceiling at which Central Bank intervention to support the peso against the 
dollar was required by law, leading to renewed selling of the peso, and its eventual float, it 
wasn't the realities of the Mexican economy that had suddenly changed -- it was the 
expectations of investors, who decided, quite suddenly, that they wanted their money back, 
not today, but yesterday. At that point, December 22, 1994, it would have been entirely 
within the Zedillo government's right to declare a financial emergency and impose temporary 
restrictions on foreign exchange. </p>
<p>Such a move was common in the early years of reconstruction following the Second World 
War, and remains permissible under the IMF's Articles of Agreement -- a point which 
explains why the IMF, under pressure from international capital and its major donor 
governments, is now &#147;considering the possibility of amending the Articles to make full 
currency convertibility an objective for all member countries&#148; (Michel Camdessus, Wall 
Street Journal). Had the Zedillo government been motivated by a desire to protect the well 
being of the Mexican people in the face of such an emergency, the adoption of temporary 
exchange restrictions would have been the responsible thing to do. Foreign investors still 
could have dumped their shares of Telmex and their Tesobonos, and whatever other 
peso-denominated securities they were holding. They wouldn't have been able to exchange 
their holdings out of pesos and into another currency. That's all. But neither the IMF nor the 
U.S. government would have stood for such an outrage: the IMF, because it's obsessed with 
preserving the sanctity of the neoliberal model, two major parts of which are unimpeded 
capital flows and full currency convertibility; and Washington with not only that, but also 
NAFTA, its hemispheric trade initiative, and the lives and livelihoods of more than a few 
&#147;emerging markets&#148; gurus on Wall Street, then climbing over each other to be the first to leap 
from the 49th floor. No. If the Zedillo government ever considered imposing exchange 
controls, surely they weren't taken seriously. The cost of extinguishing the Mexican 
Meltdown wasn't to be borne by foreign investors, or by Mexican billionaires, or by 
international loan sharks. It was to be borne by whomever lacked the power to avoid having 
to bear it. The Mexican people. </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

