<head>
<title>Jan 96: Sargent; Gals Half Naked</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>from the pages of January 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="jan96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>&#160;Gals Half Naked Men Fully Clothed </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By Lydia Sargent </strong></em></h2>
<p>At Hotel Satire, the new year always inspires a wish list, and 1996 is no exception. As gals, 
we not to wish for anything substantive or for that much. We're gals, after all, and gals really 
only wish for a handsome prince, good shopping opportunities, clothes, and a nice bottle of 
perfume, something with a femmie name like &#147;Languid&#148; or &#147;Limpid.&#148; Anyhow... </p>
<p>Our first wish was inspired by a &#147;Dear Ann Landers&#148; letter from &#147;Proud to be an old 
fashioned lady&#148; who wrote: &#147;I'd like to comment on the letter from `Disgusted in Long 
Island&#148; who complained about having to stand on the bus while men sat, some pretending to 
be asleep, others blatantly refusing to give up their seats. </p>
<p>&#147;Women have screamed for years that they want to be treated as `equals.' They call men 
`pigs,' blame them for all that is wrong in the world and insist on being included in all-male 
clubs, participating in men's sports and taking jobs that were meant for men only, such as fire 
fighting and law enforcement... I don't get it. </p>
<p>&#147;Our family recently went to Disney World with my sister and her twentysomething, 
liberated, feminist daughter. As we traveled back to our room on a crowded tram, I told my 
teenage son to offer his seat to a woman who got on at one of the stops. My niece hastened to 
criticize me. She said, `Why should he? That's sexist.' </p>
<p>&#147;I will continue to insist that my three sons give up their seats for women and the elderly 
because it is the right thing to do. When I experience a lack of consideration on the bus, I will 
point the accusing finger at the feminists who insist on having the right to stand.&#148; </p>
<p>Kudos to that old fashioned lady. She inspired this wish: gals half on their ass, men fully 
upright. We agree that gals should not have to stand on their own two feet, or open doors, or 
do anything that requires action of any kind. Not only should the man offer a gal his seat, he 
should help her into it with a little nudge, maybe a shove if she's a twentysomething gal. Not 
only should he open the door for her, he should propel her through it, guiding her firmly with 
his hand in the small of her back. When at a restaurant or concert, he should usher her to the 
table or seats by gripping her elbow or grasping the nape of her neck (my personal favorite). </p>
<p>Also, as old fashioned lady wrote, gals should leave the male jobs to the males. A male job 
is not just fire fighting and law enforcement but anything that requires opening doors or 
standing up. The Boston Globe understands this. They rarely show gals playing sports 
(except maybe field hockey) but when they do they usually picture that sports gal on her ass 
(figure 1). Gals in 1996 should assume this half ass position whenever possible. Remember 
to let the man help you into it, maybe with a swat or a well placed fist. </p>
<p>Recently we went to see Sabrina. What can we say. It was inspring to watch yet another 
version of the Cinderella story. </p>
<p>We thought the new Sabrina was better than the old Sabrina because it was about rich white 
men (Harrison Ford, Greg Kinnear), while the old one was about Sabrina, a chauffeur's 
daughter (played by Audrey Hepburn). The current Sabrina gal was so low key and 
decorative that she inspired our next wish: gals as half wits, men fully functional. Can there 
ever be too much gal mooning over rich white guys, with no other interests whatsoever? I 
think not. </p>
<p>Also, we wish for real life to be like Sabrina, where greedy, rich corporate CEOs are 
charming and wonderful, even kind. Where rich playboys are charming and funny, even 
remembering their mother's birthday. Where the servants are happy. Where marriages are, 
surprisingly romantic, corporate mergers. Where one chooses to be a chauffeur because one 
can read the classics on the job, and play the stock market; not because one has to. Where a 
chauffeur's daughter can marry anyone she chooses as long as she's incredibly beautiful and 
can somehow afford an extensive and expensive Paris wardrobe. </p>
<p>Speaking of movies, while we enjoyed Sabrina, it's not for men. So we wish for more movies 
with gals half dead, men fully cocked. Golden Eye is a good example of this. Frankly, when it 
comes to male heroes, there can never be enough killing or explosions of nuclear-proportions 
for the Satire gals. We want men straifing something every two seconds or we're just not 
attracted. By the way, have you noticed that when gals kill in movies, they are 
sluts/bimbos/nutballs with the morals of cockroaches (The Last Seduction; To Die For), but 
when guys commit virtual nuclear holocaust, they're heroes? </p>
<p>Most importantly we wish for a continuation of the delightful tendency for movies, 
newspapers, TV, etc., to depict gals half naked in all manner of venues: the office, the park, 
the street, the subway, the supermarket, the board meeting. And to place them alongside men 
who are fully clothed, we're talking up to their golden eyeballs. </p>
<p>It is so true to life, too, or at least it used to be. Remember going out on a date back in the 
1950s? It's the middle of winter, he's wearing a tuxedo, an overcoat, winter gloves, shoes and 
boots, a scarf. You're wearing practically nothing: almost no underwear, skimpy dress, light 
coat, high heeled flimsy pumps, stockings. </p>
<p>At Hotel Satire, we're going to spend 1996 unconcerned about poverty, or violence, or 
oppression. We're going to spend 1996 being propelled from place to place wearing only our 
underwear. </p>
<p>What more could one wish for than: gals half naked, men fully clothed. </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

</html>
