<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>from the pages of January 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="jan96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>France at the barricades </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By Moe Seager &amp; Kevin Phelan </strong></em></h2>
<p>On November 15, 1995 French Prime Minister Alain Juppe, addressing the National 
Assembly, presented a general outline of reforms, massive cuts to vital sectors of French 
society. The Juppe Plan, short on actual figures and dates, read more like a manifesto of the 
nouvelle capitaliste regime of President Jacques Chirac, re-sounding echoes of Reaganomics, 
Thatcherism, and Gingrich's Contract with America. The prime minister forecast &#147;painful but 
necessary&#148; cuts in spending on social security, health, education, and public transportation. 
Along with these cuts -- increased taxes with elimination of several deductions. </p>
<p>As the prime minister postured valiantly, critics claimed crocodile tears as France remains 
the world's fourth richest economy. Within hours of Juppe's declaration leaders representing 
millions of the nation's workforce, students, and minority groups collectively rejected much 
of the plan and warned against its implementation. In turn, Juppe declared the plan 
&#147;irreversible,&#148; a &#147;bitter pill necessary for the nation in order to recover from 15 years of 
mounting debt.&#148; </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>The New Monarchs </h3>
<p>True, most everyone is well aware of the country's long term debt accumulations, especially 
mounting deficits in the social security system. Health care outlays over the last 14 years rose 
on average 20 percent ahead of inflation. Public and private sector workers have anticipated 
upcoming economic reforms and have agreed in principle to certain austerity measures. So 
why have more than a million people taken part in paralyzing the country at a cost of several 
billion francs per day, with no sign of quitting? </p>
<p>Causing immediate rancor was the authoritarian, many say monarchical, style of government 
that decreed radical reforms without engaging in public discourse, or without putting its 
critical plan to public referendum. Secondly, just days before the Juppe Plan was announced 
the prime minister and the president met with their German counterparts to seal a time-table 
for the start of a single European currency. French leaders want to institute the Euro-dollar in 
1999. In order to do so economic restructuring principally the national debt must be 
substantially cut by year end 1997 to assure stability to the new currency. Single currency is a 
keystone to the Maastricht Treaty which passed in last year's referendum by a slim margin. 
Lastly, Juppe and Chirac dismissed the traditional route of negotiations with labor and 
professional organizations, declaring instead to &#147;see these reforms enacted despite the pain 
and objections from interest groups.&#148; </p>
<p>The new monarchs, as critics are calling them, had already plunged in popularity as a result 
of earlier tax increases, several government corruption scandals, and the fallout from 
Chirac's nuclear test bombings in the South Pacific. A December 7 poll revealed the fall of 
the president to a miserable 12 percent approval rate; the prime minister at a dismal 8 
percent. </p>
<p>Within 24 hours of Juppe's decree, the Communist-led Confederation of General Workers 
(CGT) called for the first wave of strikes to occur the following week. Students, already in 
their sixth week of a campaign to secure increased funding and better conditions, voiced 
greater militancy, announcing a shutdown of the nation's universities. </p>
<p>Five days passed in which the prime minister and his cabinet met with labor and student 
delegations. What transpired during the meetings amounted to &#147;impostor negotiations,&#148; 
&#147;deceit,&#148; and &#147;double-talk&#148; by government officials, according to labor and student 
delegates. They reported that ministers offered no timetables and vacillated about actual 
ways and means of enacting the reforms. A spokesperson for the Socialist Party revealed the 
obvious: &#147;At best these reforms would take five years at great pain and sacrifice. The 
government is trying to accomplish this horrendous feat in two and a half years.&#148; </p>
<p>On November 21, transport workers in rail, metro, and bus began their first strike day, 
paralyzing Paris, Lyon, and handicapping many other cities. (This was the start of the largest 
labor unrest in a decade, the last being in 1986 when Chirac, then prime minister, triggered 
large scale labor strikes and a three week student strike, the result being the loss of his job in 
the Mitterand-led coalition.) Fifty percent of all commercial activity was halted in Paris and 
the surrounding region. France's largest labor syndicate, CGT, rapidly gained the 
participation of other sectors. On November 30, a 24-hour shutdown of the state-owned gas 
and electric industry caused a partial energy shortage, forcing the government to purchase 
electricity from Spain and Britain. On the same day, postal workers shut down 45 percent of 
the nation's mail operations. Automaker Peugeot sent home nearly 8,000 of its 11,860 
member workforce, having no method to move stocks from assembly plants. Joining students, 
university professors and staff went out, along with other one day shutdowns by school 
teachers, health care workers, doctors unions, miners, and airport/airline employees. </p>
<p>At a November 28 mass demonstration involving several hundred thousand marchers 
nationally and more than 58,000 in Paris, CGT, with an approximate 10 percent share of the 
organized workforce, linked arms with smaller historic rival Worker's Force (FO) for the 
first time since 1947. The march also included the country's two other union federations. </p>
<p>Bolstering labor solidarity, the National Student Coordination Council announced its 
solidarity with the unions. Surprising all sides, growing numbers of non-union private sector 
employees announced support for the rebellious coalition. By December 4, administrative 
personnel from banks, insurance companies, and hospitals announced intentions to halt 
business. Restaurant owners threatened to shut down to protest the increase in taxes. </p>
<p>After lengthy discussions concerning patient safety health care workers decided to maintain 
&#147;safe levels&#148; of personnel on the job, hanging strike banners throughout the wards and 
offices, dialoguing with patients to promote solidarity. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Student Body Left </h3>
<p>On November 30, sections of Paris were transformed as more than 20,000 people, mostly 
students but with a notable presence of professors and union members, took to the streets in 
the third protest of its size in ten days. Similar protests, smaller in size, had occurred 
regularly in Lille, Rennes, Montpellier, Metz, and Toulouse. </p>
<p>Student unrest began in May 1995 when the government announced a plan to reduce the 
minimum wage which many students receive for work/study. Large militant protests forced 
the government to halt the wage cut. The current wave began in September 1995 at the 
University of Rouen, Normandy when students prepared to go on strike to procure an 
emergency influx of 10 million francs ($2 million). A settlement was reached with the 
government, and 6 million franc ($1.2 million) was directed to the University. </p>
<p>Students and professors were responding to an acute need for additional facilities, teachers, 
and administrative staff. French universities are trying to stay afloat despite intense 
overcrowding and severe under-funding. In the 1995-96 school year 2.2 million students are 
enrolled at the 90 universities, up from 300,000 25 years ago. The vast increase is the result 
of demands won in the 1968 student/worker revolt opening the nation's universities to those 
previously excluded by scholastic scores and competitions. This year's student population 
increased by 6 percent, while the education budget only increased by 4 percent. For example, 
the University of Nanterre, well known to be discriminated against by government since 
germinating successive generations of leftist students and faculty since 1968, bursts at the 
seams: built for a 17,000 person capacity, it's now crammed with nearly 35,000 students and 
a teaching staff of only 1,100. In Aix-en-Provence last year, overcrowding resulted in classes 
being conducted in parking lots. </p>
<p>Led by students and professors at Toulouse University, a system-wide strike all but closed 
down the universities in early November. The main point of contention was what they saw as 
a grossly insufficient education budget in the Juppe Plan. They recognized the necessity of 
controlling the debt and deficit riddled economy, but were outraged by the priorities of a 
government spending billions on nuclear test bombings in the South Pacific while universities 
face physical and financial crises. Teachers and support staff at elementary and secondary 
schools, along with striking lycee students, had staged one-day shutdowns in solidarity with 
the larger strikes. </p>
<p>In early talks, they demanded that education outlays be increased by 2 billion franc ($400 
million). After a November 21 student demonstration which drew more than 20,000 in Paris, 
Education Minister Francois Bayrou pledged that, although the level of state spending in the 
budget was non-negotiable, 200 million francs ($40 million) would be re-channeled to help 
eliminate inequality at some schools. The National Student Coordination Council rejected the 
offer outright. </p>
<p>Denis Abecassis, vice president and professor of economics at Nanterre, is unequivocal in 
his support for the students' demands. His concerns, however, go beyond lack of facilities 
and staff. He emphasizes the need to address several critical safety issues like structural 
damage to buildings, deteriorating stairwells, and dangerously inadequate fire alarms and 
sprinkler systems. He points to a more alarming condition faced by students, faculty, and 
workers alike -- the presence of large deposits of asbestos, a substance previously used for 
insulation, now banned because of its high toxicity. </p>
<p>For Kasra Vafadari, history of law professor at Nanterre, the money needed for safety, 
facilities, and personnel, while important, only scratches the surface. &#147;Universities never 
have enough money,&#148; he said as he marched along Boulevard Port Royal during the 
November 30 manifestation. He pointed out that a lot of young people helped vote the 
government of Jacques Chirac and Allain Juppe into office. &#147;They were hungry for a change 
and thought Chirac and Juppe would be nice. A good percentage of the students here today 
are the same ones who were dancing on the Champs-Elysee in July,&#148; he said, referring to the 
celebration that took place when the new president was inaugurated. &#147;They're beginning to 
see that right-wing is right-wing, and now realize that they were tired of Mitterand's face, not 
his policies.&#148; </p>
<p>The tail end of the November 30 demonstration ended with a standoff at the University of 
Jussieu. Student protesters, their faces covered by bandannas, overturned parked cars and 
threw a melange of rocks and bottles at police clad in riot gear. Police fired rounds of tear 
gas into the crowd and took up strategic positions in the surrounding streets and buildings. 
Local residents rushed for cover amidst the sounds of bricks crashing through windows. 
Desks and chairs were piled into a barricade at the sole entrance while a barrage of debris 
rained down from windows and rooftops. No further action was taken by police because 
asylum has been accorded to French universities since the Middle Ages. Nearly every 
demonstration has ended with small but violent clashes in the streets initiated by anarchists 
and several hundred other angry students. </p>
<p>What happened next in the student ranks was a complex conflagration of political passion and 
personal rage. Militants brewed Molotov cocktails with paint thinner and broke up cement 
walkways to gather fist-sized stones. Others filled classrooms to hold mass democratic 
forums. Disagreements were heated, as pockets calling for immediate confrontation with the 
police argued with more moderate factions advocating non-violent civil disobedience. A 
100-person brawl erupted between student anarchists and those belonging to the national 
student union, L'UNEF. A group of workers from France's striking rail and postal unions 
came to speak of the need for a student/worker alliance. An informal referendum calling for a 
nationwide General Strike passed with unanimous support. </p>
<p>As these meetings occurred, university shops, the cafeteria, and bookstore shelves were 
looted by rampaging students while some focused their energies on cracking open coin boxes 
of overturned vending machines. Simultaneously, in Nantes, students and sympathizers were 
waging battles in the streets with the police. </p>
<p>Five days later, violence flared again at the St. Lazare train station, as more than 500 youths 
overturned cars, destroyed phone boxes, and smashed store windows. Dozens were arrested, 
and one person seriously injured. </p>
<p>On December 2, 200 delegates from 50 universities met to discuss tactics and strategies, and 
to decide on a negotiating team for talks with the government. They called for another 
national demonstration on December 5, and revised their previous demands to include: an 
increase in education spending of 50 billion francs ($10 billion) over the next five years, the 
creation of 25,000 new professor/researcher jobs and 20,000 administration/clerical 
positions, private university faculty reclassified as public; and an end to discrimination 
against foreign students. Twenty-two representatives were elected, with a large majority of 
leftists from Marxist/Leninist, Trotskyite, and Anarchist groups unseating liberal and 
conservative delegates. </p>
<p>Reacting to student escalation, education minister Francois Bayrou broke the government line 
of no retreat by pledging a re-direction of 5 billion francs ($1 billion) over five years, still 
within the constraints of the Juppe Plan, to the universities under most financial strain. 
Bayrou's carrot was rejected by the students. </p>
<p>&gt;Serious questions in the student ranks arose because of the December 2 meeting. Almost all 
of the 200 students were from L'UNEF and L'UNEF-ID: the first a 7,000 member body nearer 
in affiliation with the Communist Party; the second, a 13,000 member group closely aligned 
with the Socialist Party. Delegates from 40 universities were unable to attend because of the 
continuing transportation strike; and 7 out of the 22 elected were from Paris, casting doubt on 
the legitimacy of a 22-member body elected by 200 delegates claiming to have the authority 
to represent 2.2 million students. Finally, bitter disputes between traditionally antagonistic 
leftist organiza&lt;P10&gt;tions re-surfaced threatening to fragment student negotiations and the 
movement as a whole. &lt;P255&gt; </p>
<p>That same weekend, the Conference of University Presidents unveiled a proposal calling for 
an immediate 2 billion francs ($400 million) to address safety issues and 200 million francs 
to hire 4,000 new teachers and administrative staff, only a fraction of the student demands. 
One professor, who wished to remain anonymous, quipped, &#147;The primary aim of the 
President's Conference is to stop the student movement.&#148; On December 3, the education 
minister accepted the platform, and met with student leaders from L'UNEF-ID to gain their 
support. Some L'UNEF-ID members considered the talks &#147;progress,&#148; but an overwhelming 
majority criticized their leaders, with the Mobilization committee of Nanterre calling it 
&#147;treason.&#148; L'UNEF-ID leaders promptly rejected the offer and accepted the rank-and-file's 
wish to continue. </p>
<p>Difficulties notwithstanding, many pundits point to the student insurgence as predecessor to a 
larger national revolt. Participation of French students has added significantly to the French 
national alliance now battling the government, a point not lost on the government conscious of 
the net power in a potential student/worker alliance (read the revolution of 1968). </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Stocks and Bond(age) </h3>
<p>Initial government and investor confidence soured rapidly in light of the unexpected 
solidarity and mobilization of workers and students. By December 1, foreign investors drove 
the franc down, the Paris Stock Exchange slipped almost 7.5 points on the CAC-40 blue chip 
index. As Juppe and Chirac re-iterated their no-compromise positions, Eric Chavic, 
economist with Morgan Stanley and Co., told the International Herald Tribune on December 
1, &#147;Some market participants have doubts about the will of the government to implement its 
reforms,&#148; a double message intended to provoke the government to tougher resolve. Adding 
to the financial scene, the chief economist of Banque Indosuez also reported on the same day 
&#147;if the strike continues we may not be able to turn around the current slowdown...&#148; Dour 
news, released one day earlier, reported that unemployment rose again in October for the 
third straight month, currently officially set at 11.2 percent. Independent analysts adjust the 
figure to near 15 percent, the highest unemployment rate in industrial Europe. Paired to 
jobless rates, the Gross Domestic Product also stagnated for the second and third quarter at a 
dismal 0.2 percent for both quarters. With the impact from the strikes, fourth quarter 
productivity is predicted to be bleak. The rail strike alone has cost the economy an estimated 
$20 million a day. Financial high rollers, retailers, and large businesses, along with finance 
ministers, are fearful of a short term economic collapse followed by a long term economic 
descent despite the rhetoric of Juppe and Chirac. Given the combination of factors, one 
senior minister admitted on December 1, &#147;Initially we were confident about implementing 
reforms. Now, we're not sure if we are going to win this contest.&#148; </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Calling Bluffs </h3>
<p>Entering its 11th day, labor upped the ante on December 4, as trucker union activists 
blockaded the major commercial arteries leading into Paris. The blockade prevented food, 
dry goods, and other essentials from reaching the capital. All parties braced themselves for a 
potential shortage of bread and other necessities. The public was notified that Paris reserves 
of high octane gasoline would run out on December 5. This announcement was followed by 
the taxi driver's union informing the government of a complete halt to taxi service for the 
same day. </p>
<p>Department stores reported a 50 percent decline in sales, this at the start of the biggest 
consumer spending period. Consumer spending had already dropped dramatically months 
before the present crisis erupted. If tourism declines through the holiday period, added 
billions will increase the national economic loss to Paris, the world's number one tourist 
city. </p>
<p>Former Socialist Party leader Henri Emmanuel denounced President Chirac and his Rally for 
the Republic party (RPR) warning &#147;this government's attitude is serious and could lead to a 
regrettable deterioration of relations between different types of French citizens.&#148; </p>
<p>Seeing themselves losing another propaganda skirmish, the president and prime minister 
divulged their own plan of escalation. Juppe was prepared to rule by decree instead of using 
normal constitutional procedures. President Chirac followed with a deck of authoritarian 
trump cards. </p>
<ul>
<li>Threatening a dissolution of Parliament to accord rule by decree </li>
<li>Calling for general elections, or a referendum on the reforms (which analysts doubt 
given the current popular hostility) </li>
<li>Mobilizing the army to transport commuters </li>
<li>Enlarging his party's creation of &#147;committees to fight for the right to work,&#148; which 
staged its first rally on December 2 (Reagan's tactics in the 1980s with the Christian 
right) </li>
<li>Organizing broader anti-strike committees and pro-government car pools </li>
<li>Juppe making a nationwide address, seen as an attempt to re-sell the plan to the nation </li>
</ul>
<p>Using his first trump card, Chirac hired 17,000 buses and an additional number of riverboats 
to transport commuters and anti-strikers on December 1, vowing to continue the intervention 
daily at a cost of 3 million francs ($600,000). The following week, during an attempted 
shutdown of Orly airport when pilots, air controllers, and firemen walked off the job, police 
were called in to keep the airport open. Despite police intervention only one in five flights 
took off and landed. The larger Charles De Gaulle airport faces the same shutdown and flight 
disruptions. Chirac voiced his contempt for popular opposition in late November, revealing 
in the process an ideological maxim: &#147;I think a politician should be a leader and not a 
follower. That means he [sic] should base his decisions on the commitments he made, on his 
idea of the future and not on public opinion.&#148; </p>
<p>On the eve of the next nationwide strike of December 2, CGT secretary general Luis Vianet 
updated labor's positions saying, &#147;The unions, the French people will not cease in this 
struggle and we are prepared to escalate our activities until the government agrees to come to 
the table offering meaningful proposals. We remain most definitely opposed to much of the 
Juppe Plan and will not accept these lies, deceits, and attacks against our way of life.&#148; Vianet 
added that his federation favored escalating to a general strike. Speaking just as militantly, 
Marc Blondel, secretary general for FO, repeated that if the government will not yield labor 
should use their biggest weapon -- the general strike. The National Student Coordination 
Council joined in with a statement declaring it was inching closer to declaring its own 
participation in a general strike. </p>
<p>Three polls released on December 4 disclosed that while the populace was unnerved by the 
growing stoppages and disruptions, two out of three were in basic support of labor's stance. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Regime Wobbles </h3>
<p>On December 5, Juppe made a nationwide broadcast pledging the regime's unflagging 
resolve. Following his address public sympathy remained as before with a majority in 
opposition. In complete contradiction, two days later Juppe announced the appointment of an 
official mediator to supervise talks with labor. After the first round of government/labor 
mediation talks, federation leaders accused the prime minister of more deceitful ploys and 
warned of further escalations in response to &#147;meaningless government talk.&#148; </p>
<p>As the December 7 International Herald Tribune headlined &#147;Disruption by Workers Seems to 
be Slowing,&#148; the opposite had actually occurred. Two days of national shutdowns on 
December 5 and December 7 drew first time support from bank employees, Treasury 
Department workers, tax collectors, the state-run France Telecom, and many other social 
service staff. Labor leadership called for the continuation of ongoing shutdowns to rail and 
transport, partial shutdowns of state-owned electric and gas companies, and the postal 
service. Leaders announced the continuation of national protests and disruptions every two 
days. Rather than waning, the strikes spread throughout the country. Marching on December 
5, in temperatures below freezing, were more than 50,000 in Paris, 700,000 nationally. On 
December 7, the marchers in Paris climbed to more than 70,000, and over one million 
nationwide. With a population of 57 million the proportion of strikers was enormous, 
comparable to 4.4 million workers and students paralyzing New York, Washington, and 
Chicago. </p>
<p>Abdul Kharim, a 28-year-old auto mechanic said, &#147;I'm afraid, really afraid this could lead to 
civil war because I don't think the French people share enough solidarity to collectively 
struggle for a national resolution of this conflict with the government.&#148; </p>
<p>Sorbonne medical student Marie-Claire Duplantier lamented, &#147;The student strike hits me at a 
terrible time in my studies but if we students don't hold out for proper conditions perhaps I 
can't finish my studies anyway. If we must continue to shut down the universities, to join a 
general strike, I agree we must.&#148; </p>
<p>Iron worker and CGT member Jean-luc Colmant, fresh from a union meeting, said, &#147;I didn't 
think Chirac and the government would go this far. This is a democracy and these people are 
treating the citizens like they're the new monarchy. Of course we must reform our 
debt-riddled system but remember government waste, like the nuclear tests which cost one 
billion francs ($200 million) each -- they have been contributing more debt than they will 
admit to. If the government thinks the French people will surrender our wages, our health, our 
education, and retirement plans, well, we won't surrender our future. This is still a rich 
country if you look at the Bourse (stock exchange) and the banks. No, we will not surrender 
to this tyranny. I believe next we will be forced to a general strike. If that doesn't put sense 
into the government, well, hey -- if the students and unions continue our solidarity we will 
move like 1968 and there will be revolution.&#148; </p>
<p>As this article goes to press, here's a sampling of the latest round of confrontations and 
economic fallout. On December 7 in a small town in Lorraine, striking miners clashed with 
police before turning on a coal company and setting one of its buildings ablaze. To date, 7 of 
France's 21 nuclear power plants have been on strike, 100 of the 130 mail sorting centers and 
151 post offices have been shutdown or slowed down. The normally busy rail service 
between Paris, Brussels, and London came to a near standstill, including the Eurotunnel 
connecting France to England. Beginning December 5, the Bank of France intervened to stop 
the tumbling value of the franc. Beneath mounting labor agitation, union leaders reported 
strike funds running out. Speaking about a possible government bail out, Jean Francoise 
Mercier, chief economist at Salomon Brothers in London, let the cat out of the bag, lamenting, 
&#147;If they give in, Maastricht is jeopardized.&#148; </p>
<p>France is bracing for a historic winter of discontent, perhaps more. </p>
<p><em>In the next issue we look at the history of France's march to Maastricht and direct ties to 
U.S. politics and trends</em>. </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

