<h3 align=center>From the pages of February 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="feb96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>France at the Barricades, Part II </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By Moe Seager </strong></em></h2>
<p>At this writing, seven weeks have passed since French Prime Minister Alain Juppe declared 
government intentions to radically reform the French welfare state. Students and trade 
unionists, along with a majority of the populace, rejected the Juppe Plan, perceiving it as too 
great a sacrifice in too short a time, measures too severe even for a troubled French economy 
(Z January 1996). </p>
<p>Though repeatedly pledging a no-compromise vow through the first two weeks of nationwide 
strikes and slowdowns, the prime minister agreed to suspend a planned overhaul of pensions 
for all public sector employees while also caving in to labor's demand for a Social Summit 
in December, where union representatives introduced their proposals for economic and 
social reforms. The government conceded to additional demands which included not 
increasing rail workers' retirement age by 2.5 years, as the Juppe Plan recommended. 
Perhaps the biggest overall negotiation concerned labor's long-time demand to cut the 
standard work week from 39 to 35 hours with full pay in return for labor flexibility along 
other lines, principally overtime shift work. Additionally, the long overdue agenda of health, 
safety, and other rights for women workers was advanced. Still hotly disputed is Juppe's plan 
to exclude the Worker's Force confederation from further partial management of the national 
health care plan. </p>
<p>On December 18, labor leaders announced a cessation of strikes and slowdowns to public 
transport; mail, telephone, gas, electric, and a host of other public services. But both the 
Confederation of French Workers and Worker's Force warned the government that 
constructive talks would have to continue or the massive strikes would be resumed. After 
paralyzing the country for four weeks and rallying nationwide demonstrations that exceeded 
one million and two million, the government was no longer confident of its ability to divide 
the popular movement with stall tactics and threats. </p>
<p>On December 29, dissatisfied rail workers struck train lines connecting Paris to both of its 
airports. At issue was a pay dispute resulting from earlier strike days. By January 6 President 
Chirac and the Prime minister admitted to defeat but continued to insist that the major 
elements of reform would be enacted, citing the implementation of a 0.5 percent increase to 
income through a &#147;debt tax.&#148; After three nationwide broadcasts by the prime minister and the 
New Year's broadcast by the president a poll revealed that 40 percent of the listeners could 
not remember any of the 22 points of the Juppe Plan. </p>
<p>By the second week of January, the French labor movement had caused some major defeats, 
no small feat considering less than 10 percent of French workers are unionized, their ranks 
decimated in the 1980s by plant shutdowns and runaway shops. Victories withstanding not all 
was solidarity in the ranks of the French labor movement. On December 13 Nicole Notat, 
leader of the French Democratic Labor Confederation, rejected CGT/FO calls for continuing 
strikes and demonstrations. Notat urged her 65,000 members to consider government 
concessions a victory and to return to work the following day. Rejecting CGT/FO calls for 
direct participation in government planning, Notat stated a preference for business trade 
unionism and chastised union leaders for &#147;going beyond work issues and getting involved in 
politics.&#148; </p>
<p>Following Notat's defection FO leader Marc Blondel defended the labor coalition's position 
of continued militancy. Appealing to Notat's members to join an upcoming demonstration 
which drew two million marchers nationally, Blondel warned the French people to reject 
social and economic climate of Britain and the United States.&#148; Two days later one of 
Blondel's aides admitted that workers were financially strapped after two weeks of strikes. 
The one million member FO then made a public appeal for strike fund donations. </p>
<p>Labor militants are well aware that rank and file, students, and others are concerned with 
restoring status quo conditions and not in favor of toppling the government or overthrowing 
the system. Pundits from all camps were quick to note that in 1968 ten million took to the 
streets. In the current crisis the numbers were less than three million. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Maastricht Menace </h3>
<p>It is increasingly apparent to the French public that the government coupled its domestic 
reform package to a larger agenda. The severity of its austerity measures are tied to the 
Maastricht Agreement, specifically to meet a European single currency introduction by 1999. 
The strategic justification for this high-risk domestic venture becomes even more evident in 
the light of post-war developments. Once again the big picture involves the competing 
ambitions of France and Germany. </p>
<p>Since 1945, French rulers have worked to gain the economic upper hand with Germany. The 
post-World War II strategy has been European integration to tie Germany's national 
aspirations to Europe as a whole, prohibiting Germany from re-assuming another era of 
nationalist aggression. Beginning with DeGaulle, and continuing with Chirac, every French 
government regardless of party and ideology, has worked toward these ends. </p>
<p>Thirty years of Cold War politics, i.e. the division of Germany, enabled France to achieve 
better economic growth and expansion than West Germany. The unification of Germany in 
1989 has changed the equation. Since unification, Germany's economic structural 
adjustments, i.e. austerity implementations, have led the Kohl government to believe the 
country is ready for a single European currency. In meetings between Chirac and Kohl last 
October the German Chancellor challenged his French counterpart to achieve the necessary 
budget deficit reduction for entrance into the single currency club. The Juppe Plan, in theory, 
readies France to meet Germany head-on as Europe's two powerhouses, wrestling for 
European dominance. </p>
<p>In France, early and continuous opposition comes from two strange bedfellows: communists 
and fascists. The fascist Frente National opposes unification on grounds of extremist 
nationalism while the French CP and Trotskyite organizations identify pro-big 
business/anti-worker mechanisms. Complex and rife with legal jargon, Maastricht is clear on 
a few essentials: business and industry have a legal right to pick up and move throughout free 
trade zones for economic objectives, including labor disputes, under uniform clauses that 
protect financial interests; unions and unorganized workers may follow capital flight by 
relocation but must submit to national labor agreements. Maastricht, at bottom line, reads like 
GATT and NAFTA; legalizing and ensuring the rights of runaway shops, and dislocation of 
workers. Critics of Maastricht, like opponents of GATT and NAFTA, identify the treaty as a 
structural mechanism of the capitalist new world order which is about de-regulating national 
management-labor traditions, entitling finance to greater freedoms while, in equal 
proportions, subjugating work forces and communities to reduced rights and guarantees, 
ultimately reducing wage earners and most salaried personnel to tentative and transitory 
states. </p>
<p>France's current crisis follows a series of crises that have polarized the nation in recent 
years. President Chirac's decision to nuclear test bomb in the Pacific has angered a large 
minority here, uniting ecologists, pacifists, and sections of the business community. Chirac's 
recklessness has seriously damaged state relations with several Pacific states. Defending the 
test bombings on grounds of national security and scientific verification, Chirac's real motive 
surfaced when he offered to use France's nuclear arsenal for the &#147;protection&#148; of European 
states. The nuclear superpower argument dovetails with his European ambitions. Shortly 
after the start of the genocidal bloodbath in Rwanda, it was established that the Mitterand 
regime had armed the Hutu killers before and after the carnage. The terrorist bombings in 
France this past summer and fall, attributed to the Algerian Front for Islamic Salvation and 
&eacute;migr&eacute; sympathizers living in France, has set off a reactionary shock wave against non-white 
immigrants, resulting in routine harassment of people of color. Muslims in France are now 
estimated at nearly 4 million of a total population of 57 million, visible targets of an 
increasing climate of xenophobia. </p>
<p>Jean-Marie Le Pen, leader of the Frente National, once a marginal voice in national affairs is 
now a frequent voice in the media, in public rallies, and is growing more popular at the 
polls. Le Pen and the Frente draw support by exploiting voters' fears of high unemployment 
due to immigration. In last year's municipal and parliamentary election the Frente won in the 
Southwest Toulon, a city of 170,000, Marigirane (33,000) and Orange (28,000) while 
placing well in Alsace, the Northeast region of the country, and the suburban Paris region. 
The Frente exhibits all of the classic nazi-like behaviors mixing a profile of impassioned 
patriotism at rallies and media events with hate literature, vandalism, injury, and murder. 
With increased unemployment and economic difficulties, an electorate disillusioned with 
mainstream parties, a weakened factionalized left -- Le Pen's group is expected to rise in 
appeal in future parliamentary and municipal elections. </p>
<p>As strikes in France brought the country to a standstill, the events sent immediate messages 
through Europe, the U.S., and international finance who are well aware that the Juppe Plan is 
a major test of will between the new capitalist order and a citizenry, have watched with 
growing degrees of anxiety, even alarm. The French backlash has rekindled controversy 
throughout Europe. By January, skeptics and opponents of Maastricht were filing numerous 
press articles and editorials against a single currency-monetary union, questioning the 
European union, in some cases. From Madrid, a former European commissioner asked, &#147;The 
problem facing politicians nowadays is: How do we tell the voters that in Europe national 
sovereignty is hollow?&#148; Oskar Lafontaine, the new leader of Germany's opposition Social 
Democratic Party, urged a delay in implementing a currency timetable, adding that the plan 
risked dividing Europe. Italy's prime minister Lamberto Dini called for a new study and 
delayed timetable. John Major again voiced British doubts. In Paris a leading parliamentary 
figure conceded that France should put a moratorium on the currency timetable. Editorialists 
from government posts throughout Europe are warning colleagues that without French 
consensus on the currency issue there can be no monetary union. </p>
<p>Writing in the International Herald Tribune, December 9, 1995, Ethan Kapstein, director of 
studies at the U.S. Council on Foreign Relations, contributed some worthwhile observations 
and advice: &#147;The government, thinking it knows better than the people, makes decisions 
without consulting them. The National Assembly is a rubber stamp. Deprived of debate, the 
French take to the streets....The French, like most Europeans, are coddled from cradle to 
grave. Most people understand that the welfare system needs changes, but they ask, `Who 
will lose?' Certainly not the rich. Most people, especially union members, say, `We will'.&#148; </p>
<p>At the moment France is engaged in a fragile truce. Workers are militant about such issues as 
strike pay, and the future of their health and education institutions. Their militant activities, 
conducted thus far with the support of a majority of students and a majority of the populace, 
have rattled their government out of its velvet chamber. By putting their leaders on notice, the 
strikers and their supporters have also put leaders and investors throughout the West on 
notice. Stay tuned. </p>
<p><em>Thanks to my research assistant Kevin P.Q. Phelan. </em></p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

