<head>
<title>Jan 96: Zielinski; Showdown in Motown</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>from the pages of January 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="jan96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>Showdown in Motown </h1>
<h2 align=center><em><strong>By Mike Zielinski </strong></em></h2>
<p>The newly elected leadership of the AFL-CIO promises to restore labor's militancy, calling 
for a movement which &#147;knows how to work the streets, not just the cities.&#148; The most pressing 
test of a renewed commitment to street heat may be in Detroit, site of an increasingly bitter 
and often violent newspaper strike. </p>
<p>On July 13, 2,500 workers in 6 unions went on strike at the city's two dailies, the Detroit 
News and the Free Press, to protest unfair labor practices and management's drive to 
eliminate union jobs. Since then, labor and management have been at war. Workers lay siege 
to printing plants, while the company uses helicopters to airlift papers over picket lines. 
Police beat and teargas strikers during hand to hand combat, while paramilitary guards in the 
pay of the newspapers ram through picket lines in speeding trucks. </p>
<p>The stakes are enormous. In an era when labor is struggling to reverse a steady decline in 
membership, Detroit represents a stronghold of industrial unionism. A labor movement 
steeped in the auto plant sit-down strikes of the 1930s squares off against the downsizing 
mega-corporations of the 1990s. If management succeeds in busting the unions in Detroit, 
labor's hopes for the future will be diminished everywhere. </p>
<p>The striking Detroit unions are caught in the cross-hairs of two media giants, Gannett and 
Knight-Ridder, owners of the News and Free Press respectively. Gannett is best known as 
the publisher of USA Today, but also operates 81 other dailies -- only 5 of which are 
unionized. Knight-Ridder is the junior partner with 28 newspapers. </p>
<p>The conflict in Detroit is driven by larger economic forces buffeting the entire newspaper 
industry. With media ownership concentrated in fewer and fewer hands, the needs of local 
communities are increasingly subordinated to distant investors demand for profits. And 
profits are becoming harder and harder to sustain in a society where newspaper readership is 
on the decline. </p>
<p>Circulation is down for virtually all big city papers. One of the few papers to report a surge 
in circulation is USA Today, with a sales increase of 49,000 papers in the first 9 months of 
this year. Gannett continues to grasp for more. Just days after the Detroit strike started, 
Gannett bid $1.7 billion to buy Multimedia, operator of 15 television stations across the 
country. The merger would give the largest newspaper chain in the country the largest 
concentration of television stations as well. Throughout the industry, the trend is to close 
papers which fail to generate sufficient profits. The Time Mirror, Co. recently sacrificed 
New York's Newsday and the Baltimore Sun, using the savings to buy more lucrative 
television stations. </p>
<p>Corporations which do maintain newspapers are determined to cut labor costs to the bone. In 
Philadelphia, Knight-Ridder announced an 8 percent cut in the workforce, threatening to shut 
down the Daily News if the unions do not submit to job and wage concessions. At the Miami 
Herald, Knight-Ridder's flagship paper, the company plans $32 million in cuts, including the 
elimination of some 200 jobs. </p>
<p>While imposing austerity measures on urban dailies, Knight-Ridder lavishes resources on 
papers appealing to more upscale suburban markets. The company recently put up $360 
million to buy Lesher Communications, publisher of 4 dailies based in affluent suburbs of 
San Francisco. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Unions Or Bust </h3>
<p>The News and Free Press publish under the terms of a Joint Operating Agreement (JOA), 
established in 1989. The two papers maintain separate news divisions, but conduct common 
business operations directed by the Detroit Newspaper Agency (DNA). Gannett and 
Knight-Ridder originally pushed for the JOA on the pretext it would protect jobs and 
preserve two editorial voices in Detroit. Now, management wants to eliminate jobs and quite 
possibly one of the papers. Under the JOA, the two corporations would split the remaining 
profits should one of the papers go under. The company may be calculating that one paper 
will corner the revenues split by two, while incurring only half the operating costs. </p>
<p>Detroit is the centerpiece of corporate America's escalating campaign to drive unions out of 
the newsroom. The newspapers began plotting the unions' demise years ago. In 1992, the 
DNA filed a secret amendment to the JOA authorizing production of a single newspaper in 
the event of a strike. </p>
<p>The corporations have made their union-busting intentions clear. In August, Detroit News 
publisher Robert Giles said: &#147;we're going to hire a whole new work force and go on without 
unions, or they can surrender unconditionally and salvage what they can.&#148; </p>
<p>The DNA appears to have studied past newspaper strikes and learned from management's 
miscues. From the beginning, the DNA ensured production of a daily paper, printing a single 
edition under a joint masthead. The paper was thin on news and advertising, yet its very 
existence conveyed management's determination to carry on without unions. Some 1,500 
replacement workers were hired for production and distribution jobs, while Gannett and 
Knight-Ridder transferred reporters and editorial writers from other parts of their empire to 
Detroit. </p>
<p>In a monumental act of hypocrisy, the Free Press editorialized against the use of replacement 
workers the year before, calling on the Senate to &#147;approve a bill that would prohibit 
companies from hiring permanent replacements for striking workers. The right to strike is 
essential if workers are to gain and preserve fair wages.&#148; </p>
<p>Throughout the strike, management has misled the public, depicting the unions as intransigent. 
It is management's bad faith, however, that sparked the strike. In 1992, the unions -- which 
include Teamster drivers and mailers, the Newspaper Guild, typesetters and press operators 
-- agreed to a pay freeze, accepting management's pleadings that the papers faced severe 
financial hardship. Workers received assurances that once profits were restored they would 
share in the wealth. In 1994, the DNA turned a profit of $355 million, all of which remains in 
management's tight-fisted grip. </p>
<p>One of management's chief objectives is to break the Teamsters. The company wants to can 
1,600 of the 3,000 news carriers. The remaining delivery personnel would become 
independent contractors, without benefits and job protection. The new distribution system 
would increase work levels by expanding delivery areas, and potentially lead to redlining as 
carriers bypass less profitable routes in the inner city and concentrate on higher volume 
subscribers in the predominately white suburbs. </p>
<p>Other unions are being asked to accept changed work rules and reduced health coverage. In 
the case of the Newspaper Guild, a major sticking point is management's push to impose a 
merit pay system. The Guild is not opposed to merit pay in principle, provided all its 
members are guaranteed regular cost of living raises. Union leaders fear, however, that 
management will arbitrarily use the power of the purse to reward submissive employees and 
punish union supporters. One reporter regarded as anti-management received a 1 percent pay 
increase after winning a Pulitzer Prize. </p>
<p>Al Derey, head of Teamsters Local 372 and chair of the Metropolitan Council of Newspaper 
Unions, says &#147;the real truth is that they want a union-free environment. They want low wages 
and they want no benefits. They want us to return to the conditions that the union movement 
fought for over 40 years to attain. Our members said no, and they are standing up fighting for 
their rights out there.&#148; </p>
<p>Bargaining has been at a standstill for weeks with no breakthrough in sight. The unions issued 
a &#147;settlement proposal in early October, including an offer to negotiate $15 million in saved 
labor costs through changes in staffing requirements, a return to work under the terms of 
contracts which expired in April, and intensive bargaining for 30 days with all unresolved 
issues submitted to binding arbitration. The DNA rejected the proposal. </p>
<p>The unions scored a potentially significant victory in September when the National Labor 
Relations Board ruled the strike was over unfair labor practices, citing the company's refusal 
to bargain economic issues jointly. If the unfair labor practice charge holds up in court, the 
company will be forced to release replacement workers and take back strikers -- provided 
their jobs have not been eliminated -- as part of any settlement. </p>
<p>The six striking unions remain united at the bargaining table, resisting management pressures 
to cut separate deals. Prior to the strike, Teamsters working in the mailroom may have shared 
little in common with reporters covering the business beat, but on the picket line strikers form 
a united front. Twenty weeks into the strike, some 2,000 workers remain out, including more 
than 1,000 Teamsters whose strike benefits amount to a scant $55 per week. The weakest 
links in the chain are the reporters represented by the Newspaper Guild. Around half of the 
Guild's 500 reporters are back at work, including star columnist Mitch Albom. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Battle Stations </h3>
<p>To better wage war against the unions, the DNA has hired its own private army. Some 1,200 
paramilitaries pledging allegiance to Vance Security have been shipped to Detroit for the 
duration of the strike. Union-busting is a boom industry and private security companies are 
cashing in. Among the most vicious is Vance Security, founded by a former son-in-law of 
ex-president Gerald Ford. Drawing on police departments and the military for recruits, these 
strike-busting firms boast in promotional brochures that their employees will &#147;arrive with all 
the personal equipment necessary to handle all levels of violence.&#148; </p>
<p>Vance runs ads in Soldier of Fortune magazine, promising to provide mercenary wannabes 
with training in the use of automatic weapons, mace, and riot batons. Its guards have seen 
action against striking Greyhound drivers, fought pitched battles with the United Mine 
Workers at Pittson, and clashed with auto workers at Caterpillar factories. Rather than 
maintain order, these security companies specialize in promoting lawlessness. At legal 
pickets outside newspaper distribution centers, jackbooted guards in full riot gear wade into 
the crowd, hitting demonstrators with batons. These tactics are designed to provoke a 
physical reaction from picketers which is then filmed by Vance. Videotapes are selectively 
edited and used in court to obtain injunctions barring union demonstrations. Employers 
seeking to discredit unions and undermine organizing drives repeatedly play these tapes to 
incite fear among workers. </p>
<p>The Detroit newspapers have used Vance to inflame the community against the unions. In 
early September, a carrier truck inside a printing plant was torched, an action the company 
blamed on strikers. But Kate Desmet, a striking religion writer, says &#147;I saw these goon 
guards standing next to the truck and the next thing I saw was this flame go up...there was no 
panic, no rushing around, no attempt to put it out. It was like they were standing around a big 
camp fire. It was then that I thought 'oh my god. They're setting their own truck on fire'.&#148; </p>
<p>An investigation by the local district attorney identified Vance guards as the arsonists. The 
DA's conclusions did not prevent the Detroit newspapers from running a highly effective 
television ad featuring the burning truck, implying the unions were responsible. </p>
<p>The Detroit newspapers draw on public sector as well as private sector police in their war 
on the unions. At the start of the strike, the DNA rented the police department of Sterling 
Heights, a suburb north of Detroit housing one of the DRA's two main printing plants. Since 
mid-July, the Sterling Heights police have been in a constant state of mobilization defending 
the property rights of the newspapers. In return, the DNA has written the city checks totaling 
more than half a million dollars for police overtime. The expenses continue to mount. 
Sterling Heights has submitted bills totaling $1.9 million, which includes $2,442.85 for 
pepper spray and crowd dispersion grenades and $405 for videotapes used in crowd 
surveillance. </p>
<p>The Sterling Heights police have not hesitated to use their freshly-stocked arsenal. In 
September, police regularly assaulted picketers with clubs and broke up legal demonstrations 
with teargas and pepper spray. </p>
<p>In October the striking unions filed suit against the DNA, Vance, and the Sterling Heights 
police alleging a conspiracy to violate the unions' constitutional rights of free speech and 
assembly. Among the abuses: </p>
<ul>
<li>A security guard rammed his car into the car of a striker while driving down the 
freeway at a speed of 60 miles per hour. </li>
<li>Sterling Heights police pulled over a striker and his wife as they drove to a 
demonstration and forced them onto the ground at gunpoint, threatening to shoot them if 
they moved. The police claimed they were acting on an &#147;anonymous tip&#148; that the union 
member was transporting automatic weapons to the picket line, a charge totally without 
foundation. </li>
<li>Vance Security guards and Sterling Heights police worked together to allow newspaper 
trucks to drive into picket lines at dangerous speeds, forcing union supporters to run for 
their lives. </li>
</ul>
<p>The judicial system has lined up with the DNA in Sterling Heights, granting an injunction 
which limits the unions to a mere ten pickets in the printing plant's driveway. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Look, Honey, I Shrunk the Profits </h3>
<p>Faced with an injunction and the combined firepower of public and private police forces, the 
unions' leadership has chosen to shift the fight from the plant gates. Instead, the unions 
concentrate on punishing the company economically by driving down circulation and 
reducing advertiser revenues. The strike has had a devastating impact on the paper's profits. 
News executives project losses of $56 million through the end of the year, while labor 
leaders and independent analysts believe losses will top $100 million. </p>
<p>The economic impact reaches far beyond Detroit. While the stock market soars and 
corporations reap record earnings, Knight-Ridder's profits are shrinking. Knight Ridder saw 
its third quarter earnings tumble by 82 percent compared to the previous year. Its stock lost 
56 cents per share, with 50 cents of the losses tied to the Detroit strike. Gannett's stock also 
suffered, losing 15 cents a share. </p>
<p>The newspapers are not alone in their losses. The city of Detroit, chronically short of funds 
for public education, transportation, and housing, spent $180,00 in police overtime during the 
first 4 weeks of the strike. </p>
<p>Anthony Ridder, Chief Executive Officer of Knight-Ridder, acknowledges that the papers 
have suffered a circulation loss of at least 20 percent. The papers claim a combined 
circulation of 736,000 compared to a pre-strike figure of 886,000. But the DNA has refused 
an independent audit of circulation, leading the unions to charge that the decline is even 
steeper. Sources inside the plant suggest that the press run barely cracks 500,000. </p>
<p>Regardless of the size of the press run, it's questionable how many papers are actually being 
read. Households which canceled their subscriptions months ago report that news carriers 
continue to litter their yards with unwanted papers. Papers pile up in dumpsters across the 
city and at least one Boy Scout Troop is gathering discarded papers as part of its annual 
paper drive. </p>
<p>Systematic leafleting outside of businesses advertising in the News/Free Press has succeeded 
in driving more than 600 advertisers out of the papers, including national chains such as Toys 
R Us, Montgomery Ward, and Goodyear Tire. K-Mart is the target of a national leafleting 
Campaign spearheaded by the AFL-CIO and the International Brotherhood of Teamsters. 
K-Marts in more than 100 cities across the country are being leafleted, adding to the woes of 
a company already haunted by the prospect of bankruptcy. J.C. Penny and Lord &amp; Taylor, 
major advertisers in Detroit, are also on the AFL-CIO's national hit list. </p>
<p>Desperate to retain advertisers, the DNA has offered businesses substantial discounts, 
amounting to 75 percent in some cases. Even so, a significant number of stores are turning to 
other means to reach consumers. In October 1994, a typical midweek edition of the Detroit 
News contained 128 pages of advertising circulars. A year later, with the strike in full gear, 
circulars ran to just 48 pages. </p>
<p>According to Al Derey, &#147;a newspaper produced and distributed by replacement workers 
violates the standards of our community. In large numbers, readers are no longer buying or 
reading the paper and advertisers are no longer buying ads. And that's why Knight-Ridder's 
profits are down so dramatically.&#148; Industry analysts believe it will take years to restore 
circulation and advertising to pre-strike levels. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>An Injury to One Is an Injury to All </h3>
<p>The Detroit strike has been distinguished by an outpouring of support from the wider labor 
movement. During the first three months of the strike, carpenters, electricians, steel and auto 
workers, janitors, teachers and government employees have participated in all night picket 
lines, leafleted advertisers, and contributed tens of thousands of dollars to striker relief 
funds. </p>
<p>The UAW has been at the forefront of this expanded labor solidarity. In mid-November, 
UAW President Stephen Yokich announced his union would pony up $300,000 to provide 
each newspaper striker with a Thanksgiving gift of $150. But the UAW's commitment is not 
limited to money. More than two dozen locals have &#147;adopted'' stores running ads in the News 
and Free Press, leafleting customers with appeals to shop elsewhere. Some 70 car dealers 
have dropped out of the papers as a result. </p>
<p>With the UAW facing major contract negotiations with the big three auto manufacturers next 
year, sentiment is widespread that the labor movement cannot appear weak in Detroit. 
According to UAW official Paul Massaron, &#147;we think any effort to bust a union should be 
fought back, in this town or any town. We don't think unionbusting should be legal in 
America.&#148; </p>
<p>With labor's prestige on the line in Detroit, the debate on what constitutes a winning strategy 
is intensifying.Since September, the unions have shied away from mass mobilizations to 
disrupt production and distribution of the papers. The first two weekends in September, the 
unions organized all night pickets outside the printing plant in Sterling Heights, mobilizing 
more than 4,000 people on Labor Day weekend. Trucks which normally roll out with the 
Sunday paper on Saturday night were penned in until 8:00 AM Sunday morning, preventing 
many suburban subscribers from receiving their papers until late that afternoon. </p>
<p>The success of the first blockade forced the DNA to employ helicopters to airlift papers out 
of the plant the following weekend. At an estimated cost of $1,000 an hour, the copters 
conducted the most expensive paper route in history. </p>
<p>Conceding the effectiveness of the unions' protest, the DNA obtained an injunction barring the 
union from blocking the driveway. Rather than challenge the injunction and risk lengthy jail 
terms and astronomical fines, the union leadership opted to concentrate on distribution 
centers, a move widely criticized by rank and file dissidents and activists in the wider 
community. </p>
<p>The DNA presently operates some two dozen distribution centers across metropolitan 
Detroit. After being printed, the papers's are transported to these centers and loaded onto 
smaller carrier trucks. The union has mobilized people for all night pickets aimed at one to 
three distribution centers, arriving in the dead of night to stop the trucks. </p>
<p>Critics contend that the switch to distribution centers diffuses the focus of the strike and does 
little to disrupt distribution of the papers. Union leadership maintains a sustained 
confrontation at the plant gate is not winnable at this time and will only drain resources from 
other vital projects. </p>
<p>Proponents of breaking the injunction frequently cite the United Mine Workers 1989 strike at 
Pittston as a model for what could be achieved in Detroit, advocating a nationwide 
mobilization of the labor movement to shut the papers down. Meanwhile, the DNA and the 
unions are hunkering down for a winter war of attrition. </p>
<p>Negotiators for the newspapers are likely to hibernate, hoping that hardship will lead more 
workers to cross the picket line. Gannett and Knight-Ridder appear ready to keep losing tens 
of millions of dollars to achieve their goal of a union-free workplace. </p>
<p>The six unions fighting for their lives will continue with a grab-bag of tactics, from picket 
lines to corporate campaigns. The unions unloaded a major salvo on November 19, 
introducing their own Sunday paper, designed to compete head to head with the News and 
Free Press for readers and advertisers. With an initial press run of 300,000, the paper 
already has the third largest circulation in Michigan. </p>
<p>Richard Trumka, the fire-breathing orator recently elected secretary-treasurer of the 
AFL-CIO, is emphatic about the larger significance of Detroit for labor. According to 
Trumka, &#147;by taking the stance they have, Knight-Ridder and Gannett have, in fact, chosen to 
take on the entire labor movement. While this is not a fight we sought, it is a fight we intend 
to win. The entire labor movement is mobilizing behind Detroit newspaper unions&#148; </p>
<p>Four months into the strike, the majority of workers remain determined to see the fight to the 
finish, understanding that the outcome in Detroit may set the parameters for how far labor can 
bounce back within an increasingly harsh economy. </p>
<p>Susan Watson, a striking newspaper columnist who frequently hits the stump for the union 
cause explains, &#147;It [the strike] frees you in ways you never have been freed before. Yes, 
we've been liberated from our paychecks, but we've been liberated from fear too.&#148; </p>
<p>In Detroit, corporate America is drawing a line, fearful that Susan Watson's feeling of 
liberation may spread to a newly-energized labor movement. </p>
<p><em>Mike Zielinski is an organizer with the Detroit newspaper strike</em>. </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

