<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>About the Wilderness Society</TITLE>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#3A0D9F" vlink="#AF0475" alink="#0E7F09">

<H1 align=center>
About the Wilderness Society
</H1>

<p>
<HR Size="2" Width="100%" Align="Left">
<P>
   Now celebrating its 60th anniversary, The Wilderness Society is a
non-profit conservation group
dedicated to the protection of America's wild lands and wildlife.  As part
of that mission, The Society
works to foster a land ethic.  We rely on a combination of public
education, advocacy, and economic and
ecological analysis.  The Wilderness Society recognizes the importance of
broad ecosystem management
and biodiversity and is building alliances with new constituencies.

<p>
<HR Size="2" Width="100%" Align="Left">


<h2>Vision</h2>

Sustaining the Community of Life:  <br>
The Wilderness Society's Vision for the Future
<p>
  In 1930, Robert Marshall declared that the only hope for the salvation of
the natural world "is the
organization of spirited people who will fight for the freedom of the
wilderness."  The Wilderness
Society, organized five years later, has fought to preserve and protect the
wilderness ever since.  But
not just the wilderness.  Aldo Leopold, one of the eight founders of The
Society, articulated an
additional purpose in his classic book, A Sand County Almanac.  He called
it the Land Ethic, which
"changes the role of Homo sapiens from conqueror of the land-community to
plain member and citizen
of it.  It implies respect for his fellow-members and also respect for the
community as such."

<p>

  This ethic is the foundation on which The Wilderness Society places its
vision for the future.  Our
vision has at its core a profound commitment to secure and maintain the
essential benefits and values
of wilderness:  habitat for the diversity of plant and animal species,
clean air and water, natural
beauty, physical recreation, spiritual renewal, scientific research, and
the opportunity to educate
ourselves and our children about the proper place of humanity in the great
tapestry of the natural
world.

<p>

  We envision a world in which streams run clean from mountain headwaters
to rivers below,
nourishing the land and all that depend upon it.  Across the American
landscape, from canyon to
prairie and forest to ocean, vigorous and healthy populations of native
plant and animal species
flourish in ecosystems sustained by ample protected wild lands.  In this
world, human beings assume
their roles as equal citizens in the great community of life, understanding
that their connection to
the natural world begins at the threshold of each home and extends in all
directions through
neighborhoods, towns, cities, and beyond to the fields, forests, mountains,
deserts, and rivers that are
a common concern of all.

<p>

  Ours is a vision, finally, of a world in which diverse human populations
and the cultural and
political institutions that guide them adhere to the principles of
sustainability and social justice and
in which people work with one another to preserve, restore, and pass on to
future generations an
environment undiminished by their
presence in it.



<p>


<h2>The Society at a Glance</h2>

<ul>
   <li>Founded in January, 1935
   <li>275,000 members nationwide (1981 membership: 54,000)
   <li>11 field offices
   <li>$16 million annual budget
   <li>Sources of funding are membership, 73 percent; foundations, 15
percent;   bequests, four percent; miscellaneous, eight percent
   <li>Full-time staff of 110, including foresters, ecologists, resource
economists, writers, and lawyers
   <li>Publications:  quarterly magazine (Wilderness); newsletters on
endangered species,
        Northwest forests and salmon, "New Voices," and the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge; and
        numerous reports on a range of issues.
   <li>President:  Jon Roush
   <li>Counselor: former Senator Gaylord Nelson, founder of Earth Day
   <li>Tax status: 501 (c)(3)  non-profit membership organization

</ul>

<HR Size="2" Width="100%" Align="Left">

<h2>The Wilderness Society</h2>
<ul>
   <li>  Protect ancient forests of Pacific Northwest and northern California
   <li>  Prevent oil drilling in Arctic National Wildlife Refuge
   <li>  Establish regionwide management for Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem
   <li>  Protect the Colorado Plateau (Four Corner States)
   <li>  Promote a land ethic
   <li>  Double size of National Wilderness System by 2015
   <li>  Reform public lands subsidy programs: logging, mining and grazing
   <li>  Protect endangered plant and wildlife species and conserve biodiversity
   <li>  Educate the public on importance of sustainable development
   <li>  Protect forests of the Southern Appalachians
   <li>  Restore Everglades ecosystem
   <li>  Reduce the external threats to national parks and wildlife refuges
   <li>  Protect the forests of northern New England and Upstate New York
   <li>  Strengthen management of natural wildlife refuges
   <li>  Protect Florida Keys from overdevelopment
</ul></ul>


<HR Size="2" Width="100%" Align="Left">

<h2>Achievements</h2>
<p>
        The Society has played a leadership role in virtually every major
public lands issue of the
     past 50 years.  In more recent years it has been a force behind the
passage of dozens of
     wilderness bills that have added 96 million acres to the wilderness
system since 1964.

<p>

        Other campaigns have included opposing efforts by the Reagan
administrations Interior
     Department to open wilderness areas to oil and gas development, and
pressuring the U.S.
     Forest Service to redo its roadless area evaluation in the mid-1970s.
Recently, The Society has
     worked with timber-dependent communities in the Northwest to help them
diversify their
     economies.

<p>

        In addition, The Society has been a leader in winning a number of
important legislative
     victories, including:

<ul>

     <li>Wilderness Act (1964)
     <li>National Wild and Scenic Rivers Act (1968)
     <li>National Trails System Act (1968)
     <li>Endangered Species Act (1973)
     <li>Federal Land Policy and Management Act (1976)
     <li>National Forest Management Act (1976)
     <li>Omnibus Parks Act (1978)
     <li>Alaska Lands Act (1980)
     <li>Land and Water Conservation Fund Reauthorization (1989)
     <li>Tongass Timber Reform Act (1990)
</ul>

<center><table border>Go back to the <a href="guide.htm">Wilderness Society
Guide to the Internet</a></table></center>


</BODY>
</HTML>



