restrictions at all (e.g. <tt>alt.feminism</tt>). There are thousands upon
thousands of newsgroups to choose from, containing postings from around the
world. Some web browsers (including Netscape) have newsreading capabilities
built in.

<ul>
<li><b><a href="http://scwww.ucs.indiana.edu/NetRsc/usenet.html">Usenet
Newsgroups: Resources</a>
<li><a href="http://gort.ucsd.edu/jj/news/eeg_69.html">EFF's (Extended)
Guide to the Internet: Usenet</a>
<li><a href="http://www.clari.net/brad/emily.html">Emily Postnews</a></b>
</ul>

<P>On LOL you have two ways to access Usenet newsgroups. Some groups are
available within LOL's forum area, for the most efficient possible access,
which you can use just as you would any other LOL forum. To access the rest
of Usenet, you can select a newsreader application from our <!--HREF
HERE-->Internet Page and install it on your computer. (We suggest <!--HERE
TOO-->Free Agent for Windows users.) Each of these applications comes with
its own instructions.

<a name="f"> </a>
<P><b>FTP</b> is a tool for transferring files. (It's short for <i>File
Transfer Protocal</i>.) You can download files on the World Wide Web (by
clicking on them), but FTP has the advantage of letting you send files to
