<title>Feb 96: Letters</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#FF0000" vlink="#001F76" alink="#001F76">
<h3 align=center>From the pages of February 1996</h3>
<h3 align=center><img src="gifs/mdzmag.gif" align=bottom></h3>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="feb96toc.htm">Back to Table of Contents</a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<p align=center><font size=7><strong>Letters </strong></font></p>
<p>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>Postmodernism </h3>
<p>Edward Herman implies with the title of his commentary, &#147;Postmodernism Triumphs,&#148; that he 
is describing &#147;postmodernism&#148; in general. But he qualifies this impression several 
paragraphs in: &#147;There are undoubtedly important elements of truth and insights in active 
audience analysis and other sectors of postmodern thought...&#148; But this qualification of his title 
does not go far enough, for Herman offers only a partial description of the recent work of 
such &#147;postmodernist&#148; writers as Fiske and Morley. </p>
<p>Herman argues that these writers focus on the autonomy of the media consumer and not 
dominant power relations, and thus leave the status quo unchanged. There are three issues 
here. </p>
<p>(1) Herman's devastating analyses of the media pay little attention to the difficult question of 
what effect media bias has on the news consumer. Does the consumer receive the message as 
intended (with intent as interpreted by Herman), or, as Chomsky sometimes implies, does the 
mass audience refuse the totality of the message (how else to explain the consistent rejection 
of Reagan's Central America policy by two-thirds of Americans, despite media bias in favor 
of that policy)? </p>
<p>(2) Part (but only a part) of the disagreement between Herman and the &#147;postmodernists&#148; lies, 
I think, in the different media they critique. Herman has largely focused on news media and 
its supposed factual statements about the world, while Fiske and others often focus on 
fictional entertainment, in which the readings preferred by the dominant ideology are not as 
easily guaranteed. In a television drama, e.g., a particular scene may resonate over other 
parts of the narrative, including the happy ending's apparent resolution of contradictions. 
News reports sometimes may be similarly unstable, but they are usually less open to a variety 
of interpretations than is a Michael Jackson video. </p>
<p>(3) Finally, Morley and Fiske, contrary to the impression Herman gives, do not disregard 
ideology and hegemony. In Power Plays /Power Works (1993), Fiske makes an explicit effort 
to meld the insights of Gramsci and Foucault (and not a politically irresponsible 
postmodernist like Baudrillard), while stressing the global problem of racism. For Morley, 
in Television, Audiences &amp; Cultural Studies (1992), &#147;the challenge lies precisely in the 
attempt to construct a model of television consumption which is sensitive to both the 
`vertical' dimension of power and ideology and the `horizontal' dimension of television's 
insertion in, and articulation with, the context and practices of everyday life.&#148; </p>
<p>Now, one can criticize the lack of clarity of the phrase &#147;articulation with,&#148; or show how 
Morley falls short of the goal he sets himself here; but to argue that Morley et al. belong in 
the camp of multinational capitalism because they avoid assessing ideological impact is 
unfair. Herman has missed an opportunity to usefully engage and criticize work that loosely 
falls under the label &#147;postmodernist.&#148; </p>
<p><em>Uday Mohan, Washington, DC </em></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Herman replies: </h3>
<p>Uday Mohan's letter raises important questions that I can only address briefly here. On point 
(1), while news consumers often do not fully accept (and may entirely reject) media and elite 
propaganda messages, those messages can still have powerful effects; in the case of the war 
on Nicaragua, paralyzing the Democrats and weakening public opposition enough to allow 
many years of aggression. In the case of the current budget controversy, the media have 
helped put over a ploy that allows majority interests to be overridden (see current &#147;Fog 
Watch&#148;). </p>
<p>On (2), it is true that active audience theorists focus heavily on entertainment, but they 
underrate both the diversionary aspect of the triumph of entertainment (displacing a public 
sphere) and the extent to which deeper propaganda-ideological messages can be imbedded in 
entertainment (as described in Barnouw's chapter on Entertainment in The Sponsor). </p>
<p>On (3), Mohan misses the strongly individualistic thrust of Morley's and Fiske's work, whose 
essence is showing audience power and deflecting attention from the impact of 
commercialization and concentrated media control. Note even the aim stated in the quoted 
sentence from Morley, to construct a model of &#147;consumption.&#148; Fiske has written a book 
entitled Media Matters because the import of his earlier work (still embedded in later 
writing) was that media (control, power) doesn't matter because viewers will read and 
inflect and the market will have to accommodate audience demands. </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

