naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h2><font color="#961814"><em>Fees</em></font></h2>
        <p><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="client on line" startspan -->Left On Line<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="17324" --> is not
        free. To remain a member of <!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> you pay
        $8 a month for unlimited access from your browser to the
        full <!--webbot bot="Substitution" s-variable="col"
        startspan -->LOL<!--webbot bot="Substitution" endspan
        i-checksum="538" --> site. The ZNet site, in contrast,
        though developed and maintained by the same people, is
        free. What's the difference?</p>
        <blockquote>
            <p><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
            height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"> The ZNet site, like
            many free sites, attempts to reach out to new
            audience and to provide resources to a wide array of
            people not yet ready to become more directly involved
            and supportive. It is a public &quot;front room&quot;
            to spread useful information and simultaneously
            attract people to various institutions and projects,
            such as Z Magazine, South End Press, and Speakout,
            and <!--webbot bot="Substitution" s-variable="col"
            startspan -->LOL<!--webbot bot="Substitution"
            endspan i-checksum="538" -->. ZNet has limited
            offerings and requires modest maintainence. The
            assumption is that users are passing through...</p>
            <p><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
            height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"> The <!--webbot
            bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
            bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> site,
            on the other hand, is for a closed community of folks
            who are more committed to sustained and supportive
            involvement. It requires far more equipment and
            maintainence on our part and offers far more content,
            community, and functionality to users. It assumes
            users believe in the site, in the offerings, in the
            project, and want to not only benefit from it, but
            also support it.</p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>Well and good, you might say, but still: why charge
        for it? </p>
        <p>Maintaining sites, whether public or private, involves
        paying fees for linkages, to maintain equipment, and to
        continually refine and update content. Where is the money
        to do all this to come from? Currently, throughout the
        internet there are only three available options.</p>
        <blockquote>
            <p><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
            height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"> Depend on ad
            revenue.</p>
            <p><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
            height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"> Charge users a
            regular fee, or</p>
            <p><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
            height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"> Have some agency or
            institution foot the bill as a donation</p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>We couldn't get sufficient ads for <!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> even if
        we wanted them, but, more important, relying on ads would
        subvert our anti-commerical aims. We are not interested
        in selling users to corporate marketeers, which is
        precisely the business any ad driven site or periodical
        is in. We also lack a benefactor, however. So we need
        user support. The long and short of it, then, is this:</p>
        <blockquote>
            <p><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
            height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"> We cannot moderate
            and enliven forums, provide ever-changing and
            enlarging online content, develop ever-diversifying
            modules and functionality, maintain reliable, robust
            equipment, attract and maintain writers and other
            content providers, etc., without charging a fee.</p>
            <p><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
            height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"> We therefore hope
            you agree with us that getting self-sustaining and
            even surplus generating progressive and left
            telecommunications projects and sites into operation
            should be a priority for socially conscious folks,
            and we hope you will join us in the effort.&nbsp;</p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>At this point, to proceed, you can choose any option
        in the list of links below to get more information about <!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" -->, or you
        can <font size="3">return to </font><a
        href="http://www.lbbs.org"><font size="2" face="Arial"><strong>ZNet</strong></font></a><font
        size="3">. </font>Ultimately, the best way to learn about
        the system is to join it. You get 3 free hours or use or
        15 days membership, whichever expires first, free to get
        a feel for the contents.</p>
        <blockquote>
            <dl>
                <dt><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
                    height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"><a
                    href="visitabout.htm"><font size="2"
                    face="Arial"><strong>About</strong></font><font
                    size="1" face="Arial"><strong> </strong></font><font
                    size="2" face="Arial"><strong><!--webbot
                    bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan
                    -->LOL<!--webbot bot="Substitution" endspan
                    i-checksum="538" -->'s Features</strong></font></a><font
                    size="2" face="Arial"><strong> </strong></font></dt>
                <dt><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
                    height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"><a
                    href="lolvisfaq.htm"><font size="2"
                    face="Arial"><strong>LOL FAQs</strong></font></a> </dt>
                <dt><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
                    height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"><a
                    href="viscommunity.htm"><font size="2"
                    face="Arial"><strong>Our Community
                    &quot;Definition&quot;</strong></font></a> </dt>
                <dt><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
                    height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"><a
                    href="loljoin.htm"><font size="2"
                    face="Arial"><strong>Information About
                    Joining</strong></font></a> </dt>
                <dt><img src="dot.gif" align="middle" width="20"
                    height="20" naturalsizeflag="1"><a
                    href="http://lbbs.org/newuser"><font size="2"
                    face="Arial"><strong>Join Now</strong></font></a> </dt>
            </dl>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
