naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><img src="images/ani4.gif" width="281" height="103"
        naturalsizeflag="3"></p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="images/redfaq.gif" width="432" height="30"
naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font color="#961814"><em><strong>(1) Why should I
        bother paying for access to a web site, particularly a
        leftist one intent on involving, educating, and
        empowering a broad public, most of whose members are
        financially hurting?</strong></em></font></p>
        <p>There are two answers to this question -- one somewhat
        crass and &quot;market oriented,&quot; the other
        embodying a higher level of consciousness and clarity of
        purpose..</p>
        <p>First, <strong><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --></strong><em><strong> </strong></em>offers
        many features that you simply cannot get elsewhere and
        that we can't provide without revenues. What are these
        unique offerings? Our closed forums, the online school,
        the book club, the kids center, the research tools, the
        wealth of special information, and the special content
        such as Marble or ShareWorld Weekly. Our community of
        users, our activism offerings, etc. And it is also our
        &quot;editorial&quot; help in dealing with the mass of
        materials that are otherwise just an amorphous blob on
        the net. It is our reviews of sites and constant updating
        of links, and much more.</p>
        <p>But, second, <strong><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>is
        part of a very ambitious undertaking to bring the
        progressive community into the world of
        telecommunications in a way which enhances activist
        outreach and organizational power. This takes money, pure
        and simple. And when you pay for <strong><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>you
        are therefore supporting not only ShareWorld and <strong><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --></strong>,
        but also <strong><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --></strong>'s
        and ShareWorld's many sponsoring organizations and the
        entire progressive and left project in the U.S. Money
        spent on <strong><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>goes
        in all these directions, in large amounts ranging from
        20% to 33% of our gross revenues, depending on how
        efficiently we are able to function..</p>
        <p>Yes, it is true that you can get a lot of information
        on the Internet free--if you ignore that the advertising
        is, like it or not, sucking you dry and compromising the
        content. But what you can't do free on the internet is
        support the development of progressive and left
        infrastructure. That requires financial support as well
        as intellectual and social participation.</p>
        <p>We are not asking you to do anything we don't do
        ourselves. We pay various organizations for content which
        they make available free to others and which we could, in
        fact, access for free ourselves as well. Why don't we go
        the free route, taking the information for nothing?
        Because we feel that these progressive sources of
        information need revenues from us if they are to continue
        doing their work well and outreach more broadly, too. And
        that is the same reason why we hope you will want to pay
        for our offerings.</p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="images/redline.gif" width="432" height="4"
naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font color="#961814"><em><strong>(2) Is <!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> complete
        and ready?</strong></em></font></p>
        <p>No. In factm it is just getting off the ground so much
        of it is still under development. But actually, this will
        never change. Because <strong><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --></strong>
        is and will always remain a project under development.
        The more that is undone, the more new facets and
        capabilities there will be in the future. It is a good
        sign. Don't read it negatively...</p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="images/redline.gif" width="432" height="4"
naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font color="#961814"><em><strong>(3) How reliable is <!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" -->; should I
        expect continual breakdowns?</strong></em></font></p>
        <p><strong><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>should
        be just as reliable as the Internet more broadly, which
        is not an entirely encouraging answer.</p>
        <p>The Internet is growing faster than it is as yet able
        to support so there will be times when your internet
        access is slow or even unavailable. Huge providers like
        UUNET and Sprintnet often have partial or even complete
        outages and this can impact virtually everyone on the
        net, and especially everyone in vicinity of the problem
        areas. But as long as you are able to browse and function
        online at all, <strong><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>should
        be available to you as well. Our E-Mail, forums, and
        other services should be as reliable as Microsoft's
        network, or AOL's, and then some. That is our aim...</p>
        <p>When we fall short, you should let us know about it.
        OK, you should be supportive and understanding, but you
        shouldn't be quiet.</p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="images/redline.gif" width="432" height="4"
naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font color="#961814"><em><strong>(4) What is the best
        browser to use to reach <!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" -->, or for
        Web Browsing more generally?</strong></em></font></p>
        <p>Some questions have no answer. Some of the technicians
        at <strong><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>and
        at ShareWorld use Netscape Version 2, more use Version 3.
        Others use Microsoft Explorer Version 3 including me, the
        system sysop. No doubt we will all update when new
        versions become available.</p>
        <p>No one who works at any ShareWorld facility uses any
        browser other than these.</p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="images/redline.gif" width="432" height="4"
naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font color="#961814"><em><strong>(5) Who should I use
        for my Internet Provider?</strong></em></font></p>
        <p>The best bet is usually an unlimited Internet Account
        which costs right around $20 a month. If you are good
        with computers and therefore can get on and off quickly,
        and if you have limited online desires, then you might do
        better with an account that costs only $5 or $10 a month
        but gives you very limited hours, say 5 or 10.</p>
        <p>OK, but which provider should you sign up with?</p>
        <p>Well, the first criterion is that the provider offers
        a dial-up number you can reach without having to pay a
        long distance charge. That is crucial, of course.</p>
        <p>But after that, grounds for choice are more subtle:
        reliability of connections, technical support, quality of
        the tools provided, etc. Competition among national
        providers is so fierce that all generally get comparable
        marks on these scores. Local providers that are stable
        and have some history often do at least as well,
        sometimes better.</p>
        <p>The next criteria would be does the provider offer
        content as well, at no extra cost. Some do, and you might
        benefit from this though sometimes it is so commercial as
        to be highly aggravating.</p>
        <p>And there is another criteria, at least for
        politically conscious people and especially folks on <strong><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --></strong>/ShareWorld:
        Is there any provider I can use which will give me top
        notch service, resources, and tools, but which is also
        going to benefit things I believe in?</p>
        <p>The answer turns out to be yes.</p>
        <p><strong><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --></strong>/ShareWorld
        has entered an alliance with Prodigy Internet. If you let
        us establish an account with them for you, they pay us
        quite a nice sum for having brought you to them. They
        also provide you with tools that are specially contoured
        to our system. All in all, you get one of the best
        Internet providers available, at the typically least
        expensive rate available, with huge numbers of local
        numbers to call, going out of its way to specially
        service you with tools contoured to use with our system
        as well as the Internet more broadly--and we get some
        much needed additional revenue. It is a choice worth
        considering... You can do it online and easily, with some
        of the benefit accruing to us, once you join <strong><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" -->.</strong></p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="images/redline.gif" width="432" height="4"
naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><em><strong>(</strong></em><font color="#961814"><em><strong>6)
        Does <!--webbot bot="Substitution" s-variable="col"
        startspan -->LOL<!--webbot bot="Substitution" endspan
        i-checksum="538" --> serve all computer users alike? Can
        we all access it equally?</strong></em></font></p>
        <p>Well, no. </p>
        <p>Anyone with a browser that will do frames such as
        current versions of Netscape Navigator (back to 2.0) and
        of Microsoft Explorer (back to 3.0) can access <strong><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>and
        enjoy its contents and features. If your browser won't do
        frames, however, then to enjoy <strong><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>you
        will need to upgrade. </p>
        <p>Beyond frames, <strong><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>also
        incorporates audio and animation features. All the more
        modern browsers can deal with this very well, but again,
        some users may need to upgrade. </p>
        <p>Also, while of course we have no leaning toward a set
        of people based on what hardware they use, the fact is,
        in the past, right now, and probably for the foreseeable
        future, depending on what hardware people use they have
        slightly different software options available. It was
        once the case that MAC users had significant software
        advantages in ease of use and functionality in many types
        of software applications, including, for example,
        graphics tool, publishing tools, and also online tools.
        These advantages for MAC users are declining, in some
        cases disappearing entirely. And now users on other
        platforms have some advantages of their own.</p>
        <p>At the moment, for example, there happen to be some
        Client Server programs that work with our underlying site
        technologies -- chosen for other reasons entirely -- that
        work on Windows platforms but no others. It makes no
        sense for us to hide these options. The fact that some
        folks have these added options, for example, in the games
        section, is not a matter of prejudice against others, or
        of favoritism toward those who benefit, but just a fact
        of programming life for the moment.</p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="images/redline.gif" width="432" height="4"
naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font color="#961814"><em><strong>(7) Who runs <!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" -->? Who
        makes the decisions? What say do you have?</strong></em></font></p>
        <p><strong><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>was
        created by <em>Z Magazine</em> staff as a system called
        ZBBS, some years ago. It metamorphised into <strong><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --></strong>,
        and then undertook to establish the broader ShareWorld
        project so that now it is but one part of that broader
        &quot;system of interlocked systems.&quot;</p>
        <p>Each ShareWorld system is partly under the auspices of
        ShareWorld per se, partly under the auspices of its
        sponsoring organization or organizations, and partly
        under the auspices of its users. That is, if you look at
        the totality of decisions and choices that go to
        determine the evolution of these systems and their
        policies, ShareWorld, the sponsoring organizations, and
        each system's users, each have a hand.</p>
        <p>ShareWorld makes decisions primarily about
        technologies, overall functionality/design, ShareWorld
        generated content, and pricing.</p>
        <p>Sponsoring organizations, such as <em>Z Magazine</em>,
        etc., make decisions about specific design elements of
        their own systems and their own system's content, about
        their contributions to universally available offerings
        such as courses, as well as their special staff
        offerings, etc.</p>
        <p>Users decide their own levels of participation, and,
        in doing so, determine the content of forums, course
        discussions, SW Weekly and SW Poetry, etc.</p>
        <p>More, forums for discussion of <strong><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> </strong>and
        ShareWorld policy give users a chance to propose new
        options and to advocate on behalf of competing policies.
        When appropriate, Polls will provide input as well.</p>
        <p>In the current world we cannot implement ideal
        decision making structures. Money, markets, state
        structures, prior habits, and many other factors all
        impede even the best intentions. What we can do, however,
        is to try to create a system and community in which
        people can impact outcomes as closely as possible in
        proportion to the degree they are affected by them.</p>
        <blockquote>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p align="center"><a
            href="http://www.lol.shareworld.com/leftonl/lolvis.htm"><font
            size="2" face="Arial"><strong>Return to <!--webbot
            bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
            bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" -->
            Visitor's Top Page</strong></font></a></p>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
