<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Visitors: LOL and ShareWorld Community</title>
<base target="viewarea">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
</head>

<body background="images/redback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFA"
link="#FF0000" vlink="#FF0000" alink="#FF0000">

<p><img src="images/redline.gif" width="432" height="4"
naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><img src="images/ani4.gif" width="281" height="103"
        naturalsizeflag="3"></p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="images/redswcom.gif" width="432" height="30"
naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p align="left">Contemporary society is marked by
        fragmentation and alienation. Loneliness is commonplace.
        Folks pass one another like isolated, jostling, atoms
        without mutual interests and potentials to explore rarely
        having an opportunity to engage one another in serious,
        meaningful discussion aimed at improving society and
        their own lives. Agendas are created only from on high,
        by the most elite elites. </p>
        <p><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="client on line" startspan -->Left On Line<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="17324" --> seeks
        to become a community of users and ShareWorld a community
        of communities, meaning a place where many many people
        respect and communicate, socialize, develop agendas,
        share resources. </p>
        <p>We are under no illusions about this. </p>
        <p>An online community, and online relationships among
        people generally, are a far cry from face to face
        friendships and involvements. But, when you start talking
        about communities of people stretching across a whole
        society, and even around the world, online tools offer a
        remarkable vehicle for developing solidarity and
        understanding and, even more, for allowing people to
        learn from and teach one another, to enjoy one another,
        to share experiences and desires, and, perhaps most
        important, to develop shared perceptions and agendas
        which can be counterposed to those handed down from on
        high by the most elite elites.</p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="images/redline.gif" width="432" height="4"
naturalsizeflag="3"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h2><font color="#800000"><em><strong>So how are we going
        to do this?</strong></em></font></h2>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p>Well, we have some ideas and tools in place, which are
        described below. But we know that these represent, at
        best, an exciting start. We need to think on this issue
        and we need to do it collectively. A few system operators
        can't build a community among thousands and thousands,
        perhaps tens and soon hundreds of thousands of people,
        unless these people are partaking of the effort,
        actively. We need <!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> members
        and ShareWorld members more generally to get excited
        about the potential pleasure, insight, knowledge, and
        political power that could accrue from our structures if
        we can create lasting ties and trust within our
        communities, and if we can together develop shared
        agendas and committments.</p>
        <p>Is it a pipedream? </p>
        <p>We can't see why. Our system can link hundreds of
        thousands, even millions of people, each able to function
        individually, each a part of a personally selected local
        community (such as Left On Line, or Nation on Line, or
        GreenPeace on Line), and each also a member of the
        neighborhood of all these communities, sharing resources
        and insights, courses and lectures, readings and
        experiences, opinions, polls, votes, activist projects,
        and desires...eventually, development of agendas and
        encompassing projects. </p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p>It seems to us the first step forward is to discuss it
        broadly, together. We have two forums for doing this: <font
        color="#FF0000" size="3"><strong>Left On Line Policy</strong></font>
        and <font color="#FF0000" size="3"><strong>ShareWorld
        Policy</strong></font>. the idea is to take off on the
        above comments and explore potentials and methods in a
        freewheeling way, hopefully leading to ideas we can
        implement.</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font size="3">We have other tools, as well. For
        example, among many forums in which solidarity and
        community can be fostered, in particular we have </font><font
        color="#FF0000" size="3"><strong>Hello, Activism, </strong></font><font
        size="3">and</font><font color="#FF0000" size="3"><strong>
        Personal Forums</strong></font><font size="3"> where
        people can tell a bit about themselves and exchange
        personal greetings, discuss activist experiences and
        propose new possibilities, and talk together about
        personal problems and needs, etc. We also have a wide
        array of </font><font color="#FF0000" size="3"><strong>Expert
        Forums</strong></font><font size="3"> where people with
        great knowledge and experience in particular fields
        answer questions and help other users.</font></p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font size="3">Another tool is our </font><font
        color="#FF0000" size="3"><strong>Pen Pal </strong></font><font
        size="3">system which allows </font><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --><font
        size="3"> users to make themselves available both as
        experts helpers and potential &quot;pen pals&quot; or
        &quot;online guides&quot; for other users.</font></p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p>We think <font color="#FF0000"><strong>SW Weekly</strong></font>
        and <font color="#FF0000"><strong>SW Poetry</strong></font>,
        which will begin to take shape as soon as we have enough
        folks online to sustain them, will also be excellent
        tools for building a sense of community. The first will
        be a user written and user edited product of the entire
        neighborhood of all the component systems of ShareWorld.
        And SW Poetry will be similar, but instead of being an
        online periodical, it will be a growing library of poetry
        contributed by members of all the online systems.&nbsp;</p>
        <p><font size="3">Also planned, in time we will be
        holding </font><font color="#FF0000" size="3"><strong>Online
        Conferences</strong></font><font size="3">. And, when
        membership in </font><!--webbot bot="Substitution"
        s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --><font
        size="3"> and other ShareWorld Systems climbs high
        enough, we will sponsor </font><font color="#FF0000"
        size="3"><strong>Local and Regional Face-To-Face
        Gatherings and Events</strong></font><font size="3"> for
        members throughout the country. Only time and experience
        will delineate all the community building potentials of </font><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> and
        ShareWorld.</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>
        <p align="center"><a
        href="http://www.lol.shareworld.com/leftonl/lolvis.htm"><font
        size="2" face="Arial"><strong>Return to <!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --> Visitor's
        Top Page</strong></font></a></p>
        <p align="center"><font size="3">&nbsp;</font><a
        href="loljoin.htm"><font size="2" face="Arial"><strong>Information
        About Joining </strong></font></a><a
        href="http://www.lol.shareworld.com/leftonl/lolvis.htm"><font
        size="2" face="Arial"><strong><!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="col" startspan -->LOL<!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" endspan i-checksum="538" --></strong></font></a></p>
        <p align="center"><a
        href="http://lol.shareworld.com/chbin/main/logon?uid=guest&amp;pw=guest&amp;link=/chbin/mod/newuser"><font
        size="2" face="Arial"><strong>Join <!--webbot
        bot="Substitution" s-variable="client on line" startspan
        -->Left On Line<!--webbot bot="Substitution" endspan
        i-checksum="17324" --> Now</strong></font></a></p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
</blockquote>
