<header>
<title>Locke Purnell Rain Harrell -  Firm History</title>
</header>
<body background="linen.gif" text="000000" link="2F4F2F" vlink="A62A2A">
<center>
<img src="lprh_grn.gif">
<BR>
<BR>
<H2>History</H2>
<BR>
<BR>
</center>
In 1891, Maurice E. Locke, a former mathematics professor at Valparaiso University, began
practicing law in Dallas.  While representing a widow against a life insurance company,
Locke utilized his mathematical expertise to confound the insurer's actuaries.  Thereafter,
insurance companies began to retain Mr. Locke in their own behalf.  By the time E. P. Locke
joined his father's law practice in 1904, the firm had begun to specialize in the representation
of life insurance companies, most notably The Mutual Life Insurance Company Of New York
and The Equitable Life Assurance Society of the United States.  These origins have evolved into
a broad commercial and financial practice.
<P>
After his father's death in 1919, E. P. Locke continued building the firm's base of life
insurance clients.  He was serving as a director of The Equitable Life Assurance Society of the
United States when he died in 1946.  For the next quarter century, Maurice E. Purnell and
Eugene E. Locke, grandsons of the founder, were the firm's dominant partners.  Purnell, the
managing partner during this period, is best remembered for having been the principal draftsman
of the Texas Trust Act of 1943.  Locke, during a leave of absence from the firm, was
Ambassador to Pakistan (1966-67), Deputy Ambassador to South Vietnam (1967-68) and an
unsuccessful candidate for Governor of Texas (1968).  Purnell and Locke both died in 1972, the
same year the firm incorporated as Locke, Purnell, Boren, Laney & Neely (A Professional
Corporation).
<P>
 Rain Harrell Emery Young & Doke was founded in 1965 by six attorneys who left
successful positions in a major Dallas firm to strike out on their own.  They developed a varied
business practice emphasizing complex corporate transactions and commercial litigation for a
broad client base, including many publicly held corporations. Morris Harrell was selected in
1988 by the Chief Justice of the United States Supreme Court, William H. Rehnquist, to serve
a minimum three year term on the Judicial Fellows Commission, an 11 member body
responsible for selecting individuals to serve in the Judicial Fellows Program.  He has also
served as President of the prestigious American College of Trial Lawyers, President of the
American Bar Association, President of the Dallas Bar Association and President of the State
Bar of Texas.

<p>On June 1, 1987, Locke, Purnell, Boren, Laney & Neely and Rain Harrell Emery Young
& Doke merged forming one of the largest law firms in Dallas and the Southwest:  Locke
Purnell Rain Harrell (A Professional Corporation).<P>

