<header>
<title>Statement of Specialization</title>
<body background="linen.gif" text="000000" link="2F4F2F" vlink="A62A2A">
<center><img src="lprh_grn.gif">
<p>
<H2>
Statement of Specialization
</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
A list of <a href="alist.htm"><b>Locke Purnell Rain Harrell attorneys</a></b> 
is provided.  Unless specified otherwise, the attorneys are either:
<p>
<ul>
     <li>Not Certified by the Texas Board of Legal Specialization; or<br>
     <li>"No designation has been made by the Texas Board of Legal 
          Specialization for a Certificate of Special Competence in [the] 
          area" of practice of the attorney.<br>
</ul>
<p>
In Texas, a Certificate of Special Competence can only be obtained for the 
<a href="area.htm"><b>certain specialties</a></b>.
<p>
     In addition to the <a href="area.htm"><b>listed areas</a></b> of "Special 
Competence", the Texas rules allow the following types of practitioners to hold 
themselves out as particular types of "specialists"<br>
<ul>
     <li>"A lawyer admitted to practice before the United States Patent Office 
          [sic] may use the designation "Patents," "Patent Attorney," or 
          "Patent Lawyer or any combination of those terms."<br>
     <li>"A lawyer engaged in the trademark practice may use the designation 
          "Trademark,""Trademark Attorney," or "Trademark Lawyer" or any 
          combination of those terms."<br>
     <li>" A lawyer engaged in patent and trademark practice may hold himself 
          out as specializing in "Intellectual Property Law," "Patents, or 
          Trademarks and Related Matters," or "Patent, Trademark, Copyright Law 
          and Unfair Competition" or any of those terms.<br>
</ul>
<p>
     <i>See</i> the Texas Disciplinary Rules of Professional Conduct, Rule 7.01.
<p>

