<BR>W.B. Carrell Clinic Association
<BR>William M. Osbourne, M.D., P.A.
<BR>W. Pennock Laird, M.D., P.A.
<P> The shareholders and associates in the firm's Health Care Practice Group have varied
experience in the following areas:

<P><B><U>GENERAL HEALTH CARE ADVICE</U></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <B>Donna D. Fraiche</B><BR>
Ms. Fraiche is a shareholder in the firm and chairs its Health Law practice.  She served as
President of the National Health Lawyers Association and chaired the Association's national
program on medical staff legal issues and co-chaired its program entitled &quot;A Regional
Perspective on the Structure and Legal Issues of Integrated Delivery Systems.&quot;  She is the
current chair of the Louisiana Health Care Commission.  Ms. Fraiche is a diplomate of the
American College of Health Care Executives and is on the adjunct faculty of Tulane University's
School of Public Health and Administration.  She has experience representing all types of health
care organizations, entities and individuals in various transactions, in litigation and general
advice.  She is focused on managed care and integrated delivery systems, antitrust, and fraud and
abuse regulations.  Ms. Fraiche is an author and frequent lecturer in the health law field.  Her
biography is included in the 1993-1994 and the 1995-1996 editions, <I>The Best Lawyers in
America</I>, Louisiana, Health Law.
<P> <B>Jan Reimann Newsom</B><BR>
Ms. Newsom, Senior Counsel, has more than 20 years of experience in the health and life
insurance industry.  She has knowledge of health care-related legal issues an regulatory
requirements.  Ms. Newsom's practice includes advising on managed care network formation and
integrated delivery systems (PHOs, IPAs, MSOs, etc.); regulatory concerns and licensing issues
involving third party administrators and utilization review agents, as well as insurance
companies, PPOs and HMOs; benefit plan design dealing with managed care issues and
Medicare and Medicaid reimbursement issues including secondary payor determinations, Stark
law and fraud and abuse compliance concerns.  Ms. Newsom is a regular speaker at health care
related seminars and workshops on structuring integrated delivery systems, managed care
liability issues and stark law and fraud and abuse compliance.
<P> <B>Elaine W. Selle</B><BR>
Ms. Selle is an associate in the Health Law Section in the firm's New Orleans office. She
graduated from Loyola School of Law with honors in 1986.  She has concentrated experience in
the medical malpractice litigation, defending hospitals, nursing homes, physicians, and other
health care providers.  She has given numerous presentations and participated in panel forums
addressing medical staff issues, managed care, contracts, risk management, peer review, and
professional liability. She has also advised hospitals and physicians on the legal issues of
informed consent, documentation, release of medical records, and data bank reporting
requirements. Ms. Selle has authored textbook chapters on medical malpractice and has given
interviews that were published in the Chicago Tribune and other health care publications on
managed care and professional medical liability.  She is a faculty member of the National
Institute for Trial Advocacy, the American Physical Therapy Association, and the Joint
Commission on Accreditation of Hospitals organization.
<P><B> </B><B>Margaret W. Silverstein</B><BR>
Ms. Silverstein is an associate in the firm's healthcare practice area.  Her experience includes
dealing with corporate issues, tax exempt 501(c)(3) issues, contractual issues and Medicare and
Medicaid reimbursement issues.  Recently, Ms. Silverstein's practice has centered on providing
advice to physicians and hospitals concerning the regulatory implications of proposed business
ventures, such as the formation of a physician organization, the sale of a physician practice, the
formation of a health care management company and the formation of a medical clinic.  Ms.
Silverstein's practice also focuses in large part on physician and hospital contracts.  
<P> <B>Danielle Lombardo Trostorff</B><BR>
Ms. Trostorff is a shareholder and member of the health care practice group.  She has served as
President and Past President of the Louisiana Society of Hospital Attorneys, an affiliate of the
Louisiana Hospital Association and is Past-President of the Women's Healthcare Executive
Network, an affiliate of the American College of Healthcare Executives and currently serves on
the American College of Healthcare Executives Regent's Advisory Council for Louisiana.  She is
admitted to practice law in Texas, Louisiana, New York and the District of Columbia.  She
serves as adjunct professor in health care law at Tulane University's School of Public Health and
Tropical Medicine.  Her health care practice includes preferred provider organizations, advising
physicians, hospitals, home health agencies, health maintenance organizations, physical
therapists, employers, and insurers on corporate, contracting, medical staff, fraud and abuse,
reimbursement, ERISA and managed care matters and is currently involved in structuring
various managed care joint ventures with insurers and providers.  She has practiced exclusively
in the healthcare area since 1981.  She has represented numerous healthcare clients in providing
general fraud and abuse advice on practice, contracting and joint venture activities. She has
successfully represented healthcare providers in termination and suspension proceedings before
the Office of Inspector General, Medicare carriers, and fiscal intermediaries.  She has also
assisted healthcare clients in post pay audits and recoupment actions and in Department of
Justice and DEA investigations.  She is a member of the Texas Hospital Association, American
College of Healthcare Executives, National Health Lawyers Association, the American Academy
of Hospital Attorneys, the ABA Health Law Forum Committee, Louisiana Society of Hospital
Attorneys of the Louisiana Hospital Association, and Federal Bar Association Health Law
Section. She has been listed as one of the Best Lawyer's in America in Healthcare and featured as
a Woman to Watch by New Orleans CityBusiness.  She was also profiled in the Washington
University Magazine and Alumni News.  She has published numerous health law articles and
frequently lectures nationally on health law issues.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><U>CORPORATE AND SECURITIES</U></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <B>Elizabeth A. Cook</B>
<P> <B>Robert Graham</B>
<BR>Mr. Graham is a shareholder in the firm's corporate and securities section. Mr. Graham's
practice focuses on the representation of business entities, including health care related entities,
that are engaged in public and private debt and equity financings, joint ventures, venture capital
financings and mergers and acquisitions.
<P> <B>Kent Jamison</B>
<BR>Mr. Jamison is a shareholder in the firm's corporate and securities section.  Mr. Jamison
has experience in asset and stock acquisitions and divestitures and corporate mergers, business
organization formations, venture capital transactions and employee benefit plan matters in such
industries as healthcare, information services, technology and manufacturing.  Recently, in the
healthcare area, Mr. Jamison's work has focused on structuring private offering alternatives with
respect to group practices. 
<P><B>Robert Taylor</B>
<P> 
<P> <B>Edward Toles</B>
<BR>Mr. Toles is a shareholder in the firm's public finance and corporate section.  Mr. Toles has
experience in structuring, negotiating and managing health care financing transactions,
particularly those involving tax-exempt bonds.  Mr. Toles' experience includes representation in
financing transaction of health care organizations, underwriters, banks and trustees.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><U>TAXATION/TAX EXEMPTION</U></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B> </B><B>Christopher F. Allison</B>
<P> <B>E. Philip Bush</B> 
<BR>Mr. Bush is a shareholder in the firm's tax section.  Mr. Bush has experience in analyzing,
negotiating and resolving tax, corporate, benefits and compensation issues unique to non-profit
hospitals and medical practices, especially in cases of integrated health delivery networks. 
Recently, his work has focused on issues arising from the merger and acquisition of professional
practices in the health care field.  As Chairman of the Personal Service Organization Committee
of the American Bar Association Tax Section, Mr. Bush is a frequent author and lecturer on
choice of entity, tax and employee benefit matters affecting health care and other professional
practices.
<P> <B>Michele Courtois</B>
<BR>Ms. Courtois is an associate in the firm's tax section and Board Certified in Taxation by
Texas Board of Legal Specialization.  Ms. Courtois has considerable experience in drafting and
operational compliance of all forms of qualified plans (defined benefit and defined contribution),
nonqualified plans and welfare benefit plans (health, disability and death benefit plans);
representing employers and plan administrators before the U.S. Department of Labor and Internal
Revenue Service on ERISA and qualified plan matters; and reviewing and analyzing complex
business structures and the impact on employee benefit programs.  She represents hospitals,
medical practice groups and other health care providers in employee benefit and tax matters and
isan author and lecturer on employee benefit and tax issues affecting the health care industry.
<P> <B>R. Kevin Hardage</B>
<BR>Mr. Hardage is an associate in the firm's tax and corporate sections.  Mr. Hardage is
experienced in the analysis of federal income tax issues associated with business transactions
pertaining to personal service organizations, including medical and practice groups and law
firms.  In addition, he has broad experience representing medical practice groups and their
members in a wide variety of business transactions including business entity formations, practice
mergers and acquisitions, divestitures and split-ups, joint ventures, managed care contracting
matters, and employment contracting matters.
<P> <B>Robert E. Wilbur</B>
<BR>Mr. Wilbur is a shareholder in the firm's tax section.  Mr. Wilbur has experience in the
formation and operation of health care provider and related entities from a tax and non-tax
analysis standpoint.  He has and continues to represent integrated and non-integrated health care
organizations including individuals, partnerships, corporations, associations, PPOs, IPAs, Phos
and related entities in all aspect of medical and health care practice.  Mr. Wilbur's experience
also includes advice and counsel on contract negotiations, mergers, acquisitions, regulatory and
other entity and transactional issues involving the health care industry.  He speaks on a regular
basis to health care providers and their advisors.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><U>ANTITRUST</U></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> 
<P> <B>Amelia Williams Koch</B>
<BR>Ms. Koch focuses on antitrust and employment issues, both in litigation matters and in
counseling clients, with a significant amount of her work being in the health care arena.  Ms.
Koch analyzes various health care entities' activities from an antitrust standpoint.  This work
encompasses assisting in the formation of provider networks, assessment of joint formulation of
joint purchasing plans.  In the employment context, Ms. Koch assists health care clients with a
broad range of employment matters including personnel policies, inhouse training, hiring and
retention procedures, and background and reference checks, with an emphasis on
&quot;preventive maintenance.&quot; She also handles all types of employment litigation
including, by way of example, staff privileges, discrimination claims, and benefits.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><U>LITIGATION</U></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>Jennifer Burr Altabef</B>
<BR>Ms. Altabef is experienced in employment litigation before state and federal courts;
representation of employers before agencies, including the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission, the Texas Human Rights Commission, the U.S. Department of Labor, and the
Texas Employment Commission; and advice, counseling, and training regarding
employment-related matters.  Ms. Altabef's representation of companies includes issues
regarding Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, the Texas Commission on Human Rights
Act, the Americans with Disabilities Act, the Age Discrimination in Employment Act, the Fair
Labor Standards Act, the Family and Medical Leave Act, the Older Workers' Benefit Protection
Act, covenants not to compete, drug testing, employment policies and handbooks, employment
contracts, severance agreements, privacy in the workplace, sexual harassment, the Texas
concealed handgun law, the Texas Pay Day Law, the Texas Workers' Compensation Act, the
WARN Act, workplace violence, and wrongful termination.  Ms. Altabef has also given
numerous speeches and conducted many prevention-oriented programs for clients on a variety of
topics, including the Americans with Disabilities Act, sexual harassment, the Fair Labor
Standards Act, and covenants not to complete.  She has also lectured at Southern Methodist
University, for graduate and undergraduate classes, regarding employment law.
<P> <B>Daniel W. Bishop, II</B>
<BR>Mr. Bishop is a shareholder in the firm's litigation section.  Mr. Bishop has experience in
the representation of doctors and other health care providers in medical malpractice cases,
licensing proceedings, peer review proceedings, Texas Medical Foundation hearings, and
managed health care litigation.  A significant portion of Mr. Bishop's docket has included
representing doctors before the Texas State Board of Medical Examiners.  Mr. Bishop has also
handled business litigation and partnership dissolution litigation for doctors and other health care
providers.
<P> 
<P> <B>Amelia Williams Koch</B>
<BR>Ms. Koch focuses on antitrust and employment issues, both in litigation matters and in
counseling clients, with a significant amount of her work being in the health care arena.  Ms.
Koch analyzes various health care entities' activities from an antitrust standpoint.  This work
encompasses assisting in the formation of provider networks, assessment of joint formulation of
joint purchasing plans.  In the employment context, Ms. Koch assists health care clients with a
broad range of employment matters including personnel policies, inhouse training, hiring and
retention procedures, and background and reference checks, with an emphasis on
&quot;preventive maintenance.&quot; She also handles all types of employment litigation
including, by way of example, staff privileges, discrimination claims, and benefits.
<P>  <B>Raymond E. LaDriere, II</B>
<BR>Mr. LaDriere is a shareholder in the firm's litigation section.  Mr. LaDriere has a broad
range of experience in trial work, including negotiation, mediation, arbitration and jury trials and
was one of the first trial lawyers in the Southwest to become actively involved in managed care
litigation.  For the past ten years, a significant part of Mr. LaDriere's trial practice has involved
the resolution of complex lawsuits on behalf of managed care companies.  These include denial
of benefits claims, as well as malpractice cases where the managed care organization is targeted.
<P>  
<P> <B>David McCracken</B>
<BR>Mr. McCracken is a shareholder in the firm's Litigation Section.  He has focused his trial
work in the areas of product liability, medical negligence and defense of life and health care
insurers, HMO's and PPO's.  He has trial experience throughout the state of Texas in both federal
and state courts.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><U>LABOR AND EMPLOYMENT</U></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>Amelia Williams Koch</B>
<BR>Ms. Koch focuses on antitrust and employment issues, both in litigation matters and in
counseling clients, with a significant amount of her work being in the health care arena.  Ms.
Koch analyzes various health care entities' activities from an antitrust standpoint.  This work
encompasses assisting in the formation of provider networks, assessment of joint formulation of
