<TITLE>m-intl.htm </TITLE>
<BODY background="linen.gif" text="000000" link="2F4F2F" vlink="A62A2A">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="lprh_grn.gif">



<P><B>LOCKE PURNELL RAIN HARRELL</B>
<BR><B>(A PROFESSIONAL CORPORATION)</B>
<P><B><U>MEXICAN LEGAL PRACTICE</B></U>
</CENTER>

<P> Locke Purnell Rain Harrell currently employs more than 170 lawyers.  Based in Dallas, with
offices in Austin and New Orleans, its practice extends throughout the United States and abroad. 
The firm dates back to 1891 and, since that time, its primary goal has been to provide the highest
quality legal services possible to its clients.
<P> Locke Purnell's international practice involves the representation of foreign business entities
operating domestically and abroad, as well as domestic businesses with international activities
and investments.  Specifically, this area of practice includes counseling regarding the
establishment of companies and joint ventures; franchising and distribution; income taxes and
other direct or indirect taxes; the export and import of products and equipment; foreign exchange
regulations and repatriation of earnings; investment laws and regulations; employment practices;
and treaties affecting commerce and taxation.
<P> The Firm has particularly extensive experience in representing clients doing business in
Mexico.  The Firm has recently represented the following clients in connection with legal matters
involving Mexico:
<UL TYPE=DISK>
<BR><LI> AMR Combs, Inc. (American
<BR><LI> Airlines Affiliates)
<BR><LI> American Fastsigns, Inc. (Fastsigns)
<BR><LI> Austin Designs, Inc.
<BR><LI> Brinker International, Inc. (Chili's)
<BR><LI> Calesa Corporativa, S.A. de C.V.
<BR><LI> CIMA Holdings, Ltd.
<BR><LI> Comet Cleaners
<BR><LI> Converting Inc.
<BR><LI> Cuplex, Inc.
<BR><LI> D.Q. Mex Ltd. (Dairy Queen)
<BR><LI> Fossil, Inc.
<BR><LI> Golden Franchising Corporation
<BR><LI> Head Sports, Inc.
<BR><LI> Hightech Ventures Company
(Hightech Signs)
<BR><LI> International Flying Colors, Inc.
<BR><LI> Jani-King International, Inc.
<BR><LI> Jones-Blair Company
<BR><LI> Leggett &amp; Platt, Incorporated
<BR><LI> Mail Boxes de Mexico
(Mail Boxes, Etc.)
<BR><LI> Mexico Cinema Management, Ltd.
<BR><LI> National Auto Center, Inc.
(Cellular Express)
<BR><LI> NationsBank Texas
<BR><LI> RE/MAX International, Inc.
<BR><LI> San Lorenzo Nursery Company
of Texas, Inc.
<BR><LI> Schlotzsky's Inc.
<BR><LI> Sfuzzi, Inc.
<BR><LI> Sports Beverage, Inc.
<BR><LI> Steamatic Incorporated
<BR><LI> TGI Friday's Inc.
<BR><LI> Trammell Crow Company
<BR><LI> TST Impreso
<BR><LI> Wet 'n Wild International, Inc.
</UL>
<P> Although the Firm draws upon the expertise of its lawyers in a wide number of fields in
connection with Mexican legal matters, those lawyers most experienced in dealing with Mexican
legal matters include John McKnight, Jerry Keys and Sara Albert.  A brief biography of each of
these lawyers is set forth below.
<P> <B><U>John</U></B><B><U> </U></B><B><U>B. McKnight</U></B> is a
shareholder in the Firm and has considerable experience in international transactions and, in
particular, the representation of U.S. companies conducting business in Mexico.  He possesses
varied corporate experience ranging from general operational matters to public and private debt
offerings, acquisitions, mergers, franchising, intellectual property matters, commercial bank
financings and venture capital financings. Mr. McKnight received his B.A. with high honors
from Vanderbilt University in 1981, and his J.D. from the University of Texas in 1985, where he
served on the editorial board of the Texas Law Review.  His most recent presentations and
publications relating to Mexico include <I>A New Dawn in the Mexican Financial Services
Industry: Current and Future Markets </I><I>and Legal Regulation,</I> Mexican Business
Review (October 1993), <I>Mexico's New </I><I>Intellectual Property Regime; Improvements
in the Protection of Industrial Property Copyright, </I><I>License, and Franchise Rights in
Mexico,</I> The International Lawyer (Spring 1993), <I>Opening the Doors to Mexico: A
General Guide to Mexican Legal Reform,</I> presented in conjunction with various trade
missions to Mexico under the auspices of the Dallas-Mexico Partnership (1992-1993), authorship
of <I>Mexico's Industrial Property and Copyright Laws: </I><I>Another Step Toward Linkage
with a Global Economy,</I> International Business Lawyer (December 1992), <I>Mexico
Enacts New Intellectual Property Protections and Continues </I><I>Liberalization of Franchise
Laws,</I> The Journal of International Franchising and Distribution Law (December 1991), and
<I>Mexico Redoubles Efforts to Attract Foreign </I><I>Franchisors,</I> Franchise Law Journal
(Spring 1990).  Mr. McKnight is a frequent lecturer on US-Mexico legal topics and currently
serves as a member of the Board of Directors and Executive Committee, and as Chairman of the
Programs Committee of the U.S.-Mexico Chamber of Commerce (Southwest Chapter).  Mr.
McKnight speaks Spanish.
<P> <B><U>Jerry M. Keys</U></B> represents industrial and technology-based companies
ranging from start-ups to multi-nationals in the areas of intellectual property, computer law,
technology transfer, the financing and siting of industrial facilities, and environmental law.  He is
a former President of the Austin Intellectual Property Law Association and former adjunct
assistant professor at The University of Texas.  He currently serves on the Executive Committee
of the Greater Austin-San Antonio Corridor Council.  He has also authored numerous articles in
his areas of practice, including guidance for companies locating and operating industrial facilities
in both the United States and Mexico.  Jerry received his J.D. with honors in 1975 after earning a
B.S. degree in Electrical Engineering, with honors, in 1970 from The University of Texas at
Austin.
<P> 
<P>  <B><U>Sara M. Albert</U></B> is an attorney in the Firm and has experience in
international transactions and domestic transactions, including general business law, contracts,
acquisitions, international franchising and distribution, patent and technology licensing,
cross-border business transactions, public debt offerings, corporation law and securities.  Sara
received her B.A., cum laude, and graduated Phi Beta Kappa, in 1976 and her J.D. in 1992 from
Southern Methodist University.  She is fluent in Spanish.
<P> <B><U>Mexican Associate Relationship</U></B><B>.</B>  In addition to the Firm's
internally developed expertise in Mexican legal matters, it has established over the years a
cooperative working relationship with the Mexico City law firm of Creel,
Garc&iacute;a-Cu&eacute;llar y M&uuml;ggenburg.  The Creel firm was founded in 1936 and is
ranked among the leading national and international law firms of Mexico, providing a broad
range of legal services to the corporate, financial and industrial communities in Mexico and
abroad.  The Creel firm has an impressive list of clients which includes a substantial number of
American, Canadian, Japanese and European corporations.  Most of the lawyers and staff
personnel in the firm are fluent in both Spanish and English, and a number of the lawyers have
attended American universities and worked in American law firms.  The Firm's relationship with
the Creel firm has grown over time and we expect to continue working with members of the
Creel firm on Mexican legal matters. The Firm's relationship with the Creel firm is not exclusive,
however, and Firm lawyers also work with other prominent Mexican law firms.


