<header>
<title> OSHA Inspection Fundamentals</title>
</header>

<body background="linen.gif" text="000000" link="2F4F2F" vlink="A62A2A">
<center>
<img src="lprh_grn.gif">
<p>
<h2>OSHA INSPECTION FUNDAMENTALS</h2><p>
<p>
JANE A. MATHESON<P>
<p>
LOCKE PURNELL RAIN HARRELL, P.C.<br>
515 Congress Avenue<br>
Suite 2500<br>
Austin, Texas 78701-3500<br>
(512) 305-4700<p>
</center>
<p>
<strong><h3>I. INTRODUCTION</h3></strong><p>
<blockquote>
Any employer who has <u>one or more employees</u> must comply with the standards issued
by OSHA.  Part-time, temporary and probationary workers are considered employees for the
purpose of determining coverage of the Occupational Safety & Health Act (the "OSH Act"). 
The purpose of this summary is to provide an overview of the OSHA inspection process and to
make certain suggestions about what to do, and what not to do, when an OSHA compliance
officer comes calling.  By taking the opportunity to become informed about OSHA procedures
<u>before</u> an inspection occurs, a company can help avoid inadvertent mistakes.  The
fundamentals of the OSHA appeals process will also be discussed.  However, as is always true
with situations involving legal issues, employers should consult with an attorney regarding
specific areas of concern.</blockquote><p>

<strong><h3>II. SELECTING EMPLOYERS FOR INSPECTIONS</strong></h3><p>
<dl>
<dd>
<strong>A. General</strong><p>
<blockquote>
The OSHA inspection process is normally initiated in one of two ways.  First, an OSHA
inspection can occur when a specific establishment is identified for inspection as the result of a
neutral, administrative plan such as the random selection of establishments within high hazard
industries.  This type of inspection is known as a "programmed" inspection.  Second, a
"non-programmed" OSHA inspection can take place if OSHA receives a referral from another
enforcement agency or an employee complaint or an imminent danger condition is detected.  In
either situation, OSHA's ability to disregard normal enforcement procedures is very limited.  For
example, if OSHA receives a formal employee complaint and does not respond, OSHA is subject
to criticism for failing to follow appropriate inspection procedure.</blockquote><p>
<strong>B. New Targeting Procedures</strong><p>
<blockquote>
OSHA has been attempting to improve its targeting criteria and manner of selecting
establishments for programmed inspections. Recently in some area offices employers
identified on high hazard industry lists are asked to submit their OSHA 200 logs for a
pre-inspection review.  OSHA then prioritizes the order of inspection based upon the information
received.  Other targeting initiatives explored by OSHA include the Maine 200, Wisconsin 200,
and focused inspection pilot programs.  An employer should always ask how and why the work
site is being inspected.  Employers who do not respond at all may find themselves at the top of
OSHA's list.</blockquote><p>

<strong>C. Employee Complaints</strong><p>
<blockquote>
Not every employee complaint will automatically result in a non-programmed OSHA inspection. 
A formal complaint is one that is filed in writing, signed by the employee (or the employee's
designated representative), and which describes an alleged violation that could result in serious
physical harm.  If OSHA receives a non-formal complaint, such as an unsigned complaint or a
complaint filed by a former employee or third party, it will generally notify the employer as to
the nature of the complaint and will ask the employer to investigate the matter and to furnish
OSHA with the results of the investigation.  If OSHA does not receive a satisfactory response to
its original inquiry, OSHA will then conduct its own investigation of the employer.  Thus,
employers should always respond promptly to any OSHA inquiry about 
complaints.</blockquote><p>

<strong>D. Exemptions</strong></p>
<blockquote>
In a very limited number of situations, a work site may be exempt from inspection.  For example,
if the work site is a participant in OSHA's voluntary protection program or is participating in a
state sponsored &#167; 7(c)(1) consultation program, the inspection would be deferred until a
later date.</blockquote><p>
</dl>
<strong>III. EMPLOYER PREPARATION</strong><p>
<blockquote>
Any employer should take the opportunity to prepare for an OSHA inspection before it happens. 
At least one or more supervisors at each company location should be designated as the
management representative for an OSHA inspection.  These management representatives should
receive specialized training regarding the nature and scope of OSHA's inspection authority. 
The management representatives should be familiar with the various OSHA standards applicable
to the workplace, the procedures for maintaining various required records, and the employer's
safety and health training program.</blockquote><p>
<strong>IV. WARRANTS</strong><p>
<blockquote>
If desired, an employer has the right to prevent an OSHA compliance officer from conducting an
inspection without a warrant.  Such a course of action is not generally followed, and should be
considered carefully and after discussion with an attorney, if possible.  In any event, even if a
warrant is requested, the employer should treat the OSHA compliance officer courteously,
professionally and in a non-confrontational manner.  If an inspection is permitted without
requesting a warrant, it is not very likely that an employer can successfully challenge the legality
of the inspection at a later date.  If a warrant is requested and presented, the management
representative should review the scope and content of the warrant to ensure that the inspection is
conducted in accordance with the warrant.</blockquote><p>
<strong>V. THE INSPECTION PROCESS</strong><p>
<dl>
<dd>
<strong>A. Opening Conference</strong><p>
<blockquote>
     An OSHA inspection begins when an OSHA compliance officer arrives at an employer's
place of business and announces an intention to conduct an investigation of the premises.  Before
the actual inspection of the workplace, the OSHA compliance officer should conduct a brief
opening conference with the employer or the employer's designated representative.  During the
opening conference, which should take place in private, the OSHA compliance officer should
inform the employer of the purpose of the inspection and advise the employer of any applicable
laws and regulations and any other informational handouts or materials relevant to the
inspection.  The employer should also use this opportunity to determine the basis for the
inspection.  OSHA inspection authority is not unlimited, and if the OSHA compliance officer
does not know or refuses to reveal whether the inspection is programmed or non-programmed,
there may be grounds to challenge OSHA's authority to conduct the inspection without a
warrant.<p>

     If the OSHA compliance officer indicates that the inspection is occurring as a result of a valid
formal complaint, the employer should ask to be provided with a copy of the complaint during
the opening conference.  OSHA, however, is not required to disclose to the employer the identity
of the employee complaint.<p>

     If certain areas of the work site contain confidential, trade secrets, or proprietary processes,
the employer representative should discuss proper protective measures with the compliance
officer and obtain an agreement as to how the proprietary information can be protected.  In some
situations it may be necessary to secure a written agreement in advance of the actual
inspection.<p>

     During the opening conference the management representative should discuss any required
safety equipment or procedures specific to the site which the compliance officer needs to know
and be prepared to personally use, such as ear protection or respirators.<p>
</blockquote>
<strong>B. Walkaround</strong><p>
<blockquote>
     Following the conclusion of the opening conference, the OSHA compliance officer will
conduct a walkaround investigation of the premises.  The main purpose of this part of the
inspection is to identify potential safety and/or health hazards in the workplace.  The employer or
the employer's representative may accompany the OSHA compliance officer during the
inspection, and such participation on the part of the employer is essential.  If there is a union, a
union representative may participate in the inspection also.<p>

     The compliance officer may want to interview employees.  Management representatives
should be aware that the statements they make may be considered to be an admission of the employer. 
Management representatives generally should not sign any statements without taking the
opportunity to discuss the questions, issues, and proposed responses with the company's
lawyers.  The company's legal counsel has the right to be present during interviews with the
company's management representatives.<p>

     OSHA generally will not permit the employer or management representative to be present
during any non-management employee interviews.  However, before any management or
non-management employee is interviewed, the employee should be generally informed about the
nature of the inspection, encouraged to be truthful and honest and to refrain from speculation or
guessing.  The employee can also be told that the employee may request a copy of any statement
given to OSHA.<p>

     During an inspection, the employer representative should document the items noted by the
compliance officer.  Ideally, if a compliance officer is photographing or videotaping an alleged
hazard, the employer should also be photographing and videotaping the same condition. 
Similarly, the employer should document any measurements or samples taken.  The employer
representative should keep detailed notes of the inspection reflecting the information
disclosed.<p>
</blockquote>

<strong>C. Records Review</strong><p>
<blockquote>
     The OSHA inspection may also include a review by the OSHA compliance officer of all the
employer's records regarding employee health and safety.  Voluntary production of documents is
not required in all situations.  However, production of records and documents can often be
required by subpoena.  When documents are copied and provided to OSHA, the employer should
maintain a log of the documents released and keep copies of any released records.  Any
documents released which contain confidential, proprietary information, should be clearly
stamped or marked as "CONFIDENTIAL COMMERCIAL INFORMATION."  If documents are
released without any labeling as to confidentiality, they may be subject to disclosure to
requesting parties under the Freedom of Information Act without prior notification to the
submitting employer.  If information about a specific employee's medical records is requested
and released, OSHA should be prepared to show that appropriate precautions are in place to
protect the confidentiality of such records.<p>
</blockquote>

<strong>D. Closing Conference</strong><p>
<blockquote>
     At the conclusion of the inspection, the OSHA compliance officer should conduct a closing
conference with the employer or the employer's designated representative.  During this
conference, the OSHA compliance officer should describe the apparent violations found during
the inspection and should indicate the applicable standards that may have been violated.  The
employer should also be given the opportunity to ask questions about the OSHA inspection
process and any rights and responsibilities the employer may have following an OSHA
inspection.  The OSHA compliance officer may also use the closing conference as an
opportunity to obtain signed interview statements, but management representatives are not
required to sign such statements and they should be encouraged not to do so, since written and
verbal admissions may be used against the employer in any subsequent OSHA proceedings.  The
employer representative and employees should respond to the OSHA compliance officer in a
truthful and honest manner, but speculation, guessing or volunteering information should be
avoided.</blockquote><p>
</dl>

<strong>VI. CITATIONS</strong><p>
<blockquote>
     If a citation is issued, it will be sent to the employer, together with information regarding the
employer's right to contest the citation.  The employer is then required to post a copy of the
citation at or near the place where the alleged violations occurred so as to inform employees of
the hazards to which they may be exposed.  If the employer does not contest the citation and it
becomes a final order, then the cited conditions must be abated by the dates set forth in the
citation and any penalties must be paid within fifteen working days of the date the citation is
received.</blockquote><p>

<strong>VII. PENALTIES</strong><p>
<blockquote>
     The penalties for an OSHA violation can be significant.  Serious and non-serious violations
can be as much as $7,000.00 per violation, and repeat and willful violations can be as much as
$70,000.00 per violation.  The minimum penalty for a willful violation can be $25,000 when
death or serious physical harm occurred.<p>

     During fiscal year 1994, for example, OSHA cited only 989 willful violations out of
approximately 146,000 violations found by inspectors.  However, despite the relatively low
number of willful violations that were cited in 1994, the penalties imposed for willful violations
in fiscal year 1994 exceeded $32 million, or approximately $32,500 for each willful violation
cited by OSHA.  In other words, willful violations represented less than 0.7 percent of all
violations cited by OSHA, but accounted for nearly 27 percent of the penalties imposed by the
agency.</blockquote><p>

<strong>VIII. CONTESTING THE CITATION</strong><p>
<dl>
<dd>
<strong>A. Informal Conference</strong><p>
<blockquote>
     The employer also has the opportunity to request an informal conference with the OSHA
Area Director to try to resolve any dispute over a citation without having to resort to litigation. 
If the employer decides to request an informal conference with the OSHA Area Director, the
conference must be scheduled and completed <u>before</u> the deadline runs out for filing a
Notice of Intent to Contest.  Employers are encouraged to take advantage of the informal
conference to reduce the time and expense associated with trying a contested case before an
administrative law judge.  At the conclusion of the informal conference, the OSHA Area
Directory has the authority to enter into a settlement agreement with the employer.  If the
employer is not satisfied with the results of the informal conference, then the employer can still
file the Notice of Intent to Contest and proceed with the litigation.  Employers should be certain
that any settlements they enter into contain an appropriate non-admissions clause.<p>
</blockquote>

<strong>B. Notice of Intent to Contest</strong><p>
<blockquote>
     If the employer intends to contest any part of the citation, the employer must notify the
OSHA 
Area Director in writing within fifteen working days after receipt of the citation.  The written
notification, called a Notice of Intent to Contest, must clearly state which items, proposed
penalties, and abatement dates of the citation are being contested.  If the Notice of Intent to
Contest is properly filed, the OSHA Area Director will forward the case to the Occupational
Safety and Health Review Commission (the "Review Commission"), at which time the case will
officially be in litigation.  Upon receipt of the Notice of Intent to Contest, the Review
Commission will assign the case to an administrative law judge, who will schedule a hearing to
be held close to the employer's place of business. Certain less complex caes may be assigned to simplified 
hearing procedures for which discovery and other similar pre-trial procedures are
more limited. Before a hearing is held, an opportunity to
settle or resolve the case is normally explored.  Employers who appear pro se should be careful
to observe and comply with all required filing deadlines and service rules.  The administrative
law judge may affirm, modify, or eliminate any item of the citation that has been challenged by
the employer.  Adverse decisions of the administrative law judge may be appealed to the Review
Commission, and, if necessary, to the applicable United States court of
appeals.</blockquote><p>

<strong>C. Follow-up Inspections</strong><p>
<blockquote>
     Employers should also be aware that OSHA may decide to conduct a follow-up inspection to
verify that the employer has corrected the violations in the manner required by the citation. 
However, unless there have been significant changes in the workplace, the inspection normally
will be limited to the subject matter of the citation.  Substantial fines and penalties can be issued
for failure to abate conditions.</blockquote><p>
</dl>
<strong>IX. CONCLUSION</strong><p>
<blockquote>
     Dealing with an OSHA inspection may be a new experience for many employers. 
Consequently, it is important to gain as much understanding as possible before the time such
knowledge is needed.  Familiarity with the procedures used by OSHA and the rules that the
OSHA compliance officers are required to follow will help to ease the anxiety that some
employers may feel about the possibility of an OSHA inspection.  In addition, it may also allow
an employer to avoid making certain mistakes during an OSHA inspection or in any subsequent
proceedings.</blockquote><p>
<dl>
<dd>
<dl>
<dd>
<i>This paper is for general information only and is not intended to be a legal opinion or legal
advice.  For advice about specific legal matters, you should consult an attorney.</I>
</dl></dl>


