<CENTER>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2> Real Estate Aspects of New Telecommunications
Laws</B></FONT><P><P><P><P>
<P><B><A HREF="mailto:rfsee@lprh.com">Robert F. See, Jr.</B></A>
<P><B><A HREF="mailto:cb.cassidy@lprh.com">C. Brian Cassidy</B></A>
<P><B>Locke Purnell Rain Harrell</B>
</CENTER>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=-3>THE AUTHORS WOULD LIKE TO THANK JAY HAILEY OF LOCKE
PURNELL RAIN HARRELL FOR HIS VALUABLE ASSISTANCE AND HIS PERMISSION
TO UTILIZE PORTIONS OF HIS PAPER ENTITLED "HIGH TECH  REAL ESTATE "
PRESENTED AT THE 1994 MORTGAGE LENDING INSTITUTE.</FONT><P>
<HR>

<P><B><A NAME="I">I. </B><B>Introduction</B></A>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE> The past twenty years has seen remarkable developments in the
telecommunications industry.  The pervasiveness of the Internet, the widespread use of electronic
mail as a means of communicating, the ubiquitous presence of cellular phones, and the myriad of
services now offered by telecommunications companies are just a few examples of the radical
differences between today&#146;s telecommunications industry and that of just a few years ago.
<P> Along with these technological developments have come radical changes in the way the
telecommunications industry is regulated.  In 1995 the Texas Legislature substantially revised
the Public Utility Regulatory Act, Tex. Rev. Civ. Stat. Ann. art. 1446c (Vernon Supp. 1996)
(&quot;PURA 95&quot;), and made major changes to the way in which the telecommunications
industry is to be regulated in Texas.  More recently, the U.S. Congress passed (and President
Clinton signed) the Federal Telecommunications Act of 1996 (the &quot;FTA&quot;), [ See 
Telecommunications Act of 1996, Pub. L. No. 104-104, 110 Stat. 56 (1996).]  which changes
amended the Communications Act of 1934, 47 U.S.C.A. &#167; 151 et seq.  Much like PURA
95, the FTA makes major changes in the regulation of telecommunications service providers, and
in some instances preempts state regulation over service issues.
<P> The rapid rate of technological advances coupled with the change in regulation of the
telecommunications industry has produced changes with far-reaching effects.  Cities are being
&quot;wired&quot; with the fiber optic cable in order to expand to the range of service offerings
beyond basic cable T.V. service.  In the real estate industry residential developers are beginning
to plan for technological changes by altering the way in which they structure new development. 
Some examples are: [ Clark, "The Implications of Telecommunications and
Information Technologies for Residential Development, " <I>ULI on
The Future of Creating Tomorrow's Competitive Advantage</I> , 1996.]

<P><BLOCKQUOTE>&#149;  Developers are laying fiber-optic cable in new communities
even though it will not be used at first.  Fiber optics gives many projects a market advantage, and
retrofitting existing communities is very expensive.
<P>&#149;  Builders often equip new houses with extra, and empty, conduits to accommodate
unknown technology that could emerge in the future.  These conduits are relatively inexpensive
when installed during construction and, again, provide a market edge.
<P>&#149;  Most new houses are being equipped with at least four telephone lines to
accommodate telephones, fax machines, and modems.
<P>&#149;  A large percentage of new houses are being designed to accommodate a separate
and fully wired room for an office or shared family computer work space. Apartment builders too
are gaining a competitive edge by offering floor plans with small offices or computer work
spaces.
<P>&#149;  Many residential and apartment communities are incorporating business centers
(similar to those found in hotels) and staffing them with technical supporters in clubhouses and
community buildings as a service to residents with home offices.
<P> Commercial developers and multi-tenant building owners are also being forced to recognize
changes brought about by technological and regulatory developments.  The range of services
being offered to tenants in commercial buildings is changing just as quickly as it is for
individuals and small business owners, and those companies marketing the services to tenants of
commercial buildings are doing so with increased vigor as regulatory barriers to competition are
eroded.
<P> This raises an issue which has received little attention but is of great significance to building
owners, developers, managers, and those professionals who advise them; that is, do
telecommunications service providers have a &quot;right&quot; to access commercial buildings
in order to install facilities to serve tenants of the building?  The purpose of this paper is to
examine this issue in detail and provide practitioners with some guidance as to the rights and
obligations of their clients vis-&agrave;-vis telecommunications service
providers.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><A NAME="II">II. </B><B>Overview of Telecommunications Regulation</B></A>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE> Regulation governing the provision of telecommunications services has
evolved over many years.  In order to understand why regulation takes its present form it is
helpful to have an understanding of the past.
<P><B> </B><B>A. </B><B>In the Beginning There Was AT&amp;T</B>
<P> A good starting point for understanding the regulatory structure is the antitrust action that
resulted in the 1984 break up of American Telephone and Telegraph Company
(&quot;AT&amp;T&quot;), which included the divestiture of the Bell System operating
companies and the creation of seven regional holding companies, including Southwestern Bell
Telephone Company.  This action began in 1949, when the U.S. Justice Department filed an
antitrust lawsuit because of AT&amp;T&#146;s attempts to expand its manufacturing and sale of
telephone equipment.  This resulted in the entry of a 1956 Consent Decree prohibiting
AT&amp;T from conducting any business unrelated to providing regulated commoncarrier
communications services.  In 1974, the Justice Department brought a second antitrust action
alleging that AT&amp;T had used its monopoly control over local telephone service to the
disadvantage of competitors in the long distance and telecommunication equipment markets. 
This resulted in the entry of a second Consent Decree in 1982.  <I>See</I>, <I>United States v.
American Telephone and Telegraph </I><I>Co.</I>, 460 U.S. 1001, 103 S.Ct. 1240 (1983).
<P> The 1982 Consent Decree split the Bell System into two basic parts: (i) the competitive
portion of the business, which would provide long distance service, manufacture
telecommunications equipment, and conduct research; and (ii) the noncompetitive portion of the
business, which would continue to provide local telecommunications service.  The competitive
portion was retained by AT&amp;T and its Western Electric and Bell Labs subsidiaries, while
the noncompetitive portion was assigned to the seven regional holding companies and their
operating company subsidiaries.  The distinction between the two portions of the business was to
be preserved by creating &quot;exchange areas&quot; generally centering on metropolitan areas,
within which the Bell operating companies would provide &quot;exchange telecommunications
services&quot; consisting principally of basic local switched telephone service.  The right to
provide long distance &quot;interexchange telecommunication services&quot; was reserved to
AT&amp;T and its non-Bell System competitors.
<P> Since 1982, there have been numerous court cases and regulatory proceedings interpreting
the Consent Decree and establishing the line of demarcation for the type of telecommunication
services that can be provided by various parties.  For example, in <I>United States v. Western
Electric </I><I>Company, Inc. et al.</I>, 797 F2d 1082 (D.C. Cir. 1986), the Court of Appeals
said that several of the Bell regional holding companies had no standing to challenge the District
Court&#146;s determination that the Consent Decree prohibits the Bell regional holding
companies from selling certain &quot;shared tenant services&quot; within their regions.  In the
District Court opinion, found at 627 F.Supp. 1090, &quot;shared tenant services&quot; are
described as follows:
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>Shared tenant services are the provision by a developer or building owner
of a package of telecommunications and related services to tenants.  Tenants&#146; needs are
then served on a shared basis using centralized voice and data switches and computers on the
building premises.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> According to the District Court, among the benefits to the tenants are the cost savings
associated with the aggregated demand which, depending upon the pricing policies of the
providers of the services, may permit these tenants to acquire customer premise equipment,
exchange services, and interexchange services at lower, volume-based prices.  The District Court
said the shared tenant services market had developed substantially over the past few years, noting
that &quot;before 1983 there were virtually no buildings with advanced shared-service
capabilities while today [1986] there are some 70 such facilities in operation and another 50
expected shortly.&quot;  Nevertheless, the District Court held that shared tenant services are
&quot;interexchange services&quot; which the Bell regional holding companies are prohibited
from providing under the terms of the Consent Decree.  According to the District Court:
<P>[I]f the Regional Companies perform such an activity, that is, if they purchase interexchange
services at a bulk price based on the demand in a particular building and then sold such services
at retail at higher prices to the building&#146;s tenants - they, too, would be resellers in the
interexchange business, and they would be in direct competition with other resellers and with
facilities-based interexchange carriers.
<P><B> </B><B>B. </B><B>Competition in the Long-Distance Market</B>
<P> As noted above, AT&amp;T&#146;s dominance over the telecommunications industry
ended in 1982 with the company being split into two market segments.  One
&quot;segment&quot; was the provision of &quot;local exchange service,&quot; or service
<I>within</I> a particular geographic area.  Southwestern Bell Telephone Company
(&quot;SWB&quot;) became the primary provider of service of this type in Texas, and it was
granted the exclusive (i.e., monopoly) right to provide local exchange service in many areas
subject to oversight by the Public Utility Commission (&quot;PUC&quot;).  The other market
segment was in long-distance service, which could generally be viewed as service
<I>between</I> local exchange areas.  The long-distance market did not have the same barriers
to competition as did local exchange service, and companies such as MCI, Sprint, MFS, Teleport
and others began to challenge AT&amp;T.  It is now estimated that on a nationwide basis there
are nearly 500 companies competing to provide service in the long distance market.
<P><B> </B><B>C. </B><B>Competition in the Local Exchange Market</B>
<P> The changes contained in PURA 95 and the FTA have set the stage for competition to be
&quot;reintroduced&quot; into the local exchange market.  The shift in policy concerning
telecommunications regulation in Texas is evident in Section 3.001 of PURA 95 (emphasis
added):
<P> <FONT SIZE=-1><B><BLOCKQUOTE>Sec.</B><B>3.001.</B><B> </B><B>
</B><B>POLICY.</B>  The legislature finds that significant changes have occurred in
telecommunications since this Act was initially adopted.  The legislature hereby finds that
<B><I>it is the </I></B><B><I>policy of this state to promote diversity of providers and
interconnectivity and to encourage a fully </I></B><B><I>competitive telecommunications
marketplace</I></B> while protecting and maintaining the wide availability of high quality,
interoperable, standards-based telecommunications services at affordable rates.  These goals are
best achieved by legislation that brings telecommunications regulation into the modern era by
guaranteeing the affordability of basic telephone service in a competitively neutral manner, while
fostering free market competition within the telecommunications industry.  <B><I>The
legislature further </I></B><B><I>finds that</I></B> the technological advancements,
advanced telecommunications infrastructure, and<B><I> </I></B><B><I>increased customer
choices for telecommunications services generated by a truly competitive
</I></B><B><I>market will raise the living standards of all Texans</I></B> by enhancing
economic development and improving the delivery of education, health, and other public and
private services and therefore play a critical role in Texas&#146; economic future.  It is the
policy of this state to require the commission to do those things necessary to enhance the
development of competition by <B><I>adjusting regulation to match </I></B><B><I>the
degree of competition in the marketplace</I></B>, thereby reducing the cost and burden of
regulation and maintaining protection of markets that are not competitive.  It is further the policy
of this state to ensure that high quality telecommunications services are available, accessible, and
usable by individuals with disabilities, unless making the services available, accessible, or usable
would result in an undue burden, including unreasonable cost or technical feasibility, or would
have an adverse competitive effect.  <B><I>However, the legislature recognizes that the strength
of competitive forces vary </I></B><B><I>widely between markets and products and services. 
Therefore, to foster, encourage, and accelerate </I></B><B><I>the continuing development and
emergence of a competitive and advanced telecommunications</I></B><B><I>environment and
infrastructure, the legislature declares that new rules, policies, and principles be
</I></B><B><I>formulated and applied to protect the public interest</FONT></I></B>.
<P> The Congressional Conference Committee working on the FTA was even more direct in its
assessment of the purpose of the regulatory changes embodied in the FTA:
<P><FONT SIZE=-1>. . . [to] provide for a pro-competitive, de-regulatory national policy
framework designed to accelerate rapidly private sector deployment of advanced
telecommunications and information technologies and services to all Americans by opening all
telecommunications markets to competition . . .</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT> [ H.R. Rep. No.
104-458, 104th Cong., 2nd Sess. 1 (1996).] 
<P>The significance of these changes to the fundamental underpinnings of state and federal
regulation is that they demonstrate an intent to &quot;open up&quot; the local exchange market
to competition from a variety of telecommunications service providers.  As that competition
takes hold, an increased number of companies will be seeking access to multi-tenant buildings in
order to install, maintain, and operate the facilities necessary to provide service to the
buildings&#146; tenants.  The manner in which the state and federal law deal with the issue of
right to access may have a significant impact on multi-tenant building
owners.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><A NAME="III">III. </B><B>State Law Regarding Access</B></A>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE> The PUC has jurisdiction over the operations and services of
telecommunications utilities [ The phrase "telecommunications utility " is defined in &#167;
3.002 of PURA  95.  Note that this definition may be affected by changes in federal law resulting
from the FTA and regulations promulgated pursuant thereto.  See , generally , discussion at
section III.A.2 below.]  operating in Texas.  Prior to the enactment of PURA 95 the Commission
primarily focused its efforts in the telecommunications arena on rates and the availability of
services throughout the state. However, the 74th Legislative Session saw a fierce battle waged
over telecommunications reform, and the result was wholesale changes to regulation which
purported to provide for essentially a controlled deregulation of major aspects of the industry. 
Although the FTA later upstaged the PURA 95 amendments, many aspects of the state law
changes appear to remain intact (see section IV.D. below).  Among those is a provision affecting
the right of telecommunications utilities to access real property.  While other provisions of
PURA and state law have addressed property related issues such as pole attachments and rights
of way, PURA 95, for the first time, creates an apparent right of access to private property.
<P> <B>A. </B><B> </B><B>PURA</B><B> </B><B>95</B> &#151;
<B>Nondiscriminatory Right of Access</B>
<P> Section 3.2555 of PURA 95 (hereinafter &quot;&#167; 3.2555&quot;) is captioned
&quot;Discrimination&quot; and it purports to govern the right of telecommunications utilities
to access public and private property. Section 3.2555(c) applies to private property, and it
generally provides that access must be given, on a nondiscriminatory basis, to any
telecommunications utility whose services are requested by a tenant.  A copy of &#167; 3.2555
is attached hereto as <I><U>Exhibit A</U></I>.
<P>  <B><BLOCKQUOTE>1. </B><B>Analysis of </B><B>&#167;</B><B>
</B><B>3.2555</B>
<P> This provision embraces several important concepts.  A closer look at the issues raised may
be helpful to the overall analysis of the impact of &#167; 3.2555.
<P>   <B><BLOCKQUOTE>a. </B><B><U>Requirement to Possess Grant of
Authority</U></B></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> Notwithstanding the objective of deregulation of the telecommunications market, the PUC
(absent preemptive federal action) will retain oversight of entry into the market by certain service
providers.  Section 3.251(c) requires that before local exchange service may be provided the
entity seeking to provide the service must obtain certification from the PUC.  In addition, nothing
in PURA 95 is intended to preclude a municipality from exercising its rights &quot;to grant or
refuse franchises to use the streets and alleys within its limits&quot; provided any franchise
agreement does not interfere with the jurisdiction of the Commission.  PURA 95, &#167; 1.103. 
<I>Thus, any service provider </I><I>seeking access to private property must hold whatever
state and local permits and franchises are </I><I>necessary to legally provide service</I>.
<P>   <B><BLOCKQUOTE>b. </B><B> </B><B><U>Protection of
Tenants</U></B></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> Section 3.2555(c)(1) contemplates that a telecommunications utility will be seeking access
to a private building because a tenant of that building has requested that particular company to
provide it with service.  Absent prohibitions to the contrary, tenants could be discouraged from
exercising their &quot;right&quot; to choose among service providers (thus requiring the
building to give access to multiple providers) by the imposition of  disincentives, such as
increased rental charges, assessment of a surcharge or other fee, and similar measures.  Sections
3.255(c)(3) and (4) protect tenants from these types of actions by prohibiting discrimination
against a tenant (or in favor of another tenant) based on their selection of a telecommunications
utility, and by prohibiting a demand for payment from a tenant for allowing their chosen provider
access to the building.
<P>   <B><BLOCKQUOTE>c. </B><B><U>Protection of Telecommunications Services
Providers</U></B></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> Similar to the restrictions against actions which would preclude tenants from exercising
their right to choose their telecommunications utility, &#167; 3.2555 (c)(1-3) precludes the
assessment of disincentives against the telecommunications companies as well.  Specifically,
interference with installation; discrimination in relation to installation, terms, conditions, and
compensation charges; and requiring &quot;unreasonable payments&quot; in exchange for
access, are all prohibited.  In other words, a building owner cannot treat different companies on a
different basis, and access and rental charges must all be assessed on an equal (i.e.,
nondiscriminatory) basis among telecommunications  service providers.
<P>   <B><BLOCKQUOTE>d. </B><B><U>&quot;Protection</U></B><B><U>&quot; for
Property Owners</U></B></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> Although purporting to require property owners to give telecommunications utilities access
to their property, &#167; 3.2555 also incorporates certain protective measures for the benefit of
thoseproperty owners.  Specifically, &#167; 3.2555(d)(1) &amp; (2) authorizes the imposition of
conditions or limitations that are &quot;reasonably necessary&quot; to protect the security,
appearance and condition of the property and the safety of the property and persons on it, as well
as the imposition of &quot;reasonable&quot; limitations on times available for installation. 
Other protections include:
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>(i)the ability of property owners to require indemnification for damage
caused by the installation, operation or removal of facilities;
<P> (ii)the ability to require tenants or the telecommunications utilities to absorb the entire cost
of installation, operation and removal of facilities; and
<P> (iii)the ability to impose reasonable limitations on the number of telecommunications
utilities having access to the property <I>if</I> it is demonstrated that space constraints justify
the limitations.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>These protections should be incorporated in any leases and license agreements between the
property owner and both tenants and telecommunications utilities.
<P>   <B><BLOCKQUOTE>e. </B><B><U>Compensation</U></B></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> In addition to allowing property owners to require indemnification for certain costs, &#167;
3.2555(d)(6) also authorizes the charging of compensation (to be paid by telecommunication
utilities) that is &quot;reasonable and nondiscriminatory&quot; among telecommunications
companies. Although implied that this is some sort of right granted to a property owner, it can
also be viewed as a limitation of a right; that is, the right to freely engage in a commercial
transaction wherein a service provider seeks access to private property.  It is a limitation because
of the requirement that compensation be charged on a nondiscriminatory basis.  This restricts the
right of property owners to negotiate different deals with different utilities.  These restrictions
may also provide the basis for a constitutional challenge to this statutory provision.  (See section
V below).
<P>  <B>2. </B><B>Possible Effects of Federal Preemption</B>
<P> As referenced above and addressed in more detail below, the FTA may preempt various
aspects of PURA 95.  While the general principles embodied in &#167; 3.2555 appear
unaffected in that regard, the federal statute (and regulations to be promulgated thereunder) may
indirectly affect its application.  For example, &#167; 3.2555(c) conditions the right of access
granted in that section on the telecommunications utility holding a certificate (of operating
authority) from the PUC and/or other grant of authority from a municipality.  However, the FTA
appears headed in the direction of largely doing away with the types of certification required
under state law to be obtained from the PUC. Should that be the case the universe of
telecommunications utilities eligible to seek access under &#167; 3.2555 may be expanded, as
companies will not be impeded by at least one currently existing regulatory barrier administered
by the PUC.  In similar fashion the FCC may reduce the level of local regulation of
telecommunications companies (at least to the point of requiring that non-exclusive franchises be
granted on a non-discriminatory basis), which may also increase the numberof companies
seeking to serve a particular area.  The point for practitioners is simply to be aware that whatever
actions the FCC takes may well impact the local markets in Texas and may facilitate a further
expansion of the number of competitors in the local markets which will be seeking access to
buildings and other private property.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <B>B. </B><B><U>Enforcement of
</U></B><B><U>&#167;</U></B><B><U> </U></B><B><U>3.2555</U></B>
<P> As of the date this paper was submitted no actions had been initiated by or at the PUC
concerning enforcement of &#167; 3.2555.  Furthermore, the Commission has no immediate
plans to initiate any rulemakings which would provide further guidance as to the interpretation
and applicability of the provisions of &#167; 3.2555.  Nevertheless, the PUC is authorized to
retain jurisdiction for enforcement of &#167; 3.2555. [ Section 3.2555(e) provides that:
"Notwithstanding any other provision of law, the commission has the jurisdiction necessary to
enforce this section. "]   The PUC&#146;s enforcement authority is contained in PURA 95
&#167; 1.321 which provides, in relevant part, as follows:
<P><FONT SIZE=-1><BLOCKQUOTE>Whenever it appears to the commission that any
public utility <B><I>or any person or corporation</I></B> is engaged in or is about to engage in
any act in violation of this Act . . . the attorney general on request of the commission . . . shall
bring an action in a court of competent jurisdiction . . . to enjoin the commencement or
continuation of any such act or to require compliance with such Act, rule, regulation or
order.</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT>
<P>Thus, violations of &#167; 3.2555 may be met with an injunctive action initiated by the
PUC (at the request of an aggrieved party).  Furthermore, willful and knowing violations of
PURA 95 (including &#167; 3.2555) are considered to be third degree felonies.  &#167; 1.325. 
Injunctive actions for violations of PURA 95 may be brought in Travis County, counties where
the violations are alleged to have occurred, or in the county of a defendant&#146;s residence. 
&#167; 1.328.
<P> It is unclear whether a private right of action may be initiated to enforce &#167; 3.2555. 
While the PUC is clearly vested with jurisdiction to enforce &#167; 3.2555, it is not apparent
that it has exclusive jurisdiction to do so.  In instances where state agencies do not hold original
or exclusive jurisdiction over a claim, courts have invoked the &quot;doctrine of primary
jurisdiction.&quot;  That doctrine embodies a form of judicial abstention whereby a court, which
has jurisdiction over a matter, nonetheless defers to an administrative agency for an initial
decision on questions of fact or law within the peculiar competence of the agency.  <I>REO
Industries v. Natural Gas Pipeline Co.</I>, 932 F.2d 447, 456 (5th Cir. 1991).  Therefore, if a
proceeding concerning the application or enforcement of &#167; 3.2555 were initiated before a
district court and that court felt that the issues would be better addressed by the PUC in the first
instance, the litigants may be directed to the Commission.  On the other hand, if a court was
persuaded that the PUC&#146;s specialized expertise was not needed to assess the issues before
it, it may decide that the doctrine of primary jurisdiction has no application and that it can
proceed to decide the issues.  <I>See Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. v. Public Utility
Commission</I>, 735 S.W.2d 663 (Tex. App.--Austin 1987, no writ).  Indeed, how the parties
frame the issues may well control a court&#146;s decision in this regard.  For example,
enforcement of &#167; 3.2555 may becharacterized as a simple matter involving an interest in
real property, or it may be characterized as a complicated matter requiring expertise in
telecommunications technology and the needs of utilities in providing service.  The latter would
appear more likely to persuade a court that the doctrine of primary jurisdiction was applicable
and referral to the PUC was warranted.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><A NAME="IV">IV. </B><B>Federal Law Regarding
Access</A></B><BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> The FTA does not contain an explicit provision concerning access to private property.
However, the Federal Communications Commission (&quot;FCC&quot;) is currently
considering at least two rulemaking proceedings in which access issues are involved, and the
FTA itself appears to leave the door open for state regulation of access issues.
<P> <B>A. </B><B>FTA Provisions</B>
<P> Lawmakers considering the FTA rejected legislative proposals that would have required
commercial and multifamily real estate owners to effectively guarantee access to a potentially
unlimited number of telecommunications service providers.  Groups opposed to such provisions,
such as the National Realty Committee, characterized such proposals as &quot;willfully
ignoring&quot; space limitations in commercial buildings as well as security and liability
concerns, and hailed Congress&#146;s action (in enacting a bill without these provisions) as
properly allowing the marketplace to solve infrastructure issues inherent in making
telecommunications services accessible to users of commercial Property. [ Cornerstone , the
Newsletter of the National Realty Committee, January/February 1996.] 
<P> Probably the closest thing in the FTA to a provision addressing access issues is &#167; 207,
which directs the FCC to:
<P><FONT SIZE=-1><BLOCKQUOTE>. . . promulgate regulations to prohibit restrictions that
impair a viewer&#146;s ability to
receive video programming services through devices designed for over-the-air reception of
television broadcast signals, multi-channel multi-point distribution service, or direct broadcast
satellite services.</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>As structured this appears to contemplate regulations regarding access to satellite reception
of video programming communications.  Nevertheless, as is discussed below, the implications of
such regulations may be broader than anticipated.
<P> <B>B. </B><B>FCC Rulemaking </B><B>&#151; Access to Private Property</B>
<P> In January 1996, the FCC released a Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (&quot;NOPR&quot;)
which addresses a variety of issues related to the provision of telecommunications services (CS
Docket No. 95-184; <I>In the Matter of Telecommunications Services Inside Wiring, Customer
Premises </I><I>Equipment</I>).  The proceeding was initiated at the request of the Media
Access Project, the United States Telephone Association and Citizens for a Sound Economy
Foundation.
<P> At first blush the rulemaking appears aimed at bringing parity between cable home wiring
rules and telephone inside wiring rules.  The Commission&#146;s notice recognizes that the
technological and regulatory differences between cable operators and telephone companies are
dissolving and that the two types of companies are beginning to enter each other&#146;s
business domains.  Furthermore, as each industry upgrades its service offerings the type of
wiring and wiring configurations used may become indistinguishable.  Thus, the Commission
perceived a need to reconsider several issues associated with cable and telephone service.
<P> One of those issues is service provider access to private property.  As stated by the
Commission in the NOPR (at &#182; 58), &quot;we also wish to examine the right of various
service providers to obtain access to private property, such as multiple dwelling unit buildings,
private housing developments, and office buildings.&quot;  The Commission acknowledges that
telephone companies have traditionally gained access to private property through private
easements and contracts with the property owners, and in some instances such companies are
able to resort to exercise of the power of eminent domain.  <I>Id</I> at &#182; 59.  In contrast,
cable operators&#146; right to access property has been less defined.  Some cable operators have
sought to obtain access to private property under a variety of legal theories, including assertion of
First Amendment rights (as they relate to freedom of speech).  <I>Id</I>. at &#182; 60.
<P> The Commission comments that parity of access rights to private property &quot;may be a
necessary predicate&quot; to any attempt to achieve parity in the rules governing cable and
telephone network inside wiring.  <I>Id</I> at &#182; 61.  In this regard the Commission noted
that:
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>An inequality in access can unfairly benefit one provider over another. 
For instance, if one service provider has an unrestricted right of access to private property--even
over the objection of the property owner--that service provider would be able to compete for
individual subscribers in every multiple dwelling unit building, private housing development and
office building, while the provider without such a right could only compete in those buildings in
which it had managed to obtain the property owner&#146;s consent.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> Clearly the FCC is contemplating rules which will govern rights of access to private
property.  To the extent that such access rights can be imbued with the appearance of necessity to
further the competitive goals of the FTA, the FCC may well be persuaded to grant such rights. 
On the other hand, the so-called &quot;takings&quot; legislation has been a much talked about
item in Congress, and protection of private property rights has been a high profile item with
many members of Congress.  How the FCC resolves these apparently divergent interests remains
to be seen.
<P> <B>C. </B><B>FCC Rulemaking </B><B>&#151; Satellite Operations</B>
<P> The FCC has also taken actions in regard to the regulation of satellite dishes.  In the first of
two recent proceedings, the Commission, on March 11, 1996, issued a report, order and further
notice of proposed rulemaking (&quot;Order and Further Notice&quot;) in IB Docket No. 95-59;
<I>In the Matter </I><I>of Preemption of Local Zoning Regulation of Satellite Earth
Stations</I>.   The &quot;further notice ofproposed rulemaking&quot; was intended to seek
comment on the implementation of &#167; 207 of the FTA. As noted above, that section directs
the FCC to preempt non-federal restrictions on certain direct-to-home video services, including
direct broadcast satellite service.  FCC action in this regard, and in particular its preemption
provisions, originated in 1986 in response to evidence that state and local governments were, in
some instances, posing unreasonably restrictive burdens on the installation of satellite antennas. 
The 1986 rule preempted ordinances that discriminated against satellite antennas and imposed
unreasonable limitations on reception or unreasonable costs on users.  Since that time, and
similar to other issues involved with telecommunications in general, technological and regulatory
changes have created a perceived need on behalf of the FCC to review its preemption rule.  In
essence, the Commission determined to assess rules with respect to satellite antennas falling into
two basic categories based on the service provided.  The first category was those antennas
designed for direct-to-home reception of video programming for home entertainment purposes,
and the second being antennas designed for two-way commercial communications.
<P> Although many local governments objected to the Commission&#146;s actions, the
Commission opined in its order (at &#182; 12) that the federal interests at stake affirmed its legal
authority to preempt state and local government regulation of satellite earth stations.  Further, the
Commission cited &#167; 207 of the FTA as support for its ability to preempt state and local
zoning regulations.  As noted in the Order and Further Notice (at &#182; 16), the Commission
believed that &#167; 207 evidences Congress&#146; recognition that the federal interests at
stake warrant preemption of inconsistent state and local regulations, even when those regulations
address a traditionally local subject such as land use.
<P> The &quot;further notice of proposed rulemaking&quot; discussed in connection with the
proceeding described above spawned the second proceeding addressing &#167; 207 of the TRA. 
On August 6, 1996, the Commission released a &quot;report and order, memorandum opinion
and order, and future notice of proposed rulemaking&quot; in consolidated dockets IB Docket
No. 95-59, <I>In the Matter of Preemption </I><I>of Local Zoning Regulation of Satellite Earth
Stations</I> and CS Docket No. 96-83, <I>In the Matter of </I><I>Implementation of
Section</I><I> </I><I>207 of the Telecommunications Act of 1996</I>.  In its order the
Commission rejected the argument that it lacked authority to prohibit nongovernmental
restrictions (on the location of satellite dishes and antennae) such as restrictive covenants because
such prohibitions would constitute a taking of private property under the Fifth Amendment to the
Constitution.  <I>Id</I> at &#182; 41.  The Commission identified three categories of property
rights which could be affected by its rules, to wit (at &#182; 48):
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>(a)  property within the exclusive use or control of a person who has a
direct or indirect
ownership interest in the property;
<P>(b)  property not under the exclusive use and control of a person who has a direct or indirect
ownership interest in the property, including the outside of the building, including the roof; and
<P>(c)  residential or commercial property that is subject to lease
agreements.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Based on these categorizations the FCC adopted a rule applying only to the first ownership
class. The Commission has requested further comment on whether the rule should be applied to
other categories of property interests and ownership, and specifically requested comment on the
constitutional and legal analysis of such a rule as it relates to takings jurisprudence.  <I>Id</I> at
&#182; 59-65. Such an analysis will likely involve many of the same principles discussed below
in connection with &#167; 3.2555 of PURA 95.  A copy of the preemption rule adopted in this
proceeding is attached as <I><U>Exhibit</U></I><I><U> </U></I><I><U>B</U></I>.  The
manner in which the rule preempts local regulation and any &quot;private covenant,
homeowners&#146; association rule or similar restriction on property . . .&quot; provides a good
illustration of how property rights are being impeded upon in the interest of promoting a
competitive telecommunications market.  Furthermore, the property rights analyses conducted in
those types of proceedings will likely be relied upon in any further proceedings considering the
adoption of similar rules extending to additional types of telecommunications services (including
telephone service).
<P>  <B>D. </B><B>Preemption of State Law</B>
<P> The enactment of the revisions contained in PURA 95 was followed closely by the adoption
of the FTA.  As a consequence there was considerable uncertainty as to the impact of both pieces
of legislation, particularly with respect to areas where the two appeared to conflict.  That
uncertainty continues today as the FCC recently released a 700-page order containing certain of
its rules for implementation of the FTA. [ CC Docket No. 96-98; <I>In the Matter of
Implementation of the Local Competition Provisions in the Telecommunications Act of
1996</I> And CC Docket No. 95-185; <I>In the Matter of Interconnection Between Local
Exchange Carriers And Commercial Mobile Radio Service Providers</I>  (Released August 8,
1996).]   One thing does appear certain and that is that the federal law will accelerate the speed
with which competition is introduced into local markets.
<P> The FTA contains a provision which appears to preempt state regulation in many respects.
Section 253 of the FTA, titled &quot;Removal of Barriers to Entry,&quot; provides (in part) as
follows:
<P><FONT SIZE=-1><B><BLOCKQUOTE>(a)</B>  <B>In general</B>
<P> No State or local statute or regulation, or other State or local legal requirement, may prohibit
or have the effect of prohibiting the ability of any entity to provide any interstate or intrastate
telecommunications service.
<P><B>(b)</B><B> </B><B> </B><B>State regulatory authority</B>
<P> Nothing in this section shall affect the ability of a State to impose, on a competitively
neutral basis and consistent with section 254 of this section, requirements necessary to preserve
and advance universal service, protect the public safety and welfare, ensure the continued quality
of telecommunications services, and safeguard the rights of consumers.
<P><B>(c)</B><B> </B><B> </B><B>State and local government authority</B>
<P> Nothing in this section affects the authority of a State or local government to manage the
public rights-of-way or to require fair and reasonable compensation from
telecommunicationsproviders, on a competitively neutral and nondiscriminatory basis, for use of
public rights-of-way on a nondiscriminatory basis, if the compensation required is publicly
disclosed by such government.
<P><B>(d)</B><B> </B><B> </B><B>Preemption</B>
<P> If, after notice and an opportunity for public comment, the Commission determines that a
State or local government has permitted or imposed any statute, regulation, or legal requirement
that violates subsection (a) or (b) of this section, the Commission shall preempt the enforcement
of such statute, regulation, or legal requirement to the extent necessary to correct such violation
or inconsistency.  . . .</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT>
<P> Although this provision has the potential to preempt state regulation in many areas, access
to private property does not appear to be one of those.   The principles contained in &#167;
3.2555 arguably have the effect of promoting the ability of entities to provide intrastate
telecommunications service.  Furthermore, there is no conflicting counterpart to &#167; 3.2555
in the FTA for which preemption would be required due to the conflict.  Thus, nothing in the
FTA appears to abrogate the intended effect of &#167; 3.2555.  Practitioners should be mindful,
however, of the FCC proceedings discussed above.  Federal regulations have the same
preemptive effect as federal statutes.  <I>See</I> <I>Fidelity Federal Savings &amp; Loan
Assoc. v. De La Cuesta</I>, 458 U.S. 141, 153 (1982).  Therefore, if regulations are issued by
the FCC which conflict with &#167; 3.2555, the state law may be
preempted.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><A NAME="V">V. </B><B>Legal Challenges to Access Provisions</B></A>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE> The right of access to private property purportedly granted by PURA 95
raises fundamental
issues concerning the compelled use of private property and the payment of compensation
therefore. While the authors have found no evidence that a statute similar to &#167; 3.2555
affecting telephone service has been challenged in any reported state or federal decisions, battles
involving cable television service have involved similar principles.  Those, along with cases
involving other related issues, may help to shed some light on the challenges which may be made
to &#167; 3.2555.  Please note that this is not intended to be a comprehensive analysis of the
constitutionality of &#167; 3.2555, but instead is intended as an overview of issues which may
be raised in such an analysis.
<P> <B>A. </B><B>Takings</B>
<P> The Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution provides, in part, that &quot;. . . nor
shall private property be taken for public use, without just compensation.&quot;  This provision
has been invoked in hundreds, if not thousands, of cases involving the propriety of governmental
actions affecting private property.
<P> The Texas Constitution contains a counterpart to the Fifth Amendment to the U.S.
Constitution.  Specifically, section 17 of Art. I states, in relevant part, as follow:
<P>Sec. 17   No person&#146;s property shall be taken, damaged or destroyed for or applied to
public use without adequate compensation being made, unless by the consent of such person; . . .
<P>Much like its federal counterpart, this provision provides the foundation for state law claims
involving takings, or &quot;inverse condemnation,&quot; and is invoked frequently in litigation
over the use of private real property.  <I>See</I> <I>e.g</I>., <I>City of Pharr v. Pena</I>, 853
S.W.2d 56, 60 (Tex. App.--San Antonio 1993, writ denied).  (&quot;If a person is arbitrarily
denied the right to subdivide his land and have a map or plat of same recorded in the deed
records of the county . . . he is arbitrarily denied the full use and benefit of his property in
violation of the Constitution&quot;); <I>Houston &amp; North Texas Motor Freight
</I><I>Lines v. Johnson</I>, 159 S.W.2d 905, 907 (Tex. Civ. App.--Galveston 1942,
rev&#146;d on other grounds 166 S.W.2d 78 (Tex. 1942)) (&quot;The right of property which is
secured by [Art. I, &#167; 19] consists not merely in the ownership and possession of property
but also in the unrestricted right of the use, enjoyment and disposal thereof subject only to the
police power.&quot;)
<P> 
<P> Perhaps the leading case involving a provision similar to &#167; 3.2555 is <I>Loretto v.
Teleprompter </I><I>Manhattan CATV Corp</I>., 458 U.S. 419, 1023 S.Ct. 3164 (1982).  At
issue in <I>Loretto</I> was a New York statute which provided that:
<P><FONT SIZE=-1><BLOCKQUOTE>1.  No landlord shall
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>  (a) interfere with the installation of cable television facilities upon his
property or premises,
except that a landlord may require:
<P><BLOCKQUOTE> (i) that the installation of cable television facilities conform to such
reasonable conditions as
are necessary to protect the safety, functioning and appearance of the premises, and the
convenience and well-being of other tenants;
<P> (ii) that the cable television company or the tenant or a combination thereof bear the entire
cost of the installation, operation or removal of such facilities; and
<P> (iii) that the cable television company agree to indemnify the landlord for any damage
caused by the installation, operation or removal of such facilities.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> (b) demand or accept payment from any tenant, in any form, in exchange for permitting
cable television service on or within his property or premises, or from any cable television
company in exchange therefor in excess of any amount which the commission shall, by
regulation, determine to be reasonable; or
<P> (c) discriminate in rental charges, or otherwise, between tenants who receive cable television
service and those who do not.</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT>
<P>This statute was challenged by the owner of an apartment building.  The previous owner had
allowed Teleprompter (a cable TV company) to install certain equipment in order to provide
cable TV service to tenants (and to neighboring buildings) and had given that company an
exclusive right to provide service to the building&#146;s tenants.  The &quot;new&quot; owner
(who was unaware of the cable installation) initiated a class action alleging, in part, that to the
extent Teleprompter relied on the statute for the installation and continued presence of its
equipment, it resulted in a taking without just compensation.  Justice Marshall characterized the
case as presenting the question of whether &quot;a minor but permanent physical occupation of
an owner&#146;s property authorized by government&quot; constitutes a &quot;taking&quot;
of property for which compensation is due under the Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments. 
<I>Id</I>. at 421.
<P> In finding that a taking had occurred the Court noted prior cases holding that when the
character of the governmental action is a permanent physical occupation of property a taking
occurs to the extent of the occupation, &quot;without regard to whether the action achieves an
important public benefit or has only minimal economic import on the owner.&quot;  <I>Id</I>.
at 434-35; citing <I>Penn Central </I><I>Transportation Co. v. New York City</I>, 438 U.S.
104, 124; 98 S.Ct. 2646, 2659 (1978).  The Court focused on the physical occupation of property
required by the New York statute, and found that it deprived property owners of one of the most
&quot;treasured strands&quot; in the bundle of property rights; that is, the right to exclude others
from possession and use of space.  <I>Loretto</I>, <I>id</I>. at 435.  The required physical
occupation conflicts with a property owner&#146;s expectation that he will be relatively
undisturbed in his occupation of property, and such an occupation is qualitatively more severe
than a regulation of the use of property.  <I>Id</I> at 436.
<P> Furthermore, the Court dismissed he notion that the amount of space taken by the
occupation affected its status as a taking.  The constitutional protection for the rights of private
property cannot be made to depend on the size of the area permanently occupied.  <I>Id</I>. at
436, citing <I>U.S. v. Causby</I>, 38 U.S. 256, 66 S.Ct. (1946).  Once the fact of occupation is
shown a court should consider the extent of the occupation as one relevant factor in determining
the compensation due.  For that reason the Court opined that there is less need to consider the
extent of the occupation in determining whether there is a taking in the first instance.  <I>Id</I>.
at 437-38.  The Court confined its opinions to determining whether a taking had occurred, and
did not provide any insight as to the amount of compensation due.
<P> Although <I>Loretto</I> would appear to provide some basis to support a constitutional
challenge to &#167; 3.2555, the holding in <I>Princeton Cablevision, Inc. v. Union Valley
Corp.</I>, 478 A.2d 1234 (N.J. Super.Ct. Ch. Div. 1983) may suggest otherwise.  That case
involved a New Jersey statute &quot;whose thrust is very much like&quot; the statute at issue in
<I>loretto</i>. [ The New Jersey statute provided that:<BR>  No owner of a dwelling or his
agent shall forbid or prevent any tenant of such dwelling from receiving cable television service,
nor demand or accept payment in any form as a condition of permitting the installation of such
service in the dwelling or portion thereof occupied by such tenant as his place of residence, nor
shall discriminate in rental charges or otherwise against any such tenant receiving cable
television service; provided, however, that such owner or his agent may require that the
installation of cable television facilities conform to all reasonable conditions necessary to protect
the safety, functioning, appearance and value of the premises and the convenience, safety and
well-being of other tenants; and further provided, that a cable television company installing any
such facilities for the benefit of a tenant in any dwelling shall agree to indemnify the owner
thereof for any damage caused by the installation, operation or removal of such facilities and for
any liability which may arise out of such installation, operation or removal.]     <I>Id</I>. at
1240.  The court recognized the import of <I>Loretto</I>, but then resorted to &quot;judicial
surgery&quot; to save the statute.  Explaining its &quot;duty to operate&quot; and the nature of
its actions the court stated that:
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>The surgery can take the form of excision of an offending provision or
supplying a constitutionally required one.  There is nothing novel about engrafting a requirement
of just compensation onto a statute that authorizes what amounts to a taking.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>Id</I>. at 1240-41; citing <I>Lomarch Corp. v. Mayor of Englewood</I>, 237 A.2d 881
(1968).  Having thus defined its role as surgeon charged with the task of saving the statute, the
court focused on indemnification language which required payment to the property owner (by the
cable company) for &quot;any damage&quot; caused by the installation, operation or removal of
the facilities.  The court found that a &quot;generous reading&quot; of that provision would
include an obligation to pay damages for the taking of the owner&#146;s property. 
<I>Princeton</I>, <I>Id</I>., at 1241.  In other words, a broad reading of the indemnification
language provided the required just compensation and therefore saved the statute from
invalidation.
<P> The relevance of these cases to an analysis of &#167; 3.2555 is obvious.  In both cases the
statutes at issue had features very similar to &#167; 3.2555.  These provide strong support for
the proposition that a taking occurs by virtue of the required access under &#167; 3.2555.  The
more difficult issue appears to be whether that taking is accompanied by &quot;just
compensation.&quot;  Recall that &#167; 3.2555 allows compensation to be paid on a
nondiscriminatory basis.  That, in essence, places a ceiling on what can be charged to
telecommunications service providers.  Whether this nevertheless allows for just compensation
remains to be seen.  Cases discussing other issues raised in this regard are discussed below.
<P> <B>B. </B><B>Just Compensation</B>
<P> By ostensibly limiting compensation that can be charged to telecommunications utilities to
no more than what is being paid by other companies, &#167; 3.2555 exerts a degree of control
over market prices.  Forms of price controls have been upheld in certain settings (such as
regulated utility rates) and invalidated in others (such as certain statutory rent controls).  One
example of a challenged price control involves wholesale and retail gasoline prices.  <I>Tenoco
Oil Co. v. Department of Consumer </I><I>Affairs</I>, 876 F.2d 1013 (1st Cir. 1989).  In 1986
the Puerto Rico Department of Consumer Affairs issued orders regulating gasoline prices.  These
orders came several years after federal controls (implemented during the oil crises of the
1970&#146;s) expired.  Various gasoline refineries and wholesalers challenged the controls,
alleging that they amounted to a taking.  The First Circuit noted that the plaintiffs could not
constitutionally be subject to controls which &quot;. . . depress the prices they may charge below
just and reasonable levels, at least in the absence of an adequate remedy under Puerto Rico law to
secure to them just compensation for the &#145;taking&#146; that such a regulation would
impose.&quot;  <I>Id</I>. at 1023, citing <I>Duquesne Light Company v. Barasch</I>, 488
U.S. 299, 109 S.Ct. 609 (1989)).  Although dismissing the case as having been filed prematurely
(since the state had not conducted full hearings to determine whether the pricing limits resulted
in just compensation), the court clearly recognized a requirement that compensation be
reasonable.
<P> A similar principle was articulated in <I>City of Berkeley v. City of Berkeley Rent
Stabilization </I><I>Board</I>, 27 Cal. App. 4th  951, 33 Cal. Rptr. 317 (Cal.Ct. App. 1994),
which involved a challenge to certain rent control regulations.  In considering the challenge the
court noted that a rent controlstandard which does not permit a just and reasonable return on a
landlord&#146;s investment is confiscatory, and if a rent control measure does not expressly
assure the landlord of that fair return on investment such a condition will be implied.  <I>Id</I>.
at 962.  This and other cases make clear that in situations of government controls affecting
property the ability to earn a just and reasonable return is a necessary constitutional requirement.
<P> At least one Texas Supreme Court decision has adopted this same approach with respect to a
rent control statute.  In <I>Culberson v. Ashford</I>, 18 S.W.2d 585 (Tex. 1929), the court
considered statutory amendments enacted in 1915 which affected the rights of landlords leasing
agricultural property.  The court noted that in a similar context the U.S. Supreme Court had
stated that:
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>The right of the owner to fix a price at which his property shall be sold or
used is an inherent attribute of the property itself.  <I>Case of the State Freight Tax</I>, 15
Wall. 232, 278 [21 L.Ed. 146], and, as such, within the protection of the due process of law
clauses of the Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>Culberson</I>, <I>Id</I>. at 587.  Based on this and other authority, the court found the
1915 rent control provisions unconstitutional because it failed to recognize the differences in
value of property or property rights involved, did not provide for fair or reasonable returns, and
did not take into account the value of a piece of property, the improvements upon it, or its
location.  <I>Id</I>. [The provision of the 1915 statutory amendment which led to its demise
provided as follows:<br>   .  .  .  any contract for the leasing or renting of land or tenements at
will or for a term of years for agricultural purposes stipulating or fixing a higher or greater rental
than that herein provided for, shall be null and void, and shall not be enforceable in any court in
this state by an action either at law or in equity and no lien of any kind, either contractual or
statutory, shall attach in favor of the landlord, his estate or assigns, upon any of the property
named, nor for the purpose mentioned in this Article. <BR><U>See</U> <I>Tigner V. First
National Bank of Angleton</I> , 264 S.w.2d 85, 87 (Tex. 1954).] 
<P> The compensation element of &#167; 3.2555 does not fit easily into the types of cases
described above.  On the one hand effectively limiting compensation to whatever level is agreed
to with one service provider may impede a property owner from earning &quot;just
compensation&quot; if, in fact, the first &quot;deal&quot; (voluntarily consummated) is at a less
than &quot;just&quot; level.  The general right to make a contract in relation to one&#146;s
business is a part of the liberty protected by the Constitution, and restricting a contract to certain
consideration may interfere with that protected right.  <I>See Hanley v. Moody</I>, 39 F.2d
198, 200 (N.D. Tex., 1930).  On the other hand, if one transaction is freely entered into, the terms
of that transaction, including its compensation element, may provide strong evidence that the
compensation is reasonable as an element of an identical transaction with another
party.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><A NAME="VI">VI. </B><B>Practical Considerations</B></A>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE> It is hoped that the following thoughts may be of some practical
assistance in representing a building owner dealing with telecommunication utilities.
<P> <B>A. </B><B> </B><B>Single or Multiple Demarcation Point</B>
<P> A building owner concerned about letting multiple telecommunications providers install
facilities in the owner's building could take the position that the building owner owns all wiring
inside the point where the main line enters the building (known as a &quot;single demarcation
point&quot;). [ See  Docket No. 14,147; <I>Complaint of Ge Capital Rescom and
Multitechnology Services, L.p. Against Gte Southwest Incorporated for Refusal to Relocate
Network Demarcation Points</I> , 21 P.U.C. Bull . 119 (August 9, 1995); also Docket No.
10,831; <I>Application of Southwestern Bell Telephone Company to Revise its Tariff to
Redefine the Point Of Demarcation ( "Demarc ") and the Location of Network Interface ( "Ni
")</I> , 20 P.U.C. Bull . 1026 (June 8, 1994).] The building owner might attempt to purchase
telecommunications services wholesale at the single demarcation point and resell the services at
retail to the building's tenants (a &quot;shared distribution system&quot;), thereby realizing a
profit.  However, this alternative has substantial drawbacks, including potential liability for
interruption of service, responsibility for maintenance of the telecommunications facilities inside
the building, the possibility of being considered a public utility subject to licensing and
regulation by the Puc, [However, several cases have held rather extensive shared distribution
systems not to be subject to regulation. <I>Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. V. Public Utility
Comm'n of Texas</I> , 745 S.W.2d 918 (Tex.App.-Austin 1988, writ denied) (non-licensed
company offering telephone service to the residential, office and commercial tenants at Dobie
Center, a multistory, privately owned dormitory near the University of Texas); <I>Southwestern
Bell Telephone Co. V. Public Utility Comm'n of Texas</I> , 735 S.W.2d 663 (Tex.App.-Austin
1987, no writ) (private, competitive switching systems serving small and distinct areas within the
geographical areas reserved to Southwestern Bell in its certificate of convenience and necessity
including one provider that supplied the equivalent of 3,800 access lines, more service than that
provided by 45 of the 71 regulated telephone companies in texas). <U>See also</U>, <I>Public
Utility Comm'n of Texas V. Federal Communications Comm'n </I>, 886 F.2d 1325 (D.C.Cir.
1989) (Southwestern Bell permitted to provide additional interconnections to Atlantic Richfield
Company so it could use its own microwave communications network to avoid using the local
telephone exchange provided by GTE).]  and, perhaps most importantly, the substantial headache
of trying to operate a complex
business with which most building owners have no experience.
<P> Accordingly, most building owners will opt to permit telecommunications providers to
maintain ownership of their wiring and other facilities to the point of contact with the individual
tenants (known as a &quot;multiple demarcation point&quot; system).
<P> <B>B. </B><B> </B><B>Non-Exclusive Agreements</B>
<P> In the interest of promoting competition and insuring the best services for its tenants, it
would probably be to the building owner's advantage to make sure that any agreement the
ownerenters into with any telecommunications provider is a non-exclusive agreement.  Further,
as discussed above, PURA 95 requires such non-exclusivity, although the statute may be subject
to constitutional challenges.
<P> <B>C. </B><B>Requiring Compensation</B>
<P> As discussed above, PURA 95 permits building owners to &quot;require [a]
telecommunications utility to pay compensation that is reasonable and non-discriminatory . . .
.&quot;  One approach to compensation issues is that being recommended by the Building
Owners and Managers Association (&quot;BOMA&quot;) to its members to &quot;think
retail&quot; and charge the telecommunications utility based upon the value to the utility of
having access to the owner's building and not on the basis of the square footage needed by the
provider (usually about 125 square feet, perhaps in the basement).  A Dallas BOMA
representative compared the situation to renting restaurant space.  The same restaurant space
would have one value in an office building housing 50 persons who would need a place to have
lunch, a greater value in an office building where 500 people worked, and a still greater value if
it were the only restaurant near any of five surrounding office buildings.
<P> BOMA strongly takes the position that PURA 95 is unconstitutional and that a building
owner is at liberty to charge each telecommunications utility desiring access to the owner's
building whatever the owner wants.  However, if a telecommunications utility desiring access to
a building already served by, say, SWB, contends that no charge is permissible under PURA 95
because the building owner is not charging SWB, BOMA recommends requesting SWB to pay.
<P> Another approach to compensation may be to tie it to a specified percentage of revenues
earned by a telecommunications utility from tenants in the building.  If all telecommunications
utilities seeking access to the building were charged the same percentage the charge is arguably
non-discriminatory (even though the revenue earned from each will differ).  Of course this
invites complications over issues such as the calculation of revenues from services provided to
tenants, and implementation of this approach will require skillful drafting.
<P> <B>D. </B><B> </B><B>Limit Number of Companies</B>
<P> PURA 95 permits building owners to &quot;impose reasonable limitations on the number of
. . . telecommunications utilities having access to the owner's property if the owner can
demonstrate space constraints that require such limitations . . . .&quot;  Such a limitation would
seem to be a practical necessity.  Building owners should also consider requiring
telecommunications companies to identify which tenants they will be serving in order to track
the effect of tenant changes on a company&#146;s right to be in the building (i.e., if the only
tenant a company serves leaves the building it may terminate that company&#146;s right of
access).   Finally, building owners should require proof that the telecommunications company
holds whatever authority to provide service is required by federal, state and/or local law. 
<I>See</I> section III.A.1.a. above).
<P> <B>E. </B><B> </B><B>Maintain Control</B>
<P> The building owner will want to maintain control over the installation of the
telecommunications company's facilities to insure that the location is as agreed upon and the
installation is proper.  For example, the building owner may have responsibility if one
telecommunications provider ties into another's lines without permission.  Also, building owners
should consider requiring that telecommunications utilities specify what equipment is necessary
to serve tenants in the building, and should consider precluding those companies from installing
any additional equipment (such as equipment used to serve tenants in a neighboring building).
<P> <B>F. </B><B> </B><B>Indemnification</B>
<P> The building owner will want any agreement it makes with a telecommunications provider
to contain an indemnification provision protecting the owner from liability for the
telecommunications provider's activities.
<P> <B>G. </B><B> </B><B>Short Contract Term</B>
<P> In view of the rapid changes occurring in the telecommunications industry and its
regulation, a building owner may wish to consider keeping any agreement it enters into with a
telecommuni cations provider relatively short, say three years rather than seven or ten years.
<P> <B>H. </B><B> </B><B>Tenant Lease Provisions</B>
<P> The building owner will also want to consider provisions in its standard tenant lease form
pertaining to telecommunications.  For example, the lease form could provide that:
<P> 1. The building owner is not liable for interruptions in telecommunications services, and any
such interruptions do not constitute constructive eviction.
<P> 2. The tenant must obtain the owner's prior written consent before entering into any
agreement that would require the installation of telecommunications wiring or equipment in the
owner's building.
<P> 3. The landlord has the option to require the removal of such equipment at the tenant's cost
upon termination of the lease.
