<img src="lprh_grn.gif">
<h1>HIGH TECH REAL ESTATE</h1><br>
<h2>Riding Along The Information Highway<br>
To The Smart Building</h2>
<p>
<p>
<h3> Royce Jay Hailey, Jr.<br>
Locke Purnell Rain Harrell<br>
Austin, TX<p>
<p>
<p>
The University of Texas School of Law<br>
and<br>
Texas Mortgage Bankers Association<br>
28th Annual Mortgage Lending Institute<br.
<p>
Austin, Texas<br>
September 22 & 23, 1994<p>
Dallas, Texas <br>
October 13 & 14, 1994<br>
<p></h3>
<hr>
</center>

<b>I.     Introduction.</b><p>
<blockquote>
     The information revolution which has occurred over the past 20 years has had a significant
effect on the real estate industry.  So-called "smart buildings" are now equipped with
state-of-the-art
technology to provide sophisticated telecommunications systems; automated climate-control 
systems; fire, safety and security monitoring systems; data processing and other computer
services;
and a constantly expanding array of other technology products.  These special features have been
used effectively by owners and developers of office buildings, apartments projects and
residential
subdivisions to attract tenants and purchasers.  These amenities will be further enhanced as the
long-awaited "information highway" becomes a reality through the expanded use of fiber optic
cable,
wider  use of cellular telephones and other wireless communication, and easier access to the
Internet
system.<p>

     In this rapidly changing technological environment, the regulatory structure for the
telecommunications industry which has developed over the past several decades has created a
confusing regulatory patchwork that can be very cumbersome for a real estate developer.  
Likewise,
many of the traditional concepts of property law do not easily fit in with these new
circumstances. 
This article gives a general overview of the regulatory issues as they relate to real estate projects
and
the application of traditional property law concepts to the new technology.  The article addresses
the questions:  Who can provide telecommunication services?  Who controls access to the
buildings
and the customers?  How can property rights be protected?<p>
 </blockquote>
<b>II.    Regulatory Issues - Who Can Provide Telecommunications Services?</b><p>
<dl>
<dd> 
     <b>A.     AT&T Break Up.</b><p>

<blockquote>   The owner of an office building, apartment project or residential subdivision who
wishes to provide state-of-the-art  telecommunications and other technology services must first
have a general understanding of the very confusing and constantly changing regulatory structure
for the telecommunications industry.  A good starting point for understanding this regulatory
structure is
the antitrust action that resulted in the 1984 break up of American Telephone and Telegraph
Company ("AT&T"), which included the divestiture of the Bell System operating companies,
and
the creation of seven regional holding companies, including Southwestern Bell Telephone
Company. 
This action began in 1949, when the U.S. Justice Department filed an antitrust lawsuit because of
AT&T's attempts to expand its manufacturing and sale of telephone equipment.  This  resulted in
the entry of a 1956 Consent Decree prohibiting AT&T from conducting any business unrelated
to
providing regulated common carrier communication services.  In 1974, the Justice Department
brought a second antitrust action alleging that AT&T had used its monopoly control over local
telephone service to the disadvantage of competitors in the long distance and telecommunication
equipment markets.  This resulted in the entry of a second Consent Decree in 1982.  See, United
States v. American Telephone and Telegraph Co.  552 F.Supp. 131 (D.D.C. 1982), aff'd mem.
sub
nom. Maryland v. United States, 460 U.S. 1001, 103 S. Ct. 1240 (1983).<p>

     The 1982 Consent Decree split the Bell System into two basic parts:  (i) the competitive
portion of the business, which would provide long distance service, manufacture
telecommunications equipment, and conduct research; and (ii) the noncompetitive portion of the
business, which would continue to provide local telecommunications service.  The competitive
portion was retained by AT&T and its Western Electric and Bell Labs subsidiaries, while the
noncompetitive portion was assigned to the seven regional holding companies and their
operating
company subsidiaries.  The distinction between the two portions of the business was to be
preserved
by creating "exchange areas" generally centering on metropolitan areas, within which the Bell
operating companies would provide "exchange telecommunications services" consisting
principally
of basic local switched telephone service.  The right to provide long distance "interexchange
telecommunication services" was reserved to AT&T and its non-Bell System competitors. <p>
     
     Since 1982, there have been numerous court cases and regulatory proceedings interpreting
the Consent Decree and establishing the line of demarcation for the type of telecommunication
services that can be provided by various parties.  For example, in United States v. Western
Electric
Company, Inc. et al., 797 F.2d 1082 (D.C. Cir. 1986), the Court of Appeals said the appellants
had
no standing to challenge the District Court's determination that the Consent Decree prohibits the
Bell
regional holding companies from selling certain "shared tenant services" within their regions.  In
the District Court opinion, found at 627 F.Supp. 1090, "shared tenant services" are described as
follows: <p>
<dl>
<dd>
     Shared tenant services are the provision by a developer or building owner of a
     package of telecommunications and related services to tenants.  Tenants' needs are
     then served on a shared basis using centralized voice and data switches and
     computers on the building premises. <p>
</dl>
     According to the District Court, among the benefits to the tenants are the cost savings
associated with the  aggregated demand which, depending upon the pricing policies of the
providers
of the services, may permit these tenants to acquire customer premise equipment, exchange
services,
and interexchange services at lower, volume-based prices.  The District Court said the shared
tenant
services market had developed substantially over the past few years, noting that "before 1983
there
were virtually no buildings with advanced shared-service capabilities while today [1986] there
are
some 70 such facilities in operation and another 50 expected shortly."  Nevertheless, the District
Court held that shared tenant services are "interexchange services" which the Bell regional
holding
companies are prohibited from providing under the terms of the Consent Decree.  According to
the
District Court:<p>
 <dl>
<dd> 
     [I]f the Regional Companies perform such an activity, that is, if they purchase
     interexchange services at a bulk price based on the demand in a particular building
     and then sold such services at retail at higher prices to the building's tenants - they,
     too, would be resellers in the interexchange business, and they would be in direct
     competition with other resellers and with facilities-based interexchange carriers.<p>
</dl>
</blockquote>
<b>  B.   Texas Public Utility Commission.</b><p>
<blockquote>
     The Public Utility Commission of Texas ("PUC") regulates "public utilities" through the
PUC's administration of the various statutory provisions that constitute the Public Utility
Regulatory
Act ("PURA"), Tex.Rev.Civ.Stat.Ann., Art. 1446(c).  Subsection 18(a) of PURA recognizes the
rapidly changing circumstances of the telecommunications industry, and gives the PUC the
authority
and power to adopt rules that may differ from the traditional public utility regulatory rules,
policies
and principles.<p>
<dl>
<dd>
     It is the policy of this state to protect the public interest in having adequate and
     efficient telecommunications service available to all citizens of the state at just, fair,
     and reasonable rates.  The legislature finds that the telecommunications industry
     through technical advancements, federal judicial and administrative actions, and the
     formulation of new telecommunications enterprises has become and will continue
     to be in many and growing areas a competitive industry which does not lend itself
     to traditional public utility regulatory rules, policies, and principles; and that
     therefore, the public interest requires that new rules, policies, and principles be
     formulated and applied to protect the public interest and to provide equal opportunity
     to all telecommunications utilities in a competitive marketplace.  It is the purpose of
     this section to grant to the commission the authority and the power under this Act to
     carry out the public policy herein stated.<p>
</dl>
     In Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. v. Public Utility Commission of Texas, 735 S.W.2d 663
(Tex.App.-Austin 1987, no writ), Southwestern Bell complained that a variety of individuals and
businesses had begun to install and utilize private, competitive switching systems serving small
and
distinct areas within the geographical areas reserved to Southwestern Bell in its certificate of
convenience and necessity.  Through these switching systems, a multitude of telephone users
gained
access to Southwestern Bell's lines servicing the individual or business that provided the system. 
Southwestern Bell argued that the new providers should be subject to the same regulatory
constraints
that applied to Southwestern Bell; i.e. they should be subject to rate of return and the other
obligations imposed on a "public utility."  The Court of Appeals described the situation as
follows:<p>
<dl>
<dd>
     For example, a landlord might install and maintain a computer "switching system"
     for the tenants in his large office building or complex, placing therein his own lines
     connecting his tenants' telephones to his "switching system" and thence to Bell's
     system to which the landlord subscribed.  While akin to the switchboard in an
     ordinary office situation, these systems (sometimes referred to as "shared tenant
     systems") were distinctive in their greater  magnitude, and in the fact that the systems
     often times included other services in addition to voice communications, such as
     word processing, security, voice mail, and environmental control.<p>
</dl>
     Southwestern Bell alleged that one provider supplied the equivalent of 3,800 access lines,
a magnitude of service that exceeded the access lines provided by 45 of the 71 telephone
companies
in Texas that held certificates of convenience and necessity issued by the PUC.  After conducting
a hearing on this issue, the PUC decided not to expand its rules to include this switching system
service as a "local exchange service," which would subject the service provider to PUC
regulation
as a public utility.  Instead, the PUC decided to make this determination on a case-by-case basis. 
The District Court  dismissed Southwestern Bell's appeal of the PUC decision for lack of
jurisdiction, which was affirmed by the Court of Appeals.<p>

     In another case styled Southwestern Bell Telephone Company v. Public Utility Commission
of Texas, 745 S.W.2d 918 (Tex.App.-Austin, 1988, writ denied), Southwestern Bell complained
that
a company was offering telephone service to the residential, office and commercial Dobie
Center,
a multi-story, privately owned dormitory near the University of Texas, without obtaining a
Certificate of Convenience and Necessity from the PUC.  The company provided telephone
service
only within the dormitory, primarily to residential tenants, utilizing its own lines and equipment
situated entirely within the building.  The company subscribed to Southwestern Bell's local
exchange
telephone service.  The Court of Appeals upheld the PUC's determination that this type of
telephone
service for one building did not required a Certificate of Convenience and Necessity from the
PUC
because (i) the company was not a dominant carrier as defined in PURA, and (ii) the company
was
not providing a local exchange telephone service.<p>

     Seeking alternatives to the local exchange companies, private businesses attempted to
establish their own "in-house telephone networks."  In Public Utility Commission of Texas v.
Federal Communications Commission, 886 F.2d 1325 (D.C.Cir. 1989), the FCC overturned an
order
of the Texas PUC that prohibited Southwestern Bell from providing additional interconnections
to
its telephone network so its customer could use its own microwave communications network to
avoid using another local telephone exchange.  Atlantic Richfield Company ("ARCO") set up its
own FCC-licensed microwave communications network that transmitted voice and other data
among
ARCO's offices throughout the United States, including facilities in Dallas and Plano, Texas. 
Local
telephone service was provided by Southwestern Bell in Dallas and GTE in Plano.  ARCO
became
dissatisfied with the service it was receiving from GTE, so it ordered additional trunk lines from
Southwestern Bell and used its microwave communications network to route all of its telephone
calls through Southwestern Bell rather than GTE.  GTE asked the  PUC to order Southwestern
Bell
to cease and desist from providing the additional interconnections to ARCO since it was
providing
service outside its franchise service area.  The PUC agreed with GTE and ordered Southwestern
Bell
to remove the additional lines it supplied to ARCO.  ARCO then petitioned the FCC to order
Southwestern Bell to continue providing the additional service to ARCO and declare the PUC's
order to be unlawful and invalid.  The FCC agreed with ARCO and asserted that any owner of a
private microwave communications system has a federal right (subject to the federal private
benefit-public detriment test) to choose its points of access to the public switched network
without any
interference from state regulators, who have regulatory jurisdiction over the telephone
companies
providing access service to the local switched network.  The Court of Appeals upheld the FCC's
order, and compared the situation to shared tenant services.<p>
<dl>
<dd>
     In the new and increasingly popular "shared telecommunications service," the
     multiple occupants of a building use voice and data equipment located on their
     premises to connect with a shared PBX or other switching device.  The switch, in
     turn, is connected to the local telephone company's central office.  The STS switch
     allows customers of the STS system to call each other directly using the local
     certificated carrier, and STS operators can purchase interexchange services at bulk
     discounts and resale them to their customers.  Thus, the STS operator , in bypassing
     the local certificated carrier, may occupy a position analogous to that of ARCO's
     private microwave network.  
</dl>
</blockquote>
    <b> C.   Telephone - Cable Television Cross-Ownership Restriction.</b><p>
<blockquote>
     The Federal Communications  Commission ("FCC") has adopted regulations prohibiting
telephone companies from directly providing cable television service to subscribers.  See,
Applications of Telephone Carriers for Section 214 Certificates for Channel Facilities Furnished
to
Affiliated Community and Antenna Television Systems, 21 FCC 2d 307, reconsidered in part,
22 FCC 2d 746 (1970), aff'd sub nom. General Telephone Co. v. United States 449 F.2d 846 (5th
Cir. 1971).  This prohibition against telephone company - cable television "cross-ownership"
was
codified in the Cable Communications Policy Act of 1984, found at 47 U.S.C. &#167533(b).
<p>

     In an important recent case, National Cable Television Association, Inc., et al v. Federal
Communications Commission and the United States of America, 1994 WL 459934 (DC Cir.
August 26, 1994), Court of Appeals upheld the FCC's determination that (i) video dialtone
service
does not constitute "cable service" within the meaning of the Cable Communications Policy Act
of
1984, and (ii) a telephone company providing video dialtone service is not a "cable operator"
subject
to the Act.  Telephone companies have historically used copper wire networks to provide voice
and
limited data communication.  Cable television systems have historically received signals through
an antenna (or more recently a satellite receiver) and transmitted them to local subscribers
through
coaxial cable laid under city streets or strung upon utility poles.  A telephone company that
wanted
to provide cable service had to construct a coaxial cable distribution system parallel to its
telephone
system.  However, technological advances since the 1984 Cable Act have made it practical to
deliver
video signals under the same common-carrier networks that are used to provide telephone
service. 
Meanwhile, cable television operators are beginning to upgrade their cable networks with
switching
and two-way capabilities that allow them to offer services in direct competition with local
telephone
companies.  In 1991, the FCC, noting the increasing convergence of previously separate markets
embracing voice, data graphics and video, propose to modify its rules to allow telephone
companies
to offer a new service it called "video dialtone," which the FCC described as an "electronic
platform" or "window" though which consumers could gain access to video programs,
information
services, video phone and other communications services.  The Court of Appeals said this was
not
a "cable service" because the telephone company was not engaged in the "transmission" of video
programming, which the FCC and Court of Appeals said require active participation in the
selection
and distribution of video programming.  Under the video dialtone arrangement, the selection and
distribution of video programming is provided by a third-party customer of the telephone
company,
which merely acts as a transparent conduit that enables the customer to send video programming
directly to subscribers.  The FCC and Court of Appeals used a similar analysis to determine that
a
telephone company providing video dialtone service is not a "cable operator" because a video
dialtone facility is not a cable system.  Therefore, the 1984 Cable Act did not require a telephone
company to get a cable franchise in order to offer video dialtone service since it was not
providing
a "cable service" and was not a "cable operator."<p>

     The National Cable Television Association case could be very important to building owners
who wish to control access to their buildings by cable television companies by selecting the
companies that will be allowed to install the wiring required to provide cable television service
to
its subscribers.  If the telephone wiring can be used as an alternate method for providing video
programming, the building owners could lose this control over access to their buildings and the
potential income this controlled access represents.  The case could also undercut the value of
existing agreements that were entered into on the assumption that telephone companies would
not
be able to provide this type of video programming to an office building, apartment project or
residential subdivision.<p>
</blockquote>

<b>     D.   Proposed Communications Act of 1994 - Hollings Bill (S 1822)</b><p>
<blockquote>
     As of the date this article was prepared, there was pending in Congress the proposed
"Communications Act of 1994" sponsored by Senator Ernest F. Hollings (S 1822).  If passed by
Congress, the Hollings Bill would substantially alter the present regulatory structure of the
telecommunications industry and redefine the roles that may be played by various parties in
providing telephone, cable television and other telecommunications services.  Proponents of the
new
law believe it will reduce regulation, increase competition and speed up the development of the
"information highway."  There are many highly technical and complex regulatory and policy
issues,
and there are very substantial economic issues that would have a significant impact on
long-distance
and local telephone companies and the cable television industry.  Even if the Hollings Bill does
not
pass during this Session ofCongress, most knowledgeable observers believe that, sooner or later,
there will be significant change in the regulatory structure of the telecommunications industry. 
These changes could substantially affect the manner in which owners and developers of office
buildings, apartment projects and residential subdivisions provide telecommunications services
to
their tenants and purchasers.<p>
</dl>
</blockquote>
<b>III. Access Issues  - Who Controls Access to the Buildings and the Customers?</b><p>
<dl>
<dd>
    <b> A.  Cable Communications Policy Act of 1984.</b><p>
<blockquote>
     Federal law rather than state law may determine questions about access to real estate projects
by cable television companies, including the Cable Communications Policy Act of 1984 (the
"Cable
Act"), codified at 47 U.S.C. &#167 &#167 521-611.<p>

     The Cable Act includes a provision which states that the granting of a cable company
franchise "shall be construed to authorize the construction of a cable system over public
rights-of-way, and through easements, which is [sic] within the area to be served by the cable
system and
which had been dedicated for compatible uses."  47 U.S.C. &#167541(a)(2).   However, in using
such
easements, the cable company must ensure:<p>
<dl>
<dd>
     (A)  that the safety, functioning, and appearance of the property and the
          convenience and safety of other persons not be adversely affected by the
          installation or construction of facilities necessary for a cable system;<br>
     (B)  that the cost of the installation, construction, operation, or removal of such
          facilities be borne by the cable operator or subscriber, or a combination of
          both; and<br>
     (C)  that the owner of the property be justly compensated by the cable operator
          for any damages caused by the installation, construction, operation, or
          removal of such facilities by the cable operator.<p>
</dl>
     Any inconsistent state or local statutes, ordinances, or regulations are preempted and
superseded by this federal law.  47 U.S.C. &#167556(c).  A real estate practitioner must be
therefore
be
aware of the Cable Act and numerous court decisions interpreting its provisions when drafting
documents affecting access of cable television companies to real estate projects.<p>
<dl>
<dd>
    <b> 1.   Public Rights-of-Way and Easements.</b><p>

     The terms "public rights-of-way" and "easements which have been dedicated for compatible
use" are not defined in the Cable Act, and must therefore be defined by state law or general real
estate principles.  Generally speaking, "public rights-of-way" include all public streets, alleys,
culverts, bridges or other property owned by public bodies that are open to travel by the public. 
The
meaning of "easements which have been dedicated for compatible use" is unsettled, primarily
because of the distinction between easements dedicated for public use and private easements.
<p>

     In Centel Cable Television Co. of Florida v. Admiral's Cove Associates, Ltd. 837 F.2d 1359
(11th Cir. 1988), the Court held that 47 U.S.C. &#167541(a)(2) gives a cable television company
a
private
right of action against a landowner to enforce access to a platted utility easement, said that
Congress
clearly had authorized the cable operator to "piggy back" onto easements dedicated for electric,
gas
or other utility transmission.<p>

     In Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad v. Heritage Cablevision of Dallas, 783 S.W.2d 273 (Tex.
App.-Dallas 1989, no writ), the Court determined that a cable television company had a right of
access under 47 U.S.C. &#167541(a)(2) through public rights-of-way that crossed railroad
property
without any obligation to compensate the railroad for such crossing.  The Court found that prior
license agreements between the railroad and the cable television company that required a license
fee
to be paid to the railroad were private agreements that had not been renewed by the cable
television
company.<p>

     In Cable Investments, Inc. v. Woolley, 867 F.2d 151 (3rd Cir. 1989), the Court of Appeals
held that 47 U.S.C. &#167541(a)(2) does not mandate access by cable television companies to
multi-unit
dwellings for the purpose of providing cable television service to the tenants.  The Court said the
legislative history of this provision does not "eliminate the critical issue, whether those
[dedicated]
easements are considered to run up to as well as into an apartment building for purposes of
mandatory access."  The Court implied that, absent an express dedication from an owner, only an
easement which is external to a private building will be a "dedicated" easement under 47 U.S.C
&#167541(a)(2).<p>

     In Cable Associates, Inc. v. Town & Country Management Corp. 709 F.Supp. 582 (E.D. Pa.
1989), the Court cited the Cable Investments case in support of its holding that a cable television
company did not have the right to use a telephone company easement to drop cable television
lines
to individual apartments without permission from the apartment building management company. 
The Court determined that a private easement - a specific grant of an easement to a utility - is not
a "dedicated" easement within the meaning of 47 U.S.C. &#167541(a)(2).<p>

     In Cable Holdings of Georgia, Inc. v. McNeil Real Estate Fund VII, Ltd., 953 F.2d 600 (11th
Cir. 1992), the Court of Appeals held that 47 U.S.C. &#167541(a)(2) did not give a cable
television
company the right to use private, nondedicated easements as a means of providing cable
television
service to an apartment building.  The Court said the statute only authorized the right of access to
easements which the property owner has dedicated for general utility use.<p>

     In Media General Cable v. Sequoyah Condominium Council 991 F.2d 1169 (4th Cir. 1993),
the Court of Appeals held that 47 U.S.C. &#167541(a)(2) did not give a cable television
company the
right of access to individual condominium units through private easements held by other utilities. 
The cable television company wanted access to serve potential customers by using an exclusive
easement previously granted to another company to provide satellite master antenna and cable
television service.  The Court noted that the word "dedicated" has a very technical meaning in
property law, which, in this context, means that land or an easement therein has been set aside
for
the use of the public, and has been accepted for such use on behalf of the public.  According to
the
Court, if this provision gave the cable television company the right of access to private
easements,
it would amount to a compensable taking under the Fifth Amendment, citing Loretto v.
Teleprompter Manhattan CATV Corp., 458 U.S. 419 (1982).  The Court also noted that, as
originally introduced, the Cable Act contained a provision providing cable television companies
access to individual condominium or apartment units over the objection of the condominium
association or apartment owner.  This provision was deleted from the bill before it was passed,
indicating that Congress did not intend the remaining provision of the bill to create such a
right.<p>

     <b>2.   Restrictions on Access.</b><p>

     The Cable Act will not permit a landowner to enter into an agreement that restricts or
interferes with access to a dedicated compatible easement by a cable television franchise holder. 
In Centel Cable Television Co. v. Burg & Divosta Corp., 712 F. Supp. 176 (S.D. Fla. 1988), the
Court held that a developer cannot, by private agreement, determine when it is "safe" for a cable
television company to enter the premises or grant access to one cable company and deny access
to
another.  The Court granted a preliminary injunction to enjoin the developer from interfering
with
the cable television company's access for the purpose of constructing a cable television system
utilizing public rights-of-way and easements dedicated for compatible uses, including all utility
easements. <p>

     In Centel Cable Television Co. v. Thos. J. White Development Corp., 902 F.2d 905 (11th
Cir. 1990), the Court of Appeals held that a plat providing that all roads within a development
were
private rights-of-way could not be enforced so as to prohibit a competitor cable television
company
from using such private roads in order to reach the platted utility easements within the
subdivision. 
The Court found that the cable television company had a right of access to the platted utility
easements under 47 U.S.C. &#167541(a)(2) and under Florida statutes.  Because the cable
television
company had the right to use the utility easements, it had the same right of access across the
property
in order to reach the utility easements as did the utility companies.<p>

     In Timberlake Planation Company v. County of Lexington, 415 S.E.2d 824 (S.C. App. 1992) 
the Court held that the developer of a residential subdivision could not grant an exclusive
contract
to the provider of cable television where the developer dedicated its streets for maintenance only
and
granted electricity and telephone easements. <p>

 <b>    3.   Compensation for Taking.</b><p>

     Two years before the adoption of the Cable Act, the United States Supreme Court held that
the attachment of a cable system was a permanent physical attachment to the building of another
person that constituted a taking of that party's property.  Loretto v. Teleprompter Manhattan
CATV
Corp., 458 U.S. 419 (1982).  The Court stated that a permanent physical invasion of another's
property, no matter to what extent, is essentially a taking per se and requires compensation.  The
extent of that taking would determine the amount of damages due.  The Loretto holding is
limited
to buildings and does not involve the use of compatible easements that have been dedicated or
granted to utilities.<p>

     In Centel Cable Television Co. v. Thos. J. White Development Corp., 902 F.2d 905 (11th
Cir. 1990), the Court of Appeals rejected the property owner's argument that, under the
reasoning
of the Loretto case, the Cable Act violates the takings clause of the Fifth Amendment.  The Court
rejected this contention by quoting from its prior holding in Centel Cable Television Co. v.
Admiral's Cove Associates, Ltd. 835 F.2d 1359 (11th Cir. 1988).<p>
<dl>
<dd>
     Since most developers voluntarily grant easements for use by utilities, however,
     Congress may force the developer to allow a cable franchise to use the easement
     without offending the taking[s] c[l]ause of the Constitution.  Such "voluntary" action
     by developers may be an integral part of zoning procedures or the obtaining of
     necessary building permits.  However obtained, once an easement is established for
     utilities it is well within the authority of Congress to include cable television as a
     user.<p>
</dl>
     Subsection 541(a)(2)(C) of the Cable Act provides "that the owner of the property be justly
compensated by the cable operator for any damages cased by the installation, construction,
operation, or removal of such facilities by the cable operator."  Does this provision provide for
just
compensation for taking, or does it merely provide for reimbursement of the  property owner for
physical damage to the property while the cable is being installed?  A specific provision dealing
with
just compensation for takings was deleted from the final version of the Cable Act, which has led
some courts to conclude that this provision deals only with physical damage to the property and
not
just compensation for takings.  On the other hand, if the Cable Act does not, one way or another,
provide for just compensation for takings, it may be subject to constitutional attack for violating
the
takings clause of the Fifth Amendment.<p>

     However, as stated in the descent in the White Development Corp. case, a final determination
of the takings issue may require a more thorough analysis of the federal takings law and state
easement law.  Among the unresolved takings issues is the party entitled to compensation for use
of the easement.  Is the party entitled to compensation, the landowner, the easement holder or
both?<p>
</dl>
    <b> B.   Pole Attachment Act.</b><p>

     The Pole Attachment Act of 1978, codified at 47 U.S.C. &#167 224, was adopted by
Congress to
provide a mechanism to resolve disputes over the use of utility poles by cable television
companies. 
The construction of a separate set of poles for cable television system is a wasteful duplication of
resources, because space on existing utility poles is usually not fully utilized, and the cost of
leasing
space on the existing poles is far less than the cost of constructing separate poles.  However,
cable
television companies have not always been in a good bargaining position to lease space on
existing
poles from telephone and utility companies, which have sometimes used their superior
bargaining
position to charge excessive rents and sometimes engage in anticompetitive practices.  Without
this
legislation, the FCC did not have sufficient authority to deal with this issue because, although it
had
jurisdiction over telephone companies, it had no jurisdiction over electric utility companies. <p>

     Subsection 224(b) of the Pole Attachment Act provides that the FCC "shall regulate the rates,
terms, and conditions for pole attachments to provide that such rates, terms, conditions are just
and
reasonable, and shall adopt procedures necessary and appropriate to herein resolve complaints
concerning such rates, terms, and conditions.  Subsection 224(d) provides that "a rate is just and
reasonable if it assures a utility the recovery of not less than the additional cost of providing pole
attachments, nor more than an amount determined by multiplying the percentage of the total
usable
space... which is occupied by the pole attachment by the sum of the operating expenses and
actual
costs of the utility attributable to the entire pole..."<p>

     In Federal Communications Commission v. Florida Power Co., 480 U.S. 245 (1987), the
Supreme Court addressed the issue of whether the FCC rate determination formula amounted to
an
unconstitutional taking of property without just compensation.  The Supreme Court found that
the
rate-limiting regulations of the Pole Attachment Act constituted neither a per se taking of the
utilities' property, nor a taking under traditional Fifth Amendment standards.  When deciding the
per
se taking issue, the Court compared the provisions of the Pole Attachment Act to the standards
for
a per se taking previously announced in Loretto v. Teleprompter Manhattan CATV Corp., 458
U.S.
419 (1982).  The Supreme Court concluded that the per se rule discussed in the Loretto case was
inapplicable to the Pole Attachment Act because the FCC did not require the power companies
to
provide pole attachment access to the cable television companies.<p>

     Although the Pole Attachment Act grants broad powers to the FCC, the legislative history
of the Act indicates several restrictions on the scope of this authority.  First, FCC jurisdiction can
be established only where space on utility poles has been reserved for communication facilities
and
is presently occupied by a communications system.  Second, the FCC does not have the authority
to guarantee access to pole attachments for cable television systems, nor can it require an electric
utility company to dedicate a portion of its poles for communications space.  Third, the FCC
does
not have the authority to involve itself directly in the agreements entered into between the
parties;
instead, FCC involvement will occur only in terms of resolving disputes which parties bring
before
it.<p>

     In addition to these jurisdictional limitations, FCC authority can be preempted by individual
state regulation.  Subsection 224(c) of the Pole Attachment Act provides a mechanism whereby
states may obtain jurisdiction over the regulation of Pole Attachment Agreements.  To preempt
federal jurisdiction, each state must satisfy to the FCC that: (i) it regulates the terms, rates and
conditions for pole attachments; and (ii) in so regulating, it has the authority to consider and does
consider the interest of both the subscribers of cable televisions services and the consumers of
utility
services.<p>

    <b> C.   State Law.</b><p>

     There are several Texas statutes dealing with rights-of-way and easements for various types
of public utilities.  Corporations created for the purpose of constructing and maintaining
magnetic
telegraph lines (which has been interpreted to include telephone lines) are authorized to set their
poles, piers, abutments, wires and other fixtures, along, on and across any of the public roads,
streets, and waters of the state as long as the public is not inconvenienced in using such roads,
streets
and waters.  Tex.Rev.Civ.Stat.Ann., Art. 1416.  However, no corporation has power to contract
with
any owner of land for the right to erect and maintain such lines over his lands to the exclusion  of
the lines of other companies. Tex.Rev.Civ.Stat.Ann., Art. 1418.  Cities, towns and villages may,
by
ordinance or otherwise, specify where the posts, piers or abutments shall be located, the kinds of
posts that shall be used, and the height at which the wires shall be run.<p>

     Although the Public Utility Regulatory Act gives the PUC exclusive jurisdiction over the
business and property of all telecommunications utilities in Texas,  nothing in PURA may be
construed in any way as limiting the rights and powers of a municipality to grant or refuse
franchises
to use the streets and alleys within its limits and to make the statutory charges of the use thereof. 
PURA &#16721.<p>

     The above-referenced Art. 1416 that authorizes telegraph and telephone companies to use
public roads, streets and waters does not make any distinction between local and long distance
telephone service.  However, there is a significant distinction insofar as the regulatory rights of
municipal corporations are concerned.  In the case of telegraph companies and long distance
telephone companies, a city, town or village may make reasonable rules and regulations, but they
have no right whatsoever to deny them the use of its streets.  The situation is different with
respect
to local telephone companies.  These corporations have no absolute  right to use the streets, and
can
do so only with the consent of the municipal authorities, which is commonly manifested by the
grant
of a franchise.  See, Brownwood v. Brown Telephone & Telegraph Co., 106 Tex. 114, 157 S.W.
1163 (1913).<p>

     In any unincorporated area in the state, a person in the business of providing community
antenna or cable television service to the public may install and maintain equipment, through,
along,
across, and over a utility easement, a public road, an alley, or body of public water in the state. 
Tex.Rev.Civ.Stat.Ann., Art. 9021.<p>

     
<b>     D.   911 Emergency Telephone Service.</b><p>

     House Bill 1544, which was enacted by the Texas Legislature in 1993, imposes certain new
requirements relating to 911 emergency telephone service on companies that provide telephone
service to residential users through a private telephone switch.  As of September 1, 1994, a
"business
service user" must provide its residential users the same level of 911 emergency telephone
service
a service provider is providing to other residential users in the area participating in the 911
regional
plan.  Texas Health and Safety Code &#167771.060.  "Business service user" means a business
service
that provides telecommunications service, including 911 service, to residential end users through
a private telephone switch.  Texas Health and Safety Code &#167771.001.  The required level of
service
includes the 911 service relating to number and location identification that a service supplier
provides to other residential end users in the county.  Texas Health and Safety Code
&#167772.406. 
Each
line that terminates at a residential unit, and is a communication link equivalent to a residential
local
exchange access line, must be charged a 911 emergency service fee.   Texas Health and Safety
Code
&#167771.017(a).   The business service user is required to collect and remit the 911 emergency
service
fee to the regional planning commission  or other entity designated by the commission to collect
the
fee.  A business service user is subject to a civil cause of action and other penalties if the fee is
not
collected and remitted to the commission.  Texas Health and Safety Code &#167771.073(b). 
These
new
requirements should be dealt with in service provider Lease, Franchise and License Agreements. 
See, for example, Subsection IV-B below.<p>
<dl>
<dd>
    <b> A.   Smart Building Lease Agreements.</b><p>

     If an office or apartment building has been equipped with special telecommunications and
other technology features, the standard Lease Agreement should be modified to address the
potential
problems that may arise with the addition of these features.  The manner in which these issues
are 
handled will depend, in part, on whether the services are provided directly by the building or
apartment owner or by third-party service provider.  The following are drafting tips for "Smart
Building" Lease Agreements:<p>
<dl>
<dd>
          The Lessor will wish to separate itself as much as possible from the service provider
          so the Lessor will not be responsible for failure to provide required service.<p>

          The Lessor's desire to insulate itself from responsibility may be contradicted by the
          Lessor's marketing efforts and economic interest in the service to be provided, so it
          is important to clearly spell out the separate relationships in the Lease.<p>

          To maintain these separate relationships, payment for the services should be made
          to the third-party service provider, even if it is more convenient for the Lessor to
          collect the amount due and remit it to the service provider.<p>

          The Lessor will wish to include an express limitation or waiver of liability and
          indemnification if the service is not provided.<p>

          If there is an interruption of service, the Lessor will wish to have the Lessee waive
          any claim for constructive eviction, particularly if the interruption of service is
          caused by a third party.<p>

          If the Lessee objects to the waiver of constructive eviction, the Lessor might agree
          to an abatement of rent after a specified period of time, particularly if the interrupted
          service is essential to the Lessee's business. <p>

          If there is a constructive eviction or abatement of rent, the Lessor will want to be
          certain that it is fully indemnified for such loss by the third-party service provider.<p>
     
          If the furnishing of any shared-use service becomes a problem because the demand
          for the service is greater than its availability, the Lessor will wish to have the right
          to allocate the use or specify which parties have priority.<p>

          If it is not possible for the Lessor to allocate or prioritize the use, the Lease should
          make it clear that the availability of the service may be limited because of use by
          other paraties.<p>

          If the service is essential to the Lessee's business, the Lessee will wish to have the
          Lease state that the service is essential and the Lessee would not have entered into
          the Lease without the promise of such service by the Lessor.<p>

          The Lessee will wish to avoid any contractual obligations that would limit the
          Lessee's access to the latest technology at the lowest cost.<p>

          The Lessor will also wish to avoid contractual commitments to third-party service
          providers that cannot deliver the latest technology at competitive prices to its
          Lessees.<p>
     
          The third-party service provider should have the right to enter the leased premises
          to install and repair the wiring and equipment, and should be required to indemnify
          the Lessor and Lessee for any damages.<p>

          Notwithstanding the Lessor's desire to limit access by third-party service providers,
          the Lessee may challenge the Lessor's right to limit such access.<p>

          The Lessor's attempts to restrict the Lessee's access to third-party service providers
          might be overridden by government action deregulating the telecommunications
          industry or other policies favoring greater access to telecommunications services.<p>

          Such government intervention might entitle the Lessor to compensation for the
          taking of its property; if not, the Lessor may wish to provide for liquidated damages
          or other remedies if the economic benefit of such limited access is adversely
          affected.<p>

    <b> B.   Service Provider Lease Agreements.</b><p>

     In another type of Lease Agreement, the owner of the office or apartment building, as Lessor,
enters into a Lease Agreement with the service provider, as Lessee.  In this type of arrangement,
space is provided in the building so the service provider can install and operate the equipment,
wiring and other infrastructure needed to provide telecommunications and other technology
services
to the tenants.  The actual amount of space made available to the service provider in the building
is
relatively small.  The real purpose of this arrangement is to allow the service provider access to
the
building and its tenants and provide a means for the owner and service provider to share the
income
derived from such services.  The following is a summary of some of the provisions that might be
included in this type of Lease Agreement:<p>
<dl>
<dd>
          Parties  - The Lessor is the owner of the office or apartment building and the Lessee
          is the third-party provider of telecommunications and other technology services to
          the persons leasing space in the building.<p>

          Premises - The premises leased by the service provider might be described as
          follows:  "An adequate and secure space with electricity to house Lessee's switch and
          related system equipment, which shall consist of a locked room meeting Lessee's
          specifications, and which Lessor is obligated to make available to Lessee during the
          term of this Lease."<p>

          Rent - The rent payable by the Lessee to the Lessor is based on the number of
          building occupants subscribing to Lessee's telecommunications services, which gives
          the Lessor an incentive to promote such telecommunications services.<p>

          Term - The Lessee service provider will wish to have as long a term as possible with
          several options to renew, while the Lessor wish to have the right to terminate the
          Lease if the Lessee fails to provide state-of-the-art telecommunications services at
          competitive prices.<p>

          Insurance - The Lessor will require the Lessee to maintain adequate liability
          insurance coverage since the Lessee will have access to the Lessor's building and the
          offices or apartments occupied by the building tenants.<p>

          Rights Granted - The rights granted by the Lessor to the Lessee might include the
          sole and exclusive right (i) to provide telephone service, including voice mail,
          conference calling, call waiting and speed dialing; and (ii) to provide data
          communications services, video on demand, audio on demand, and other means of
          two-way communication distribution to the extent delivered through telephone
          delivery medium such as copper wire, fiber optics or other telephone cable, so long
          as it does not unreasonably interfere with any preexisting cable television company's
          right to provide cable television services through co-axial cable.<p> 

          Exclusive Access - The Lessor will not grant access to the building to any party other
          than the Lessee to operate or maintain the telecommunications system or perform the
          services described above.<p>

          Expenses - The Lessee will pay all expenses to install, operate, maintain and repair
          the telecommunications system.<p>

          Installation - The Lessee will be responsible for installing the telecommunications
          system in accordance with the plans and specifications approved by the Lessor.<p>

          Ownership - The telecommunications system will be the sole property of the Lessee
          and will retain its character as personal property, and will not become subject to any 
          Deed of Trust lien on the Lessor's real property and improvements.<p>

          Service to Occupants - The Lessee will provide telecommunications services to each
          occupant of the building requesting such services and signing a separate service
          agreement.  The Lessee will be solely responsible for billing and collecting fees
          charged for such services.<p>

          Lessee's Additional Obligations - The Lessee will be required to provide various
          additional services to the Lessor and the building occupants, including:  (i) routine
          service calls and emergency repairs; (ii) marketing services; (iii) training; and (iv)
          regulatory compliance.<p>

          Lessor's Additional Obligations - The Lessor will also have other obligations to the
          Lessee and the occupants of the building, including:  (i) making the premises
          available to the Lessee; (ii) promoting the use of the telecommunications services to
          the occupants; (iii) providing information to the Lessee concerning the building and
          the occupants; and (iv) obtaining necessary permits and licenses.<p>

          911 Service - The Lessor and the Lessee will take steps to insure compliance with
          the state law requirements concerning "911" emergency telephone service.<p>

          Independent Contractor - The Lessee is an independent contractor, and there is no
          employer-employee partnership, joint venture or agency relationship between the
          Lessor and the Lessee.<p>

          Termination by Lessor - Lessor may terminate the Lease for various types of default
          by the Lessee, including:  (i) failure to maintain specified minimum levels of service;
          (ii) three system-wide failures in a 90-day period; (iii) more than 25 % of the
          building occupants convert to services provided by the local telephone company; (iv)
          another service provider offers to provide a new technology or feature not provided
          by the Lessee; or (v) the Lessor sells the building in the first 10 years and the
          purchaser does not assume the Lease.<p>

          Termination by Lessee - In addition to termination of the Lease for default by the
          Lessor, the Lessee may terminate the lease or discontinue any of the
          telecommunications services if it becomes infeasible for legal, economic or
          regulatory reasons for the Lessee to provide the telecommunications services.<p>

          Assignment - The Lessee may not assign the Lease without the Lessor's prior written
          consent, except (i) to a subsidiary or affiliate of the Lessee; or (ii) the Lessee may
          collaterally assign the Lease as security for a loan to purchase and install the
          telecommunications system.<p>

          Confidential Information - The Lessor agrees to keep certain confidential
          information concerning the Lessee's business (including possible earnings and value)
          confidential.<p>

          Disclaimer of Warranties - The Lessee disclaims any representations or warranties
          concerning the telecommunications system.<p>

          Indemnification - The Lessor and the Lessee agree to mutually indemnify each other
          against any damages suffered because of a default by the other party.<p>

          Limitation of Remedies - The Lessor and Lessee both disclaim any liability to the
          other party or to any occupant of the building for incidental or consequential
          damages or lost profits.<p>

          Subordination and Attornment - The Lessee agrees that the Lease will be subordinate
          to any liens on the real property and improvements owned by the Lessor, but only
          if the lender acknowledges that the telecommunications system is the Lessee's
          personal property and not a fixture.<p>
</dl>
<b>     C.   Service Provider Franchise or License Agreements.</b><p>

      Instead of entering into a Lease Agreement, the owner and service provider might enter into
a Franchise or License Agreement that grants the service provider an exclusive franchise or
license
to design, install, maintain and operate a telecommunications system and provide other
technology
services for the building and its tenants.  In this context, a Franchise or License Agreement is
functionally equivalent to a Lease Agreement, and many of the provisions are similar.  If at all
possible, the service provider will wish to have its rights under the Franchise or License
Agreement
characterized as an interest in real property so it will be in a better position with respect to the
competing claims of the owner, tenants, lenders and subsequent owners of the building.  The
following sample provisions from a License Agreement for providing telecommunications
services
to an apartment project illustrate how a Franchise or License Agreement can affect various
property
interests:<p>
<dl>
<dd>
     Grant of License - Owner hereby grants Company an exclusive license to design, install,
maintain,
     operate and enhance the Communications System (including contracting for third-party
services) on
     the Property for the term and renewals thereof of this Agreement, as defined in Section ___
hereof,
     for the sole use by the Company and its subcontractors and lessors for the purposes
hereinafter set
     forth and for no other use or purpose.  Company acknowledges and agrees that this License
shall be
     subject to (i) local, state and federal statutes, and (ii) the rules and regulations established or
     hereafter promulgated by the governmental agencies which regulate Company's activities,
including
     but not limited to, service access rights which must be granted to local exchange carriers or
operators
     to allow connection to the Property in the event that a tenant or other user desires to utilize
     alternative communication services which are allowed by such laws.  Notwithstanding the
foregoing,
     in the event such laws reduce or eliminate third-party access or connections, Company shall
not be
     further obligated to provide such access to connections under this Agreement.<p>

     Exclusivity - Owner acknowledges and agrees that Company shall be the exclusive provider
of
     Communication System services to the Property, with the exception of services which are
made
     available from Company approved third-party providers, including local telephone
exchange.<p>

     Property Access - Company is granted a non-exclusive right to access the common areas
within the
     Property to satisfy the obligations of Company under this Agreement for a period
commencing from
     the date hereof through termination of this Agreement; provided, however, Company shall
have the
     exclusive right of access to the Communications System.  The foregoing includes, but is not
limited
     to, all matters related to service and equipment installation, solicitation of prospective
Subscribers,
     collection of Subscriber accounts, storage and removal of Company's property, including
equipment,
     tools, records and the like.  Company's right of access to the Property also includes access
rights for
     its contractors, subcontractors and all other agents or employees of the Company necessary or
     desirable to fulfill Company's obligations or to exercise Company's rights under this
Agreement.  If
     requested by a Subscriber, and with the written authorization from such Subscriber, Owner
will
     provide access to a Subscriber's apartment unit for installation, repair or maintenance of any
part of
     the Communications System.<p>


     Control Room - Owner shall provide a secure, enclosed control room accessible only to
Company
     personnel in which the Company's control equipment may be installed, operated, maintained
or
     removed.<p>

     Competition - Company's exclusive license hereunder is deemed to preclude any competitive
     Communications Service providers on or providing service to the Property.  The foregoing
precludes
     Owner from at any time becoming competitive with Company and shall also preclude
Owner's tenants
     from using on-Property equipment or other devises to duplicate Company services.  To
prevent such
     tenant activity, Owner covenants that every tenant lease entered into during the term of  this
     Agreement or any renewal thereof shall prohibit use of Communication System services or
equipment
     not provided through the Company (other than telephone system services), including but not
limited
     to the use of high power antennas, microwave reception devices or satellite dishes.<p>


     Property Rights (Easement) - Upon execution of this Agreement, Owner shall execute and
deliver to
     Company a blanket easement to the Property in the form set forth herein as Exhibit "___". 
This
     exclusive easement ("Easement") shall define Company's (i) right of access in and to the
Property for
     Installation, maintenance, repair, removal of assets and operations in connection with the
     Communications System, and (ii) Company's Easement over the Communications System
     infrastructure (all demarcation points, entrances and exits, grounding stations, routing of
cable and
     conduit wires, cable, conduit, jacks and other components of the Communications System
     infrastructure).  Such Easement shall acknowledge that portion of such infrastructure which
becomes
     a capital or fixture improvement and will be transferred to Owner at the beginning of the
Term;
     provided, however, Owner acknowledges and agrees that Company has an exclusive
easement to
     operate the Communications System within and over such Infrastructure.<p>

     Third Party Contractors and Lessors - Owner shall acknowledge and protect third party
property
     rights and interests on the Property and within the Communications System as set forth in
Section ___
     hereof.<p>

     Lender and Lien Holder Consent - Notwithstanding any contrary provision herein, it shall be
a
     condition precedent to all Company's obligations hereunder that Owner obtain and deliver to
     Company a consent and non-disturbance letter in the form set forth in Exhibit "___" attached
hereto
     (the "Consent"), duly executed by all lenders and lien holders holding a montage or lien
interest upon
     the property.  Such Consent letter shall include, but not be limited to, (i) consent to this
Agreement,
     and all documents and instruments entered into in connection therewith, (ii) Company's
agreement
     that its interests under this Agreement, with the express exception of the Easement, shall be
     subordinate to the lenders or lien holders security interest created by its controlling
documents, (iii)
     Company shall be provided with all notices which Owner is required to give to any lender or
lien
     holder, (iv) Company's right to make payments directly to the lender upon receipt of an
attornment
     notice, as defined in the Consent letter, (v) lender or lien holder's agreement to be obligated
under
     this Agreement in the event of a foreclosure or forced sale of the Property, (iv) to honor all
options
     and rights under the Agreement, including the purchase requirement set forth in Section ___,
and (vii)
     Company's right to "quiet enjoyment" under the License Agreement with respect to all of its
rights in
     the Agreement and pursuant to its Easement.<p>

     Transfer of Agreement Upon Sale  - In the event the Owner sells or otherwise transfers the
Property,
     a provision of the sale or transfer document shall include the obligation of the purchaser or
transferee
     to assume this Agreement in its entirety, without change or modification.  The parties
acknowledge
     and agree that any such sale or transfer document which does not include the assignment and
     assumption of this Agreement (the "Assignment and Assumption Agreement"), shall cause
immediate
     and irreparable harm to the Company, damages for which cannot be adequately or reasonably
     ascertained, and Company shall, in such event, be entitled to injunctive and other equitable
relief
     without the necessity of posting bond.  The Assignment and Assumption Agreement between
Owner
     and its transferee shall provide, at a minimum, that all rights, duties, obligations and liabilities
under
     this Agreement shall be assumed in their entirety, without exception, by the purchaser or
transferee.<p>

     Financing Statement - In addition to the foregoing, Owner shall also execute notice financing
     statements in favor of the Company to evidence Company's ownership interest in its
equipment and
     other assets located on the Property, including but not limited to, Company's switching
equipment,
     microwave transmission devices and satellite dishes.<p>
</dl>
</blockquote>
    <b> D.   Easements.</b><p>
<blockquote>
     A service provider may enhance its position under a Lease Agreement, License Agreement
or Franchise Agreement  by obtaining one or more easements across the owner's land and inside
the
building to install and maintain the equipment, wiring and other infrastructure for the
telecommunications and other technology services.  Ideally, the service provider would wish to
have
the easement create a permanent property interest that would survive a foreclosure or  other sale
of
the land and building.  The granting of an easement in connection with a Franchise or License
Agreement may also cause the Agreement to become "coupled with an interest" so that it
becomes
an irrevocable interest in real property.  The following is a sample Blanket Easement from the
owner
of an apartment project to the provider of telecommunications services pursuant to a License
Agreement similar to the one described in Subsection IV-C above.<p>

          For and in consideration of Ten and No/100 Dollars ($10.00) and other good and valuable
     consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged,
_____________,
     (hereinafter called "GRANTOR") hereby GRANTS, SELLS AND CONVEYS TO
__________________
     (hereinafter called "GRANTEE"), and its successors and assigns, an exclusive and perpetual
right-of-way and easement on, across and within the tract of land owned by GRANTOR
described in the
     attached Exhibit "A" (hereinafter called the "Land"), for the purpose of constructing,
installing,
     maintaining, repairing, replacing, and operating the Communications System (as defined in
that
     certain License Agreement dated ____________, 199__, between _____________ and
     _______________________ on, across and within various portions of the Land and inside the
     apartment buildings and other structures now or hereafter located on the Land (hereinafter
called the
     "Apartments") in order to provide telephone, cable television and other telecommunications
services
     to the Apartments.<p>

          To HAVE AND TO HOLD the above-described easement, together with all and singular
the
     rights and appurtenances thereto in anywise belonging to GRANTEE, and GRANTEE'S
successors
     and assigns forever, and GRANTOR does hereby bind itself and its successors and assigns to
     WARRANT AND FOREVER DEFEND all and singular the easement unto GRANTEE, and
its
     successors and assigns, against every person whomsoever lawfully claiming or to claim the
same, or
     any part thereof.<p>

          The exact location of the Communications System across the Land and inside the
Apartments
     shall be determined by GRANTEE, but GRANTEE agrees not to locate the Communications
System
     in a manner that would interfere with any other underground utilities or other improvements
located
     on the Land or in the Apartments.  The above-described easement shall also include the right
to place,
     operate or remove switch and junction boxes, manholes, equipment and other devices on the
Land and
     in the Apartments at locations to be determined by GRANTEE for the purpose of operating
and
     maintaining the Communications System.<p>

          GRANTEE and its agents shall have the right to enter upon the Land and into the
Apartments
     for the purpose of constructing, installing, maintaining, repairing, replacing, removing and
operating
     the Communications System and the related switch and junction boxes, manholes, equipment
and
     other devices.  GRANTEE shall be responsible for repairing any damage to the Land, the
Apartments
     or any other improvements caused by GRANTEE or its agents.<p>

          GRANTEE shall have the right to assign its rights and interests in the easement and other
     rights granted hereby to any other party to whom GRANTEE may hereafter assign its right to
provide
     the Communications System to the Apartments.<p>
</blockquote>
<b>     E.   Homeowner and Tenant Associations.</b><p>

     The service provider and owner of an office building, apartment building or residential
subdivision might wish to jointly control and profit from the furnishing of the
telecommunications
and other technology services created by a non-profit Homeowner or Tenant Association, which 
would contract with the service provider for telecommunications and other technology services
to
the building or subdivision.  The owner can facilitate this arrangement by creating a Homeowner
or Tenant Association with the authority and resources to provide such services and by granting
easements to the Association in the building or the subdivision to facilitate the Association
entering
into agreements with a third-party service provider.  Although the owner does not have a direct
financial interest in this arrangement,  it provides a useful mechanism for creating an amenity
that
would be attractive to potential homeowners and tenants.  The following are sample provisions
from
a Declaration of Covenants, Conditions and Restrictions concerning telecommunications
services
to be provided by a Homeowner Association for a residential subdivision:<p>
</blockquote>
<b>                   TELECOMMUNICATION SERVICES </b>
<blockquote>
          The Association, with the prior approval of the Board of Directors, may provide, either
     directly or by contracting with other parties, various telecommunication services to the Lots
and
     Common Areas within the Subdivision.  The Board of Directors of the Association shall have
the sole
     discretion to determine whether or not such telecommunication services are provided, the
types of
     services to be provided, the manner in which such services will be provided, the amounts to
be
     charged, and the method of paying for such services.  The amounts charged for such services
shall
     not exceed those authorized or required by any regulatory authority with jurisdiction over
such
     matters.<p>

          SECTION 1.  TYPES OF SERVICES.  The types of telecommunication services that may
be
     provided by or through the Association shall include, but not be limited to, the following:  (i)
local and
     long-distance telephone service; (ii) voice mail service; (iii) cable television service; (iv)
private
     television channels for education and community purposes; (v) security monitoring of Streets,
     Common Areas, and other public areas; (vi) central home security systems for fire and
burglary
     detection; (vii) electronic utility meter reading systems; (viii) electronic mail systems; and
(ix) such
     other similar telecommunication services the Board of Directors determines to be necessary
or
     beneficial for the safety, welfare or enjoyment of the Association Members or the
Subdivision.<p>

          SECTION 2.  COMMON AREA FACILITIES.  The telecommunication equipment,
wiring and
     other facilities that are necessary to provide the telecommunications services for the Common
Areas,
     Streets and other public areas in the Subdivision shall either be owned by the Association or
the
     Association shall contract with other parties to provide such facilities on behalf of the
Association. 
     The cost and expense of constructing, installing, operating, maintaining, repairing and
replacing such
     facilities shall be paid by the Association, and may be included as part of the annual
assessments and
     special assessments to the Members.<p>

          SECTION 3.  LOT FACILITIES.  Each residence constructed on a Lot shall include a
     Residential Service Unit to provide optional access to the residence for the
telecommunication
     services described in Section 1 above.  The Residential Service Unit will provide a
connecting
     terminal for the wiring that extends to each outlet or point of access in the residence for the
     telecommunication services.  The Association shall have the right to designate the type of
Residential
     Service Unit to be installed and the manner in which such Residential Service Unit shall be
operated,
     maintained and repaired, and may, from time to time, designate appropriate replacements or
     improvements to the Residential Service Unit.  The Association may contract with other
parties to
     provide the foregoing services relating to the Residential Unit.  Each Owner shall pay all
costs and
     expenses required to purchase, install, maintain, repair, replace or improve the Residential
Service
     Unit for the Owner's residence, which shall be paid by each Owner in the same manner as a
special
     assessment, except that no approval of the Members of the Association shall be required for
such
     special assessment.  The Residential Service Unit shall remain as a permanent fixture to the
residence
     and may not be removed from the residence without the written permission of the
Association, and
     shall remain as a part of the residence when the residence is sold to another party.  The
Association
     and the parties with whom it contracts to provide services relating to the Residential Service
Unit
     shall have an easement and right of entry over and across each Lot and into each residence for
the
     purpose of installing, maintaining, repairing, replacing and making improvements to the
Residential
     Service Unit.<p>

          SECTION 4.  OPTIONAL SERVICES.  The installation of the Residential Service Unit in
a
     residence does not obligate the Owner of the Lot to accept or pay for any of the
telecommunication
     services to the residence that may be provided by, or available through, the Association. 
Each Owner
     shall have the right to (i) accept and pay for any such services provided by or through the
Association,
     (ii) contract with another party to provide such services, or (iii) decline such services, in
whole or in
     part.<p>
</blockquote>
<b>     F.   Third-Party Agreements. </b><p>
<blockquote>
     The above described documents which create and protect the property rights of the service
provider, the owner and the tenant can adversely affect the rights of third-party lenders,
subsequent
owners and other parties.  For example, a lender with a first lien Deed of Trust lien on the land
and
improvements may not be willing to recognize the service provider's claim that the equipment,
wiring and other infrastructure is personal property, rather than fixtures covered by its Deed of
Trust
lien.  Even if it is recognized to be personal property, the lender may claim a prior lien under its
Security Agreement covering the owner's personal property.   If there is a foreclosure by the real
estate lender, the service provider will want to be certain that its rights under the Lease
Agreement,
License Agreement or Franchise Agreement survive the foreclosure and that any easement rights
remain intact.  The lender may not be willing to allow this, unless it can be assured that the
service
provider will subordinate its interest and attorn to the lender.  Also, the service provider's
third-party
lender may require assurances from the owner and the real estate lender that its security interest
in
the equipment, wiring and other infrastructure will have priority and that it will have no problem
recovering its collateral in the event of a default.   One or more parties may therefore require the
other parties to execute various Estoppel Certificates and Waiver Agreements acknowledging the
various property interests and priorities.<p>
</blockquote>
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
<b>V.   Conclusion.</b><p>
<blockquote>
     The rapidly changing technology and the many new providers of telecommunications and
other technology services create a very challenging situation for real estate developers, tenants
and
lenders, and their lawyers.  It is not clear how some of the issues addressed in this article will
finally
be resolved, but it is clear that the real estate industry has an important stake in the resolution of
these matters, and should be an active and informed participant in the construction of the
"information highway" and the continued development of "smart buildings."<p>

If your have any comments or questions concerning this page, contact <b><a
href="mailto:webmaster@lprh.com">webmaster@lprh.com</a></b>.</h5>
<hr>
<p>
