<HR>


<P><B>EVIDENCE IN ADMINISTRATIVE HEARINGS</B> [ This paper is an updated and
expanded version of similar papers (by the same author) presented at previous Advanced
Administrative Law Seminars .  Several subject areas have been updated to reflect recent
decisions which modify or help to clarify the application of evidentiary rules in those areas.  It is
the author s hope that the paper will be a comprehensive resource tool for administrative law
practitioners engaged in contested case hearings.] 

<P><B>C. Brian Cassidy</B>

<A NAME="I">
<P><B>I. </B><B>INTRODUCTION.</B></A>

<P> Administrative hearings are, in essence, a specialized type of litigation.  As is the case with
most other types of litigation, properly constructing an evidentiary record is critical to a
party&#146;s success in an administrative hearing.  For that reason administrative lawyers need
more than just a basic familiarity with rules which may affect their ability to present (or exclude)
evidence. Instead they need a comprehensive understanding of the rules (and the sources of those
rules) which will control their efforts to build an evidentiary record. 

<P> Building an evidentiary record in an administrative hearing can be viewed as a two-step
process. The first step is the discovery phase, during which parties attempt to elicit information
from their opponents which is useful to their case and/or is damaging to the contrary positions of
others.  It is important to be cognizant of evidentiary rules during the discovery phase because of
the impact they may have on a party's ability to incorporate the fruits of discovery in the
evidentiary record.  The second phase is the contested case hearing itself.  It is at this point where
critical decisions are made as to what information, including that which is obtained through
discovery, will actually be admitted into evidence and will become part of the evidentiary record
upon which the agency's decision should be based.
<P> This paper is intended to identify sources of evidentiary rules and review many of the rules
which may be encountered in the course of building an evidentiary record in an administrative
hearing.

<A NAME="II">
<P><B>II. </B><B>SOURCES OF EVIDENTIARY RULES.</B></A>

<P> The primary sources of evidentiary rules governing administrative hearings are the
Administrative Procedure Act, Tex. Gov&#146;t Code Ann. &#167; 2001.001, et seq. (Vernon
Pamph. 1996) (APA or the &quot;Act&quot;), the Texas Rules of CivilEvidence
(&quot;TRE&quot;), the rules governing practice and procedures before specific agencies
(including the State Office of Administrative Hearings (&quot;SOAH&quot;)) and, to a lesser
degree, specific orders of the presiding hearings officer.  Each of these is addressed below.

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>A. </B><B>The APA and TRE.</B>

<P> The APA governs most contested administrative hearings before state agencies.  The Act
provides, in section 2001.081, that &quot;[t]he rules of evidence as applied in a nonjury civil
case in a district court of this state shall apply to a contested case...&quot;.  The clear result of
this provision is that the TRE will apply in all agency proceedings governed by the APA. 
<U>See</U> <U>Smith Motor Sales v. </U><U>Texas Motor Vehicle Comm.</U>, 809
S.W.2d 268, 272 (Tex.App. - Austin 1991, writ denied); <U>Beaver </U><U>Express Service,
Inc. v. Railroad Comm. of Texas</U>, 727 S.W.2d 768, 778 (Tex.App. - Austin 1987, writ
denied).  This principle is often reflected in specific agency rules as well. [. See, e.g . 30 Tex.
Admin. Code   80.127(a) (Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission ( "TNRCC ")); 16
Tex. Admin. Code &#167;  1.101 (Railroad Commission ( "RRC ")).] 

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. </B><B>The TRE </B><B>&quot;As Applied in a Nonjury Civil
</B><B>Case</B><B>&quot;.</B>

<P> The directive in &#167; 2001.081 of the APA that contested cases shall be governed by the
TRE as applied in <I>nonjury</I> civil cases is significant.  Many provisions of the TRE are
written with the presence of a jury in mind.  For example, TRE 403, addressing exclusion of
relevant evidence on special grounds (see section III.E. below), includes the danger of
&quot;misleading the jury&quot; as one of the grounds for exclusion.  In administrative
proceedings the functions of a jury are subsumed within the duties of an administrative law judge
and ultimately within the duties of the agency&#146;s governing body.  Given their specialized
knowledge these individuals (and those who comprise the governing bodies) are not as
susceptible to the danger of being misled as are ordinary lay people who typically serve on juries
in civil proceedings.  The result is that a provision such as that described above may not be as
strong a basis for excluding relevant evidence in anadministrative proceeding as it would be in a
nonjury civil trial.  Practitioners should keep this distinction in mind whenever dealing with a
provision from the TRE which appears to contemplate the presence of a jury.

<P><B>2. </B><B>The APA</B><B>&#146;s </B><B>&quot;Escape
Clause</B><B>&quot;.</B>

<P> Section 2001.081 of the APA also contains what has been referred to as an &quot;escape
clause&quot;; that is, criteria which, if met, will allow evidence to be admitted in administrative
hearings that would otherwise not be admissible in nonjury civil proceedings applying the TRE. 
Specifically, evidence inadmissible under the TRE may be admitted in an administrative
proceeding if it is:
<OL>
<P><LI> necessary to ascertain facts not reasonably susceptible of proof under those rules;

<P><LI> not precluded by statute; and

<P><LI> of a type upon which a reasonably prudent person commonly relies in the conduct of
their affairs.
</OL>
<P> The origin of this provision may provide some insight as to its intended application.  It was
included in the original version of the Administrative Procedure and Texas Register Act
(&quot;APTRA&quot;), the predecessor to the APA, as a compromise between competing
factions involved in the drafting of the act.  One group believed that the rules of evidence should
be strictly applied in agency proceedings, while the other argued that strict application of a rigid
set of rules undermined the goals of the administrative process and ignored the diversity of
agencies and their functions. [. Kuhl,  Evidence in Texas Administrative Adjudications , 15
Hous. L. Rev. 682, 688-90 (1978).]   One commenter has suggested that the only way to give the
resulting compromise meaning is to <I>strictly</I> apply the predicate elements to admission
under the escape clause, as to do otherwise would disturb the balance inherent in the compromise
provision. [. Id ., at 698-701.] 

<P> Currently there are no reported cases discussing this clause as having been utilized to admit
otherwise inadmissible evidence. Nevertheless it is a familiar tool to mostexperienced
administrative law practitioners and, though it should be viewed as a means of last resort, it may
facilitate a broader range of evidence being admitted under the proper circumstances.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><B>B. </B><B>Agency Specific Rules.</B>

<P> Practitioners must also be knowledgeable of the rules and policies of the agencies which
they appear before.  In most instances those policies will reiterate the general notion of the
applicability of the TRE (coupled with the &quot;escape clause&quot;) to proceedings before
that agency, but they may also add further refinement to the applicability of those rules.  For
example, the APA is clear that official notice may be taken of facts or documents, but some
agencies require that motions be filed to request that such notice be taken. [. See, e.g ., 16 Tex.
Admin. Code &#167; 22.222(b) (PUC); 16 Tex. Admin. Code (RRC) &#167; 1.102.]   Similarly,
some agency rules prescribe the manner and form in which exhibits are to be presented. [. See,
e.g ., 16 Tex. Admin. Code &#167;  1.106 (RRC); 16 Tex. Admin. Code &#167; 22.226(a)
(PUC); 30 Tex. Admin. Code &#167;  80.127(d) (TNRCC); 37 Tex. Admin. Code &#167; 29.34
(Texas Dept. of Public Safety).]   These types of provisions go beyond what is enumerated in the
APA but are nevertheless important for purposes of properly presenting or preserving evidence.

<P><B>C. </B><B>Proceedings Before SOAH.</B>

<P> The &quot;Rules of Procedures&quot; governing hearings conducted by the State Office of
Administrative Hearings specifically provide that evidence in SOAH proceedings is to be
admitted in accordance with the APA.  1 Tex. Admin. Code &#167; 155.45(a).  (&quot;SOAH
Rules&quot;).  Section 2001.058 of the APA, which applies to hearings conducted by ALJs
employed by SOAH, requires that an agency provide an ALJ with a written statement of the
agency's applicable rules or policies, and further requires that the ALJ who presides over a
contested case consider those rules or policies in the hearing. Section 155.5(b) of the SOAH
Rules also requires that in the event there is a conflict between the SOAH rules and the agency
rules, the latter will control unless specifically provided otherwise (or unless the rules are
contrary to statute).  Thus, the fact that a hearing may be conducted by SOAH (rather than an
agency's own hearings division) does not diminish thesignificance of the APA, the TRE or
specific agency rules.

<P><B>D. </B><B>Orders of the Presiding Hearings Officer.</B>

<P> It is not uncommon for rules governing the presentation of evidence to be embodied in the
orders of a hearings examiner or administrative law judge.  Most often these will be procedural
in nature.  For example, a prehearing order may direct that copies of exhibits to be used by a
party be provided to the other parties in the hearing the day before they are to be offered into
evidence. While this type of rule does not address the legal aspects of the admissibility of certain
evidence, it is nevertheless a type of requirement which, if not followed, may adversely impact a
party&#146;s efforts to build an evidentiary record.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<A NAME="III">
<P><B>III. </B><B>SELECTED EVIDENTIARY RULES.</B></A>

<P> While the TRE as a whole apply to administrative proceedings (as they would in a nonjury
civil proceeding), several rules are encountered more often than others or are particularly suited
for the types of evidence typically presented in agency hearings.  A discussion of these, as well
as the corresponding APA provisions (and, in some instances, corresponding SOAH Rules), is
set forth below. To facilitate easier cross-referencing the rules are addressed in the order in which
they appear in the TRE.  

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>A. </B><B>Evidentiary Objections and Preservation of
</B><B>Error (TRE 103; APA </B><B>&#167;</B><B> </B><B>2001.084; SOAH
</B><B>Rule </B><B>&#167;</B><B> </B><B>155.37(c)).</B>

<P> In any disputed evidentiary offer at least one party  will receive a ruling with which they
disagree.  In this instance it is important to know how to properly preserve the error that the
&quot;losing&quot; party feels was made by the ALJ.  The objective in preserving error is to
create a record which can be considered by the agency and ultimately a reviewing court, and
which is sufficient to demonstrate the substance (and significance) of the objection, the evidence
(if excluded), and the basis for the legal argument regarding the objection. 

<P> TRE 103 indicates that, for perceived error in <I>admitting</I> evidence, a timely objection
stating the specific grounds therefore must be reflected in the record, and if the ruling is one
<I>excluding</I> evidence an offer of proof should be made. Section 155.37(c) of the SOAH
Rules succinctly states that objections &quot;shall be timely noted in the record,&quot; and it
specifically refers to TRE 103. The APA, in &#167; 2001.084, reflects these concepts in a more
direct fashion by simply stating that &quot;an objection to an evidentiary offer in a contested
case may be made and shall be noted in the record.&quot;

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. </B><B>Admission of Evidence - The Requirement </B><B>for
Timely and Specific Objections.  </B>

<P> The characteristics of a proper objection to the admission of evidence are embodied in TRE
103(a)(1).  Simply stated, an objection must be (i) timely; and (ii) specific.  <U>Rendelman v.
</U><U>Clarke</U>, 909 S.W.2d 56, 58 (Tex. App.-Houston [14th Dist.] 1995, dism. as moot).

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>a. </B><B>Timely Objections.</B>

<P> With respect to timeliness, an objection to the admission of evidence must be made
<I>when the </I><I>evidence is offered</I>, not after it has been introduced.  <U>Boyer v.
Scruggs</U>, 806 S.W.2d 941, 946 (Tex.App.--Corpus Christi 1991, no writ) (emphasis added). 
As characterized by one court, to be timely &quot;an objection to the admission of evidence
must be made<I> before</I> testimony has been introduced regarding the substance of the
objectionable evidence&quot;.  (emphasis in original). <U>Commercial Union Insurance Co. v.
LaVilla </U><U>Independent School District</U>, 779 S.W.2d 102, 110 (Tex.App.--Corpus
Christi 1989, no writ).  Note also that an objection will be waived where testimony of the same
type has been previously admitted without objection.  <U>Boyer v. Scruggs</U>, 806 S.W.2d at
946; <U>In the Interest of A.V.</U>, 849 S.W.2d 393, 396 (Tex. App.--Ft. Worth 1993, no
writ).

<P> During cross examination a timely objection is one that is made prior to the witness
responding to a question where it is reasonably obvious that the question calls for inadmissible
evidence.  <U>Beall</U><U>v. Ditmore</U>, 867 S.W.2d 791, 794 (Tex. App.--El Paso 1993, 
writ denied).  Where it is not reasonably obvious that the answer will contain inadmissible
evidence, an objection should be made as soon as is practicable after the answer is given and a
motion should be made to strike the objectionable testimony.  <U>Id</U>. at 794, citing
<U>Johnson </U><U>v. Hodges</U>, 121 S.W.2d 371 (Tex. Civ. App.--Fort Worth 1938, writ
dism&#146;d). A motion to strike under these circumstances must be specific, as failure to
identify the objectionable testimony has been held too general to preserve error.  <U>Top
</U><U>Value Enterprises, Inc. v. Carlson Marketing </U><U>Group, Inc.</U>, 703 S.W.2d
806, 811 (Tex. App.--El Paso 1986, writ ref&#146;d n.r.e.).

<P> The importance of lodging a timely objection is  illustrated by the opinion in <U>Texas
Department </U><U>of Human Services v. Green</U>, 855 S.W.2d 136, 149
(Tex.App.--Austin 1993, writ denied).  Green, a former state employee, filed against the state for
retaliatory firing under the Whistleblower Act. Among the testimony offered at trial was that of
an expert witness who expressed his opinion that the Department of Human Services&#146; 
(&quot;DHS&quot;) referral of a 13 cent personal telephone call for prosecution was likely in
retaliation for Green having reported suspected fraud and corruption in the DHS.  The question
of a retaliatory motive was clearly important to the ultimate outcome of the case, and, though
perhaps objectionable,  the appeals court found that because the DHS failed to timely object to
the testimony it waived its right to complain about that testimony on appeal.  <U>Id</U>.

<P> A point related to the issue of timely objections is the use of &quot;running
objections&quot;; that is, a continuous objection to a type of testimony or line of
cross-examination.  Lawyers will sometimes make objections in this manner so as not to be
overly disruptive in a hearing.  Texas cases are split on whether such objections properly
preserve error.  One possible course of action may be to obtain the ALJ&#146;s permission to
lodge a running objection and then specifically outline, on the record, the nature, grounds and
extent of the objection. [. James P. Wallace and Cathleen C. Herasimchuck, Texas Rules of
Evidence Handbook (Part I); Article I: General Provisions , 30 Hous. L. Rev. 137, 159 (1993).]  
The objection should be renewed each time a witness testifies so as to reduce questions over
when and how far the objection runs. [. Id .; see  also  Jim Parker,  Running Objections - A
Practical Tool for Trial Lawyers , 58 Tex. B. J. 668 (July, 1995).] 

<P><B>b. </B><B>Specific Objections.</B>

<P> The second &quot;requirement&quot; for objections under TRE 103(a) is that they be
specific.  An objection must be stated with such specificity that a reviewing court will be able to
discern the grounds for the objection from the record. <I> See</I>, <U>Crider v. Appelt</U>,
696 S.W.2d 55, 57 (Tex.App.--Austin 1985, no writ) (objection was made but error was not
preserved because the grounds for the objection was not evident from the record).  In
<U>Celotex Corp. v. Tate</U>, 797 S.W.2d 197, 205 (Tex.App.--Corpus Christi 1990, no writ),
the court noted that a specific objection is &quot;one which enables the trial court to understand
the purpose of the question and to make an intelligent ruling, affording the offering party the
opportunity to remedy the defect if possible&quot; (citing <U>de los Angeles Garay v. Texas
Employers' </U><U>Insurance Assoc.</U>, 700 S.W.2d 657, 659 (Tex.App.--Corpus Christi
1985, no writ).  In <U>Scott v. Scruggs</U>, 836 S.W.2d 278, 280 (Tex. App.--Texarkana 1992,
writ denied) the court held that merely objecting to the form of a question, without specifying the
precise grounds, can be a general objection that does not properly preserve error.  Similarly, in
<U>Dalworth Trucking Co. v. </U><U>Bulen</U>, 924 S.W.2d 728, 736 (Tex.
App.--Texarkana 1996, n.w.h.), the court held that a party&#146;s <I>hearsay</I> objection had
been waived because, during the trial, that party had only raised a <I>relevance</I> objection to
the evidence in question. Thus practitioners should be specific and enumerate all bases for
objection in order to properly preserve error.  

<P> 

<P> Although it has been suggested that general objections are sufficient <I>if</I> the
&quot;real&quot; objection is obvious, practitioners are better advised to make objections in a
specific enough manner so that the necessary information is contained in the record. <I>
</I><I>See</I>, <U>Sternenberg v. Marshall</U>, 257 S.W.2d 312, 319 (Tex. Civ.
App.--Austin 1953, writ ref'd n.r.e.).  Another benefit of making specific objections is that if only
part of a particular piece of evidence is admissible, it will be easier for a judge or ALJ to identify
and strike the objectionable part.  <U>Celotex Corp. v. Tate</U>, 797 S.W.2d at 206.  Finally,
note that while specificity is important, resorting to a &quot;shotgun&quot; approach(i.e., citing
multiple specific grounds for an objection) can result in a failure to properly preserve error.  This
occurred in <U>Berry v. State of </U><U>Texas</U>, 813 S.W.2d 636, 638-39
(Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1991, pet. dism'd), a criminal case in which the court held that
reciting approximately 30 grounds for objection obfuscated the desired grounds for ruling and
failed to preserve error.  Thus, a slew of specific objections may not be specific at all.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><B>2. </B><B>Exclusion of Evidence - The Requirement </B><B>for an Offer of
Proof.</B>

<P> When evidence is offered and excluded, it is incumbent upon the party offering the evidence
to make an offer of proof to properly preserve error. TRE 103(a)(2); <U>Mosley v. Employers
Casualty </U><U>Company</U>, 873 S.W.2d 715, 718 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1993, writ granted);
<U>Hartford Insurance Co. V. </U><U>Jiminez</U>, 814 S.W.2d 551, 552 (Tex.
App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1991, no writ); <U>Posner v. </U><U>Dallas County Child
Welfare</U>, 784 S.W.2d 585, 588 (Tex.App.--Eastland 1990, writ denied).  The purpose of an
offer of proof is to provide a reviewing court with a basis for determining whether a trial court
erred in excluding evidence. <U>Blackburn v. Brazos Valley Utilities, Inc.</U>, 777 S.W.2d
758, 760 (Tex.App.--Beaumont 1989, writ denied).  In the absence of a bill of exceptions or an
offer of proof a court (or reviewing commission) has no basis to review a contention that
documents or cross examination were wrongfully excluded from the record.  <U>Walker v.
</U><U>Kleiman</U>, 896 S.W.2d 413, 417 (Tex. App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1995, no writ). 
For example, in <U>Hood v. Hays County</U>, 836 S.W.2d 327, 328-29 (Tex.App.--Austin
1992, no writ), a defendant in a suit brought by the county to foreclose a lien and recover
property taxes was considered to have properly preserved error by making an offer of proof
concerning evidence that was excluded by the trial court relating to the value of certain property. 
The opposite result was reached in <U>Weng Enterprise, Inc. v. Embassy World Travel,
</U><U>Inc.</U>, 837 S.W.2d 217, 221 (Tex.App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1992, no writ), where
the appeals court found that even though the trial court had abused its discretion by precluding a
witness from testifying, the proponent of the testimony failed tomake the necessary offer of proof
(or bill of exceptions to properly preserve the error).

<P> Excluded cross-examination need not be preserved through an offer of proof; in that
instance the offering party must only show that the substance of the evidence was apparent from
the context within which questions were asked.  <U>Life </U><U>Insurance Company of the
Southwest v. Brister</U>, 722 S.W.2d 764, 774 (Tex.App.--Ft. Worth 1986, no writ).  Also,
upon the request of any party an offer of proof must be made in question and answer format. 
TRE 103(b).  Absent such a request a mere recitation of the type of evidence excluded is
sufficient.

<P> In administrative proceedings a record of the offer can be made at the end of the day (when
the witness, court reporter and counsel are present but after the ALJ has left), or can be made at
the time the evidence is excluded.  The timing may be prescribed by the agency's procedural
rules or it may be a matter of discretion for the hearings officer.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>B. </B><B>Evidence Admitted for a Limited Purpose.</B>

<P> On occasion evidence may be presented which is admissible for one purpose but not for
another or not as a general offer.  TRE 105(a) addresses such scenarios, and it provides that a
party may request that evidence be restricted to its proper scope or use.  For example, in
<U>Wal-Mart </U><U>Stores, Inc. v. Berry</U>, 833 S.W.2d 587 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1992,
writ denied), a stack of soft drink cans fell on a shopper at a Sam's Wholesale Club. The injured
shopper filed suit alleging negligence and gross negligence.  Among the evidence adduced at the
hearing was testimony from two witnesses who claimed to have heard Sam's employees
acknowledge that the cans were stacked in a dangerous condition.  The court, over Wal-Mart's
hearsay objection, admitted the testimony as evidence that Sam's had knowledge of the
dangerous condition. <U>Id</U>. at 593.  Furthermore, because Wal-Mart made only a general
hearsay objection and failed to seek a limiting instruction under TRE 105, the court held that the
testimony could be considered for all purposes,  including that the statements constituted
evidence that thecans were, in fact, stacked in a dangerous condition.  <U>Id</U>. at 593-94.

<P> As was the case under TRE 103, the timeliness of a request for a limiting instruction is
important.  In the decision in <U>In the Matter of </U><U>A.F.</U>, 895 S.W.2d 481, 484
(Tex. App.--Austin 1995, no writ), the court held that a request for a limiting instruction must be
made when the evidence is admitted. In that instance a party had attempted to request the
limiting instruction at the time the jury charge was being prepared, and that was determined to be
too late.  Applying this to an administrative law context means that it would probably be
improper to request a limitation at the close of the evidentiary hearing or at the briefing stage of
the proceeding.  Indeed, the proper course, as the decision above suggests, is to request the
limitation when the evidence is offered so that questions as to its admissibility (and the basis
therefore) can be addressed while the witness is present.

<P> Note too that it is not only a party who opposes an offer of evidence who must request a
limiting instruction to properly preserve error. TRE 105(b) provides that if evidence is excluded,
the party offering the evidence must &quot; . . . offer(s) the evidence for its limited, admissible
purpose or limit[s] its offer to the party against whom its admissible.&quot;  <U>Porter v.
Nemir</U>, 900 S.W.2d 376, 383 (Tex. App.--Austin 1995, n.w.h.).  For example, in
<U>Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing, </U><U>Inc. v. Nishika Ltd.</U>, 885 S.W.2d 603,
631 (Tex. App.--Beaumont 1994, writ granted), 3M complained that the trial court had
improperly excluded evidence regarding the grounds for one of its expert&#146;s opinions.  The
court of appeals found that any such error was harmless (because the excluded evidence was
introduced through another witness), and also noted that evidence of the basis of an
expert&#146;s opinion is admissible only for the limited purpose of identifying that basis. 3M
had not properly preserved any error because it failed to make a limited offer of the excluded
testimony.  <U>Id</U>.  In this instance 3M should have made a limited purpose offer (e.g., as
evidence of the basis of its expert&#146;s opinion) once the testimony was excluded after a
general offer. Note that it is also incumbent on the offering partyto draw, in the context of a
request for admission for a limited purpose, any necessary distinction between the parties against
whom the offer is made.  In <U>Porter v. Nemir</U>, 900 S.W. 2d at 383, the court refused to
find an abuse of discretion for the trial court&#146;s refusal to admit evidence where the offering
party failed to limit its offer to use against only one of adverse parties.  

<P> The language of TRE 105(a) indicates that upon receiving a limiting request, the court
&quot;shall&quot; restrict the evidence to its proper scope.  The rule also notes that in the
absence of such a request, admission of the evidence with no limitation is not grounds for appeal. 
This principle was applied in <U>City of Austin v. Houston Lighting &amp; Power Co.</U>,
844 S.W.2d 773, 793 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1992, writ denied), where the court noted that it is the
burden of the opponent of evidence to seek a limiting instruction, and absent such a request the
admission of evidence without limitation is not grounds for appeal.  The responsibility of the
party seeking to limit the use of testimony was also demonstrated in <U>Aluminum Company of
America </U><U>v. Alm</U>, 785 S.W.2d 137, 139 (Tex. 1990), where the trial court
sustained an objection to a general offer of evidence but allowed its admission as a limited offer. 
However, because the objecting party did not request a limiting instruction (the trial court
imposed the limitation on its own), the Texas Supreme Court held that admission of the evidence
was, for all practical purposes, made pursuant to a general offer.  <U>Id</U>. at 139.  <I>See
also</I>, <U>Cigna Insurance Co. v. Evans</U>, 847 S.W.2d 417, 421 (Tex.App.--Texarkana
1993, no writ).  It is clear that under TRE 105 an objection and limiting request must be timely
made if evidence is to be restricted in its scope or use.

<P><B>C. </B><B>Supplementation of Evidence Offered by </B><B>Another Party (TRE
106).</B>

<P> TRE 106 provides as follows:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>When a writing or recorded statement or part thereof is introduced by a
party, an adverse party may at that time introduce any other part or any other writing or recorded
statement which ought in fairness to be consideredcontemporaneously with it. &quot;Writing or
recorded statement&quot; includes depositions.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P> This rule may be better known by its common law name, the &quot;rule of optional
completeness.&quot;  It essentially provides that when a party seeks to introduce all or part of a
document or recording into evidence an opposing party may introduce other parts of the same
document (or recording) or other documents (or recordings) which should &quot;in
fairness&quot; be considered at the same time.  <I>See</I> <U>Travelers </U><U>Insurance
Company v. Creyke</U>, 446 S.W.2d 954, 957 (Tex. Civ. App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1969, no
writ).  The purpose of the rule is to prevent documents, or passages therefrom, from being
selectively excerpted and/or taken out of context in light of the complete document or other
documents relating to the same issue.  <I>See</I> <U>McAllen Kentucky </U><U>Fried
Chicken No. 1 v. Leal</U>, 627 S.W.2d 480, 484 (Tex.App.--Corpus Christi 1981, writ ref'd
n.r.e.).

<P> The rule was amended in 1984 to specifically include depositions within the definition of
&quot;writing or recorded statement&quot;.  It is therefore clear that if a party seeks to introduce
into evidence passages from a witness' deposition, opposing counsel may seek admission of other
passages which should, for reasons of fairness, be considered contemporaneously with those
being introduced by the proponent.  Also, while prior practice was that a party seeking to
supplement another's offer was required to wait until it was their turn to cross-examine the
witness, the rule now makes clear that the supplementation may occur when the initial offer is
made. [. Hardberger, Texas Courtroom Evidence , 4th Ed.,   18.16.] 

<P> The comment to the 1984 amendments also gives some insight into the nature of evidence
which may be used to supplement a prior offer. [. The comment cross-references TRE 610(a).  It
appears that this reference should be to TRE 611(a), since a new TRE 610 was added in 1988
requiring a renumbering of subsequent rules.  TRE 611(a) addresses control by the court over,
among other things, presentation of evidence.]  The comment states that the rule does not:

<P><BLOCKQUOTE>alter the common law doctrine that the rule of optional completeness, as
to writings, oral conversations, or other matters, may take precedence over exclusionary
doctrines such as the hearsay or best evidence rule or the first-hand knowledge
requirement.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>While this is significant because it gives a party seeking to supplement an opposing party's
offer the potential to do so with evidence which might otherwise be excluded, the principle is not
without limitations.  For example, despite the suggestion that otherwise inadmissible evidence
may be admitted as a matter of fairness, this may not be the case where the subsequent offer is
seeking to clarify evidence which, if a proper objection had been lodged, would not have been
admitted in the first place.  In other words, where one party introduces improper evidence
without objection it does not necessarily justify introduction of similar (i.e. improper) evidence
by another.  <U>Evans v. </U><U>State Bar of Texas</U>, 768 S.W.2d 326, 329-30
(Tex.App.--El Paso 1989), rev'd on other grounds, 774 S.W.2d 656 (Tex. 1989).  In addition, at
least one court has noted that the rule &quot;contemplates&quot; that the evidence to be
presented will be &quot;relevant to and explanatory of&quot; the portion already introduced. 
<U>Texas Casualty Ins. Co. v. Crawford</U>, 340 S.W.2d 110, 112 (Tex. Civ. App.--Amarillo
1960, no writ).  Thus, courts considering supplemental offers under TRE 106 may view them
with a particularly critical eye in assessing relevance.  (<U>See</U> <U>also</U> <U>Neal v.
Neal</U>, 470 S.W.2d 383, 386 (Tex. Civ. App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1971, no writ): &quot;If
one party in a civil case introduces in evidence part of a statement ... the other party may then
introduce as much of the remainder of such evidence as is necessary or proper to explain the part
previously admitted&quot;.)

<P> A more recent trend for cases involving the application of TRE 106 relates to edited
versions of videotaped depositions.  In <U>Texas Department </U><U>of Human Services v.
Green</U>, 855 S.W.2d at 151, the court of appeals found no error with the trial court's having
admitted edited versions of videotaped depositions of certain of the plaintiff's witnesses, despite
the claim of the DHS that the editing involved &quot;extensive splicing and mismatching [of]
questions and answers&quot;.  The court held that as a matter of trial strategy a party is entitled
to offer evidence in the order that will most effectively present its case, provided the presentation
does not convey a distinctly false impression.  <U>Id</U>.  Furthermore, the court concluded
that even if the edited videotape had been misleading, there was no harm because DHS
wasallowed to present its own videotape of the same witness.  <U>Id</U>.  Presumably this was
allowed under TRE 106.

<P> Another videotaped deposition scenario was presented in <U>Jones v. Colley</U>, 820
S.W.2d 863 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1991, writ denied) a negligence case concerning the
administration of anesthesia during a cesarean section.  The plaintiff had offered the videotaped
deposition of her expert witness, and the tape had been edited to put the questions and answers in
an order most favorable to the plaintiff's case.  The trial court disallowed introduction of the tape,
and the jury made a no negligence finding.  The court of appeals affirmed the decision (because
the entire deposition had been read to the jury and the videotape would have been cumulative),
but nevertheless indicated that the videotape should have been admitted.  The court noted that
TRE 106 is not enforced by <I>excluding</I> a partial statement, but rather by allowing an
opponent to introduce other portions of the same statement.  In this case the defendants,
according to the court, had no right to object because the tape was out of chronological sequence,
and instead could have introduced their own edited version or, alternatively, the entire unedited
version.

<P> The application of TRE 106 to both written documents and a tape recording was considered
in <U>Meuth v. Hartgrove</U>, 811 S.W.2d 626 (Tex.App.--Austin 1990, writ denied).  In that
case a negligence claim was asserted by a former employee against his employer (individually
and under a d/b/a) and a corporation alleged to be the alter ego of the individual defendant.  The
first issue under TRE 106 involved the admission of insurance certificates for the purpose of
proving ownership of the defendant company.  The policy limits were redacted from the
certificates, and the appellant claimed that the entirety of the documents (including the policy
limits) should have been admitted.  The court disagreed, holding that the policy limits were not
relevant to ownership and would be prejudicial to the issue of damages.  The court noted that the
fairness considerations of TRE 106 did not come into play to warrant the requested
supplementation.

<P> The second issue in <U>Meuth v. Hartgrove</U> concerned the admission of a tape
recorded conversation.  The entire tape recording was offered and admitted, although it only
contained a part of the entire conversation.  The court refused to exclude the tape on the grounds
that it evidenced only part of an occurrence, instead noting that TRE 106 provides for entering
the complete document or recording in evidence at the time a portion is admitted.  Because the
entire recording was presented, the court held there was no error.
<P> Finally, a case which illustrates the more traditional application of TRE 106 is <U>Azar Nut
Co. </U><U>v. Caille</U>, 720 S.W.2d 685 (Tex.App.--El Paso 1986), aff'd 734 S.W.2d 667
(Tex. 1987), in which the plaintiff alleged that she had been wrongfully discharged from her job
in retaliation for having filed a worker's compensation claim. Counsel for the defendant
introduced a letter written by an officer of the defendant company offering the plaintiff another
job, at the same salary, with an affiliated company.  The defendant had hoped to use the letter to
establish that the plaintiff had failed to mitigate her damages.  In response, the plaintiff's attorney
objected, and noted that if it was admitted into evidence he would request admission of his own
correspondence rejecting the defendant's job offer and explaining the reasons therefore. 
Defendant's counsel nevertheless offered the letter, and the court, with a few deletions, admitted
the letter of plaintiff's counsel as well.   The court of appeals affirmed the trial court's admission
of the plaintiff's letter, and noted that even if there was error in the admission of the letter of
plaintiff's counsel, &quot;such was invited by the Appellant and it cannot now complain&quot;. 
<U>Id</U>. at 688.  Thus, counsel should be wary of what it may see in return when seeking
admission of documents (or parts thereof).

<P><B>D. </B><B>Judicial and Official Notice of Adjudicative </B><B>Facts (TRE 201 and
204; APA </B><B>&#167;</B><B>2001.090; </B><B>SOAH Rule
</B><B>&#167;</B><B>155.45(d)).</B>

<P> Judicial and official notice refer generally to a court or an agency recognizing a fact as true
or conclusive without that fact having to be proven through conventional means.  In other
words,judicial or official notice will allow a trier of fact to accept as true a fact for which no
testimony or evidence will be presented.  Of course, there are restrictions on the types of facts
which may be judicially or officially noticed, but provided these restrictions can be met judicial
and official notice can be useful tools in building an evidentiary record.

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. </B><B>Judicial Notice Under the TRE.</B>

<P> TRE 201 delineates the types of facts which may be judicially noticed by a court, and sets
forth the general principles governing when such notice is discretionary and when it is
mandatory. The rule has been interpreted to require that an adjudicative fact, to be judicially
noticed, must not be subject to reasonable dispute; it must be capable of accurate and ready 
determination by resort to sources whose accuracy cannot be questioned. <U>First National
Bank of Amarillo v. Jarnigan</U>, 794 S.W.2d 54 (Tex.App.--Amarillo 1990, writ denied).  For
example, the Texas Supreme Court has held that an order of the Public Utility Commission
(&quot;PUC&quot;) which is published in the PUC Bulletin can be judicially noticed because
the authenticity and contents of the order &quot;are capable of accurate and ready determination
by resort to a published record whose accuracy cannot reasonably be questioned.&quot; 
<U>Office of Public </U><U>Utility Counsel v. PUC</U>, 878 S.W.2d 598, 600 (Tex. 1994). 
Also, judicial notice may be taken of facts which are not subject to reasonable disputes and
which are generally known within the territorial jurisdiction of the court.  <U>Settlers Village
</U><U>Community Improvement Assoc. v. Settlers </U><U>Village</U>, 828 S.W.2d 182,
184 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1992 no writ) (taking judicial notice of the
&quot;fact&quot; that $0.015 commonly means one and one-half cents).  Note that it is only
adjudicative facts, and <I>not</I> matters of law, which can be judicially noticed. 
<U>Lawrenson v. Global </U><U>Marine, Inc.</U>, 869 S.W.2d 519, 525
(Tex.App.--Texarkana 1993, no writ).

<P> In general, the taking of judicial notice is mandatory when requested by a party and the
necessary information is supplied, and is discretionary in all other instances.  TRE 201(c), (d);
<U>City of Mesquite v. Moore</U>, 800 S.W.2d 617,619 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1990, no writ). 
The rule is founded on concerns over expediency and convenience, and it was adopted to save
time in the trial of controversies.  <U>Skinner v. HCC Credit </U><U>Co. of Arlington,
Inc.</U>, 498 S.W.2d 708, 711 (Tex. Civ. App.--Ft. Worth 1973, no writ).

<P><B>2. </B><B>Official Notice Under the APA.</B>

<P> Given the sometimes extraordinary length of administrative proceedings, arguments in favor
of official notice founded on expediency and efficiency have particular appeal.  Fortunately the
APA, in &#167; 2001.090, has its own corollary to TRE 201, and the SOAH Rules, in
&#167;155.46 (d), merely adopt by reference the APA approach.  Section 2001.090 of the APA
provides that in proceedings governed by the Act, official notice may be taken of:
<UL>

<P> (1) all facts that are judicially cognizable; and

<P> (2) generally recognized facts within the area of the state agency's specialized knowledge.
</UL>

<P> Section 2001.090 broadens the scope of items which may be officially noticed by
encompassing facts within the area of an agency's &quot;specialized knowledge&quot;. 
Presumably this recognizes that administrative proceedings occur in forums where the
participants and the trier of fact have specific expertise in the subject area governed by that
agency (in contrast, for example, to a state district court, which may hear a wide variety of civil
and criminal cases).  It is clear, however, that officially noticed information, standing alone and
without supporting evidence in the record, is not a substitute for proof notwithstanding the
agency's expertise.  <U>Common Carrier Motor Freight Assoc. </U><U>v. Railroad
Commission of Texas</U>, 699 S.W.2d 291, 293 (Tex.App.--Austin 1985) rev'd on other
grounds, 704 S.W.2d 741 (Tex. 1986).

<P> Similarly, the expertise of the agency's board or commission members cannot provide facts
to be officially noticed in the decision-making process. In <U>Dotson v. Texas State Board of
Medical </U><U>Examiners</U>, 612 S.W.2d 921, 923-24 (Tex. 1981),two doctors appealed
the suspension of their licenses for allegedly prescribing drugs in a non-therapeutic manner. 
Although no evidence was presented to controvert the doctors' contention that the drugs were
prescribed in proper amounts, the Board of Medical Examiners argued that, because all of its
members were professionals, expert testimony was unnecessary (as the board members possessed
the knowledge necessary to make that determination).  The court disagreed, noting that there had
been no effort to officially notice the facts allegedly known by the board members, and therefore
those facts were not in the record available for review by the court.  (<U>See</U> <U>also</U>
<U>Wood </U><U>v. Texas State Board of Medical Examiners</U>, 615 S.W.2d 942
(Tex.App.--Ft. Worth 1981, no writ)).

<P> Note also that while APA &#167; 2001.090 provides for official notice of matters within an
agency's specialized knowledge, that notice must still follow the general parameters of TRE 201
concerning the opportunity for other parties to contest that notice.  Section 2001.090 requires that
each party be notified of material to be officially noticed and be given an opportunity to contest
that notice.  In <U>Railroad Commission of Texas v. Lone </U><U>Star Gas Co.</U>, 611
S.W.2d 911, 913 (Tex. Civ. App.--Austin 1981, writ ref'd n.r.e.), the court stated that the purpose
of official notice provisions such as section 14(q) of APTRA (now APA &#167; 2001.090) is
&quot;to require notice be given of the officially noticed materials at a time in advance of the
hearing, adequate to permit the parties to contest the materials during the hearing&quot;. 
Official notice cannot be taken, for the first time, in a hearings examiner's proposal for decision. 
<U>Id</U>. at 914.

<P> Official notice can be a useful tool to expedite a proceeding and to eliminate fact issues
which may otherwise require proof through testimony or other record evidence.  It should be
approached with caution, however, and parties urging that an agency take official notice should
be prepared to follow the procedures set forth in TRE 201, as well as the agency's own rules.

<P><B>3. </B><B>Judicial Notice of the </B><B><I>Texas Register </I></B><B>and
</B><B>the</B><B><I> Texas Administrative Code</I></B><B>.</B>

<P> While TRE 201 speaks generally to judicial notice, TRE 204 specifically addresses judicial
notice of the contents of the <I>Texas Register</I>, codified rules of agencies published in the
<I>Texas </I><I>Administrative Code</I>, and ordinances of municipalities and counties in
Texas.  The rule prescribes essentially the same procedures as are in TRE 201, as the party
requesting that notice be taken must provide the court (or agency) with enough information to
support the request, and other parties must be given an opportunity to contest the notice.  The
comments to TRE 204 indicate that the taking judicial notice at the request of a party is
mandatory rather than discretionary.

<P> In administrative hearings this rule may have particular appeal with respect to the<I> Texas
Register</I> and the <I>Texas Administrative Code</I>.  In <U>Mullinax, </U><U>Wells,
Babb and Cloutman v. Sage</U>, 692 S.W.2d 533 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1985, writ ref'd n.r.e.), the
court took judicial notice of the &quot;judgment rate&quot; which had been computed by the
Consumer Credit Commissioner and published in the <I>Texas Register</I>. The rate was used
in computing an interest amount on a judgment the court was entering.  The court noted that it
was appropriate to take judicial notice of the contents of the <I>Texas Register</I>, and that
publication in the <I>Texas Register</I> constituted prima facie evidence of the text of the
documents as well as prima facie evidence of the fact that the provisions published were in effect
on and after the date of the notation.  <U>Id</U>. at 536 (fn. 1).  With respect to judicial notice
of the <I>Texas </I><I>Administrative Code</I>, the court, in <U>Bower v. </U><U>Edwards
County Appraisal District</U>, 697 S.W.2d 528 (Tex.App.--San Antonio 1985, no writ), held
that it was proper to have taken judicial notice of the State Property Tax Board Guidelines for
valuation of certain types of property since they were rules promulgated pursuant to statutory
authority and were published in the <I>Texas </I><I>Administrative Code</I>.  The court
overruled an objection that these were not properly authenticated public records under TRE
902(5), and instead noted that judicial notice could betaken without a request and without need
for extrinsic evidence of authenticity.  <U>Id</U>. at 530.

<P> There are also two little known statutory provisions which address the evidentiary value of
the <I>Texas Register</I> and the <I>Texas Administrative </I><I>Code</I>.  The first is Tex.
Gov&#146;t Code Ann. &#167; 2002.022(a) (Vernon Pamph. 1996), which relates to the
<I>Texas Register</I>.  It provides that:
<UL>
<P> (a) The contents of the Texas Register are to be judicially noticed and are prima facie
evidence of the text of the documents and of the fact that they are in effect on and after the date
of notation.
</UL>
<P>The second is Tex. Gov&#146;t Code Ann. &#167; 2002.054, which is virtually identical to
the <I>Texas Register</I> provision quoted above and pertains to &quot;state agency rules
published in the administrative code, as approved by the Secretary of State and as amended by
documents later filed with the Office of the Secretary.&quot;  These provisions, while rarely
cited or encountered, provide further support for the principle of TRE 204 as it relates to the
<I>Texas </I><I>Register</I> and <I>Texas Administrative Code</I>.  Both, in their official
form, must be officially noticed.

<P><B>4. </B><B>Cases Illustrating Judicial and Official </B><B>Notice.</B>

<P>  The following is a description of cases addressing judicial notice of facts of a type, or based
upon a theory, which may be encountered in an administrative proceeding:

<P>1. <U>Thomas v. Thomas</U>, 917 S.W.2d 425, 437 (Tex. App.--Waco 1996, n.w.h.);
court of appeals presumed that trial court took judicial notice of usual and customary attorneys
fees.  (<I>See</I> Tex. Gov&#146;t. Code &#167; 2007.026 for an example of administrative
proceeding where attorney&#146;s fees may be awarded).

<P>2. <U>Apostolic Church v. American Honda Motor </U><U>Company</U>, 833 S.W.2d
553, 555-6 (Tex.App.--Tyler 1992, writ denied):  The court noted that highway nomenclature
and designations within the trial court's jurisdiction are matters of commonknowledge and can be
proper subjects for judicial notice.<I>  </I>(<I>But see</I>: <U>Butts Retail, Inc. v.
</U><U>Diversifoods, Inc.</U>, 840 S.W.2d 770, 774 (Tex.App.--Beaumont 1992, writ
denied), where the court refused to take judicial notice of the fact that the cities of Beaumont,
Port Arthur and Orange are all in the same metropolitan area.)

<P>3. <U>City of Mesquite v. Moore</U>, 800 S.W.2d 617, 619 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1990, no
writ):  The court of appeals took judicial notice of the population of the City of Mesquite.  The
court acknowledged that the record included an official United States Department of Commerce
Bureau of Census estimate, which supplied the court with the necessary information.

<P>4. <U>Allied General Agency, Inc. v. Moody</U>, 788 S.W.2d 601, 607 (Tex.App.--Dallas
1990, writ denied):  The trial court took judicial notice of the definition of the word
&quot;promotion&quot; from the <I>Oxford, Webster</I> and <I>Merriam</I> Dictionaries.

<P>5. <U>Drake v. Holstad</U>, 757 S.W.2d 909 (Tex.App.--Beaumont 1988, no writ):  The
court of appeals held that the trial court had erred in not taking judicial notice of the number of
feet traveled at a given rate of speed.  The court explained that Texas courts take judicial notice
of natural forces as well as the primary laws of physics, mechanics, and mathematics, and stated
that a fact is generally known even though it has to be processed with commonly possessed
mental skills.  <U>Id</U>. at 910, quoting <U>Searcy v. Sellers</U>, 470 S.W.2d 103, 110
(Tex. Civ. App.--Amarillo 1971, writ ref'd n.r.e.); C. Wright v. K. Graham, <U>Federal
</U><U>Practice and Procedure</U> Sec. 5105, at 232 (1987 Supp.).  The court acknowledged
that just because a matter is susceptible to judicial notice does not require the court take such
notice, and the party seeking mandatory judicial notice must supply the court with the necessary
information.  In this case the party seeking judicial notice of the facts had provided the court with
a sheet of type-written computations, although it had not supplied the court with verification that
there are, in fact, 5,280 feet in a mile.  Nevertheless, the court noted that, also under TRE 201,
courts may judicially notice facts generally known within the territorial jurisdiction without
confirmation of those facts,and that 5,280 feet is the figure found under the definition of
&quot;mile&quot; in a standard desk-side dictionary (referring to <I>The American Heritage
</I><I>Dictionary of the English Language</I> (1975)).  The court concluded that once the
number of minutes in an hour, seconds in a minute, and  feet in a mile are ascertained, it is a
matter of simple mathematical computation to arrive at the number of feet traveled in a second
by an object traveling at a given rate per mile.

<P>6. <U>Eikel v. Corry</U>, 687 S.W.2d 488, 489 (Tex. Civ. App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1985,
writ ref'd n.r.e.):  The court of appeals found that the trial court was correct in refusing to take
judicial notice of a driver's braking time.  The court recognized that courts have judicially noticed
a normal driver's reaction time, but they have not judicially noticed the correlation of minimum
stopping distance with speed.

<P>7. <U>Railroad Commission v. Rio Grande Valley </U><U>Gas Co.</U>, 683 S.W.2d 783,
788 (Tex.App.--Austin 1984, no writ): Although an agency may take official notice of facts
within the general areas of its specialized knowledge, a copy of a cover page of a report and a
one-page excerpt therefrom (written by an unidentified author) concerning a methodology for an
allocation formula was insufficient to support a finding that the document was within an area of
the agency's specialized expertise.  Official notice was therefore not appropriate.

<P>8. <U>Haden Co., Inc. v. Mixers, Inc.</U>, 667 S.W.2d 316, 318 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1984,
no writ): Judicial notice could be taken of fact that the symbol ` refers to feet and &quot; refers
to inches.

<P>9. <U>United Savings Association of Texas v. </U><U>Vandygriff</U>, 594 S.W.2d 163,
166-67 (Tex. Civ. App.--Austin 1980 writ ref'd n.r.e.).  The Savings and Loan Commission
properly took official notice, under APTRA &#167; 14(q), of the names of all savings and loan
associations chartered in the state.  The Commission's records contained this information, and the
fact that none of the institutions had a name similar to that in issue was &quot;generally
recognized&quot; to be within the area of the agency's specialized knowledge.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>E. </B><B>Relevance and Exclusion of Relevant </B><B>Evidence (TRE 401, 403;
APA </B><B>&#167;</B><B> </B><B>2001.082).</B>

<P> Whether evidence is &quot;relevant&quot; is a key determinant of whether it will become
part of the evidentiary record.
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>1. </B><B>Relevance Defined.</B>

<P> Evidence is relevant if it has a tendency to make the existence of a fact that is of
consequence to the determination of an action more probable or less probable than it would be
without the evidence.  TRE 401; <U>Ebasco Constructors, Inc. v. </U><U>Rex</U>, 923
S.W.2d 694, 700 (Tex. App.--Corpus Christi 1996, n.w.h.).  As noted in <U>Keene Corp. v.
</U><U>Gardner</U>, 837 S.W.2d. 224, 230 (Tex.App.--Dallas, 1992, writ denied), evidence is
relevant and material only if it tends to prove or disprove any fact in issue.  Unless otherwise
provided by statutes, rules, etc., all relevant evidence is admissible and evidence which is not
relevant is inadmissible.  TRE 402; <U>Durbin v. Dal-Briar </U><U>Corp.</U>, 871 S.W.2d
263, 268 (Tex. App.--El Paso 1994, writ denied).  Section 2001.082 of the APA and &#167;
155.45(e) of the SOAH Rules reflect these principles by providing, in essence, that  evidence
which is irrelevant, immaterial, or unduly repetitious shall be limited or excluded.

<P><B>2. </B><B>Exclusion of Relevant Evidence.</B>

<P> What is often overlooked with respect to questions of relevancy is that in some instances
even relevant evidence may be excluded.  TRE 403 provides as follows:

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Although relevant, evidence may be excluded if its probative value is substantially
outweighed by the danger of unfair prejudice, confusion of the issues, or misleading the jury, or
by considerations of undue delay, or needless presentation of cumulative evidence.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P> In civil proceedings this rule requires the trial judge to use a balancing test which weighs the
probative value of evidence against its prejudicial nature.  <U>Perez v. Baker Packers</U>, 694
S.W.2d 138,140 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist] 1985, writ ref'd n.r.e.).  One case has
characterized TRE 403 as requiring the trier of fact to: (i) identify the probative value of the
proffered evidence; (ii) identify the costs of admitting the evidence; and (iii) weigh one against
the other.  <U>Service Lloyds </U><U>Insurance Co. v. Martin</U>, 855 S.W.2d 816, 825
(Tex.App.--Dallas 1993, no writ) (citing Wendorf, Schlueter &amp; Barton, <U>Texas Rules of
Evidence </U><U>Manual</U>, IV-18 (1991)).  Because TRE 403 provides for the exclusion of
probative evidence, it is an extraordinary remedy that must be used sparingly.  <U>LSR Joint
Venture No. 2 v. Callewert</U>, 837 S.W.2d 693, 698 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1992, writ denied),
citing <U>Dartez v. Fibreboard Corp.</U>, 765 F.2d 456 (5th Cir. 1985).   (<I>But</I>
<I>see</I> <U>TCA Building </U><U>Company v. Northwestern Resources Company</U>,
922 S.W.2d 629, 637 (Tex. App.--Waco 1996 n.w.h.) holding that a court has &quot;wide
latitude&quot; to exclude evidence if it results in undue prejudice, distracts the jury, consumes
an undue amount of time, or if it unfairly surprises the proponent&#146;s adversary). Several
decisions have noted that rules which exclude relevant evidence must be supported by good
cause and sound policy reasons.  <U>Farr v. Wright</U>, 833 S.W.2d 597, 599
(Tex.App.--Corpus Christi 1992, writ denied); <U>Day </U><U>&amp; Zimmerman, Inc. v.
Hatridge</U>, 831 S.W.2d 65, 71 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1992, writ denied).  As one court has
noted, TRE 403 generally comes into play when the probative value of the evidence is low or the
problems with the evidence are serious.  <U>Williford v. Submergible Cable</U>, 895 S.W.2d
379, 390 (Tex. App.--Amarillo 1994, no writ).

<P> Where questions of delay and cumulative evidence are not factors in the consideration of the
application of TRE 403, the trial court must balance and weigh the probative effect of evidence
sought to be excluded against its potential for unfair prejudice or confusion.  <U>Farr v.
Wright</U>, 833 S.W.2d at  602.  Little evidence in a lawsuit will not be prejudicial to at least
one party, so the court must consider whether the danger of <I>unfair</I> prejudice is
substantially outweighed by probative value.  <U>Porter v. Nemir</U>, 900 S.W.2d at 381.
Unfair prejudice has been defined as &quot;an undue tendency to suggest a decision on an
improper basis, commonly, though not necessarily, anemotional one.&quot;  <U>Turner v. PV
International Corp.</U>, 765 S.W.2d 455, 471 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1988), writ ref'd per curiam,
778 S.W.2d 865 (Tex. 1989) (citing advisory committee note to Fed. R. Evid. 403).  In weighing
the probative value of the evidence against the danger of unfair prejudice, the court must
consider the necessity for, and probative effect of, the evidence, and should consider whether the
same facts could have been proven by other evidence.  <U>LSR Joint Venture No.
</U><U>2</U>, 837 S.W.2d at 698; citing <U>Gross v. Black &amp; </U><U>Decker (U.S.),
Inc.</U>, 695 F.2d 858, 863 (5th Cir. 1983).

<P> Also note that evidence initially excluded under TRE 403 may later be admitted in light of
other evidence presented.  For example, in <U>Carter </U><U>v. Exxon Corp.</U>, 842
S.W.2d 393 (Tex.App.--Eastland 1992, writ denied), the trial court initially excluded evidence
concerning the amount of oil royalties paid to a lessor-estate of property since the dispute was
over gas royalties.  Evidence concerning oil royalties reflected on the wealth of a party, and such
evidence is typically considered inadmissible in civil trials (because it is irrelevant and often
prejudicial).  <U>Id</U>. at 399.  In this case, however, the trial court reversed itself and
admitted the evidence after the plaintiff presented a witness (an heir of the estate) who testified
that he had worked for 34 years as a bus driver and was continuing to do so to build up
retirement benefits.  The trial court stated that this testimony had the effect of portraying the
heirs of the lessor-estate as &quot;poor folk,&quot; and admission of evidence concerning the
amount of oil royalties paid was not unfairly prejudicial because it tended to offset the prejudice
caused by the plaintiffs' testimony. <U>Id</U>. at 400.  Thus, what is excluded on grounds of
prejudice may later become &quot;less&quot; prejudicial (and therefore admissible) because of
other evidence presented.

<P> The question of exclusion of relevant evidence comes up most frequently in civil
proceedings where inflammatory evidence, or evidence which could be unfairly prejudicial, is
sought to be excluded.  In  administrative proceedings it is more likely to arise with respect to
claims of confusion of the issues, delay or cumulative evidence.  Lengthy
administrativeproceedings can generate huge evidentiary records with expert testimony, exhibits,
and other technical documentation, and hearings examiners are often reluctant, and rightfully so,
to permit such records to be further burdened with evidence which has clearly been presented
through other witnesses, testimony or exhibits.  The right of an ALJ to exclude cumulative, or
&quot;unduly repetitious&quot; evidence is explicit in APA &#167; 2001.082 and SOAH Rule
&#167; 155.45(e).  One recent decision has specifically articulated the test to be applied in
deciding whether to exclude &quot;cumulative&quot; evidence.  In <U>Sims v. Brackett</U>,
885 S.W.2d 450, 454, (Tex. App.--Corpus Christi 1994, writ denied), the court stated that to
exclude cumulative evidence under TRE 403 a balancing test must be conducted, and only when
the balance weighs significantly on the side of judicial efficiency may relevant evidence be
excluded as cumulative.  It is reasonable to expect that a similar analysis will, or should, be made
by ALJs in assessing unduly repetitious evidence.

<P> Another area where TRE 403 may have particular applicability in administrative
proceedings is in the area of expert testimony and disclosure of the basis for expert opinions. 
Expert testimony is subject to scrutiny (under TRE 702) as to whether it aids the trier of fact, and
it &quot;may be further tested by Rule 403 to avoid confusing or misleading the jury&quot;. 
<U>Gregg County Appraisal </U><U>District v. Laidlaw Waste Systems, Inc.</U>, 907
S.W.2d 12, 19 (Tex. App.--Tyler 1995, writ denied).  As is discussed in section III.H. below,
expert witnesses may base their opinions on otherwise inadmissible evidence, and may even be
entitled to disclose that basis while testifying. (TRE 703, 705).  As a result, otherwise
inadmissible evidence may be admitted into the record as the basis of an expert witness' opinion.
However, at least one decision has clarified a party's right to exclude such evidence through an
objection under TRE 403.  In <U>Dudley v. Humana </U><U>Hospital Corp.</U>, 817 S.W.2d
124, 127 (Tex.App. -Houston [14th Dist.] 1991, no writ), a plaintiff filed a negligence claim
against a doctor in relation to hip replacement surgery, and also sued the hospital for negligence
for allowing the doctor to perform surgery while allegedly under investigation for illegal
dispensation ofprescription drugs.  The appeals court upheld the trial court's exclusion of expert
testimony concerning the drug investigation and related issues, holding that evidence which
meets the requirements for admissibility under TRE 702-705 is nevertheless <I>not</I>
admissible if it is irrelevant under TRE 401 or if its admission would present problems of undue
prejudice or confusion of the issues under TRE 403.  <U>Id</U>.  (<I>See also</I>, <U>First
</U><U>Southwest Lloyds Insurance Co. v. MacDowell</U>, 769 S.W.2d 954, 958
(Tex.App.--Texarkana 1989, writ denied) noting that even if all facts or data relied upon by an
expert were admissible, the trial court had the discretion, under TRE 403, to exclude the facts or
data if it found a danger of unfair prejudice, confusion or undue delay.) Practitioners should
therefore consider an objection under TRE 403 when faced with expert testimony based on
otherwise inadmissible testimony.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><B>F. </B><B>Privileges and Protections Against </B><B>Disclosure (TRE 503,</B><B>
</B><B>507; Tex. R. Civ. P. </B><B>166b; APA </B><B>&#167;</B><B>
</B><B>2001.083).</B>

<P> Privileges against disclosure of communications, information, data, and other material are a
complicated and often controversial area of the law.  Although commonly considered to be a
discovery issue, several rules relating to privileges are contained within the TRE.  Also, the
availability of a privilege may control whether a party has the right to prevent the disclosure of
otherwise relevant evidence, and that has serious implications in the fact finding process and the
development of the evidentiary record.  For these reasons rules regarding privileges warrant at
least a brief discussion.

<P> The privileges most often encountered in administrative proceedings are those protecting (1)
attorney/client communications; (2) attorney work product; and (3) trade secrets.  The privileges
against disclosing attorney/client communications and trade secrets are addressed in TRE 503
and 507, respectively, while the attorney work product privilege is derived from Tex. R. Civ. P.
166b(3). Section 2001.083 of the APA states that in a contested case &quot;a state agency shall
give effect to the rules of privilege recognized by law&quot;, making it clear that all privileges
(whether or notcontained in the TRE) are applicable in administrative proceedings.

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>1. </B><B>Attorney/Client Privilege.</B>

<P> The rule governing the privilege for attorney/client communications is contained within
TRE 503(b), which states:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>A client has a privilege to refuse to disclose and to prevent any other
person from disclosing confidential communications made for the purpose of facilitating the
rendition of professional legal services to the client (1) between himself or his representative and
his lawyer or his lawyer's representative, (2) between his lawyer and the lawyer's representative,
(3) by him or his representative or his lawyer or a representative of the lawyer to a lawyer, or a
representative of a lawyer representing another party in a pending action and concerning a matter
of common interest therein, (4) between representatives of the client or between the client and a
representative of the client, or (5) among lawyers and their representatives representing the same
client.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>a. </B><B> </B><B>Purpose of the Privilege</B>.

<P> Although most lawyers are familiar with the general purpose for the attorney-client
privilege, the Texas Supreme Court recently had occasion to articulate that purpose in a useful
form.  In <U>Ford </U><U>Motor Co. v. Leggat</U>, 904 S.W.2d 643, 657 (Tex. 1995), the
court stated that (cites omitted):

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The attorney-client privilege has been recognized as &quot;the oldest of
the privileges for confidential communications known to the common law. ... Among
communications privileges, it is the only one recognized by every state, even though its scope ...
may vary.  ...The purpose of the privilege is to ensure the free flow of information between
attorney and client,ultimately serving the broader societal interest of effective administration of
justice...  A client must be able to confide in an attorney secure that the communication will not
be disclosed....</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>The <U>Leggat</U> decision involved, in part, a dispute over internal corporate documents
and whether the law of Michigan or Texas should apply in considering a  claim of privilege.  The
court held that the state of most significant relationship with the communication applied, in this
case Michigan since that is where the communication took place. <U>Leggat</U>, id at 647.   

<P><B>b. </B><B>Privilege Belongs to the Client.</B>

<P> The term &quot;client&quot; is defined broadly in TRE 503  to include a person, public
officer, or corporation, association or other organization or entity, either public or private, who is
rendered professional legal services by a lawyer or who consults a lawyer with a view to
obtaining professional legal services.  TRE 503(a)(1).  A recent Texas Supreme Court decision
considered the application of TRE 503 to the relationship between the trustee of a trust and his or
her attorney relating to trust administration, and held that, notwithstanding the trustee&#146;s
fiduciary duty to a beneficiary, only the trustee (and not the beneficiary) is the client of the
trustee&#146;s attorney. <U>Huie v. DeShazo</U>, 922 S.W.2d 920, 925 (Tex. 1996).

<P> 

<P> It is clear from TRE 503(b) and (c) that to the extent a privilege against disclosure exists, it
belongs to the client and not the attorney.  This was illustrated in <U>Cole v. Gabriel</U>, 822
S.W.2d 296 (Tex.App.--Ft. Worth 1991, no writ), where an attorney sought a writ of mandamus
ordering a district judge to vacate an order requiring the attorney to respond to questions
concerning communications between he and his client.  The court dismissed the petition, holding
that the attorney did not have standing to bring the action on his own behalf in support of his
client's privilege.  There was no indication in the case that the attorney was appearing on behalf
of the client. Thus, the privilege must be invoked by, or on behalf of, the client.

<P><B>c. </B><B>Identifying Representatives of a Client.</B>
<P> The concept of a &quot;representative&quot; is also important to an understanding of the
rule.  A representative of a client is one having the authority to obtain legal services (or act on
advice rendered pursuant thereto) on behalf of the client. TRE 503(a)(2).  A representative of the
lawyer is one employed by the lawyer to assist in the rendition of legal services, or an accountant
who is reasonably necessary for the lawyer's rendition of legal services.  TRE 503(a)(4). 
Although seemingly unambiguous, these descriptions can present difficulties in application.

<P> For example, while it is not difficult to identify a representative of a client when the client is
an individual, it can be very difficult to do so where the client is a corporation, association or
other organization.  To make this determination Texas has adopted, through TRE 503(a)(2), the
&quot;control group&quot; test (which has been rejected by the U.S. Supreme Court). [. In
Upjohn Co. v. United States , 101 S.Ct. 677 (1981) the Supreme Court rejected the control group
test, finding that it "overlooks the fact that the privilege exists to protect not only the giving of
professional advice to those who can act on it but also the giving of information to the lawyer to
enable him to give sound and informed advice. "  Id . at 683.  Although not adopting the
competing "subject matter " test, the Court described it as finding that an employee's statement
will be deemed to be that of the corporation if: the employee makes the communication at the
direction of his supervisors in the corporation and where the subject matter upon which the
attorney's advice is sought by the corporation and dealt with in the communication is the
performance by the employees of the duties of his employment. Id . at 491 - 92; as cited in
National Tank Co. v. Brotherton , 851 S.W.2d at 193.]   The control group test has been
interpreted generally to mean that a corporation can claim the attorney/client privilege only as to
&quot;statements made by employees in a position to control or even to take a substantial part in
a decision about any action which the corporation may take upon the advice of an
attorney.&quot;  <U>National Tank Co. v. Brotherton</U>, 851 S.W.2d 193, 197 (Tex. 1993)
(cites omitted).  The <U>National Tank Co.</U> case is a much cited decision of the Texas
Supreme Court which addresses many of the concepts associated with the attorney/client
privilege, particularly with respect to its invocation as to communications between client
representatives and an attorney.  As noted in that decision, courts applying the control group test
generally protect only statements made by the upper echelon of corporate management, and the
test is based on the premise that only an employee who controls the actions of the corporation
can personify the corporation.  <U>Id</U>. at 197 (cites omitted).  In <U>National Tank
Co.</U> the court applied the test and held that the attorney/client privilege did not extend to
interviews of employees (following a plant explosion) taken by a representative of the company's
lawyer.  The court held that those employees interviewed were not &quot;representatives&quot;
of the company within theframework of the control group test.  <U>Id</U>. at 197-199.

<P> The importance of <I>proving</I> that a corporate representative is a member of the control
group was illustrated in <U>El Centro Del Barrio, Inc. v. </U><U>Barlow</U>, 894 S.W.2d
775, 778-80 (Tex. App.--San Antonio 1994, no writ).  El Centro was a non-profit health care
corporation, and Dr. Ernesto Gomez was its executive director.  Both were sued by former
employees of the corporation over events related to the employees&#146; firings.  El Centro was
a member of the Texas Association of Community Health Centers, and the executive director of
the association (Mr. Camacho) was also its general counsel.  Mr. Camacho routinely provided
legal advice to the association&#146;s members, including El Centro.  Dr. Gomez, ostensibly on
behalf of El Centro, sought legal advice from Mr. Camacho regarding the employees&#146;
claims concerning their firings, and the court ultimately found that these communications were
discoverable.  In so holding the court stated that while &quot;it is tempting&quot; to presume to
know that an executive director is a member of the control group, &quot;no presumptions are
indulged when determining whether to restrict discovery based on the attorney-client
privilege.&quot;  <U>Id</U>., citing <U>Cigna </U><U>Corp. v. Spears</U>, 838 S.W.2d
561, 565 (Tex. App.--San Antonio 1992, orig. proceeding).  The lesson for practitioners is clear:
do not assume that control group status will be recognized merely by virtue of a job title.
<P><B>d. </B><B>Identifying Representatives of a Lawyer.</B>

<P> Representatives of a lawyer are not as difficult to identify (as are client representatives) for
purposes of determining the availability of the privilege.  TRE 503(a)(4) sets forth the general
concept that one employed by a lawyer to assist in the rendition of legal services is a
&quot;representative&quot; of the lawyer. Thus, an investigator hired by the lawyer with respect
to a specific matter will be considered a representative of the lawyer for purposes of the
privilege.  <U>IMC Fertilizer, Inc. v. </U><U>O'Neill</U>, 846 S.W.2d 590, 591-92
(Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1993, orig. proceeding); <U>Bearden v. Boone</U>, 693
S.W.2d 25, 27-28 (Tex.App.--Amarillo 1985, no writ).

<P> In administrative proceedings the &quot;representative&quot; issue may arise with respect
to expert witnesses (who are often retained by lawyers) as a discovery dispute governed by Tex.
R. Civ. P. 166b.  In general, Tex. R. Civ. P. 166b facilitates the division of experts into three
types, with separate rules regarding discovery from each. These are:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P> (i) <U>Testifying experts</U> -- parties may obtain, through discovery,
the name and location of an expert who will testify, as well as the subject matter about which
they will testify, the mental impressions and opinions held by the expert, and the facts known to
the expert which relate to or form the basis of the expert's mental impressions and opinions. 
Reports, models, data compilations and other material prepared by or for a testifying expert are
also discoverable.  Tex. R. Civ. P. 166b(2)(3)(1&amp;2).

<P> (ii) <U>Nontestifying experts whose work is not </U><U>reviewed or relied upon</U> --
the identity, mental impressions and opinions of an expert who has been informally consulted,
who will not testify and whose work is not reviewed or relied upon by a testifying expert are not
discoverable.  Tex. R. Civ. P. 166b(3)(b).  (<I>See also</I>, <U>Axelson, Inc. v.
</U><U>McIlhany</U>, 798 S.W.2d 550, 554 (Tex. 1990), holding that communications with
consulting experts are privileged and should remain so).

<P> (iii) <U>Nontestifying experts whose work is </U><U>reviewed or relied upon</U> -- the
identity, mental impressions and opinions; documents containing those impressions and
opinions; reports, models, data compilations, facts known to the expert and other materials are
discoverable from a nontestifying expert if they are reviewed by a testifying expert.  Tex. R. Civ.
P. 166b(2)(e) and 166b(3)(b); <U>Martin v. Boles</U>, 843 S.W.2d 90, 92
(Tex.App.--Texarkana 1992, no writ).
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>e. </B><B>Confidentiality of Communications.</B>

<P> In order to benefit from the attorney/client privilege the communications involved must be
confidential.  A communication is confidential if it is not intended to be disclosed to third
persons other than those to whom disclosure is made in furtherance of the rendition of
professional legal services to the client or those reasonably necessary for the transmission of the
communication.  TRE 503(a)(5).  For example, if a communication between the attorney and the
client is made in the presence of a third person (who is not a representative of the lawyer or the
client) the communication will not be considered as confidential and therefore will not qualify
for the privilege.  <U>Ledisco Financial Services, Inc. v. </U><U>Viracola</U>, 533 S.W.2d
951, 959 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1976, no writ).  Also, the communication must be made in
connection with the rendition of professional services.  In <U>Parker v.
</U><U>Carnahan</U>, 772 S.W.2d 151, 156 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1989, writ denied), the
court held that the mere signing of tax returns by the wife of a client in a lawyer's office did not
create an attorney/client relationship between the wife and the lawyer.  There was no
communication, in that context, made to facilitate the rendition of legal services.  <U>Id</U>.

<P> In assessing attorney-client communications the focus must be on the existence of a
communication between an attorney and client, rather than on the substance of the
communication. In <U>GAF Corp. v. Caldwell</U>, 839 S.W.2d 149, 151 (Tex.App.--Houston
[14th Dist.] 1992, orig. proceeding) the appeals court found fault with a trial judge having found
certain attorney-client communications to be discoverable because they contained factual
information and not legal advice or opinions.  The court stated that: 

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>. . . the subject of the information communicated between the attorney
and client is of no concern in determining whether the privilege is applicable to the documents. 
[The trial judge] erred in distinguishing between the documents based on the subject contents as
opposed to the fact that thedocuments constituted communication between attorney and client
under Rule 503(b). </BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><U>Id</U>. at 151.  In a similar case (involving the same trial judge and appellate court),
the court noted that the attorney-client privilege extends to the complete communication (not just
those aspects dealing with legal advice), and that the fact that certain information within the
documents may be discoverable through other means does not overcome the privilege. 
<U>Keene Corp. v. Caldwell</U>, 840 S.W.2d 715, 720 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1992,
orig. proceeding).  In yet another case involving the same judge the appellate court noted that the
privilege attaches to legal advice <I>and</I> factual information included in completed
communications between attorney and client. <U>Pittsburgh Corning Corp. v. Caldwell</U>,
861 S.W.2d 423, 425 (Tex. App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1993, orig. proceeding) (emphasis
added).  The event of a communication is clearly the relevant inquiry in any privilege analysis;
the substance of the communication holds little, if any, significance in determining whether the
privilege applies.

<P><B>f. </B><B>Burden of Proof</B>.

<P> To establish the existence of a privilege, a party must plead the particular privilege, produce
evidence to support the privilege (through affidavits or testimony), and produce documents for
an<I> in camera</I> review if the court (or ALJ) determines that such a review is necessary.
<U>Marathon Oil Co. v. Moye</U>, 893 S.W.2d 585, 589-90 (Tex. App.--Dallas 1994, no writ);
<U>Humphreys </U><U>v. Caldwell</U>, 881 S.W.2d 469, 470 (Tex. 1994) There are no
presumptions of privilege, and parties asserting a privilege should be prepared to prove, at a
minimum, the existence of an attorney-client relationship and of a confidential communication.
<U>El Centro Del Barrio, Inc. v. Barlow</U>, 894 S.W.2d at 778-79.  Furthermore, any
affidavits offered in support of the existence of a privilege must &quot;positively and
unqualifiedly&quot; represent the facts to be true and within the affiants&#146; personal
knowledge, and anything less (e.g. facts the affiant &quot;believes&quot;) may well be deemed
inadequate to carry the burden.  <U>Humphreys v. Caldwell</U>, 888 S.W. 2d at 470.  Keep in
mind that proving anattorney-client relationship with respect to a corporation should include
proof as to the existence of a control group and the inclusion of a particular individual (who was
a party to the communication) within that group.

<P><B>g. </B><B>Waiver of the Privilege</B>.

<P> A question which often arises with respect to attorney/client privilege is the circumstances
under which the privilege may be waived.  TRE 511 addresses this issue, and generally provides
that a waiver can occur through voluntary disclosure or consent to disclosure of any significant
part of the privileged matter (unless the disclosure is itself privileged), or when the holder of the
privilege (or their representative) calls a person to whom privileged communications have been
made to testify as to the client's character insofar as the communications are relevant to that
character or character trait.  The privilege may be waived by the client, his guardian or
conservator, the personal representative of a deceased client, or the successor, trustee, or similar
representative of a corporation, association, or other organization, whether or not in existence. 
<U>General Resources </U><U>Organization, Inc. v. Deadman</U>, 907 S.W.2d 22, 29 (Tex.
App.--San Antonio 1995, writ denied).  TRE 512 limits the types of disclosure that rise to the
level of a waiver, and it states that a claim of privilege is not defeated by a disclosure which was
compelled erroneously or made without opportunity to claim the privilege.

<P> Inherent in these rules and  in  many  of  the cases addressing waiver are actions which
undermine the  confidentiality  of a communication.  For example, in <U>Eloise Bauer and
</U><U>Associates, Inc. v. Electronic Realty Associates, </U><U>Inc.</U>, 621 S.W.2d 200,
204 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1981, writ ref'd n.r.e.), the court held that voluntary production of a
document during discovery resulted in a waiver of the privilege (i.e., the privilege could not be
claimed later or the disclosure reneged).  Similarly, in <U>Axelson, Inc. v.
</U><U>McIlhany</U>, 798 S.W. 2d at 553-54, the court held that any privilege which might
have attached to an investigative report was waived since there was evidence that the report had
been disclosed to the FBI, IRS and the <U>Wall Street Journal</U>.  Note alsothat once a claim
of privilege is made, if subsequent disclosure occurs and questions as to a waiver of the privilege
arise the burden will be on the party asserting the privilege to show that no waiver has occurred.
<I> See</I> <U>Jordan v. Court of </U><U>Appeals for the Fourth Supreme Judicial
District</U>, 701 S.W.2d 644, 649 (Tex. 1985, orig. proceeding).

<P> The attorney-client privilege may also be waived through the &quot;offensive&quot; use of
the privilege.  In essence, this addresses situations where the party seeking affirmative relief tries
to protect documents or communications related to the relief requested. The theory underlying
the offensive use rule is that a party who is seeking affirmative relief should not be permitted to
maintain the action and at the same time maintain evidentiary privileges that protect from
discovery outcome determinative information not available to the other party.  <U>Public Safety
Officers Assoc. v. </U><U>Denton</U>, 897 S.W.2d 757, 761, (Tex. 1995).  The Texas
Supreme Court identified the factors to consider in determining whether a waiver of the privilege
has occurred as a result of its offensive use in <U>Republic Insurance Co. v. Davis</U>, 856
S.W.2d 158, 163 (Tex. 1993) where the court specified that: (i) before a waiver may be found the
party asserting the privilege must seek affirmative relief; (ii) the privileged information sought
must be such that, if believed by the fact finder, it would in all probability be outcome
determinative; and (iii) disclosure of the confidential communication must be the only means by
which the aggrieved party may obtain the evidence.  All three factors must be present for a
waiver to have occurred.  <U>Transamerican Natural </U><U>Gas Corp. v. Flores</U>, 870
S.W.2d 10, 11-12 (Tex. 1994).

<P> In administrative proceedings prehearing orders issued by a hearings officer may prescribe
the procedures by which the attorney/client privilege is to be asserted.  Counsel should be aware
of these procedures and should follow them strictly, for it has been held that failure to follow
specific procedures can result in a waiver of the privilege.  <U>Freeman v. Vianchi</U>, 820
S.W.2d 853, 858-59 (Tex.App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1991, orig. proceeding) (finding no privilege
with respect todocuments which were not segregated and produced for an <I>in camera</I>
inspection in accordance with the standards set forth in <U>Peeples </U><U>v. Honorable
Fourth Supreme Judicial District</U>, 701 S.W.2d 635 (Tex. 1985) (orig. proceeding) and later
codified, with minor changes, in Tex. R. Civ. P. 166b(4)).  Whether referred to as waiver or
simple failure to invoke the privilege, failure to follow specified procedures can have serious
consequences.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>2. </B><B>Attorney Work Product.</B>

<P> While the attorney/client privilege provides protection for communications between an
attorney and their client, the exemption from discovery for attorney work product is generally
thought to cover a broader range of materials.  <I>See</I> <U>Bearden </U><U>v. Boone</U>,
693 S. W. 2d at 28.  The exemption is embodied in Tex. R. Civ. P. 166b(3)(a), and has been held
to protect from disclosure all documents, reports, communications, memoranda, mental
impressions, conclusions, opinions, or legal theories prepared and assembled by an attorney in
anticipation of litigation or for trial.  <U>Toyota Motor </U><U>Sales, U.S.A., Inc. v.
Heard</U>, 774 S.W.2d 316, 317 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1989, mand. denied).  Note
that the privilege extends not only to documents the attorney generates, but also to memoranda,
reports, notes or summaries of interviews, etc., prepared by other persons for an attorney&#146;s
use.  <U>Marathon Oil Co. v. Moye</U>, 893 S.W.2d at 589.  In <U>National Union Fire
Insurance </U><U>Company v. Valdez</U>, 863 S.W.2d 458 (Tex. 1993) the Texas Supreme
Court held that an attorney's litigation file goes to the heart of the privileged work area
guaranteed by the work product exemption, and that the organization of the file, as well as what
is in it, necessarily reveals the attorney's thought processes.  Thus, even documents not subject to
any individual privilege may be protected because disclosure could reveal the attorney's mental
impressions, strategy, etc.

<P> The Texas Supreme Court's decision in <U>National Tank Co. v. Brotherton</U>, 851
S.W.2d at 202, addressed several attorney work product issues and confirmed that the
&quot;privilege&quot; is available only for those documents prepared &quot;in anticipation of
litigation.&quot;  With respect toinvestigative documents, the court held that they are to be
considered as prepared in anticipation of litigation if: (a) a reasonable person would have
concluded from the totality of the circumstances surrounding the investigation that there was a
substantial chance that litigation would ensue; and (b) the party resisting discovery believed in
good faith that there was a substantial chance that litigation would ensue and conducted the
investigation for the purpose of preparing for such litigation.  <U>Id</U>. at 195, 203-204. 
Much of the controversy which has arisen over the work product doctrine has centered on the
&quot;in anticipation of litigation&quot; standard.  With the court's decision in <U>National
Tank Co. v. </U><U>Brotherton</U>, some of that uncertainty should be resolved.  

<P> Finally, issues sometimes arise as to the continuing availability of the work product
privilege in proceedings other than that for which the documents were originally prepared.  In
other words, does the work product privilege continue once the specific proceeding that caused
the work product to be generated has ended?  The simple answer is that the privilege continues. 
As the Texas Supreme Court noted in <U>Humphreys v. </U><U>Caldwell</U>, 888 S.W. 2d
at 471, &quot;it is irrelevant that many of these documents were prepared in connection with the
suit between [other parties] rather than the underlying suit since the work product privilege is of
continuing duration.&quot; (citing <U>Owens-Corning Fiberglas Corp. v.
</U><U>Caldwell</U>, 818 S.W.2d 749, 751-52 (Tex. 1991). Thus, the privilege does not end
when the proceeding ends.  

<P><B>3. </B><B>Trade Secrets.</B>

<P> Although not nearly as common as disputes over the attorney/client privilege or the
exemption from discovery for attorney work product, questions concerning disclosure of trade
secrets can arise in administrative proceedings.  For evidentiary purposes this issue is addressed
by TRE 507, which provides generally that there is a privilege from disclosing a trade secret if
the allowance of the privilege will not tend to conceal fraud or otherwise work injustice.  The
rule further provides that when disclosure is directed, suchprotective measures shall be taken as
the interest of the holder of the privilege and of the parties and the furtherance of  justice may
require.  <U>Id</U>. Note that the burden is on the party asserting the privilege to prove its
existence, and that proof should go beyond mere conclusory statements in an affidavit. 
<U>Humphreys v. Caldwell</U>, 888 S.W.2d at 470.
<A NAME="E7E361"></A>
<P> A trade secret has been defined as &quot;any formula, pattern, device or compilation of
information which is used in one's business, and which gives him an opportunity to obtain an
advantage over competitors who do not know or use it.  It may be a formula for a chemical
compound, a process of manufacturing, treating or preserving materials, a pattern for a machine
or other device, or a list of customers.&quot;  <U>American </U><U>Precision Vibrator
Company v. National Air </U><U>Vibrator Company</U>, 764 S.W.2d 274, 276 (Tex. Civ.
App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1988, no writ), quoting from 4 <U>Restatement of Torts</U> &#167;
757, Comment b (1939), cited with approval in <U>Hyde </U><U>Corp. v. Huffines</U>, 314
S.W.2d 763, 776 (Tex. 1958).  In order to be considered a trade secret there must be a substantial
element of secrecy, and courts have refused to give trade secret protection when the material or
procedure sought to be protected has been publicly disclosed.  <U>Gonzales v.
</U><U>Zamora</U>, 791 S.W.2d 258, 264 (Tex.App.--Corpus Christi 1990, no writ);
<U>Rimes v. Club Corporation </U><U>of America</U>, 542 S.W.2d 909, 913 (Tex. Civ.
App.--Dallas 1976, writ ref'd n.r.e.)  A public disclosure of trade secrets should not be required
except in such instances and to such extent as may appear to be indispensable for the
ascertainment of truth.  <U>Automatic Drilling Machines, Inc. v. Miller</U>, 515 S.W.2d 256,
259 (Tex. 1974).  When a question of trade secret protection arises in administrative proceedings,
it is typical for a protective order to be entered where parties to the proceeding are given access
to the material but are restricted in their ability to relate it to third parties. In many instances the
rules of the particular agency will authorize the issuance of a protective order.  Counsel should
consult those rules to determine what the scope of such orders may be, and should seek the
opportunity to comment on the terms of an order before it is adopted by the examiner for use in a
particular proceeding.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>G. </B><B>Cross Examination (TRE 611, 612; APA </B><B>&#167;</B><B>
</B><B>2001.087; SOAH Rule </B><B>&#167;</B><B>155.37).</B>

<P> Cross examination has been called the greatest tool to arrive at the truth.  <U>Minnesota
</U><U>Mining &amp; Manufacturing v. Nishika, Ltd.</U>, 885 S.W.2d at 631.  Article VI of
the TRE is devoted entirely to rules regarding witnesses and cross examination, and while many
of the rules deal with issues not typically encountered in most administrative proceedings (such
as competency of witnesses to testify, admissibility of testimony regarding religious beliefs,
etc.), three of the rules (TRE 611, 612 and 613) can be important for both practitioners and
hearings officers.

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. </B><B>The Scope Of, and Control Over, Cross
</B><B>Examination.</B>

<P> TRE 611 grants a court the authority to exercise reasonable control over &quot;the mode
and order of interrogating witnesses and presenting evidence.&quot; [. The purpose of the
control is to: (1) make the interrogation and presentation effective for the ascertainment of the
truth; (2) avoid needless consumption of time; and (3) protect witnesses from harassment or
undue embarrassment.  TRE 611(a).  ]   <U>Great Global Assurance Company v.
</U><U>Keltex Properties,</U> <U>Inc</U>., 905 S.W.2d 771, 777 (Tex. App.--Corpus
Christi 1995, n.w.h.).  TRE 611 also embodies the traditional Texas rule of &quot;wide-open
cross examination&quot;; that is, that cross examination may occur on any matter relevant to any
issue in the case.  TRE 611 (b); <U>Harrison v. </U><U>Texas Employers Insurance
Association</U>, 747 S.W.2d 494, 498 (Tex.App.--Beaumont 1988, writ denied).  As the court
stated in <U>Hogue v. Kroger </U><U>Store No. 107</U>, 875 S.W.2d 477, 480 (Tex.
App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1994, writ denied), the allowed scope of cross examination is broad
and wide ranging and, because it extends to any matter relevant to the issues, permits inquiring
into a witness&#146; interest, bias, motives, inclinations and prejudices.  The APA reflects this
same concept in &#167; 2001.087, which authorizes parties in contested cases to conduct cross
examination &quot;required for a full and true disclosure of the facts&quot;.  This broad scope
of cross examination is contrary to Fed. R. Evid. 611(b) and the rules of a majority of states,
which limit cross examination to the subject matter of the witness' direct testimony. [. Thomas
Black and Cathleen C. Herasimchuk, Texas Rules of Evidence Handbook (Part II); Article VI:
Witnesses ,  30 Hous. L. Rev. 673, 754 (1993).]   Finally, TRE 611(c) sets forth the general rule
governing the use of leading questions; that is, that leading questions should not be used in direct
examination but&quot;ordinarily&quot; should be permitted on cross examination.  TRE 611(c).

<P> Cross examination is a valuable right and it is error to restrict it so as to prevent the
cross-examining party from going fully into all matters connected with the examination in chief. 
<U>Minns v. </U><U>Piotrowski</U>, 904 S.W.2d 161, 171. (Tex. App.--Waco 1995) writ
denied per curiam, 917 S.W.2d. 796 (Tex. 1996).   There is no question that the right to cross
examine witnesses is as fundamental in administrative hearings as it is in other litigation.  In
<U>J.B. Advertising v. Sign Board of </U><U>Appeals</U>, 883 S.W.2d 443, 449 (Tex.
App.--Eastland, writ denied) the court succinctly compiled relevant authority in addressing this
issue in the following passage:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>A fair opportunity for the parties to prove their respective cases is
essential to an administrative hearing comporting with due process.  <U>Lewis v.
</U><U>Metropolitan Savings &amp; Loan Assoc.</U>, 550 S.W.2d 11 (Tex. 1977).  In
<U>Richardson v. City of Pasadena</U>, 513 S.W.2d 1 (Tex. 1974), the Supreme Court stated:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The right to cross examination is a vital element in a fair adjudication of
disputed facts. The right to cross examine averse witnesses and to examine and rebut all evidence
is not confined to court trials, but applies also to administrative hearings.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> While TRE 611(a) grants presiding officers the ability to control the conduct of proceedings,
that control must be exercised reasonably and in a manner which gives a party a fair opportunity
to present its case.  <U>Prezelski v. Christiansen</U>, 775 S.W.2d 764, 766 (fn. 2) (Tex.
App.--San Antonio 1989), rev&#146;d on other grounds per curiam, 782 S.W.2d 842 (Tex.
1990); <I>see also</I> <U>Metzger v. </U><U>Sebek</U>, 892 S.W.2d 20, 38 (Tex.
App.--Houston [1st Dist.) 1994, writ denied) (courts are afforded broad, but not unfettered,
discretion in handling trials).  Consider, for example, the decision in<U>Sims v. Bracket</U>,
885 S.W.2d at 450.  That case involved a medical malpractice claim by a single plaintiff against
multiple defendants.  The trial judge became frustrated with the pace of the trial because cross
examination of witnesses had been lengthy and was frequently interrupted by motions and
objections.  As a consequence, the judge precluded the parties from conducting any re-direct
and/or re-cross examination of witnesses. Furthermore, when a defense witness was presented,
the judge allowed the other defendants to cross examine <I>after</I> the plaintiff.  <U>Id.</U>
at 452. The appellate court noted that some decisions have suggested that redirect examination is
a matter of right.  <U>Id</U>. at 455, citing <U>Southland Life Ins. Co. v.
</U><U>Norwood</U>, 76 S.W.2d 166, 167-68 (Tex. Civ. App.--Ft. Worth 1930, writ
dism&#146;d).  The court further held that the actions taken to control procedures in this case,
coupled with the wrongful exclusion of evidence, denied the plaintiffs&#146; due process rights
to such an extent that the trial court&#146;s judgment was reversed and remanded.

<P>     Issues of the type addressed by TRE 611 often arise in multi-party administrative
proceedings. When there are multiple parties there can be alliances which can vary among issues
in the case. As a result there is frequently debate over the proper order in which to conduct cross
examination.  The concern is that parties more closely aligned with the position to be espoused
by a particular witness should not be allowed to cross-examine after parties more adverse to that
witness.  This is because the &quot;friendly&quot; parties will then have an opportunity to
rehabilitate the witness from whatever damage was done on prior cross examination.  To combat
this problem hearings examiners will often try to determine an order of cross examination (which
is within their power to do under TRE 611(a)) where more adverse parties cross examine after
those parties more closely aligned with the position of the witness.  Another common occurrence
is for parties with similar interests to be &quot;grouped,&quot; so that their participation in a
hearing (or parts thereof) occurs through one common representative.

<P>     A similar concern arises with respect to the use of leading questions and
&quot;friendly&quot; cross examination.  Leading questions have been definedas ones which
support the desired answer, and questions which instruct the witness how to answer or put words
into the witness' mouth to be echoed back.  <U>GAB Business Services, Inc. v. Moore</U>, 829
S.W.2d 345, 351 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1992, no writ);  <U>Implement Dealers Mutual
Insurance </U><U>Company v. Castleberry</U>, 368 S.W.2d 249, 253 (Tex. Civ.
App.--Beaumont 1963, writ ref'd n.r.e.).  Again, the concern is that parties aligned with the
position of a witness will use leading questions to elicit what is essentially direct testimony even
though it occurs under the technical guise of cross examination.  TRE 611(c) addresses this by
noting that &quot;ordinarily&quot; leading questions are permitted on cross examination.  The
comments to that rule make clear that the qualification is intended to provide a basis for denying
the use of leading questions during &quot;friendly&quot; cross examination (i.e. cross
examination of a witness in agreement with the examining party's position.)  <U>Cecil v. T.M.E.
</U><U>Investments, Inc.</U>, 893 S.W.2d 38, 47 (Tex. App.--Corpus Christi 1994).  In
<U>GAB v. Moore</U> 829 S.W.2d at 351, the court denied, based on TRE 611(c) and the
comments thereto, admission of the deposition testimony of a &quot;friendly&quot; witness
elicited through leading questions.  Thus, hearings examiners in administrative proceedings can
restrict the use of leading questions under TRE 611.

<P> Another issue that can arise in administrative proceedings is that of scheduling, or order, of
witnesses.  Because proceedings can go forward at an unpredictable pace, it is common to
encounter scheduling conflicts for witnesses.  While this is typically addressed by simply taking
that witness out of order (i.e. either before or after they would normally have testified), even this
can present problems.  For example, <U>Wal-Mart Stores, Inc. v. </U><U>Cordova</U>, 856
S.W.2d 768 (Tex.App.--El Paso 1993 writ denied) was a &quot;slip and fall&quot; case in which
the trial judge allowed an expert for the plaintiff to testify out of order.  One aspect of the expert's
testimony concerned Wal-Mart's net worth, which is only supposed to be allowed in civil cases
after the establishment of a prima facie case of gross negligence.  The defense objected to this
testimony, and the plaintiff responded that the objection was &quot;moot&quot; because it
would meet itsburden and make the prima facie  showing later. <U>Id</U>. at 773.  The trial
court allowed the testimony. The appeals court reversed, and noted that while a decision to allow
a witness to testify out of order is discretionary under TRE 611(a), it can be reversed if there is a
clear showing of abuse of discretion.  <U>Id</U>.  An abuse of discretion exists if the trial court
acted without reference to any guiding rules and principles or if the act complained of was
arbitrary or unreasonable.  <U>Id</U>.  In this instance the court held that allowing the
&quot;net worth&quot; testimony so early in the hearing (and prior to establishment of a prima
facie case of gross negligence) likely prejudiced the remainder of the case, and therefore was an
abuse of discretion.  So while it is common to juggle the order of presentation of witnesses to
accommodate scheduling conflicts, thought should be given as to the impact that may have on
subsequent presentation of the issues.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>2. </B><B>Writings Used to Refresh a Witness' </B><B>Memory.</B>

<P>     It is not unusual for witnesses, in the course of preparing for a proceeding or even while
testifying, to review written documents in order to &quot;refresh&quot; their memory. 
Questions may arise as to whether opposing parties have a right to compel production of those
documents and use those in the course of a hearing.  TRE 612 addresses the issue, and provides
as follows:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P> If a witness uses a writing to refresh his memory for the purpose of
testifying either --
<OL>
<P> <LI> while testifying, or

<P> <LI> before testifying, if the court in its discretion determines that it is necessary in the
interests of justice,
</OL>
<P>an adverse party is entitled to have the writing produced at the hearing, to inspect it, to cross
examine the witness thereon, and introduce in evidence those portions which relate to the
testimony of the witness.  If it is claimed that thewriting contains matters not related to the
subject matter of the testimony the court shall examine the writing <I>in </I><I>camera</I>,
excise any portion not so related, and order delivery of the remainder to the party entitled thereto.
Any portion withheld over objections shall be preserved and made available to the appellate
court in the event of an appeal.  If a writing is not produced or delivered pursuant to order under
this rule, the court shall make any order justice requires.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> This rule sets out the principles governing two scenarios:  (1) where a witness refers to a
document <I>while testifying</I>; and (2) where a witness reviews documents <I>before
testifying</I>.

<P> With respect to the first situation (where a witness refers to documents while testifying), the
rule is clear.  The documents must be produced, and the trier of fact has no discretion in
determining whether an adverse party is entitled to inspect the documents at issue.  The
implications of this rule may best be illustrated by the decision in <U>City of Dennison v.
Grisham</U>, 716 S.W.2d 121, 123 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1986, no writ), where a witness, while
testifying at a deposition, examined notes prepared by himself <I>and his attorney</I>.
Opposing counsel requested the documents, but that request was refused on the grounds that they
constituted attorney work product.  The court held that the use of a writing to refresh the memory
of a witness <I>while</I> he is testifying waives both the attorney-client privilege and work
product protection of the document.  <U>Id</U>.  The lesson of this case for practitioners is
clear:  never let one of your witnesses review documents, while testifying, that you believe are
privileged or otherwise protected from disclosure.  Note that this rule applies to testimony given
during a deposition as well as while testifying at trial or in the course of a contested case
proceeding.

<P> With respect to documents reviewed in advance of a witness' testimony, it is within a court's
discretion whether or not to require the production of the documents relied upon.  <I>See</I>
<U>Portland Savings &amp; Loan Asso. v. Bernstein</U>, 716S.W.2d 532, 541 (Tex. Civ.
App.--Corpus Christi 1985, writ ref'd n.r.e.), cert. denied, 475 U.S. 1016 (1986).  In a federal
court proceeding where a witness had used notes and a deposition summary to refresh his
recollection while preparing to testify, the Fifth Circuit held that the trial judge had not erred in
denying an opposing party access to the documents <I>even though</I> the witness had the
notes on the witness stand.  <U>Cosden Oil v. Karl O. Helm </U><U>Aktiengesellschaft</U>,
736 F.2d 1064, 1076-77 (5th Cir. 1984).  The trial judge indicated that she had not seen the
witness refer to the notes while testifying so that disclosure was not mandatory, and the
&quot;interests of justice&quot; did not require her to order disclosure, which was within her
discretion to do.  <U>Id</U>.  This illustrates that the &quot;in the interest of justice&quot;
standard embodied in the rule will require a case-by-case determination with respect to
documents reviewed by a witness prior to testifying.

<P><B>3. </B><B> </B><B>Prior Statements of Witnesses -</B><B>Impeachment.</B>

<P> One of the most effective tools in cross examination is the impeachment of an opposing
party&#146;s witness.  Impeachment has been defined as adducing proof that a witness is
unworthy of belief or credit.  <U>Willingham v. State</U>, 897 S.W.2d 351, 358 (Tex.Crim.
App., 1995).  Typically, this involves confronting a witness with prior oral or written statements
which are inconsistent with their current testimony or which show interest or bias on the part of
the witness.

<P> Impeachment is governed by TRE 613.  Note that despite <I>similar</I> purposes, the
process for impeachment is different than that for using admissions of a party opponent under
TRE 801(e)(2).  When impeaching a witness under TRE 613, the prior inconsistent statements of
a witness are not admissible for the truth of the matters previously asserted, whereas admissions
under TRE 801(e)(2) will not be considered hearsay and may be admitted without a limited use. 
<U>Pope v. </U><U>Stephenson</U>, 774 S.W. 2d 743, 745 (Tex.App.--El Paso 1989, writ
denied per curiam 787 S.W.2d 953 (Tex. 1990).  This distinction explains the more strict
requirements under which a priorinconsistent statement must have been made in order to be
admissible (as nonhearsay) under TRE 801(e)(2).  

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>a.  Impeachment with Prior Inconsistent </B><B>Statements.</B>

<P> Impeachment with prior inconsistent statements is governed by TRE 613(a).  A prior
statement may be oral or written, and it need not have been given under oath.  However, before
cross examining a witness about a prior statement the proper foundation must be established. 
This includes establishing where, when and to whom the prior statement was made, and the
witness must be allowed to admit or deny making the prior statement.  <U>Downen v. Texas
Gulf Shrimp Co</U>., 846 S.W.2d 506, 512 (Tex. App.--Corpus Christi, 1993, writ denied).  If
the witness <I>unequivocally </I>admits having made the prior statement, the impeachment is
considered complete and extrinsic evidence of the statement will not be admitted. TRE 613(a). 
If, however, the witness fails to unequivocally admit making the statement, the evidence of the
prior statement should be admissible.  <U>Ramsey v. Lucky Stores, Inc.</U>, 853 S.W.2d 623,
637 (Tex. App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1993, writ denied).  If the prior statement is in writing it
need not be shown to the witness but it must be shown to opposing counsel if requested.  

<P><B>b. </B><B> </B><B>Impeachment Based on Bias or Interest</B><B>.</B>  

<P> The rules governing impeachment based on the bias or interest of a witness are generally the
same as those concerning prior inconsistent statements.  TRE 613(b) requires that when
impeaching a witness &quot;by proof of circumstances or statements showing bias or
interest&quot;, the circumstances supporting the claim or the details of the statement (including
where, when and to whom made) must be made known to the witness and the witness must be
given an opportunity to explain or deny the circumstances or statements prior to further cross
examination.  If the witness unequivocally admits their bias or interest, extrinsic evidence is not
admissible.  TRE 613(b). If the witness fails to unequivocally admit their bias or interest, the
extrinsic evidence thereof willbe admissible for that purpose.  <U>Walker v. Packer</U>, 827
S.W.2d 833, 839 (fn. 5)(Tex. 1992).  Note that there is  a distinction between unequivocally
admitting a bias or interest and unequivocally admitting the facts or circumstances which suggest
the existence of the bias or interest.  The rule, by its terms, contemplates admission of the
existence of the bias or interest, and anything less than that will likely justify admission of the
extrinsic evidence of bias or interest.  <I>See </I><U>Penwall v. </U><U>Barrett</U>, 724
S.W.2d 902, 907 (Tex.App.--San Antonio 1987, no writ).  
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>H. </B><B>Expert Testimony (TRE 702, 703, 705).</B>

<P> Administrative proceedings can be highly technical in nature and often rely extensively on
the use of expert testimony.  Issues frequently arise as to whether witnesses are properly
qualified to offer such testimony and whether a particular fact setting is appropriate for expert
testimony. Questions may also be raised concerning acceptable bases for expert opinions and
whether those bases may, or must, be disclosed when the expert testifies.  Finally, evidence of a
scientific nature may present particular difficulties because of reliability concerns.  These issues
are addressed in TRE 702, 703 and 705, each of which is discussed below.

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. </B><B>Qualifications of Experts and Effect of </B><B>Expert
Testimony.</B>

<P> TRE 702 sets forth the principles governing when expert testimony is appropriate and who
is qualified to give it.  That rule provides:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>If scientific, technical or other specialized knowledge will assist the trier
of fact to understand the evidence or to determine a fact in issue, a witness qualified as an expert
by knowledge, skill, experience, training or education, may testify thereto in the form of an
opinion or otherwise.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>a. </B><B>Expert Testimony Defined.</B>

<P> TRE 702 generally defines expert testimony as testimony which, if involving
scientific,technical or other specialized knowledge, will assist the trier of fact to understand the
issues at hand.  One court has described it as the testimony of persons who are particularly
skilled, learned, or experienced in a particular art or science, trade, business, profession or
vocation, a thorough knowledge of which is not possessed, in regards to matters connected
therewith, by persons in general. <U>Swearingen v. Swearingen</U>, 578 S.W.2d 829, 832
(Tex. Civ. App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1979, writ dism'd).    Incompetent opinion testimony is no
evidence at all, and mere fact witnesses cannot testify to matters that will require them to give
expert opinions.  <U>Id</U>; <U>Baylor Medical Plaza </U><U>Services v. Kidd</U>, 834
S.W.2d 69, 74 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1992, writ denied).  Opinions which are purely speculative
or conjectural in nature should be excluded.  <U>UMC, Inc. v. Coonrod Elec. Co.,
</U><U>Inc.</U>, 667 S.W.2d 549, 559 (Tex. App.--Corpus Christi 1983, writ ref&#146;d
n.r.e.).

<P> TRE 702 and its definition of expert testimony effectively embodies two requirements.
First, the testimony must be of a type for which scientific, technical or other specialized
knowledge will assist the trier of fact.  Expert opinions are received in evidence based on the
theory that the expert, by reason of study or experience, has a special knowledge which the trier
of fact generally does not possess, and the expert is therefore better able to draw conclusions
from the facts.  <I>See</I> <U>Glasscock v. Income Property Services, Inc.</U>, 888 S.W.2d
176, 180 (Tex. App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1994, dism.agr.); <U>Evin v. Gulf States, Inc.</U>,
594 S.W.2d 134, 137 (Tex. Civ. App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1979, writ ref'd n.r.e.).
<A NAME="E7E433"></A>
<P> Second, expert testimony must come from a source qualified to give it.  In order for an
expert's testimony to be competent (i.e., to have any evidentiary value), it must be shown that the
expert is trained in the science about which they testify (or that they have knowledge of the fact
issue in question).  <U>Missouri Pacific Railroad Co. </U><U>v. Buenrostro</U>, 853 S.W.2d
66, 77 (Tex.App.--San Antonio 1993, writ denied).  It is not necessary for an expert to be a
specialist in a particular branch of a field as long as the expert has knowledge and skills which
are not possessed by people in general.  <U>Potter v. Anthony Crane Rental of Texas</U>,896
S.W.2d 845, 851 (Tex. App.--Beaumont 1995, n.w.h.)  Specific issues concerning qualifications
of experts are addressed in more detail below.

<P><B>b. </B><B>Qualifications for Experts.</B>

<P> There are no definitive guidelines for determining the knowledge, skill or experience
required of a witness to qualify as an expert; that determination is within the trial court's
discretion, and the court's decision will not be disturbed absent a clear abuse of that discretion. 
<U>E.I. Du </U><U>Pont de Nemours and Co. v. Robinson</U>, 923 S.W.2d 549, 558 (Tex.
1995); <U>In the Interest of </U><U>A.V.</U>, 849 S.W.2d at 396-97; <U>Celotex Corp. v.
</U><U>Tate</U>, 797 S.W.2d at 201.  It is the offering party's burden to establish that an
expert is qualified, and admissibility of the expert's opinion will depend primarily on whether or
not the expert has special knowledge in the area of their testimony which can assist the trier of
fact.  <U>James v. Hudgins</U>, 876 S.W.2d 418, 421 (Tex.App.--El Paso 1994, writ denied)
(offering party's burden may only be met by showing that the expert is trained in the science of
which he or she testifies or has knowledge of the subject matter of the fact in question);
<U>Warner </U><U>v. Hurt</U>, 834 S.W.2d 404, 406 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1992,
no writ).  Furthermore, an expert, in stating his or her opinion, must be restricted to their
particular field of expertise. <U>Missouri Pacific v. Buenrostro</U>, 853 S.W.2d at 77 (citing
<U>Adamson v. Burgle</U>, 186 S.W.2d 388, 397 (Tex. Civ. App.--San Antonio 1945, writ
ref'd)).

<P> The Texas Supreme Court recently addressed the issue of expert qualifications in
<U>Broder v. </U><U>Heise</U>, 924 S.W. 2d 148 (Tex. 1996), where a unanimous court held
that expert qualifications must be assessed with regard to the specific issued being addressed.  In
<U>Broder</U> a woman who had been attacked by an unknown assailant was brought to a
Dallas hospital at 9:30 p.m. in the evening.  Although she experienced a desire not to be treated
and to leave the hospital, Dr. Broder, the attending physician, requested that a security guard
ensure that she not leave.  She stayed through the night, and though vomiting twice and
complaining of a headache, she slept relatively soundly.  The next morning she allowed the new
doctor on duty to examine her.  After notingminor injuries and a headache he attributed to a
hangover, the new doctor released the woman. Later that same evening she was brought back to
the hospital where certain narcotics were prescribed to combat her intensified symptoms (intense
headache and vomiting).  A neurosurgeon&#146;s review of a CT scan revealed a fractured
skull.  The woman died the next morning.

<P> Her parents filed a wrongful death suit alleging negligence in failing to diagnose and
properly treat their daughter.  They sought to qualify their expert witness by proving that he was
a licensed doctor and that he had previously practiced emergency medicine.  Although he was
allowed to testify on certain issues, the trial court excluded his testimony concerning the
likelihood of survival had the initial treatment been different and that, but for negligence, the
woman would have survived.  The court of appeals reversed the trial court decision in this
regard, finding that the doctor was qualified to give the excluded opinions because he possessed
knowledge and skill not possessed by people generally.

<P> The Texas Supreme Court reversed the court appeals decision.  The court noted that
qualification of an expert is within a trial court&#146;s discretion (citing <U>Robinson</U>,
923 S.W. 2d at 558) and that the party offering the testimony bears the burden of proving
qualification under TRE 702. <U>Id</U>.  at 151.  Focusing on the TRE 702, the court noted
that the possession of knowledge and skill not possessed by people generally does not, in and of
itself, mean that such expertise will assist the trier of fact regarding the issue before the court.
<U>Id</U>.  at 153.  In this instance the plaintiffs&#146; did not establish that their
doctor&#146;s medical expertise qualified him, under TRE 702 to testify as to &quot;cause in
fact&quot;. <U>Id</U>.

<P> The <U>Broder</U> opinion clearly emphasizes the need to prove  qualification of an
expert as to the specific subject matter before the court.  The test articulated by the court is that:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>What is required is that the offering party establish that the expert has
&quot;knowledge, skill, experience, trainingor education&quot; regarding the specific issue
before the court which would qualify the expert to give an opinion on that particular subject. 
And when a party can show that a subject is substantially developed in more than one field,
testimony can come from a qualified expert in any of these fields.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><U>Id</U>. at 153-54; (cites omitted).  This decision is not particularly surprising given the
<U>Robinson</U> decision and the court&#146;s concern expressed therein over abuses in the
&quot;business&quot; of providing expert testimony.

<P> Note that it is possible for practical experience to be an acceptable way of gaining expertise
so as to qualify one as an expert.  <U>See</U> <U>Walter Baxter Seed Co. v. Rivera</U>, 677
S.W.2d 241, 244 (Tex.App.--Corpus Christi 1984, writ ref'd n.r.e.).  For example, in <U>Petrolia
Insurance </U><U>Co. v. Everett</U>, 719 S.W.2d 639, 641 (Tex.App.--El Paso 1986, no writ)
a witness with little formal education but nine years of experience in building and repairing
swimming pools was allowed to testify concerning the cause of damage to the &quot;cool
deck&quot; around a pool.  A minimum level of formal education was not required, a fact which
is reflected in the text of the rule itself (which specifically identifies &quot;experience&quot; as
one of the possible qualifying factors for an expert witness). Experience will not <I>always</I>
suffice, however, as at least two courts have held that a witness who is to testify concerning the
standard of care in a licensed profession must be licensed in that same profession.  <U>Parkway
Co. v. Woodruff</U>, 857 S.W.2d 903, 919 (Tex.App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1993, aff&#146;d
901 S.W.2d 434 (Tex. 1995); <U>Prellwitz </U><U>v. Cromwell, Truemper, Levy, Porbar and
</U><U>Woodsmale</U>, 802 S.W.2d 316, 317-18 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1990, no writ) (expert
testimony of witnesses who were not licensed as architects and mechanical engineers on proper
standard of care related to those fields was excluded).  Note that there is a distinction between
&quot;standard of care&quot; testimony and other types.  In <U>Ponder v. </U><U>Texarkana
Memorial Hospital, Inc.</U>, 840 S.W.2d 476, 478 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1991, writ
denied) the court of appeals found that a Ph.D. in neuroscience was not competent to testifyas to
the proper standard of care for a doctor (since he himself was not an M.D.), but he was
competent to testify concerning causation with respect to brain damage.  The court noted that
&quot;non-physicians may qualify as medical experts by virtue of special experience.&quot; 
<U>Id</U>.

<P> This principle was also applied in <U>Harris </U><U>County Hospital Dist. v.
Estrada</U>, 872 S.W.2d, 759, 762 (Tex. App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1993, writ denied), where
the court noted that a nonphysician nurse, &quot;even one who is not a registered nurse but is
familiar with the standard of care at another similar hospital,&quot; can qualify by experience to
testify as a medical expert in a medical malpractice action.  In that case familiarity with the
standard of care at another similar hospital was all that was required.  <U>Id</U>.  As a practical
matter, when disputes arise to the qualifications of an expert to testify on a particular subject, the
ruling will often be that the adequacy of the qualifications goes to the weight of the testimony
itself.

<P><B>c. </B><B>Effect of Expert Testimony.</B>

<P> In administrative hearings an agency is not compelled to accept the testimony of a witness
just because they are an &quot;expert&quot;.  <U>See</U> <U>Public Utility
</U><U>Commission v. Houston Lighting &amp; Power</U>, 715 S.W.2d 98, 109
(Tex.App.--Austin 1986), aff'd in part, rev'd in part (on other grounds), 748 S.W.2d 439 (Tex.
1987); appeal dism'd 109 S.Ct. 36 (1988)).  It is within the sole province of the trier of fact who
has the opportunity to observe the demeanor of the witness on the stand to judge their credibility,
to weigh their given testimony, to resolve conflicts in the testimony of one witness with the
testimony of another witness, and to believe part of a witness&#146; testimony and disregard
other portions thereof.  <U>American Motorists </U><U>Insurance Co. v. Volentine</U>, 867
S.W.2d 170, 174 (Tex. App.--Beaumont 1993, no writ).  In other words, a determination of the
credibility of a witness is up to the exclusive province of an agency, and the agency has the
authority to accept or reject all or part of any expert testimony.  <U>City </U><U>of El Paso v.
Public Utility Commission</U>, 839 S.W.2d 895, 906 (Tex.App.--Austin 1992), aff'd in part,
rev'd in part 883 S.W.2d 179 (Tex. 1994);<U>Texas State Board of Dental Examiners v.
Silag</U>, 766 S.W.2d 280, 283 (Tex.App.--El Paso 1989, error denied).   Furthermore, the
opinion testimony of an expert witness does not establish any material fact as a matter of law,
and the mere qualification of a witness as an expert does not preclude the fact finder from
exercising considerable judgment of its own regarding the reliance on opinion testimony. 
<U>Id</U>., <U>Field </U><U>Distributors, Inc. v. Railroad Comm. of Texas</U>, 727
S.W.2d 56, 61 (Tex.App.--Austin 1987, writ ref'd n.r.e.).   Note also that the members of an
agency may not rely on their own expertise to make the equivalent of expert opinions in reaching
their decision; their qualifications are not placed in evidence and they are not subject to cross
examination.  <I>See</I> <U>Sizemore v. Texas State Board </U><U>of Dental
Examiners</U>, 747 S.W.2d 389 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1987) rev'd on other grounds, 759 S.W.2d
114 (Tex. 1988), cert. denied 490 U.S. 1080 (1989); <U>Dotson v. Texas State Board of Medical
</U><U>Examiners</U>, 621 S.W.2d at 923-24.  In short, the effect of expert testimony in
administrative proceedings is not binding or preclusive; it simply becomes part of the evidentiary
record upon which the hearings examiner, and ultimately the agency, must make their decisions.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>2. </B><B>Application of TRE</B><B> </B><B>702 to Expert </B><B>Scientific
Testimony.</B>

<P> In 1993 the U.S. Supreme Court issued an opinion intended to resolve a split among various
federal appeals courts as to the appropriate standard for admitting expert scientific testimony in a
federal trial.  In <U>Daubert v. Merrell Dow </U><U>Pharmaceuticals, Inc.</U>, 113 S.Ct.
2786 (1993), vacating and remanding 951 F.2d 1128 (9th Cir. 1991), the Court rejected the
application of the &quot;general acceptance&quot; test derived from <U>Frye v.
</U><U>U.S.</U>, 293 F. 1013 (D.C. Cir. 1923) in favor of a literal application of the standards
embodied in Rule 702 of the Fed. R. Civ. Evid.  Because TRE 702 and the federal rule are
identical, this foreshadowed a significant change at the state court level.

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>a. </B><B>Federal Rule 702 After </B><B><U>Daubert</U></B>.

<P> The <U>Frye</U> test rejected by the Court had been generally characterized as requiring
that expert opinions based on a scientific technique be found inadmissible unless the technique
was &quot;generally accepted&quot; as reliable in the relevant scientific community. 
<U>Daubert</U>, 113 S. Ct. at 2792.  The Court noted that this &quot;test&quot; predated the
Federal Rules of Evidence by &quot;half a century&quot;, and that nothing in Rule 702
establishes general acceptance as a prerequisite to admissibility.  <U>Id</U>. at 2794.

<P> In applying the analysis required under Rule 702, the Court in <U>Daubert</U> stated that
a trial judge must determine whether the expert is proposing to testify to (a) &quot;scientific
knowledge&quot; that (b) will assist the trier of fact to understand or determine a fact in issue. 
<U>Id</U>. at 2796.  &quot;Scientific knowledge&quot; relates to questions of evidentiary
reliability (i.e., an inference or assertion must be derived by the scientific method and proposed
testimony must be supported by appropriate validation), and assistance to the trier of fact relates
to questions of relevance.  <U>Id</U>. at 2795.  The Court characterized this analysis as
requiring:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>...a preliminary assessment of whether the reasoning or methodology
underlying the testimony is scientifically valid and of whether that reasoning or methodology
properly can be applied to the facts in issue.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><U>Id</U>. at 2796.

<P> As to the broader assessment to be undertaken by a trial court, the Court offered the
following observations:

<UL>
<P> (1) A key question to be answered in determining whether a theory or technique is scientific
knowledge that will assist the trier of fact will be whether it can be (and has been) tested. 
<U>Id</U>.

<P> (2) Another important consideration is whether the theory or technique hasbeen subjected to
peer review and publication.  <U>Id</U>. at 2797.

<P> (3) In the case of a particular scientific technique, the court ordinarily should consider the
known or potential rate of error.  <U>Id</U>.

<P> (4) Although &quot;general acceptance&quot; is not the sole source of assessing
admissibility, it can still be an important factor in ruling on admissibility, and a known technique
that has been able to attract only minimal support within the community may properly be viewed
with skepticism. <U>Id</U>., citing <U>U.S. v. Downing</U>, 753 F.2d 1224.
</UL>
<P>As the foregoing illustrates, the Supreme Court not only rejected the <U>Frye</U> test in
favor of the application of Fed. R. Civ. Evid. 702, but also set forth a general framework within
which it apparently envisioned federal courts analyzing the admissibility of scientific testimony.

<P><B>b. </B><B>TRE 702 and </B><B><U>Robinson</U></B>.

<P> The Texas Supreme Court deliver its assessment of <U>Daubert</U> and its applicability
under state law in <U>E.I. Du Pont de Nemours and Co. v. </U><U>Robinson</U>, 923 S.W.
2d at 549.  <U>Robinson</U> dealt with a claim that a fungicide manufactured by DuPont was
contaminated and had damaged the pecan orchard of C.R. and Shirley Robinson.  In support of
their claim the Robinsons offered expert testimony from a witness who opined that the DuPont
product was indeed contaminated and damaged the Robinson&#146;s orchard.  The expert based
his opinion on the following:

<UL>
<P> (1 ) an inspection of the orchard conducted at the request of the Robinson&#146;s attorney,
which, based on his observations, led him to apply a method called &quot;comparative
symptomology&quot; and to conclude from application of that methodology that the DuPont
product was contaminated;

<P> (2) an experiment he conducted on behalf of a previous claimant in a similar case;

<P> (3) laboratory analyses of ten boxes of the DuPont product (none of which was actually used
by the Robinson&#146;s in their orchard);

<P> (4) his review of reports of other plants treated with the suspected contaminants; and

<P> (5) his review of internal DuPont documents.
</UL>
<P> <U>Robinson</U> at 558-59.  The trial court excluded the testimony for several reasons
which, it concluded, undermined the data&#146;s reliability so as to preclude it from assisting
the trier of fact.  The court of appeals reversed, suggesting that the concerns raised by the trial
court properly went to the weight to be afforded the expert&#146;s testimony and the
expert&#146;s credibility as assessed by a jury.

<P> The Texas Supreme Court, in a 5-4 opinion authored by Justice Gonzales, reversed the court
of appeals and affirmed the trial court decision.  The opinion cites many of the concerns voiced
by other courts and commentators regarding the use and ready availability of
&quot;expert&quot; testimony.  The court expressly adopted <U>Daubert</U>, holding that in
addition to showing that an expert witness is qualified under TRE 702, the proponent of expert
testimony must also show that the testimony is relevant to the issues in the case and is based
upon a reliable foundation.   <U>Robinson</U> at 556.  In other words, in order to constitute
admissible scientific knowledge which will assist the trier of fact, the proposed testimony must
be relevant and reliable.

<P> The relevance analysis required under <U>Robinson</U> is no different than that currently
required under TRE 401 and 402.  As noted by the court, to be relevant the proposed testimony
must be &quot;sufficiently tied to the facts of the case that it will aid the jury in resolving a
factual dispute,&quot; <U>Id</U> at 556; citing <U>U.S.  v. Downing</U>, 753 F.2d 1224,
1242 (3rd Cir. 1985).

<P> Reliability is where the more difficult analysis lies.  The court noted the <U>Daubert</U>
standard that scientific evidence which is not grounded &quot;in the methods and procedures of
science&quot; is no more than &quot;subjective belief or unsupported speculation.&quot; 
<U>Robinson</U>, at 557; citing <U>Daubert</U>, 509 U.S. at 590.  The court also listed
several factors that should be considered  in making the threshold determination of admissibility
under TRE 702.  They are:
<UL>
<P> (1) the extent to which the theory has been or can be tested;

<P> (2) the extent to which the technique relies upon the subjective interpretation of the expert;

<P> (3) whether the theory has been subjected to peer review and/or publication;

<P> (4) the technique&#146;s potential rate of error;

<P> (5) whether the underlying theory or technique as been generally accepted as valid by the
relevant scientific community; and

<P> (6) the non-judicial uses which have been made of the theory or technique.
</UL>
<P> <U>Robinson</U> at 557.  The court emphasized that the above factors are intended to be a
nonexclusive list, and that trial courts may consider other factors which are helpful to
determining the reliability of the scientific evidence.  Indeed, the court noted that each particular
case may require different factors to be considered in determining whether the underlying
theories and techniques are scientifically reliable. Finally, the court noted that even if testimony
is determined to be relevant and reliable, an analysis still must be made under TRE 403
concerning whether the probative value of the evidence is outweighed by the &quot;danger of
unfair prejudice, confusion of the issues, or misleading the jury, or by considerations of undue
delay, or needless presentation of cumulative evidence.&quot;  <U>Id</U>.  <I>(See</I>
<I>also</I> discussion above at section III.E.).

<P> With respect to the evidence presented by the Robinson&#146;s, the court found that the
expert testimony was not based upon a reliable foundation.  The expert had conducted no testing
to exclude other possible causes of damage to the Robinson&#146;s orchard, even though he
admitted that many of the symptoms he observed could be caused by substances other than the
suspected contaminant.  As the court noted, &quot;an expert who is trying to find a cause of
something should carefully consider alternative causes.&quot;  <U>Robinson</U> at 559. 
Otherwise, his failure to rule out other causes renders his opinion little more than speculation
<U>Id</U>.  The court also criticized his opinion as, essentially, being one where he came to the
conclusion first and then did the research to support it.  Specifically, the expert had no proof that
the product used by the Robinson&#146;s was contaminated, yet he concluded from the fact that
there was damage and that the Robinson&#146;s had used the DuPont product that it must have
been contaminated.  <U>Id</U>.  The court also found fault with the fact that the expert&#146;s
research and opinions were conducted and formed for the purpose of litigation.  The court stated
that &quot;the fact an opinion was formed solely for the purposes of litigation does not
automatically render it unreliable.  However, &#145;when an expert prepares reports and
findings before being hired as a witness, that record will limit the degree go which he can tailor
his testimony to serve a party&#146;s interest&#146;.&quot;  <U>Robinson</U> at 559; citing
<U>Daubert</U>, 43 F.3d at 1311, 1317 (9th Cir. 1995) (upon remand). On the other hand
opinions formed solely for the purpose of testifying are more likely to be biased toward a
particular result. <U>Robinson</U> at 559. Finally, there was no evidence to support the
Robinson&#146;s claim that &quot;comparative symptomology&quot; is an appropriate and
reliable method to determine chemical contamination.  The method has not been subjected to
peer review or publication, nor is there evidence that it has been generally accepted by members
of the relevant scientific community.  For these reasons the court found that the expert&#146;s
testimony was not reliable and that the trial court was correct in disallowing it. 
<U>Robinson</U> at 559-60.

<P> The applicability of <U>Robinson</U> in administrative proceedings is uncertain. 
Certaintypes of agencies deal with issues which can be of a scientific nature (e.g., predicted
environmental impacts in matters considered by the TNRCC; issues related to alleged
misconduct in various medical licensing areas, etc.).  Expert testimony is heavily relied upon in
these and other types of administrative hearings, and practitioners should be aware of the
<U>Robinson</U> analysis and its potential application.  

<P><B>c. </B><B> </B><B>Application of </B><B><U>Robinson</U></B><B> in Texas
Cases</B>

<P><B> </B>Illustrations of the application of the &quot;reliability&quot; principles articulated
in <U>Robinson</U> are evident in several recent decisions.  These include:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P> i. <U>K-Mart Corporation v. Rhyne</U>, No. 06-95-00042-CV, 1996
WL 294483 (Tex. App.--Texarkana, June 4, 1996, n.w.h.) -chiropractor should not have been
allowed to offer expert testimony about the cost of surgical treatment.

<P> ii. <U>Jordan v. State of Texas</U>, No. 831-94, 1996 WL 313228 (Tex. Cr. cv. App. June
12, 1996) - criminal proceeding in which expert scientific testimony concerning the reliability of
an eyewitness identification of a robber was allowed into evidence.

<P> iii. <U>Burroughs Wellcome Co. v. Crye</U>, 907 S.W. 2d 497 (Tex. 1995) - concurring
opinion (by Justice Gonzalez) applying <U>Robinson</U> analysis and finding expert scientific
testimony unreliable.

<P> iv. <U>Merrell Dow Pharmnaceuticals, Inc. v. </U><U>Havner</U>, 907 S.W. 2d 535
(Tex. App.--Corpus Christi 1994, writ granted) - a Benectin case (the same drug at issue in
<U>Daubert</U>).  The original court of appeals opinion found the plaintiff&#146;s scientific
expert testimony legally insufficient to prove causation between the drug and birth defects.  On
rehearing before the court <I>en banc</I>, the court made a detailed analysis of the
plaintiff&#146;s evidence in accordance with <U>Robinson</U> and found that the trial court
had not abused itsdiscretion in admitting the testimony on causation.  Thus, ironically, the
<U>Robinson</U> analysis resulted in the acceptance of scientific evidence previously found to
have been insufficient for its intended purpose.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> These cases (and others where <U>Robinson</U> was cited  for the more general
proposition that expert testimony must be relevant and reliable) indicate that courts are still
grappling with how to apply the more stringent analysis of expert testimony. Courts have clearly
picked upon the theme that expert testimony should be more closely <I>scrutinized</I>, but the
contours of that scrutiny remain uneven.  The Texas Supreme Court has heard oral argument in
the <U>Havner</U> case, and it will therefore have an opportunity, in the near future, to shed
further light on the meaning and application of <U>Robinson</U>.  
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>3. </B><B> </B><B>Do </B><B><U>Robinson</U></B><B> and
</B><B><U>Daubert</U></B><B> Apply to Non-</B><B>Scientific Testimony?</B>

<P> One fundamental issue which remains unresolved is whether the standards enunciated in
<U>Daubert</U> and <U>Robinson</U> apply to non-scientific expert testimony.  While no
state court decision has addressed this issue, federal courts are split.

<P> For example, in <U>Compton v. Subaru of </U><U>America, Inc.</U> 82 F.3d 1513,
1518 (10th Cir. 1996) the Tenth Circuit stated that application of the<U> </U><U>Daubert</U>
factors was unwarranted in cases where expert testimony is based solely upon experience or
training.  The court views <U>Daubert</U> as setting out additional factors a court should
consider under Rule 702 if an expert witness offers testimony based upon a particular
methodology or technique, and absent testimony warranting application of the additional factors
the court should make its &quot;traditional analysis under Rule 702&quot;.  <U>Id</U>. at
1519.  Similarly, in <U>Iacobelli </U><U>Construction Inc. v. County of Monroe</U>, 32 F.3d
19, 25 (2nd Cir. 1994) the Second Circuit found reliance on <U>Daubert</U> misplaced in
analyzing the expert opinion affidavits of a geotechnical consultant and an underground
construction consultant.  The court opined that <U>Daubert</U> clarified the standard for
admissibility of scientifictestimony, and that testimony of the type offered in this case did not
present the kind of &quot;junk science&quot; problem that <U>Daubert</U> meant to address.
<U>Id</U>.  The Seventh and Ninth Circuits appear to be in agreement with the limited
application of <U>Daubert</U>.  <I>See</I> <U>United States v. Sinclair</U>, 74 F.3d 753,
757 (7th Cir. 1996) and <U>Thomas v. Newton </U><U>International Enterprises</U>, 42 F.3d
1266, 1270 (9th Cir. 1994).

<P> In contrast, at least three circuits have found <U>Daubert</U> applicable to non-scientific
evidence.  In <U>Den Morske Bank AS v. First National Bank of </U><U>Boston</U>, 75
F.3d 49, 57 (1st Cir. 1996) the First Circuit found expert testimony on banking practices
admissible under Fed. R. Civ. Evid. 702 and <U>Daubert</U>.  Similarly the Sixth Circuit, in
<U>Berry </U><U>v. City of Detroit</U>, 25 F.3d 1342, 1350 (6th Cir. 1994) stated that
although <U>Daubert</U> dealt with scientific experts, &quot;its language relative to the
gatekeeper function of federal judges is applicable to all expert testimony offered under Rule
702&quot;. Finally, the Eighth Circuit found certain economic testimony admissible under the
general <U>Daubert</U> standard in a business dispute between professional wrestler Jesse
&quot;the Body&quot; Ventura and Titan Sports, Inc., the operator of the World Wrestling
Federation.  <U>Ventura v. Titan Sports, Inc.</U> 65 F.3d 725, 733-36 (8th Cir. 1995).

<P> The Fifth Circuit has yet to address the applicability of <U>Daubert</U> to non-scientific
expert testimony.  Thus, while several decisions have embraced the stricter scrutiny of expert
testimony encouraged by <U>Robinson</U>, it is unclear whether the analysis articulated
therein applies to non-scientific expert testimony.

<P><B>4. </B><B>Acceptable Bases for Expert Opinions and </B><B>the Disclosure
Thereof</B>.  

<P> Because of the sometimes extensive reliance on expert witnesses and testimony in
administrative proceedings, information concerning the underlying basis of an expert opinion
holds particular importance.  The rules concerning acceptable bases for those opinions, as well
rules governing the disclosure of the bases, are deceptively simple on their face.  In practice,
these rules, and particularly the combined effect of therules on the disclosure of otherwise
inadmissible evidence, is fraught with uncertainty.  The rules bearing on these issues are set forth
below:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P> TRE 703:

<P>The facts or data in the particular case upon which an expert bases an opinion or inference
may be those perceived by or reviewed by the expert at or before the hearing.  If of a type
reasonably relied upon by experts in the particular field in forming opinions or inferences upon
the subject, the facts or data need not be admissible in evidence.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P> TRE 705:

<P>The expert may testify in terms of opinion or inference and give his reasons therefore
without prior disclosure of the underlying facts or data, unless the court requires otherwise.  The
expert may in any event disclose on direct examination, or be required to disclose on cross
examination, the underlying facts or data.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>a. </B><B>Inadmissible Evidence as the Basis for an
</B><B>Expert Opinion.</B>

<P> TRE 703 addresses the issue of the appropriate basis upon which an expert witness may
base their opinion.  Generally, the factual basis underlying an expert's opinions and conclusions
goes to the weight of the testimony and not to its admissibility.  <U>Century 21 Page One
</U><U>Realty v. Naghad</U>, 760 S.W.2d 305 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1988, no writ);
<U>Bufkin v. Texas Farm </U><U>Bureau Mutual Ins. Co.</U>, 658 S.W.2d 317
(Tex.App.--Tyler 1983, no writ).  However, expert opinion testimony cannot be based on mere
guess or speculation; it must have a proper factual basis. <U>Naegeli Transportation v. Gulf
Electroquip, Inc.</U>, 853 S.W.2d 737, 741 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1993, writ denied);
<U>Ochs v. Martinez</U>, 789 S.W.2d 949, 958 (Tex.App.--San Antonio 1990, writ denied).

<P> TRE 703 also makes clear that experts may rely upon information which is not otherwise
admissible in evidence for the purpose of forming their opinion.  (<I>See</I> <I>e.g.</I>,
<U>New Braunfels Factory </U><U>Outlet Center, Inc. v. IHOP Realty Corp.</U>, 872
S.W.2d 303, 310 (n. 5) (Tex. App.--Austin 1994, no writ), noting that an expert witness can
testify from a published hearsay article as the bases for his or her expert opinion).  In an opinion
which squarely addressed the issue with respect to hearsay evidence, the Texarkana court of
appeals held that TRE 703 specifically provides that inadmissible facts or data may be relied
upon by an expert in forming an opinion if they are of the type reasonably relied upon by other
experts to make opinions or draw inferences.  <U>Baylor </U><U>Medical Plaza v. Kidd</U>,
834 S.W. 2d  at 76.  The court also noted that TRE 703 effectively rejects the Texas Supreme
Court's decision in <U>Moore v. </U><U>Grantham</U>, 599 S.W.2d 287, 289 (Tex. 1980),
which predated the current version of the rule and purported to disallow hearsay evidence as the
basis for an expert opinion.  <I>(See</I> <I>also</I> <U>Liptak v. </U><U>Pensaben</U>,
736 S.W.2d 953 (Tex.App.--Tyler 1987, no writ) and <U>Sharpe v. Safeway Scaffold, Inc.</U>,
687 S.W. 2d 386 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1985, no writ), both rejecting the application
of <U>Moore v. Grantham</U> in light of TRE 703).  

<P> The determination of whether experts in a particular field reasonably rely upon certain data
is a preliminary matter for the trier of fact to decide. <U>St. Paul Medical Center v. Cecil</U>,
842 S.W.2d 808, 815 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1992, no writ); <U>Moore v. </U><U>Polish Power,
Inc.</U>, 720 S.W.2d 183, 191-92 (Tex. App.--Dallas 1986, writ ref&#146;d n.r.e.).  In
<U>Polish Power</U>, the court considered the interpretation given the federal hearsay rule
which &quot;came to be adopted as the federal rule of evidence from which our Rule 703 is
taken.&quot; <U>Polish Power</U>, 720 S.W.2d at 192.  The court quoted the following from a
Fifth Circuit decision:
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The rationale for this exception to the rule against hearsay is that the expert, because of his
professional knowledge and ability, is competent to judge for himself the reliability of the
records and statements on which he bases his expert opinion.  Moreover, the opinion ofexpert
witnesses must invariably rest, at least in part, upon sources that can never be proven in court. 
An expert&#146;s opinion is derived not only from records and data, but from education and
from a lifetime of experience.  Thus, when the expert witness has consulted numerous sources,
and uses that information, together with his own professional knowledge and experience, to
arrive at his opinion, that opinion is regarded as evidence in its own right and not as hearsay in
disguise.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>Citing <U>United States v. Williams</U>, 447 F.2d 1285, 1290 (5th Cir. 1971) (<I>en
banc</I>), cert. denied, 405 U.S. 954, 92 Sup. Ct. 1308 (1972)).  It is interesting to note that the
deferrence to, and trust in, experts which is reflected in the excerpt above seems to have eroded
given the concerns about expert testimony raised by the Texas Supreme Court in the
<U>Robinson</U> opinion.

<P> A good illustration of the application of TRE 703 can be found in <U>State of Texas v.
Resolution </U><U>Trust Corp.</U>, 827 S.W.2d 106 (Tex.App.--Austin 1992, writ denied). 
That case involved the condemnation of property owned by the RTC and a resulting dispute over
the proper amount of damages to be awarded as a consequence of the taking.  As evidence on the
issue of the pre-condemnation value of the property, the RTC presented an appraiser who gave
his opinion based, in part, on previously made but unaccepted offers to purchase the property. 
There is abundant authority stating that unaccepted offers to purchase property are not admissible
as evidence to show value.  In this case, however, the unaccepted offers were not admitted as
&quot;independent&quot; evidence of value, but were admitted (under TRE 703) as part of the
basis for the appraiser's opinion.  In other words, the fact that unaccepted offers might not have
been admissible to prove value did not affect the admissibility of the expert's testimony provided
that unaccepted offers were a type of data that a real estate appraiser would reasonably rely upon
in forming an opinion of value.

<P> Note, however, that the facts or data relied upon must themselves be reliable, regardless of
whether they are of a type that others would rely upon.  In <U>Texas Workers Compensation
</U><U>Commission v. Garcia</U>, 862 S.W.2d 61 (Tex.App.--San Antonio 1993),
rev&#146;d on other grounds, 893 S.W.2d 501 (Tex. 1995), the appellate court considered the
exclusion by the trial court of an actuarial study prepared at the request of the State Board of
Insurance (comparing the costs and benefits of the &quot;new&quot; Workers' Compensation
Act to the &quot;old&quot; act).  While the study was done using accepted procedures, it was
based on data characterized by the preparer as &quot;far from perfect&quot; and
&quot;outdated&quot;, and it caused results for which statistical significance could not be
attributed to the calculations of certain benefits.  <U>Texas </U><U>Workers Compensation
Commission v. Garcia</U>, 862 S.W.2d  at 105.  The appellate court upheld the trial court's
exclusion of the study and testimony relying on the study, noting that the &quot;court must
determine, not only that the facts or data are of a type relied upon by experts in the field, but also
that such reliance is reasonable.&quot; <U>Id</U>.  The ultimate goal of expert testimony is to
provide some assistance to the trier of fact, and if such testimony or opinion evidence is so
&quot;infected by untrustworthy data&quot; that it would not prove useful it should be excluded. 
<U>Id</U>.

<P> Another example of the application of TRE 703 is the decision in <U>Lipsey v. Texas Dept.
of </U><U>Health</U>, 727 S.W.2d 61, 72 (Tex.App.--Austin 1987, writ ref'd n.r.e.).  That
case involved a landfill permit hearing before the Texas Department of Health, where an expert
witness relied upon, as part of the basis for his opinion, a contour map which was not in
evidence.  The examiner ruled, and the court of appeals ultimately agreed, that the testimony was
admissible because the expert's opinion was not shown to rest exclusively upon the map, and also
that the witness had testified that the map was a source customarily relied upon by those in the
field.  <U>Id</U>.

<P> In sum, under TRE 703 experts are entitled to rely upon hearsay (or other types of
inadmissible evidence) in forming their opinions <I>if</I> that information is of a type
reasonably relied upon by experts in the field and<I> if</I> the information is itselfreliable. 
While expert opinions should be inadmissible if they are purely speculative or based on
conjecture, most questions as to the factual basis upon which an expert arrives at an opinion will
be deemed to go to the weight of the testimony and not to its admissibility.

<P><B>b. </B><B>Disclosure of the Basis of an Expert </B><B>Opinion.</B>

<P> Where many of the battles are fought in the area of expert opinions is over the admissibility
of the basis of an expert's opinion when that basis would otherwise be inadmissible.  It is one
thing for an expert to rely, as is permitted by TRE 703, upon otherwise inadmissible evidence; it
is another for that otherwise inadmissible evidence to be brought before the trier of fact,
particularly during direct examination.  The dispute centers on whether an expert has an absolute
right to disclose the basis for his or her opinion, even if that basis is comprised of inadmissible
evidence.  At the appeals court level, there are currently holdings going both ways.

<P> On one side of the issue is <U>Decker v. Hatfield</U>, 798 S.W.2d 637
(Tex.App.-Eastland 1990, writ dism'd w.o.j.), where the court of appeals affirmed the trial court's
decision to allow an expert to testify, on direct examination, concerning substantive
conversations he had which amounted to hearsay.  The court emphasized the language of TRE
705 which makes it permissive to disclose such evidence on direct examination. [. The court also
noted that the objecting party failed to request, under TRE 403, that the evidence be excluded
because its probative value was substantially outweighed by the danger of unfair prejudice.  Id. 
at 639.] 

<P> On the other side is <U>First Southwest Lloyds </U><U>Ins. Co. v. MacDowell</U>, 769
S.W.2d at 958, where the court affirmed the trial court's refusal to allow an expert witness to
testify as to hearsay matters which formed, in part, the basis for his opinion. The court
emphasized that the permissive nature of TRE 705 (with respect to disclosure of facts and data
upon direct examination) does not indicate &quot;an absolute right of the expert to disclose
<U>all</U> of the facts and underlying data under all circumstances&quot;.  <U>Id</U>.
(emphasis in original).  The court stated its belief that the &quot;better judicial position is not to
allow the affirmative admission of otherwise inadmissible matters merely because such matters
happen to be underlying data uponwhich an expert relies.&quot;  <U>Id</U>.  The court later
noted that if the expert were held to be entitled to detail every statement made to him that
contributed to his conclusion, then the expert could be effectively used to present an infinite
amount of evidentiary matters to the jury.  <U>Id</U>., <U>See</U> <U>also</U> <U>Hall v.
</U><U>Birchfield</U>, 718 S.W.2d 313 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1986), rev'd on other grounds,
747 S.W.2d 361 (Tex. 1988) (TRE 705 cannot be used as a guise to use one's own expert witness
to admit hearsay testimony).

<P> The most recent appeals court decision addressing the issue is <U>Kramer v. Lewisville
</U><U>Memorial Hospital</U>, 831 S.W.2d 46, 49 (Tex.App.--Ft. Worth 1992), aff'd 858
S.W.2d 397 (Tex. 1993).  That decision effectively agrees with the holding in <U>First
Southwest Lloyds</U> that TRE 705 does not indicate an absolute right of an expert to disclose
all of the facts and underlying data under all circumstances.  <U>Id</U>. at 49, citing
<U>Beavers v. </U><U>Northrop Worldwide Aircraft</U>, 821 S.W.2d at 674 (citations
therein omitted).  The court deemed it essentially a matter of discretion, stating that: &quot;while
such supporting evidence is not automatically admissible because it <I>is</I> supporting data to
an expert's opinion, neither is it automatically excluded simply because it is hearsay&quot;. 
<U>Id</U>., (emphasis in original).  The <U>First </U><U>Southwest Lloyds</U> decision
made a similar suggestion, noting that <I>even if</I> it ruled that all facts or data relied upon by
an expert were <I>ipso facto</I> admissible, courts would still have the discretion under TRE
403 to exclude the evidence.  <U>First </U><U>Southwest Lloyds Ins. Co. v. MacDowell</U>,
769 S.W.2d at 958.  This notion was bolstered by the decision in <U>Dudley v. Humana
Hospital Corp.</U>, 817 S.W.2d at 127, where the court suggested that even if the underlying
basis for an expert opinion met the admissibility requirements of TRE 705, it would still be
excluded if it was irrelevant (under TRE 401) or if its admission could be prejudicial or
confusing (under TRE 403) (see section III.E. above).  

<P> The Texas Supreme Court has yet to directly address the issue, although it touched upon it
in <U>Birchfield v. Texarkana Memorial Hospital</U>, 747 S.W.2d 361 (Tex. 1987).  There the
court stated that &quot;ordinarily an expert witness should not bepermitted to recount a hearsay
conversation with a third person, even if that conversation forms part of the basis of his
opinion&quot;. <U>Id</U>. at 365.  The <U>Birchfield</U> decision was recently relied upon
by the Beaumont court of appeals in <U>Minnesota Mining </U><U>and Manufacturing v.
Nishika Ltd.</U>, 885 S.W.2d at 631-32, where the court, considering the admission of hearsay
statements, found that the &quot;sounder rule is that an expert witness should not and must not
be permitted to recount hearsay conversations and hearsay statements from a third person even if
that conversation or statement formed some part of the basis of his opinion.&quot;  On the other
side of the issue, the <U>Decker</U> court, which made a contrary ruling, acknowledged the
existence of the Texas Supreme Court's position in <U>Birchfield</U> and noted the fact that it
had been sharply criticized in another forum as &quot;ill considered and overbroad.&quot;
<U>Decker</U>, 798 S.W. 2d at 638, citing Goode, Wellborn &amp; Sharlot, <U>Texas Rules
of Evidence: </U><U>Civil and Criminal</U> &#149; 705.3 (Tex. Prac. 1988).

<P> Although not binding on Texas courts, a recent Fifth Circuit decision offers further insight
on the issue.  In <U>Polythane Systems v. Marina </U><U>Ventures International</U>, 993
F.2d 1201 (5th Cir. 1993) cert. denied 114 S.Ct. 1064 (1994), the court considered the
admissibility of a report prepared by an expert who did not testify, but upon which another
(testifying) expert relied.  The court found error in the federal district court's admission of the
document (which was clearly hearsay), noting that while Fed. R. Civ. Evid. 705 (which is
virtually identical to the Texas rule) allows the <I>disclosure</I> of the basis for an expert's
opinion, it does not facilitate the <I>admission</I> of otherwise inadmissible evidence.

<P> The result of these various decisions is that it is currently unclear as to whether an expert has
an absolute right to disclose the details of hearsay testimony and other inadmissible evidence that
he or she may have relied upon.  Counsel seeking to oppose such disclosure should make the
appropriate objections, including those under TRE 401 and 403 which enable, if appropriate, the
presiding officer to disallow evidence even though relevant.
</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>I. </B><B>Hearsay and Exceptions to the Hearsay </B><B>Rule (TRE 801, 802,
803).</B>

<P> The hearsay rule may be the most frequently cited objection to evidence made in
administrative hearings.  While the rule itself is not complicated, the myriad of exceptions and
exclusions greatly complicate its application.  Several of these concepts are addressed below.

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. </B><B>Hearsay Defined.</B>

<P> Hearsay is generally defined as a statement (oral, written or nonverbal conduct) made by a
person not testifying at a hearing or trial which is offered in evidence to prove the truth of the
matter asserted.  TRE 801.  Out of court statements which are <I>not</I> offered to prove the
truth of the matter asserted are <I>not</I> hearsay statements.  <U>Busse </U><U>v. Pacific
Cattle Feeding Fund</U>, 896 S.W.2d 807, 816 (Tex. App.--Texarkana 1995, writ denied). For
example, in <U>City of Austin v. Houston </U><U>Lighting &amp; Power Co.</U>, 844
S.W.2d 773 (Tex.App.--Dallas 1992, writ denied), the court admitted certain newspaper articles
concerning Austin's involvement in the South Texas Nuclear Project.  While it is clear that
newspaper articles are typically considered to be hearsay, in this instance they were deemed
admissible because they were not offered for the truth of the matter asserted but rather for
&quot;the limited purpose of showing that the statements were made and for the limited purpose
of showing the state of public knowledge in the City of Austin at the relevant times&quot;. 
<U>Id</U>. at 791-93.  <I>See also</I> <U>McCraw v. Maris</U>, 828 S.W.2d. 756 (Tex.
1992) (copy of a beneficiary form was admissible in dispute over life insurance proceeds when
not offered for truth of matter asserted but merely to show that the form existed).  Absent rules or
laws requiring otherwise, hearsay is not admissible, although if it is admitted without objection it
is not to be denied probative value merely because it is hearsay.  TRE 802; <U>De La Garza v.
Salazar</U>, 851 S.W.2d 380, 383 (Tex.App.--San Antonio 1993, no writ). The hearsay rule is
typically applied in the same manner in proceedings before an administrative agency as in trials
before a court.  <U>Lubbock Radio </U><U>Paging v. Southwestern Bell</U>, 607 S.W.2d.
29, 32(Tex. Civ. App.--Beaumont 1980, writ ref'd n.r.e.).

<P> While there are many &quot;exceptions&quot; to the hearsay rule (i.e., hearsay which is
nevertheless admissible), certain types of out-of-court statements are simply excluded from the
hearsay definition entirely.  Among these are depositions, prior inconsistent statements of a
witness, prior consistent statements of a witness, and admissions made by, on behalf of, or which
are adopted by, a party.  TRE 801(e).  These are addressed below.

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>a. </B><B>Depositions.</B>

<P> A deposition will <I>not</I> be hearsay if it was taken in the same proceeding (as defined
in Tex. R. Civ. P. 207) in which it is to be used.  The deponent need not be
&quot;unavailable&quot; for it to be admissible.  TRE 801(e)(3); <U>Romero v. Parkhill,
</U><U>Smith &amp; Cooper, Inc.</U>, 881 S.W.2d 522, 527 (Tex. App --El Paso 1994, writ
denied).  Note that this differs from the permitted use of depositions under the Fed. R. Civ. Evid.,
where depositions may only be used as substantive evidence if the witness is unavailable.  It is a
common practice in complex administrative proceedings for opposing parties to depose each
other's witnesses (as well as agency staff members).  This rule makes clear that such depositions
should be admissible in the administrative hearing itself regardless of the availability of the
witness and provided the deposition was taken in the same proceeding.  <I>See</I>, <I>e.g</I>.,
<U>Hall v. White</U>, 525 S.W. 2d 860, 862 (Tex. 1975) (discussing distinction between
admission of deposition testimony from same and different proceedings).

<P><B>b. </B><B>Prior Inconsistent Statements.</B>

<P> Prior inconsistent statements of a witness will not be considered hearsay if:  the witness
testifies at the hearing; the witness is subject to cross examination concerning the statement; the
statement is inconsistent with his testimony; and the prior statement had been given at a trial,
hearing, deposition or other proceeding.  TRE 801(e)(1)(A).  Note that prior inconsistent
statements may be used for impeachment purposes (TRE 613; see section III.G. above), but will
notbe admissible as non-hearsay unless the requirements of TRE 801(e)(1)(A) are met. 
<U>See</U> <U>Cecil v. Zivley</U>, 683 S.W.2d 853, 857 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.]
1984, no writ).

<P> The use of prior inconsistent statements is most likely to arise in administrative proceedings
with expert witnesses who testify frequently before a particular agency and are cross examined
by opposing parties concerning perceived deviations from prior positions.  Another manner in
which they may arise is through written answers to discovery.  In <U>American Maintenance
&amp; Rentals v. </U><U>Estrada</U>, 896 S.W.2d 212, 218-20 (Tex. App.--Houston [1st
Dist.] 1995, vacated pursuant to settlm&#146;t), the court admitted a party&#146;s interrogatory
answers in the same proceeding as evidence of the truth of the matter asserted (i.e., non-hearsay).
The court noted that the answers were &quot;statements&quot; under TRE 801(a) because they
were a &quot;written verbal expression&quot;; the declarant testified at trial; his answers were
inconsistent with his testimony; and the previous answers were given under oath.  <U>Id</U>. 
This was sufficient to allow their admission under TRE 801(e)(1)(A).  (Note also that, because
they were allowed to be used against the declarant, the court found that the answers would also
be admissible as a party admission under TRE 801(e)(2)(a).  <U>Id</U>. at 219 (fn. 3)).

<P><B>c. </B><B>Prior Consistent Statements.</B>

<P> Prior consistent statements of a witness will not be considered hearsay if:  the witness
testifies at the hearing; the witness is subject to cross examination concerning the statement; the
statement is consistent with his testimony; and it is used to rebut an express or implied change of
recent fabrication or improper influences or motive.  TRE 801(e)(1)(B).  <U>See</U>,
<U>e.g.</U>, <U>McInnes v. </U><U>Yamaha Motor Corp.</U>, 673 S.W.2d 185, 190 (Tex.
1984), <U>Ochs v. Martinez</U>, 789 S.W.2d 949, 959 (Tex.App.--San Antonio 1990, writ
denied).  The party offering the prior consistent statement must lay the foundation necessary to
show that the statement was being offered to rebut a charge of recent fabrication, improper
influence, or improper motive in testifying.  <U>In the Matter of G.M.P.</U>, 909 S.W.2d 198,
207 (Tex. App.--Houston [14th Dist.]1995, n.w.h.).  In administrative hearings these types of
statements may be used to show that a witness has not, despite suggestions to the contrary, 
changed their position on an issue in the case.  Note that the consistent statement must be raised
while the witness is still testifying so that other parties have a right to cross-examine concerning
circumstances under which the statement was made; otherwise the statement may be excluded. 
<U>Missouri Pacific Railroad Company </U><U>v. Vlach</U>, 687 S.W.2d 414, 417-18
(Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1985, writ ref'd n.r.e.).  This requirement, as well as the others
associated with prior consistent and inconsistent statements, are intended to ensure the reliability
of the statements that are inadmissible except as permitted under TRE 801(e)(1)(A) and (B).

<P><B>d. </B><B>Party Admissions.</B>

<P> An admission of a party-opponent will not be considered hearsay if the statement is offered
against a party and is any of the following:  his own statement (in his individual or representative
capacity); a statement which he has adopted or indicated agreement with; a statement made by a
person authorized by the witness to make a statement concerning the subject; or a statement
made by his agent or servant concerning a matter within the scope of his agency or employment
made during the existence of the relationship. TRE 801(e)(2).   The court has noted that
admissions also tend to impeach the admitter&#146;s credibility, and that all that is required for
virtually any type of document which might otherwise be condemned as being hearsay in nature
to fully qualify for admission is that the document or instrument must contain some statement
relevant to a material issue in the case on trial and be inconsistent with the position taken by the
party against whom it is introduced.  <U>Westchester Fire </U><U>Insurance Company v.
Lowe</U>, 888 S.W.2d 243, 250 (Tex. App.--Beaumont 1994, no writ).  

<P> In cases involving declarations of an agent or employee, the fact of their agency must be
clearly established before the declarations will be admitted against the principal or employer.  In
<U>Patterson v. </U><U>Mobiloil Federal Credit Union</U>, 890 S.W.2d 551 (Tx.
App.--Beaumont - 1994, no writ), theplaintiff offered the affidavit of a former member of
Mobiloil&#146;s board of directors in support of her claim to supplemental retirement benefits. 
The court refused to admit the affidavit, finding that the affiant was not a member of the board at
the time the statements were made and the statements were outside the scope of his agency or
employment.  <U>Id</U>. at 555.  The affidavit was therefore hearsay and was not admissible as
an admission of a party opponent. <I>See also</I> <U>American </U><U>Maintenance &amp;
Rentals v.Estrada</U>, 896 S.W.2d at 226. To the extent admissions arise in administrative
proceedings they often involve statements of a current or former employee of an applicant or
permit holder.  For example, in <U>State </U><U>of Texas v. City of Greenville</U>, 726
S.W.2d 162, 168 (Tex.App. Dallas 1986, writ ref'd n.r.e.), a city administrative assistant sent a
letter to the Texas Department of Health expressing inability to meet landfill closure
requirements by a specified date.  This was admissible as a party admission in subsequent
proceedings initiated by the state for improper closure of the landfill.

<P> Another example of an admission in an agency-related proceeding occurred in <U>Flores v.
</U><U>Texas Department of Health</U>, 835 S.W.2d 807 (Tex.App.--Austin 1992, writ
denied).  In <U>Flores</U> the TDH issued a municipal solid waste permit which, for design
purposes, specified a groundwater depth of 33 feet.  Differing expert testimony concerning the
groundwater table pegged it at either 16 feet (according to the protestants) or 60 feet (according
to the applicant). At the district court level the TDH, through the Attorney General's office, filed
an amended answer in which it <I>admitted</I> that it had acted arbitrarily and capriciously and
stated its belief that the groundwater finding was not supported by substantial evidence. 
<U>Id</U>. at 811.  While the district court nevertheless affirmed the permit issuance, the
appellate court reversed, noting that the TDH had made what amounted to a judicial admission,
and while not determinative it created a strong presumption and amounted to a &quot;virtual
confession of error&quot;.  <U>Id</U>.

<P> Yet another form in which admissions may arise in administrative proceedings is through
pleadings filed in the case.  Admissions made inpleadings will be conclusive on the party
admitting the fact, and such admissions relieve the opposing party from having to prove the
admitted fact. <U>Dokmanovic v. Schwarz</U>, 880 S.W.2d 272, 275 (Tex. App.--Houston
[14th Dist.] 1994, no writ); <U>Hill v. Steinberger</U>, 827 S.W.2d, 58, 61
(Tex.App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1992, no writ). Even pleadings of a party in another case can
constitute admissions, as can abandoned, superseded or amended pleadings (though they may
cease to carry the force of a judicial admission).  <U>Westchester Fire Insurance Co. v.
</U><U>Lowe</U>, 888 S.W. 2d at 252.  Similarly, admissions made in testimony, while
generally considered as quasi-admissions, may nevertheless have the effect of judicial
admissions.  <U>Pako Corp. v. Thomas</U>, 855 S.W.2d 215, 217-18 (Tex.App.--Tyler 1993,
no writ).  Note that, like the various requirements concerning prior consistent and inconsistent
statements, the requirements associated with admissions are intended to bolster the reliability of
the statements.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>2. </B><B>Exceptions to the Hearsay Rule.</B>

<P> In addition to the exclusion of certain items from the definition of hearsay, there are
numerous exceptions to the hearsay rule which allow otherwise inadmissible evidence to be
admitted for the truth of the matter asserted.  In any instance it is the burden of the party seeking
to admit evidence to clearly show that the evidence is of a type to which the exception applies,
and all hearsay exceptions require a showing of trustworthiness.  <U>Roberts v. Allison</U>,
836 S.W.2d 185, 191 (Tex.App.--Tyler 1992, writ denied), <U>Lacy v. Lacy</U>, 922 S.W.2d
195, 198 (Tex. App. --Tyler 1995, writ denied).  The applicability of the various exceptions is
where much of the controversy concerning the rule arises.  TRE 803 lists 24 separate exceptions
to the hearsay rule.  Of these, four tend to arise with more frequency than others in administrative
proceedings.  Those four are specifically addressed below.

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>a. </B><B>Business Records Exception.</B>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>TRE 803(6) provides as follows:

<P>(6) Records of regularly conducted activity.  A memorandum, report, record, or data
compilation, in any form, of acts, events, conditions, opinions, or diagnoses, made at or near the
time by, or from information transmitted by, a person with knowledge, if kept in the course of a
regularly conducted business activity, and if it was the regular practice of that business activity to
make the memorandum, report, record, or data compilation, all as shown by the testimony of the
custodian or other qualified witness, or by affidavit that complies with Rule 902(10), unless the
source of information or the method or circumstances of preparation indicate lack of
trustworthiness.  &quot;Business&quot; as used in this paragraph includes any and every kind of
regular organized activity whether conducted for profit or not.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P> This provision is commonly referred to as the &quot;business records&quot; exception. 
<U>Overall v. </U><U>Southwestern Bell Yellow Pages</U>, 869 S.W.2d 629, 633 (Tex.
App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1994, no writ).  In establishing whether a document falls within the
exception and therefore may be admitted as evidence for the truth of the matter asserted, an
offering party must show that the document or record is generated pursuant to a course of a
regularly conducted business activity and that the record is, as a practical matter, always created
by or from information transmitted by a person with knowledge, at or near the time of the event. 
<U>General Resources Organization, Inc. v. </U><U>Deadman</U>, 907 S.W. 2d at 29;
<U>Clark v. Walker-</U><U>Kurth Lumber Co.</U>, 689 S.W.2d 275 (Tex.App.--Houston
[1st Dist.] 1985, writ ref'd n.r.e.).  At least one court has held that the term &quot;made&quot; in
TRE 803(b) does not mean the same as &quot;authored by&quot;.  In <U>GT &amp; MC, Inc.
v. Texas City Refining, </U><U>Inc.</U>, 822 S.W.2d 252 (Tex.App.--Houston [1st Dist.]
1991, writ denied) the court refused to exclude invoices offered by a party as business records
but which had originated with a vendor ofthat party's.  The court noted that the manner in which
the invoices were processed indicated that they had become the primary record of information
about the underlying transactions for the party offering them.  <U>Id</U>. at 258.  Thus, it is not
necessary that the party (or an employee thereof) offering documents as business records have
personally authored them.  Nor is it necessary that the proponent have personal knowledge
concerning information contained within the business records, as the lack of knowledge simply
goes to the weight to be given the evidence, and not its admissibility.  <U>Longoria </U><U>v.
Greyhound Lines, Inc.</U>, 699 S.W.2d 298, 303 (Tex.App.--San Antonio 1985, no writ).

<P> The primary emphasis of TRE 803(6) is on the reliability and trustworthiness of the records
sought to be introduced.  <U>Curran v. Unis</U>, 711 S.W.2d 290, 295 (Tex.App.--Dallas
1986, no writ).  Once the TRE 803(6) requirements are shown by the proponent to have been
met, the burden shifts to other parties to show why the records should be considered
inadmissible.  <U>Texon </U><U>Energy Corp. v. Dow Chemical Co.</U>, 733 S.W.2d 328,
330 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1987, writ ref'd n.r.e.).  The determination as to whether the
requirements of the rule have been met are typically fact specific and are within the purview, in
an administrative proceeding, of the presiding hearing examiner or administrative law judge.

<P> Note that documents prepared specifically for an administrative proceeding will not likely
meet the business records exception.  <U>Railroad </U><U>Commission of Texas v. Rio
Grande Valley Gas </U><U>Company</U>, 683 S.W.2d 783 (Tex.App.--Austin 1984, no writ). 
Documents prepared solely for this purpose will typically fail to meet the requirement that the
records must be of a type prepared or maintained in the regular course of the entities' business.

<P> Note also that establishment of the factors required to admit business records under this
exception may be accomplished through an affidavit prepared in accordance with TRE 902(10). 
A form of affidavit sufficient for this purpose is included within that rule.

<P><B>b. </B><B>Public Records.</B>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>TRE 803(8) appears as follows:

<P> (8) Public records and reports.  Records, reports, statements, or data compilations, in any
form, of public offices or agencies setting forth (A) the activities of the office or agency, or (B)
matters observed pursuant to duty imposed by law as to which matters there was a duty to report,
or (C) factual findings resulting from an investigation made pursuant to authority granted by law;
unless the sources of information, or other circumstances indicate lack of
trustworthiness.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P> This provision allows records, reports, statements or data compilations of public offices or
agencies to be admitted as an exception to the hearsay rule.  At least one court has held that there
is a presumption of admissibility of public records (because they are prepared by public officials
who perform their duties without motive or interest) and that the burden is on the party opposing
its admission to prove its untrustworthiness.  <U>Beavers </U><U>v. Northrop Worldwide
Aircraft</U>, 821 S.W.2d. at 674-75 (citing <U>Moss v. Ole South Real Estate,
</U><U>Inc.</U>, 933 F.2d 1300, 1305 (5th Cir. 1991)). Nevertheless, to secure admission of a
public record an offering party should show that it is authentic and that it contains one of the
three types of matters specified in the rule.  <U>Castro v. </U><U>Sebesta</U>, 808 S.W.2d
189, 195 (Tex.App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1991, no writ); <U>Porter v. Texas
</U><U>Department of Public Safety</U>, 712 S.W.2d 263 (Tex.App.--San Antonio 1986, no
writ) (neither regularity or contemporaneity is required to qualify a public record under TRE
803(8)).  

<P> Not just any document generated by a public agency will qualify (even if authenticated) as a
public record.  Instead the document must be of a type or subject matter described in the rule. 
<I>See</I> <U>Horvath v. Baylor University Medical Center</U>, 704 S.W.2d 866, 870
(Tex.App.--Dallas 1985, no writ).  Furthermore, it is well established that hearsay statements
contained within public records are inadmissable unless they independently  fit within  an 
exception  to  the hearsay rule.  <U>Mary </U><U>Lee Foundation v. Texas Employment
</U><U>Commission</U>, 817 S.W.2d 725, 728 (Tex.App.--Texarkana 1991, writ denied)
(public records exception does not mean that <I>ex parte</I> statements, hearsay, conclusions,
and opinions contained within such records are admissible); <U>Harris County v. Jenkins</U>,
678 S.W.2d 639, 643 (Tex.App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1984, writ ref'd. n.r.e.).  Properly
authenticated government documents which contain hearsay, conclusion, conjecture and opinions
are subject to exclusion on those grounds.  <U>Lister v. Employment Reinsurance
</U><U>Corp.</U>, 590 S.W.2d 803, 805 (Tex. Civ. App.--Houston [14th Dist.] 1979, writ
ref'd n.r.e.). Thus, parties seeking admission of public records which contain hearsay statements
should be prepared to argue alternative bases or exceptions to the hearsay rule in the event that
the public document for which they seek admission itself contains otherwise inadmissable
statements.

<P> A related issue arises under TRE 803(10) which addresses the absence of a public record or
report.  This rule allows the use of a certification or testimony to show that public records had
been searched and no record, report, statement or data compilation related to a particular issue
(for which records are normally kept) was found.  This is typically used in an effort to show that
an event did not happen or a document does not exist.  In <U>Harris County v. Allwaste Tank
Cleaning</U>, 808 S.W.2d 149 (Tex.App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1991, writ dism'd w.o.j.), Harris
County attempted to use an affidavit from the Executive Director of the Texas Air Control Board
to establish that, after a review of the agency's records revealed no permit, special permit, permit
exemption or other authorization for Allwaste, the company had no authority to operate in Harris
County.  Allwaste was, at the time, operating pursuant to an agreed order, and the County was
attempting to use the affidavit to establish that the TACB did not view the agreed order as
granting operating authorization.  The trial court excluded the affidavit and the appeals court
affirmed.

<P><B>c. </B><B>Market Reports, Quotations, Etc. </B>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P> TRE 803(17) reads as follows:

<P>(17) Market reports, commercial publications.  Market quotations, tabulations, lists,
directories or other published compilations generally used and relied upon by the public or by
persons in particular occupations.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P> This rule provides an exception to the hearsay rule for market quotations, tabulations, lists,
directories or other published compilations generally relied upon and used by persons in
particular occupations.  (<I>See, e.g.</I>, <U>Lewis v. </U><U>Southmore Savings
Assoc.</U>, 480 S.W.2d 180, 186 (Tex. 1972)).  In <U>Curran v. Unis</U>, 711 S.W. 2d at
296, the court admitted, under this exception, excerpts from Dunn and Bradstreet reports.  The
court stated that where it is proven that publications of market prices or statistical compilations
are generally recognized as reliable and regularly used in a trade or specialized activity by
persons so engaged, those publications are admissible for the truth of the matter published.
<U>Id</U>. at 297.  Note that in <U>Curran</U>, the excerpts from the reports were admitted
to show the identity of an individual as a partner in a company.  In proving up the reliability of a
document to be admitted under this exception, the proponent should focus on the use of the
document by those in the trade or business with emphasis on the specific information within the
report that the party wishes to rely upon.

<P> Another case which considered the application of TRE 803(17) is <U>New Braunfels
Factory Outlet </U><U>Center, Inc. v. IHOP Realty Corp.</U>, 872 S.W.2d at 310.  That case
involved the interpretation of a restrictive covenant in favor of IHOP Realty that, in general,
precluded the entity from which it purchased a restaurant site from selling any of the adjacent
property to any other type of &quot;family oriented coffee shop or restaurant&quot; that would
compete with it.  <U>Id</U>. At 304-306.  The property owner sold a portion of the adjacent
property to an entity which wanted to put a Cracker Barrel restaurant there.  IHOP sued, and, as
part of its proof that Cracker Barrel was a similar type of restaurant, it offered a reader&#146;s
poll from a magazine rating 36 restaurant chains in which bothIHOP and Cracker Barrel were
listed as &quot;family restaurants&quot; and as being &quot;in the coffee shop class.&quot; 
<U>Id</U> at 310.  The trial court admitted the article under TRE 803(17), but the court of
appeals disagreed.  The appellate court found that IHOP was not using the results of the survey,
but rather the survey&#146;s characterization of the restaurants.  <U>Id</U>.  Also, the party
who conducted the survey was not made available as the court believed was required under TRE
803(17).  <U>Id</U>. Thus, survey results are admissible provided the party opposing
admission has a right to cross examine the person who conducted the survey, and are not
admissible with respect to their characterizations of the subject(s) of the survey.

<P><B>d. </B><B>Learned Treatises.</B>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P> TRE 803(18) provides as follows:

<P>(18) Learned treatises.  To the extent called to the attention of an expert witness upon cross
examination or relied upon by him in direct examination, statements contained in published
treatises, periodicals, or pamphlets on a subject of history, medicine, or other science or art,
established as a reliable authority by the testimony or admission of the witness or by other expert
testimony or by judicial notice. If admitted, the statements may be read into evidence but may
not be received as exhibits.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>  The exception applicable to learned treatises and similar documents extends to those types
of publications which are recognized as authoritative or upon which an expert relies.  If they
meet this threshold requirement, they may be used in the course of cross-examining the witness. 
In <U>Carter </U><U>v. Steere Tank Lines, Inc.</U>, 835 S.W.2d 176, 182-3
(Tex.App.--Amarillo 1992, writ denied), the court held that the trial court had erred in allowing
an expert witness to be cross examined on whether he agreed or disagreed with statements from
an article the expert had not relied upon and which he didnot recognize as authoritative. 
Likewise, <U>Reynolds </U><U>v. Warthan</U>, 896 S.W.2d 823 (Tex. App.--Tyler 1995
n.w.h.) was a medical malpractice action based on a doctor&#146;s recommendation of the use
of a topical lotion for treatment of scabies.  The plaintiff attempted to impeach the
defendant-doctor&#146;s testimony by introducing the package inserts from the lotion (as
containing evidence of the proper standard of care).  The doctor indicated that he did not
recognize the inserts as authoritative and the court, relying on TRE 803(18), upheld the exclusion
of the inserts. <U>Id</U> at 827.  If an expert does, however, recognize as authoritative a book,
article, or similar type document, or if such a document is relied upon by the witness in forming
their opinion, the expert may be cross-examined based on excerpts therefrom.  <U>Wendell v.
Central Power &amp; Light </U><U>Co.</U>, 677 S.W.2d 610, 620 (Tex.App.--Corpus Christi
1984, writ ref'd n.r.e.).  Based on these holdings as well as the text of the rule, counsel seeking to
cross examine an expert with the aid of excerpts or passages from authoritative documents must
first establish that the witness recognizes the documents as reliable authority.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>J. </B><B>Authentication of Documents (TRE 901, </B><B>902).</B>

<P> Article IX of the TRE deals generally with methods of authentication of documents and
other evidence as a prerequisite to admissibility.  TRE 901 sets forth the general rule that
authentication requirements can be satisfied by &quot;...evidence sufficient to support a finding
that the matter in question is what its proponent claims&quot;, and the rule provides several
examples of acceptable types of authentication.  In general, a document will be considered
authentic if a sponsoring witness vouches for its authenticity or if the document meets the
requirements of self-authentication (see below).  <U>In the Matter of G.F.O.</U>, 874 S.W.2d
729, 731 (Tex.App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1994, no writ). The importance of authenticity should
not be overlooked, as the failure to authenticate a document renders it inadmissible even if it is
otherwise relevant and admissible.  <U>Durkay v. </U><U>Madco Oil Co., Inc.</U>, 862
S.W.2d 14, 24 (Tex.App.--Corpus Christi 1993, writ denied); <U>Wirtz v. Massachusetts
Mutual Life Insurance Co.</U>,898 S.W. 2d 414, 423 (Tex. App.--Amarillo 1995, no writ),
(<I>see also</I> <U>Herzing v. Metropolitan Life </U><U>Insurance Co</U>., 907 S.W.2d
574, 580-81, (Tex. App.--Corpus Christi 1995, n.w.h.) (authentication of telephone conversation
admissible pursuant to TRE 801(e)(2)(i)).

<P> This point was made in dramatic fashion in <U>Campbell v. C.D. Payne &amp; Gelderman,
Inc.</U>, 894 S.W.2d 411 (Tex. App.--Amarillo 1995, writ denied).  That case involved a
plaintiff&#146;s claims that she was, among other things, fraudulently and wrongfully induced
into making an investment. Part of her evidence was an employment application one of the
defendants completed for employment with a securities brokerage firm. However, in tendering
the document several other documents were attached.  The court, relying on TRE 901(a), held
that because the documents were tendered as a whole, each should have been individually
authenticated.  <U>Id</U>. at 421.  Also, the mere fact that they were received in response to a
discovery request was not, in and of itself, sufficient to entitle their receipt into evidence. 
<U>Id</U>.; citing <U>Steenbergen v. Ford Motor Co.</U>, 814 S.W.2d 755, 759-60 (Tex.
App.--Dallas 1991, writ denied), cert denied, 113 S.Ct. 97 (1992).  A related issue arose in
<U>Miles v. Ford Motor Co.</U>, 922 S.W. 2d 572 (Tex. App.--Texarkana 1996, n.w.h.), where
the court of appeals held that a letter from a party&#146;s lawyer forwarding a document to the
opposing side did not sufficiently authenticate the document under TRE 901.  The court held that
although the letter could possibly be used for impeachment evidence (to show the lawyer
conceded authenticity in the letter while challenging it in court), it was not the testimony of a
witness and was not sworn to and therefore did not meet the authentication requirements (of TRE
901) which are a condition precedent to admissibility. <U>Id</U>. at 597.  

<P> TRE 902 sets forth several types of evidence which are self-authenticated, which means that
no extrinsic evidence of authentication (such as the types identified in TRE 901) is required. 
Several of these are self-explanatory and/or are unlikely to have frequent application in
administrative proceedings.  Certain others warrant elaboration.

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. </B><B>Self-Authentication of Public Documents.</B>

<P> TRE 902(4) relates to certified copies of public documents.  Generally, documents of a type
identified in the rule (e.g., official records or reports, documents authorized to be filed or
recorded and which are filed or recorded in a public office) which are certified (in conformance
with the rule) as being a correct copy of the original by the custodian or other authorized person
are deemed to be self-authenticated. <U>Mullins v. State of Texas</U>, 699 S.W.2d 346, 349-50
(Tex.App.--Corpus Christi 1985, no writ). Note that even though documents without the proper
seal and signature or certification are not self-authenticating, they may be admissible as business
records if accompanied by the proper affidavit.  <U>Fullick v. City of Baytown</U>, 820
S.W.2d 943, 945 Tex.App.--Houston [1st Dist.] 1991, no writ).  Self-authentication does
<I>not</I> mean that documents may be admitted for the truth of the matters asserted therein;
only that they have been authenticated as being what they are represented by the proponent to be. 
Failure to secure authentication of a public record will preclude it from being admissible. 
<U>ESIS, Inc. Servicing </U><U>Contractors v. Johnson</U>, 908 S.W.2d 554, 561
(Tex.App.--Fort Worth 1995, writ denied).

<P><B>2. </B><B>Self-Authentication of Official Publications.</B>

<P> Similar to TRE 902(4) is TRE 902(5), which addresses &quot;official publications&quot;. 
That rule simply states that &quot;books, pamphlets, or other publications purporting to be
issued by public authority&quot; do not require other evidence of authenticity.  For example, in
<U>Bower v. Edwards County Appraisal </U><U>District</U>, 752 S.W.2d 629, 632-33
(Tex.App.--San Antonio 1988, writ denied), an appraisal district offered into evidence &quot;an
officially published copy of the <I>Guidelines for the Valuation of Agricultural
</I><I>Land</I> promulgated by the State Property Tax Board&quot;.  The court held that, as to
authenticity, this type of document (having been published by a public authority) was
self-authenticating under TRE 902(5).  Given the emphasis on application of agency rules in
administrative proceedings, this rule may be particularly useful in contested cases.

<P><B>3. </B><B>Newspapers and Periodicals as Self-</B><B>Authenticating
Documents.</B>

<P> TRE 902(6) covers newspapers and periodicals, and it simply provides that documents
purporting to be of this type are self-authenticating.  In a case challenging the validity of an
election in which a constitutional amendment (authorizing the issuance of bonds to fund prison
construction) was passed, the court held that copies of newspaper articles attached to the affidavit
of a state senator (showing that voters were informed about the issue) was self-authenticating,
and no extrinsic evidence of authenticity was required for their admissibility. <U>Hardy v.
Hannah</U>, 849 S.W.2d 355, 358-59 (Tex.App.--Austin 1992, writ denied).

<P><B>4. </B><B>Self-Authentication of Business Records.</B>

<P> Perhaps most important of the self-authentication provisions is the business records affidavit
described in TRE 902(10).  Recall that under TRE 803(6) business records meeting the
requirements of that rule can be admitted as an exception to the hearsay rule if they meet certain
requirements which are attested to by the custodian or other qualified witness.  That attestation
can occur through testimony <I>or</I> affidavit, and TRE 902(10) provides the form of affidavit
which can be used for this purpose.  The form is not exclusive, and substantial compliance with
the text of the form will suffice.  <U>Fullick v. </U><U>City of Baytown</U>, 820 S.W.2d. at 
944.  Note that if business records are authenticated through use of an affidavit, they should be
submitted (with the affidavit) <I>at least 14 days</I> before the start of the hearing.  Also, even
with an affidavit which meets the requirements of TRE 902(10) the documents must still meet
the admissibility requirements of TRE 803(6).  <U>United Pacific Insurance Co. v.
</U><U>Jones</U>, 710 S.W.2d 760, 762 (Tex.App.--Beaumont 1986, writ ref'd n.r.e.).
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>K. </B><B>Best Evidence Rule (TRE 1002-1006; APA </B><B>&#167;</B><B>
</B><B>2001.086).</B>

<P> TRE 1002 requires that to prove the content of a writing, recording or photograph, the
original is required (except as otherwise provided by therules of evidence or by law).  This rule
generally requires that a document be introduced when the party is attempting  to prove up its
contents. <U>Parkway/Lamar Partners v. Tom Thumb</U>, 877 S.W.2d 848, 850 (Tex.
App.--Fort Worth 1994, writ denied).  This is often referred to as the &quot;best evidence&quot;
rule.  Copies are admissible to the same extent as originals <I>unless</I> (1) a question is raised
as to authenticity of the original, or (2) it would be unfair under the circumstances to admit a
copy in lieu of an original.  TRE 1003.  <I>See also</I> <U>ESIS, </U><U>Inc. Servicing
Contractor v. Johnson</U>, 908 S.W. 2d, at 561.  <U>Closs v. Goose Creek School Dist.</U>,
874 S.W.2d 859, 868 (Tex. App.--Texarkana 1994, no writ).  <U>Centennial Bonding Agency v.
</U><U>State of Texas</U>, 705 S.W.2d 865, 868 (Tex.App.--Ft Worth 1986, no writ). 
Furthermore, pursuant to TRE 1004, originals are not required and other evidence of their
content is admissible if: (1) the original is lost or destroyed; (2) the original is not obtainable; (3)
the original is not located in Texas; (4) the original is in the possession of an opponent; or (5) the
document is not related to a controlling issue in the case.  <I>See</I>, <U>Arrechea v.
</U><U>Arrechea</U>, 609 S.W.2d 852, 854-55 (Tex. Civ. App.- Houston [14th Dist.] 1980,
writ ref'd n.r.e.) (in light of dispute over whether copy was accurate reproduction of original,
explanation by proponent that original was not lost or destroyed but was in her files did not
reasonably account for absence of original).

<P> The APA, in Section 2001.086, has a similar provision which reads as follows:

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>A copy or excerpt of documentary evidence may be received in a
contested case if an original document is not readily available.  On request, a party shall be given
an opportunity to compare the copy or excerpt with the original document.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P> Note that the &quot;not readily available&quot; standard appears to be less strict than the
requirements of TRE 1004 concerning when originals will not be required.  As a practical matter,
assuming the lawyers involved in a contested case are reasonable and there is no legitimate
dispute overthe authenticity of a document, disputes over original documents should be
infrequent.

<P> One decision which may help illustrate certain appeals of the Article X rules is <U>In Re
Thoma</U>, 873 S.W.2d 477 (Tex. Rev. Trib. 1994), in which  a Review Tribunal considered a
recommendation of the State Commission on Judicial Conduct that a county court at law judge
be removed from his office for judicial misconduct.  Part of the evidence against the judge were
tape recordings of conversations between he and an informant. Duplicates of the tapes were
admitted as evidence under TRE 1003, but only after the proper predicate had been laid.  The
Review Tribunal identified evidence of the following as being required for the admissibility of
audio records:

<UL>
<P>(1) that the recording device was capable of taking testimony;

<P>(2) that the operator of the device was competent;

<P>(3) the authenticity of the correctness of the recording;

<P>(4) that changes, additions, or deletions have not been made;

<P>(5) the manner of the preservation of the recording;

<P>(6) the identification of the speakers; and

<P>(7) that the testimony elicited was voluntarily made without any kind of inducement.
</UL>
<P><U>Id</U>. at 486-87, citing <U>Seymour v. Gillespie</U>, 608 S.W.2d 897, 898 (Tex.
1980).  Another type of evidence against the judge was written excerpts from the audio tapes. 
The Review Tribunal held that these were not admissible, as the &quot;general rule&quot; is that
a transcript made from a recording or re-recording is not an &quot;original&quot; and because it
is the product of human agency is not a &quot;duplicate&quot; as those terms are defined in
TRE 1001(3) and (4).  <U>Id</U>. at 487.

<P> Two other aspects of the Article X rules may be of some use in administrative proceedings.
First, under TRE 1005, the contents of an official record (or of a document authorized to filed or
recorded and actually recorded or filed), if otherwise admissible, may be proven by copy
(certified under TRE 902 or through testimony of a witness).  <U>Airline Commerce Bank v.
</U><U>Commercial Credit Corp.</U>, 531 S.W.2d 171, 174 (Tex. Civ. App.- [14th Dist.]
1975, writ ref'd n.r.e.) This simply makes clear that <I>copies</I> of public records, if otherwise
admissible and if properly authenticated, are admissible.

<P> Second, TRE 1006 authorizes the use of summaries, charts, or calculations of otherwise
admissible evidence.  The originals (or duplicates) of the underlying documents must be made
available for review, they must be voluminous and they must, themselves, be admissible in
evidence. <U>V.M. Solis Underground Utility and Paving Co. v. </U><U>City of Laredo</U>,
751 S.W.2d 532, 536 (Tex.App.--San Antonio 1988, writ denied); <I>see also</I> <U>First
</U><U>Heights Bank F.S.B. v. Gutierrez</U>, 852 S.W.2d 596, 617 (Tex.App.--Corpus
Christi 1993, writ denied).  Given the often-times extensive reliance on data, sampling, etc. in
administrative proceedings, this can be a useful tool by which that data can be presented in a
more reasonable form.
</BLOCKQUOTE>



<A NAME="IV">
<P><B>IV. </B><B>THE USE OF WRITTEN TESTIMONY </B><B>IN
ADMINISTRATIVE HEARINGS.</B></A>

<P> Section 2001.085 of the APA authorizes evidence to be received in a contested case in
written form if the hearing will be expedited and the interest of the parties will not be
&quot;substantially prejudiced&quot;.  This authorizes a practice employed by some state
agencies (e.g., PUC, TNRCC) of requiring or allowing parties to prefile their direct testimony in
written form.  Agency rules may provide further details concerning the use of written testimony
and the form in which it should be submitted, and the SOAH Rules acknowledge that prefiled
written testimony may be received in accordance with an agency's statute and rules.  1 Tex.
Admin. Code &#167; 155.45(e).

<P> Prefiled testimony is subject to objection to the same extent that the testimony would be if
presented live.  Oftentimes this will require a written motion specifically identifying the
objectionable testimony and setting forth the basis for the objection.  Other times hearings
officers will simply require the objections to be considered as a witness takes the stand and their
prefiled testimony is sought to be admitted into evidence. At any rate practitioners assisting in
the preparation of prefiled testimony and those involved in reviewing the testimony filed by
others should approach the process with the same evidentiary concerns and objectives as if the
testimony were offered live.  

<A NAME="V">
<P><B>V. </B><B>CONCLUSION.</B></A>

<P> The evidentiary record in an administrative proceeding is generally comprised of evidence
received or considered, a statement of matters officially noticed and offers of proof, objections
and rulings thereon.  APA &#167; 2001.060.  Decisions as to what specific items warrant
inclusion in the evidentiary record are primarily governed by the TRE, with the APA, agency
specific rules, and orders of the presiding officer adding further refinement to the rules.  It is
therefore important for practitioners involved in contested case proceedings to be familiar with
all of the potential sources of evidentiary rules which may affect the manner in which evidence is
properly presented and error is properly preserved.  These will in essence, be the tools for
building an evidentiary record. 


</BODY></HTML>
